<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astros erupt late, subdue Indians
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CLEVELAND _ The Astros woke up from their three-game nap Saturday,
and boy, were they fussy.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, nothing pacifies them like a come-from-behind
victory, and they mangled embattled Cleveland Indians relief
pitcher Jose Mesa as if he were their favorite chew toy.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros overcame a three-run deficit, forced extra innings
and scored four runs in the 11th to claim a much-needed 9-5 victory
at Jacobs Field. Their 23rd comeback victory of the season halted a
three-game losing streak and kept the Astros from going 0-4 on
their current five-game road trip.
</P>
<P>
   Moises Alou's two-out single against Mesa proved to be the
game-winning hit, and Carl Everett provided plenty of insurance
with a three-run homer as the Astros won for the 13th time in their
last at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a huge win for us,'' Astros second baseman Craig
Biggio said. ``After three tough losses _ games that could have
gone either way _ we really needed this one.''
</P>
<P>
   There could not have been two more appropriate heroes than Alou
and Everett. Not surprisingly, the Astros' drought coincided with
cold stretches by both players. Before Saturday, Alou and Everett
had combined for just three hits in the first three games of the
trip.
</P>
<P>
   Alou's run of bad luck dates even farther than the previous
three games. After watching his batting average peak at .351 at the
end of May, the Astros outfielder is hitting just .221 this month.
The hit off Mesa was one of Alou's few recent at-bats that didn't
end with his batting helmet being slammed into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moises has been pretty cold for the last week or so, and I'm
hoping this is the sort of thing that can break him out of it,''
Astros manager Larry Dierker said. ``For some reason, I just
thought he would get a hit there.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Alou and Everett jumped on first-pitch fastballs from Mesa,
who was booed and hissed throughout his brief stint on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time Mesa is on the mound, I'm going to be looking for a
fastball every time,'' Everett said. ``That's his out pitch, so
that's what you have to go up there looking to get. I'm glad I was
able to give us a few insurance runs, because Cleveland has the
kind of team that can come back on you with one swing. We lost
three games in a row, and it wasn't any fun watching the other team
come back on us, because that's what we're usually able to do.
Hopefully, this will get us back on track.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' bullpen, which had been derailed the previous few
days, was chugging at full speed Saturday. Doug Henry, Billy Wagner
and Reggie Harris combined for 4 scoreless innings and only
surrendered two hits. Wagner, who struck out three batters in 1
innings, qualified for the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bullpen is going to have its ups and downs just like
everyone else's bullpen,'' said Wagner, who lowered his earned run
average to 1.99. ``You just have to take the good with the bad and
go on about your business. Today was a good day, and more times
than not, we've been getting the job done. Doug and Reggie were
great.''
</P>
<P>
   After falling short of expectations in the first three games of
the trip, the Astros' offense was pretty good, too, piling up 15
hits, including three home runs and two doubles. Two of the homers
were particularly timely, because they tied the score against a
pair of tough relief pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Ausmus' three-run shot off Eric Plunk tied the score at 4
in the seventh, and Jeff Bagwell's 15th homer of the season _ a
first-pitch solo effort off Paul Shuey _ knotted the score at 5 in
the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our (scouting) reports told us this is the hardest-throwing
staff in the (American) league,'' Dierker said. ``Hard throwers
like to get strike one, and our guys seemed to be ready. We've got
guys up and down the lineup who can hit home runs, and today we got
some big ones.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros needed those long balls to offset the 1,209 feet's
worth of home runs surrendered by starter Jose Lima, who has served
up 18 gopher balls in his 17 starts this season. Four of the five
runs Lima allowed Saturday came on homers by Mark Whiten, Manny
Ramirez and David Justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a couple of mistakes, and they've got a great club,''
said Lima, who had a 2.61 ERA at the end of April but owns a 4.48
ERA in his last nine starts. ``If you make mistakes against these
guys, they're going to hurt you. They've got a hell of a lineup,
and you can't pitch around them all day. But I'm pleased, because
my job is to keep my club in the game, and that's what I did. I got
a no-decision, but I'll take 10 no-decisions if we win those 10
games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros are 11-6 in games started by Lima, who has six
no-decisions, including five in his last eight outings. Indians
starter Dwight Gooden also received a no-decision, but he pitched
well enough to win, leaving the game to a standing ovation after
holding the Astros to three runs (two earned) in six innings.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the way Gooden was pitching, the Astros were happy
to seen the Indians' bullpen, especially Mesa, who lost his
closer's role to Houstonian Mike Jackson earlier this season.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa retired the first batter he faced in the 11th before giving
up a one-out single to Bill Spiers, who was thrown out trying to
steal second base. After Derek Bell beat out an infield single and
Bagwell drew a walk, the stage was set for Alou, who has quite a
reputation for coming through in the clutch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be aggressive,'' said Alou, who is hitting .310
with runners in scoring position. ``I wanted Bagwell to walk,
because that would put me on the spot, and I love being on the
spot. Fortunately, I was able to come through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been playing the way I'd like to be playing lately,
but I knew (a slump) like this was coming, and I know how to get
out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Saturday's go-ahead hit was just the thing to get Alou
and the Astros going again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
