<HEADLINE>
KINGS TAKE BIRON IN DRAFT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 
  
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the National Hockey League draft began Saturday in Buffalo,
the Kings rated 18-year-old Mathieu Biron the eighth-best player
available, and the third-best defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings were focusing on defensemen Saturday, but considering
their first selection wasn't until No. 21, they weren't exactly
counting on having a chance to add the mountainous 6-foot-6,
212-pounder to their collection of prospects.
</P>
<P>
   But Biron - rated the seventh-best player by NHL Central
Scouting - was still available when the Kings' turn came, and
General Manager Dave Taylor snapped him up. Biron had eight goals
and 36 points last season for Shawinigan in the Quebec Major Junior
Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea,'' Taylor said when asked why Biron slipped so
low. ``Our scouts who see him all the time really like him. He's
got excellent size, he's a good skater for his size, he has good
reach, and he moves the puck well.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, Taylor classified Biron ``a bit of a project,''
mainly because he needs to grow into his body by adding 10 or 15
pounds of muscle, and to become a more consistently physical
player.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing important is being drafted by an NHL team,''
Biron said when asked if he was disappointed not to have been
chosen sooner. ``To be drafted in the first round is not so bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings used this draft to stock up on defensemen. Among the
players they chose were two goalies, three forwards and four
defensemen.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kings had to wait to get started. Nearly two hours
before the Kings chose Biron, the Tampa Bay Lightning surprised no
one by picking QMJHL star center Vincent Lecavalier with the first
pick. Moments later, after moving up a spot by swapping picks with
the San Jose Sharks, the expansion Nashville Predators chose
talented Ontario Hockey League center David Legwand, a Detroit
native, with the second selection.
</P>
<P>
   The Mighty Ducks used the fifth pick to make Russian defenseman
Vitaly Vishnevsky their first selection.
</P>
<P>
   All told, the Kings selected one player in each of the nine
rounds: Biron, center Justin Papineau of Belleville in the Ontario
Hockey League; Russian goalie Alexey Volkov; Ontario defensemen Kip
Brennan; Quebec defenseman Joe Rullier; Czech defenseman Tomas
Zizka; Finnish center Tommi Hannus; center Jim Henkel from the New
England junior hockey league; and goalie Matthew Yeats from the
Alberta junior hockey league.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor seemed almost as excited about Papineau as he did about
Biron, comparing the tiny center from Ottawa to NHL stars Steve
Yzerman of Detroit and Joe Sakic of Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   But Taylor acknowledged that the 5-foot-10, 160-pound Papineau
has a way to go (and grow) before he will be ready to play in the
NHL. Papineau scored 41 goals in 66 games for Belleville, but his
size makes him a rarity among recent King draft choices. In the
last four drafts, the Kings have chosen 34 skaters, and only four
have been under six feet tall. Still, Papineau is considered a
solid all-around player with decent speed and playmaking ability,
and though the Kings got him with the 46th selection, he was rated
27th by Central Scouting.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very good player,'' Taylor said. ``He's been one of the
top players in his age group all along. He'll have to get stronger
before he can play in Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   KING NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Rob Blake and fiancee Brandy Fleming were married
Saturday night in Marina del Rey. ... The Kings lost goalie
Frederic Chabot to Nashville in Friday's expansion draft, meaning
they cannot lose a goalie in the draft to stock the new Atlanta
franchise next year. That's the good news. The bad news is the
Kings are completely without NHL-ready goaltending depth in their
organization after Stephane Fiset and Jamie Storr. General Manager
Dave Taylor said, ``I think there are probably some goalies who
would be very interested in coming to Los Angeles because of our
lack of depth in goaltending.'' One possibility is Mike Buzak, 25,
who played in the IHL for the Ice Dogs and was under contract to
the Kings late last season. He's an unrestricted free agent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
