<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-BRAZIL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Brazil displays championship form
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PARIS _ As night fell and the lights of Paris twinkled, a cool,
damp sky draped itself around Parc des Princes.
</P>
<P>
   It was a little Chile.
</P>
<P>
   But a lot of Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   As if to show all doubters that what they saw in the meaningless
first-round finale against Norway was just that _ meaningless _ the
Brazilians showed off their real game Saturday in a 4-1 romp past
Chile.
</P>
<P>
   It was a night when neither slick conditions nor an inspired
Chilean team would keep Brazil from being wholly Brazil, from head
to toe.
</P>
<P>
   More precisely, it was Cesar Sampaio's head and Ronaldo's toe.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you hit the net twice, you have a lot more friends'' said
Ronaldo, criticized by some for a lack of offense in the first
round. ``I like my friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Cesar Sampaio scored two goals, the first on a beautiful header
off a free kick by Dunga in the 11th minute. The goal seemed to set
the Brazilian machine in motion and spark Ronaldo, who also
finished with two goals.
</P>
<P>
   From the 11th minute, Brazil began looking much more comfortable
at both ends of the field. Cesar Sampaio added his second goal in
the 27th minute and the creative Ronaldo scored his two on a
penalty kick in first-half injury time and a nice shot to the left
post after suckering Chile goalkeeper Nelson Tapia on a move to the
right post in the 70th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldo had two great chances to add to his goal spree but
ricocheted both shots off the post.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to defend our title,'' Ronaldo said. ``It's our title
and tonight we played our best because from now on every moment
could be our last. We don't want it to end until we are champions
again.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a marvelous show, if maybe not spectacular for Brazil,
which moves on to the quarterfinals Friday to face the winner of
today's game between Nigeria and Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw the kind of football that we can play tonight,''
Brazil coach Mario Zagallo said. ``The difference between the
Norway game (a 2-1 loss) and tonight was we had our full team back
and it played very well. We're going to keep winning. We're going
to go all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   It sure looked like a championship team Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   A steady rain made the field soggy and had players slipping and
sliding, but Brazil used quicker movements and shorter passes to
adjust.
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldo and Cesar Sampaio, who missed the Norway game because he
had received two yellow cards in the first two games, were by far
the most active players.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Dunga, Roberto Carlos and Cafu controlled possession
at midfield. Chile had no chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against most teams, we are even,'' Chilean striker Ivan
Zamorano said. ``Today we thought we had a chance. But Ronaldo and
Cesar Sampaio can score at any moment and they beat us today. They
were better than us.''
</P>
<P>
   The only question possibly facing Brazil as it moves on is
whether Denilson will replace Bebeto at forward in the next game.
</P>
<P>
   Bebeto, a star at USA '94, never clicked with Ronaldo and looked
a step slow. When Denilson, 20, replaced Bebeto, 34, in the second
half, the Brazil offense clearly kicked into a higher gear.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it wasn't as if Brazil struggled with Bebeto on the
field. It was his rebound pass to Cesar Sampaio that set up
Brazil's second goal.
</P>
<P>
   And even if Bebeto was jeered and whistled by Brazil's
perfectionist fans when he was replaced by Denilson in the 65th
minute, the score was 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw a team that did everything it needed to do,'' Zagallo
said, when asked about whether Bebeto would be replaced. ``We went
ahead early. That's always what you want.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, Chile's national anthem lasted longer than their
chances, although they got a nice goal on a Marcelo Salas header
off an assist by Zamorano in the 68th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Despite controlling the ball early and making a few runs up the
sideline toward the Brazilian goal, the early Chilean control
proved a mere charade.
</P>
<P>
   Literally every chance the Brazilians had in the early going was
converted.
</P>
<P>
   They took their first shot in the 11th minute. And scored.
</P>
<P>
   They took their second shot in the 27th minute. And scored.
</P>
<P>
   They took their third shot on Ronaldo's penalty kick in
first-half injury time. And scored.
</P>
<P>
   The efficiency made Chilean heads spin. And it made Brazilians
look ahead to bigger and better things, like defending their 1994
championship and winning an unprecedented fifth World Cup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
