</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-HOLLAND-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Holland has usual lofty goal
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PARIS _ They are perennial heartbreakers, like a sort of Chicago
Cubs of the world soccer stage.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs traditionally boot baseballs. The Dutch boot soccer
balls.
</P>
<P>
   In any language and with any appendage, hearts break just the
same.
</P>
<P>
   ``In almost every other nation, people celebrate going to the
second round,'' Dutch coach Guus Hiddink said. ``Our people expect
much more. We are in the second round, but they are not happy yet.
They want to win the World Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, could this be the year for the Dutch?
</P>
<P>
   As the elimination round of the 1998 World Cup began with
Saturday's victories by Brazil and Italy _ traditionally clutch
teams with seven World Cup championships between them _ perhaps the
most intriguing contender left in the field is the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   It has no championships, but quite the World Cup story in its
wake.
</P>
<P>
   So many times the Dutch have come to the World Cup with an
immensely talented squad. So many times they have looked virtually
untouchable, but never more than in 1974 and 1978, when opponents
were all but conceding the trophy to a veritable dream team of
Dutch players.
</P>
<P>
   Johan Cruyff, Robbie Rensenbrink, Johan Neeskens, Ruud Krol.
</P>
<P>
   They are Ernie Banks-type of Hall of Fame names within the
sport, players who pioneered the ``total football'' style to which
all ensuing Dutch teams have aspired.
</P>
<P>
   But they lost in the Cup championship game, twice.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``total football'' is a reputation the Dutch cherish and
this 1998 team seems to have again mastered, at times showing
remarkable skill in every phase of the game, depending on the
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   The English are known for ``long-ball'' soccer, in other words,
tightening the defense and booting the ball long upfield hoping for
a break and an individual effort. The Brazilians are known for
ball-handling skill and quick-striking attacks. Italy likes to
counterattack and build from midfield.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dutch have won using any of those styles. Total
football.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the Dutch have won the European Championship and
reached the World Cup finals tournament seven times. The Dutch
professional league, led by Ajax, which is one of the winningest
professional teams in Europe, has produced countless superstars.
The youth and developmental programs in Holland are emulated around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the years and all the great teams, the Dutch have
zero World Cup trophies. And zero tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are here for one reason,'' Dutch goalkeeper Edwin van der
Sar said. ``We are here to win the Cup. I don't think we will be
happy unless we win. You need luck and skill. I know we have the
skill.''
</P>
<P>
   That much has been obvious to anyone who has seen the Dutch in
France.
</P>
<P>
   The play of Ronald de Boer, Phillip Cocu, Marc Overmars, Wim
Jonk and the super-popular Dennis Bergkamp have conjured up images
of the great 1974 and 1978 teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch won the tough Group E, which included Belgium, South
Korea and Mexico. They will face Yugoslavia, a dark horse by most
accounts, Monday in Toulouse.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's Bebeto has said he considers this Netherlands team the
toughest he has seen.
</P>
<P>
   And Cruyff, in France as a commentator, says this team has
something the 1974 and 1978 sides did not have _ cohesion.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are all pulling in the same direction,'' Cruyff told the
French sports daily, L'Equipe. ``This team has extremely great
qualities.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet notice the hints of underachieving that have crept into the
picture.
</P>
<P>
   After the Dutch took command of Group E with a scoreless draw
with Belgium and a 5-0 whipping of South Korea last week, they
opened against Mexico with a blurring display.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch took a 2-0 lead over Mexico in the first 20 minutes,
meaning that in their first 225 minutes of the 1998 World Cup they
had not allowed a goal.
</P>
<P>
   But then there was a complacency that seemed to set in, a lack
of an ``over-my-dead-body'' attitude, as Hiddink called it.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico controlled the ball in the second half of the game and
cracked the Netherlands' defense for two goals to tie the score,
including one just 15 seconds before the final whistle.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Amsterdam reporters grilled players and coaches,
one asking Hiddink, ``Why have you failed?''
</P>
<P>
   Hiddink's response: ``We're through (to the second round). We
haven't failed.''
</P>
<P>
   Dutch fans, who are among the most supportive in the world,
decked out in bright orange jump suits and carrying horns and
whistles, looked in shock as they filed out of the stadium after
the Mexico game.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the two halves against Mexico might have perfectly
epitomized this nation's World Cup history.
</P>
<P>
   It can devastate opponents. But it also can devastate itself.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, the inconsistency was clear in sluggish
first-round games. Then, there was a hugely impressive win over
Ireland, then a heartbreaking 3-2 loss to eventual champion Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the team fell well short of expectations again, playing
miserably in the European Cup.
</P>
<P>
   And the ghosts that continue to haunt and hurt the most are from
1974 and 1978.
</P>
<P>
   The 1974 team dominated every opponent leading up to the Cup and
once the tournament began, Cruyff, Neeskens and Resenbrink charged
to remarkably easy wins, 4-0 over Argentina, 2-0 over East Germany
and 2-0 over Brazil. But in the final, even though the Netherlands
took a 1-0 lead before West Germany even touched the ball,
everything collapsed and West Germany prevailed 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, the Dutch again overwhelmed supposed
contenders, taking out Austria, Italy and West Germany on the way
to the final. But, again, they fell apart in extra time against
Argentina and lost 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the Dutch again look potentially overwhelming. They
say it could be their year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to learn from the (Mexico) game,'' van der Sar said.
``If we don't play the whole game, we could be in trouble.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
