<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-DRAFT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES SELECT TOP-RATED GOALIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO _ The loudest applause during Saturday's entire NHL
entry draft came when the Coyotes, of all teams, made their
first-round selection. And they only had the 14th overall pick.
</P>
<P>
   The noise was so deafening, the Marine Midland Arena almost
started to shake.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was my family and a bunch of my friends,'' said Patrick
DesRochers, the top-rated goalie in the draft, referring to the
wild celebration in the crowd when his name was announced by NHL
Commissioner Gary Bettman.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's at least 50 of them here today. They've all been
great. Especially my family. They've always been supportive of my
hockey career.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Coyotes' planned trade with Nashville for one of
the players the Predators took in Friday's expansion draft once
again was delayed. It will be announced early this week. Phoenix
likely will trade a draft pick to get a third- or fourth-line
forward.
</P>
<P>
   The traded pick probably won't be the 18-year-old DesRochers. If
he turns out to be half as good as the way his relatives can raise
the roof, the Coyotes may have found themselves the next Dominik
Hasek. According to scouts, he should be pushing Nikolai Khabibulin
for the No. 1 job in Phoenix within the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   `We had him ranked really high,'' General Manager Bobby Smith
said. `We've always thought this guy was a genuine top prospect. We
watched him a lot and (goalie coach) Benoit Allaire has worked with
him before and we know he's a tremendous talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were smiles all around our table today when the 14th
pick came up and he was still there.''
</P>
<P>
   DesRochers, who was 26-17-11 with a 3.35 goals-against average
last season for Sarnia in the Ontario Hockey League, is the first
goaltender the franchise has ever picked in the first round.
Previously, the highest-drafted goalie in club history was Scott
Langkow, the 31st overall pick in 1993, whose job, like
Khabibulin's, just got a little tougher.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a while before I'm ready to step in and play
at the NHL level, but who knows what's going to happen down the
road?'' said DesRochers, whose size (6-foot-3 {, 195 pounds) and
brilliant butterfly style impressed scouts across North America.
`I'm sure I'll go back (to Sarnia) for one more year of juniors and
then spend some time in the minors before I do anything in the
NHL.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said there was only one other player rated higher in the
draft that he considered trading up to get. He wouldn't say who,
but he did say he would have done the same thing to get DesRochers.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of teams drafting ahead of Phoenix were rumored to be
eyeing him. Especially the Edmonton Oilers, who picked just before
the Coyotes at No. 13, and likely will lose star goalie Curtis
Joseph to free agency. But Edmonton took Barrie right wing Michael
Henrich instead, opening the door for the Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal picked the next highest-rated goalie, Eric Chouinard,
with the following selection at No.15.
</P>
<P>
   Considered to be almost as good as Roberto Luongo, last year's
goalie sensation who went fourth overall to the New York Islanders,
DesRochers had the eye of Coyotes scouts long ago. One of them, in
fact, Terry Doran, drafted him into juniors with a first-round
pick, making DesRochers only the second goalie in OHL history to go
that high.
</P>
<P>
   With their second pick, the 43rd overall, Phoenix took Finnish
defenseman Ossi Vaananen, a 6-foot-3, 200-pounder from Helsinki who
plays a rugged style and can skate extremely well. The Coyotes have
done well scouting in Finland, finding players such as Teppo
Numminen and Juha Ylonen, in addition to defenseman Juha
Gustafsson, their first pick last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was glad to go in the second round, although, you know, I
was kind of hoping there was a chance I might go in the first,''
said Vaananen, who was ranked 13th among all European players in
the draft. ``I will go back to Finland and work very hard until my
time is ready to play for Phoenix.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to drafting the first goalie and the first Finn, the
Coyotes also drafted the first high-school player when, in somewhat
of a surprise, they took Minnesota-born center Pat O'Leary with the
73rd pick in the third round. He averaged 25 goals and 52 points
each of his last two seasons and will play for the University of
Minnesota in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really like our draft,'' Smith said. ``We probably took more
defensemen than we wanted to (four overall), but they were the best
players available at the time. Your first-round picks really
determine your draft, though, and we love the player we picked up
there.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
