<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY-FOX-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX STRUGGLES TO REGAIN HIS RACING PROMISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Stan Fox still can't remember the crash or the two
months that followed. They remain sealed in a place where memories
go when the race car you're in slams head-on into a concrete wall.
</P>
<P>
   The accident occurred seconds after the start of the 1995
Indianapolis 500, when Fox's machine veered sharply into the
outside wall in Turn 1 after apparently running over some rumble
strips.
</P>
<P>
   Although the impact sheered off the front half of the car, which
exposed Fox's dangling feet and legs, he miraculously suffered no
lower-extremity injuries.
</P>
<P>
   But Fox took such a massive blow to the head that it left him
with a serious brain injury and put him in a coma for five days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember anything about that wreck or my rehab,'' Fox
said. ``Maybe that's good.''
</P>
<P>
   It is good.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the horrible accident and its consequences, Fox is
determined to one day again return to the sight of one of the most
brutal crashes in Indy 500 history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to start the 1999 Indianapolis 500,'' said Fox, who
will be 46 on July 7. ``That's all I want to do. I want to go back
there. I have to get back there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   What Fox did for three days this week at the Bob Bondurant
School of High Performance Driving near Chandler was participate in
an advanced oval driving course. A few weeks ago, Fox said he
attended a similar course in Florida at another driving school.
</P>
<P>
   Fox also drove several practice laps in a midget car Tuesday at
Manzanita Speedway, but he said the rust of a three-year layoff was
evident.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I didn't hurt the car or spin out,'' Fox said. ``That was
my last time in a midget.''
</P>
<P>
   But not the last time in a race car, Fox said. Although he has
no set plan in an attempt to regain his driving touch, he wants to
move up the driving ladder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could drive an Atlantic car or whatever,'' said Fox, who
returned home Thursday to Wisconsin. ``I just want to keep driving
a bigger and bigger car. And I want to keep improving.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not going to go talk to any Indy-car owners yet. I
don't want to jack them around until I know I'm getting somewhere
with my driving.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be a long road back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got some work to do,'' Bondurant instructor Mike McGovern
said. ``He realizes that, too. He's going to get in as many cars as
he possibly can to bring himself, he hopes, back up to the same
speed he was before.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got the feel. I can tell that. The feel is still there,
meaning if the car gets loose, he can handle it. The part he's
having trouble with is the decision making that a driver goes
through on the racetrack. You know, learning which is the most
efficient way around a corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox spent about nine hours over the three days in an open-wheel
Formula Ford and drove only on a small oval approximately a
quarter-mile in size.
</P>
<P>
   ``He definitely improved over the three days,'' McGovern said.
``His skills are still there.''
</P>
<P>
   But driving on a makeshift quarter-mile oval and driving on
Indianapolis Motor Speedway's 2.5-mile oval are two different
things, as different as a Volkswagen Beetle is to an army tank.
</P>
<P>
   And Fox knows it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole goal is to get back to Indy,'' Fox said. ``That's
where I crashed and I want to get back there to pay it back. I
don't have to win. I just have to make it back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to drive as hard as I can in all sorts of cars so I
can get better. I thought I did pretty good (in the Bondurant
course). My body knows what's going on, but there's other things I
have to work on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I got in the car (Monday), I forgot to buckle
my helmet. That happened again (Tuesday). That's never happened
before. But I'm going to remain positive. And I'm going to spend a
whole year in rear-engine cars trying to get back to Indy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've heard of (the movie) ``Mr. Smith Goes To Washington.''
Well, I'm going to be ``Mr. Fox Goes to Indy.'' Just watch.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
