<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-LOCKOUT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA LABOR PROBLEMS MAY SPLIT PLAYERS' RANKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A league built on individual stars and free agents faces a
dangerous test that threatens to divide players.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA shutdown will begin Wednesday with owners in one camp
and the players union in another. The battle is drawn along classic
lines. For now.
</P>
<P>
   The owners can play a waiting game. Money from television
contracts will continue to fill their coffers. But there will be no
dependable stream of income for many players.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 percent of the players made minimum wage last season.
Nearly $300,000 a year is a very nice minimum, but nothing about
the NBA lifestyle is minimal.
</P>
<P>
   When bills start to add up in the fall, some owners are betting
the union will fall apart. November is when many players get
paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   The most explosive issue is the so-called Larry Bird exception.
Under the current collective-bargaining agreement, teams can pay
their free agents any sum. The result: The salary cap is a sham.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the cap was supposed be $26.2 million. The average
payroll was $32.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Owners contend 15 to 20 teams lost money. There's debate about
that number, but there's been little argument that players get 57
percent of total revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is enough there for everybody, but the system isn't
working,'' said Suns President Jerry Colangelo, a member of the
owner's committee.
</P>
<P>
   The system, in fact, isn't working for a plurality of the
players. There are 39 stars who make at least $5 million a year and
149 players making the minimum.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, a divide exists between the filthy rich and merely
wealthy. In part, the owners have themselves to blame.
</P>
<P>
   But, at some point, it's fair to predict that players at the
bottom will question the fairness of a system that seems to enrich
a few at the expense of many. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-98 0013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
