<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DID THE SUNS GET A STEAL IN BAI LEY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY(at) 
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - They gathered around the television, a mixture of
relatives and home boys from Ladera Heights, and nobody could
understand. The names would come and go, including a couple of
schoolboys who wouldn't know the first thing about dropping in 26
points to win an NCAA championship. And as two hours stretched into
a lifetime, a night of celebration became a lay-up drill of
condolences.
</P>
<P>
   Just like that, Toby Bailey was back on the playground. Not the
Los Angeles legend dunking on impostors. Rather, like a kid no one
wants on their team, waiting to be picked, smiling through the
humility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most disappointing thing in the world,'' Bailey said,
``to see players you know you're better than, players who haven't
proven themselves, getting picked ahead of you.''
</P>
<P>
   It is five days after the NBA draft, and you still need an
industrial-size fan to clear the smoke away from Jefferson Street.
Notre Dame Coach John McLeod says Pat Garrity will make a bigger
impression in the pros than he did in college. The brain expert is
touting the shape of someone's cranium. Danny Ainge is smiling as
if he stole Babe Ruth from the Red Sox. And, by the way, please
welcome Mark Bryant, your starting center for 1998-99.
</P>
<P>
   For all their bluster, the Suns' draft-day adventures cannot be
assessed until they parlay a first-round pick from the Dallas
Mavericks into a breathing entity. And by that time, the real coup
may have nothing to do with the peddling of Steve Nash.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to Toby Bailey, who is smiling now, holding a
Suns' jersey in his arms, ready for a large helping of revenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely happy to be here,'' Bailey said. ``But I'm also
kind of (upset) that people disrespected me and didn't pick me in
the first round. So I'm definitely putting in the work this summer.
People will see a new Toby Bailey by next year.''
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing as reliable as an athlete who has been picked
apart by experts, robbed of a nice signing bonus, implicitly
informed that his game isn't so special, after all.
</P>
<P>
   Not that much has changed about Bailey's game since he was
touted for stardom. He's a wonderful rebounder for his size, a
nimble defender who once shut down Damon Stoudamire, an incredibly
gifted athlete with a 40-inch vertical. And if he ever develops a
consistent jump shot, the game is his.
</P>
<P>
   Why Bailey lasted into the second round is a mystery. Scouts
frowned on his performance at a rookie camp in Chicago, although
Bailey claims classes at UCLA hindered his workouts. Some say he
tapered off after his freshman season, even though he played out of
position for two years, inside a program swimming in controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt kind of stifled in college,'' Bailey said. ``The NBA
game is more suited for me. I'll be playing my natural position,
I'll have that wide-open court, I'll be able to excel.''
</P>
<P>
   Get past the overwhelming doses of optimism regarding the draft,
and we'll concede this: When the second round was on the clock and
Bailey's name remained unspoken, Ainge and general manager Brian
Colangelo did something smart. They picked up the phone, and the
Lakers bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have taken him ahead of 20 players in the draft,'' Ainge
said. ``I think Toby hasn't begun to scratch the surface of his
potential. Besides, we'll pass the ball a little more than UCLA
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Some day, you might look back and rue the day the Suns gave away
Nash. Or maybe, you'll only remember the day they stole Toby
Bailey. Either way, the Suns currently have enough players under
contract for a 3-on-3 tournament. Bailey will get a fair shot.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why his father is smiling, too, holding a Suns hat in
his hands, knowing something only a father would know.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Toby signed with UCLA, he was like a throw-in,'' John
Bailey said. ``He saw it as a chance to prove people wrong, and he
did. We have a saying in our family: `Things always happen for the
best,' And, for some reason, Toby always plays well coming out of
adversity.''
</P>
<P>
   Like now. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
