<HEADLINE>
ROENICK-FOR PICK DEAL NIXED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Had the San Jose Sharks not asked for the moon,
the Coyotes could have had themselves one of the brightest stars in
Saturday's NHL entry draft.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Coyotes passed on highly-touted center  &UR; David
 &UR; Legwand, &UR; who went to the Nashville Predators with the second
overall pick after the expansion team struck a last-minute trade
with San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks, who talked with at least a half-dozen teams about
moving the No. 2 pick, apparently wanted center  &UR; Jeremy
Roenick, &UR; and possibly more, in exchange for the right to draft
Legwand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to them, but their price was way beyond what we were
willing to pay,'' Smith said, adding, ``I wouldn't trade Jeremy
Roenick for a No. 2 pick.
</P>
<P>
   Smith did take a fifth-round pick from the Sharks, however,
dealing away the Coyotes' fifth-round pick next year so he could
take his second goalie in Saturday's draft,  &UR; Josh Blackburn.
</P>
<P>
   This is at least the third time in the past two years Roenick's
name has been linked to trade rumors involving San Jose. At the
trading deadline last season, the Sharks supposedly were willing to
deal center  &UR; Jeff Friesen and a player to be named for Roenick.
</P>
<P>
   Legwand, who scored 54 goals and 105 points last season for
Plymouth in the Ontario Hockey League, was rated as the second-best
prospect in the draft behind fellow center  &UR; Vincent Lecavalier, &UR; who
went No. 1 to Tampa Bay. Both are seen as can't-miss future stars.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, however, said he won't lose any sleep over passing on
Legwand. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Bowman watch &QL; 
 &QL; 
Detroit Red Wings Coach  &UR; Scotty Bowman said during a break in
Saturday's draft that he will make an announcement next week
regarding his decision to retire after winning eight Stanley Cup
championships or to return in hopes of leading Detroit to a third
consecutive title.
</P>
<P>
   He sounded like a man who won't be back. And the recent death of
his 61-year-old brother,  &UR; Jack, &UR; may have something to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife has been very considerate. For the last seven years,
she's pretty much let me live with the team. . . . But with my
brother dying, she's worried. She wants me to enjoy life a bit
more.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Ossi and the Worm &QL; 
 &QL; 
Smith didn't know how correct he was when he said Finnish
defenseman &UR; Ossi Vaananen, the Coyotes' second-round pick from
Helsinki, has a ``colorful character.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaananen, 17, convinced the entire Finnish national junior team
to dye their hair white on the eve of the European championships.
</P>
<P>
   Has he ever heard of  &UR; Dennis Rodman, the king of colored
hairdos?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh sure, I know who he is,'' Vaananen said. ``He's a
character. Just like me.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Trading places &QL; 
 &QL; 
Nashville acquired eight players to bolster its roster following
Friday's expansion draft, in which the Predators selected one
player from each of the NHL's 26 established teams. The Coyotes
lost defenseman  &UR; John Slaney.
</P>
<P>
   Nashville acquired  &UR; Darren Turcotte (St. Louis),  &UR; Sergei
 &UR; Krivokrasov (Chicago),  &UR; Sebastien Bordeleau (Montreal),  &UR; Jim Dowd
(Calgary) and  &UR; Jan Vopat and  &UR; Kimmo Timonen (Los Angeles) for
future considerations. The Predators also got goalie  &UR; Dominic
Roussel and  &UR; Jeff
 &UR; Staples from Philadelphia for a seventh-round draft choice and
 &UR; Ville
 &UR; Peltonen from San Jose for a fifth-round pick. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
