<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-SCHOENFELD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS FALL FROM SUPER BOWL HEIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Quarterback  &UR; Neil O'Donnell's troubles began in Sun Devil
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   He threw two bad interceptions in Super Bowl XXX, costing the
Pittsburgh Steelers the 1995 NFL title and assuring Dallas
cornerback
 &UR; Larry Brown of winning the game's Most Valuable Player award and
becoming a rich man.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's two interceptions enabled him to get a $2.5
million-a-year free-agent contract from the Oakland Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell, meanwhile, turned down an $18.75 million deal from
the Steelers and signed a five-year, $25 million deal with the New
York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, both have been humbled.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, possibly the biggest free-agent bust ever, was released
by the Raiders this off-season and signed a deal with the Minnesota
Vikings that pays him $425,000 for one year.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell is looking for work after being dumped by the New York
Jets last week. He was cut because he refused to reduce his '98
salary from $4.2 million to $2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   His two seasons in New York were disastrous. Consider:
</P>
<P>
   He was sacked eight times in his first game, a 31-6 loss to
Denver in the 1996 opener.
</P>
<P>
   He was 0-5 as a starter that season.
</P>
<P>
   He suffered a separated shoulder in the sixth game.
</P>
<P>
   He tried to come back six games later but suffered a torn calf
muscle in pregame warm-ups.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell's options for next season are to sign with San Diego,
Seattle, Carolina or Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   The Chargers are the only team for which he could start, and
that would only be until first-round draft pick  &UR; Ryan Leaf is
ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's far from being over for me,'' O'Donnell said. ``I have a
lot left. I'm going to find the right situation and make a run at
it.'' &QL; 
Straight shooters? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With O'Donnell gone, the Jets' quarterback job will go to  &UR; Glenn
 &UR; Foley, backed up by  &UR; Vinny Testaverde, signed after O'Donnell's
release.
</P>
<P>
   Foley, a Coach  &UR; Bill Parcells favorite, is unproven.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give me a fair chance for the No. 1 spot,'' Foley said.
``That's all I want.''
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde, who was 8-20-1 as a starter in Baltimore, is joining
the team he rooted for growing up in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Like O'Donnell, he also doesn't have fond memories of Sun Devil
Stadium, throwing five interceptions for the University of Miami in
a loss to Penn State in the Fiesta Bowl's 1987 national title
game. &QL; 
Liar, liar &QL; 
Two years ago,  &UR; Steve DeBerg was Coach Dan Reeves' quarterbacks
coach on the New York Giants.
</P>
<P>
   With Reeves' Atlanta Falcons looking for a backup quarterback,
DeBerg had a tryout last week.
</P>
<P>
   When DeBerg was asked his age, he told reporters he was 39.
</P>
<P>
   The former San Francisco/Denver/Tampa Bay/Kansas City/Miami
quarterback is 44. &QL; 
Nobody's Buddy &QL; 
Former Philadelphia Eagles owner  &UR; Norman Braman, the man who
gave &UR; Buddy Ryan his first NFL head coaching job, has few fond
memories of Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll probably be remembered historically in the National
Football League as the man who revolutionized defensive football,''
Braman said of Ryan, who later brought his ``46'' defense to the
Cardinals. ``Everything you see today (on defense) evolved out of
his system.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he had a problem functioning within an organization. He
was a little man with a little man's inferiority (complex). I felt
a coach had to be a mirror image of the owner. And when I looked in
the mirror at Buddy Ryan, I didn't like what I saw.'' &QL; 
Short shots &QL; 
Former Valley resident  &UR; Max McGee, the ex-Green Bay Packers tight
end, is retiring as the team's radio analyst after this season.
McGee, who lived in the Valley from 1978 to '90, has been working
for the Packers' radio network for 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   Includes information from other media sources. Steve Schoenfeld
can be reached at 602-444-8334 or at steve.schoenfeld(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
