<HEADLINE>
AINGE DEFENDS GARRITY TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Coach  &UR; Danny Ainge rejects criticism that the Suns
goofed in a draft-day deal for No. 19 pick  &UR; Pat Garrity, a Notre
Dame forward, instead of Kentucky center  &UR; Nazr Mohammed, picked No.
29 by Utah and traded to Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Ainge said  &UR; Horacio Llamas will be more effective next season
than the unproven Mohammed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a few years for these guys to develop,'' Ainge said.
``I absolutely like Horacio better then Mohammed, or a few other
guys who were taken in the second round. We've been working with
him for a couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Ainge also said  &UR; Loren Meyer can be better next season than
Mohammed. Meyer spent last season on the injured list, recovering
from back surgery. Ainge remembers how effective he was in
match-ups against
 &UR; Charles Barkley and others.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ainge said the 6-foot-11 Llamas has a good chance to
be a reliable backup next season. There was some surprise that
Ainge left Llamas off the playoff roster against San Antonio's big
men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Horacio was legitimately hurt,'' said Ainge, who added that
the Suns' acquisition of Dallas' 1999 first-round pick might one
day be a cornerstone in a deal for a first-rate center. ``I know
people thought we were hiding him, but he just underwent surgery
for a spur on his foot.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Briefly &QL; 
 &QL; 
Name-dropping: Bulls guard  &UR; Steve Kerr has been mentioned as a
possible successor to  &UR; Steve Nash, whom the Suns traded to Dallas.
Kerr was the Suns' second-round pick in 1988 after a brilliant four
years at the University of Arizona. He still has a home in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   And former Suns Coach  &UR; John MacLeod of Notre Dame says Garrity
reminds him of Minnesota's  &UR; Tom Gugliotta and  &UR; Dave DeBusschere,
who helped the Knicks win two NBA titles. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
