<SLUG> BC-BKL-MERCURY-MYSTICS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCURY TAKES TO ROAD  
 GAME VS. MYSTICS BEGINS 5-GAME TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It's one thing to win at home, where the Mercury
already has drawn a third of the WNBA's 15 five-digit crowds and
was 11-3 last season. The road is entirely different.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix was 5-9 away from America West Arena in 1997 and just
1-5 in three of the cities it will visit during a seasonlong
five-game trip that begins today.
</P>
<P>
   Even here at the MCI Center, where the Mercury (5-1) is playing
for the first time, the environment will be plenty hostile. The
expansion Mystics (1-5) drew a WNBA record 20,674 for its first
home game, followed that up with a crowd of 14,314 and figure to
draw well again for a Sunday afternoon game that brings
media-friendly Cheryl Miller and her troops to entertain the
nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury broke on top, 11-0 and 22-8, in beating the Mystics,
69-54, less than two weeks ago, but has improved vastly since.
Closing its five-game homestand with a win over defending league
champion Houston and 96-63 mauling of Utah puts Phoenix in position
to accomplish what it previously couldn't in places such as Madison
Square Garden (0-2) and Charlotte Coliseum (0-2).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a whole different ballgame on the road,'' Miller said.
``As comfortable and confident as we feel here (at home), people
feel in their arenas. We'll have some growing pains probably, but
the experience on the road will allow us to bond and jell as a
team.''
</P>
<P>
   The 11-day trip actually is a two-parter. After playing here
today and in a nationally televised game against the New York
Liberty on Monday, the Mercury gets an extra day in the Big Apple
before games against Cleveland on Thursday and Charlotte, again on
national TV, on the Fourth of July.
</P>
<P>
   A flight to Phoenix immediately after the Sting game, which
begins at 10 a.m. (Arizona time), gives the team two full days at
home before it travels to Detroit for a July 8 initial meeting with
the Shock, coached by former Mercury guard Nancy Lieberman-Cline.
</P>
<P>
   If Phoenix, which opened the season with a road win vs.
Sacramento, finishes over .500 on the trip, it will be at least 8-3
when it returns July 10 to launch a season-long six-game homestand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we really believe we can win on the road,'' said
center Jennifer Gillom, the Mercury's leading scorer with an
18.2-point average. ``We didn't have this type of feeling last
year, and it stems from the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   A bench that outscored Utah, 42-25, even without forward
Michelle Griffiths, bumped to the starting lineup in place of
injured Toni Foster (stress fracture right leg). The Mystics will
be seeing 6-foot-5 backup center Marlies Askamp and Japanese
sharpshooter Mikiko Hagiwara for the first time, both having been
on the injured list for the first meeting June 15.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's lone victory came before Tipper Gore, among those
at a sold-out home opener, 85-76 over Utah. Since then, the Mystics
twice dropped the battle of expansion teams in losing home and away
to Detroit, cut co-captain Tammy Jackson and nearly lost its other
captain, Nikki McCray.
</P>
<P>
   The former American Basketball League MVP suffered a severe cut
that sliced a nerve below her left elbow and required 12 stitches
to close during practice Wednesday. She played Thursday, scoring 23
points in a 79-71 loss to the Shock, as did starting point guard
Rita Williams, who took an elbow to the forehead Wednesday and had
to leave practice.
</P>
<P>
   McCray is averaging 21.5 points, second in the league behind
Houston's Cynthia Cooper, but so far not getting nearly enough help
from a lineup that includes Brazilian center Alessandra Santos de
Oliveira and rookie power forward Murriel Page from the University
of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   McCray had 20 and Deborah Carter 11 in the first game with the
Mercury, but the rest of the roster combined for only 23. Phoenix
is giving up a league-low 64.2 points per game. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
