<SLUG> BC-BBO-GOMEZ-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VERY GOOD YEAR
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The folks who run baseball have always talked about
how it's an amazingly resilient game, one that, basically, could
never really kill itself, no matter how stupid some of their
decisions have been.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 season is proof positive that the people running the
game are probably right, at least on this subject. Baseball is
enjoying its finest season since 1994, at least in terms of
record-breaking offensive numbers and attendance.
</P>
<P>
   That season, then-San Francisco Giant  &UR; Matt Williams, now with
the Diamondbacks, had 43 home runs when the season ended abruptly
on Aug. 11. We'll never know if he could have made a serious run at
 &UR; Roger
 &UR; Maris' single-season home run record of 61.
</P>
<P>
   What we do know is that three players _ St. Louis'  &UR; Mark
McGwire,
 &UR; Sammy Sosa of the Chicago Cubs and Seattle's  &UR; Ken Griffey Jr. _
have had the kind of first half necessary to make a run at Maris.
</P>
<P>
   We also know that Texas'  &UR; Juan Gonzalez has a legitimate shot at
chasing down  &UR; Hack Wilson's single-season RBI record of 190, a
record once believed untouchable. A September run by the four
sluggers would be wonderful for the game.
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of shot in the arm the sport can badly use. There
are those who believe baseball is a dying sport. They are the same
people who believe basketball and football are overtaking baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Hah! It won't happen, no matter what the television numbers say.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball remains this country's game. Try and quickly remember
who won the 1986 Super Bowl or NBA Finals. If you're having
trouble, try and remember who won the '86 World Series. It's easy.
It was the year of  &UR; Bill Buckner and  &UR; Mookie Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   We've always been able to associate years with the World Series.
The same cannot be said for football or basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it. Years from now we may be talking about 1998 as
the year Roger Maris' and Hack Wilson's records fell in the same
season. &QL; 
The Boss is in a jam &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New York Yankees Boss  &UR; George Steinbrenner had a firsthand taste
of what Yankees fans must endure to watch a game in the south
Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner, who flew into a New jersey airport last week and
then jumped into a limo to make his way to a Yankees game, got
stuck in traffic, just like everyone else on their way to Yankee
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough, but I saw what some of these people have to go
through to get to the games,'' said Steinbrenner, who is pushing
for a new home in midtown Manhattan. ``You have to love the Yankees
to do that, and they do, and I give them credit. Bumper to bumper
to bumper to bumper. I pulled up alongside one wagon full of kids
and the driver. I could tell they were all upset _ they all had
their Yankees hats on. I rolled down the window and said, `Don't
worry, they ain't starting until I get there.' They didn't have any
idea who I was.'' &QL; 
La-La Land or Lu-Lu Land? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The once stable-as-a-mountain Los Angeles Dodgers have turned
into a daily soap opera, with the players and coaching staff
changing more frequently than  &UR; Dennis Rodman's hair color.
</P>
<P>
   So in the interest of clearing up some of the rampant talk
surrounding the Dodgers, here's some more of the same (caution, use
at your own risk):
</P>
<P>
   Early talk from within the Dodgers organization has new
president  &UR; Bob Graziano and GM  &UR; Tommy Lasorda already sniping
behind each other's back and jockeying for power. It's anyone's
guess how long this marriage will last.
</P>
<P>
   All that talk of  &UR; Mike Piazza and  &UR; Bobby Valentine heading west
after the season is probably nothing more than talk. Piazza loves
New York, and Valentine has another year on his contract to manage
the Mets, who must waive a clause in order to allow Valentine to
manage elsewhere during the length of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   If  &UR; Tommy Lasorda wins the power play, expect  &UR; Jim
 &UR; Leyland to be the front-runner to land the managing post. If
Lasorda loses to Graziano, expect San Diego coach  &UR; Davey Lopes, and
possibly Yankees third-base coach  &UR; Willie Randolph, to be the
favorite. The only way  &UR; Glenn Hoffmann keeps the job is if he
guides the Dodgers into the playoffs. &QL; 
La-La or Lu-Lu, Part II &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers could have some serious payroll problems next year.
They are on the hook to pay  &UR; Gary Sheffield,  &UR; Raul Mondesi,  &UR; Bobby
 &UR; Bonilla,  &UR; Eric Young,  &UR; Eric Karros and  &UR; Jose Vizcaino a combined
$36.9 million next season.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Dodgers have relievers  &UR; Dave Mlicki and  &UR; Greg
 &UR; McMichael under contract for a combined $4 million. Catcher
 &UR; Charles
 &UR; Johnson is arbitration eligible and can easily expect to be paid at
least $5 million. Even if  &UR; Ramon Martinez is injured and cannot
pitch, the Dodgers would probably have to acquire a front-line
starter. Price for that? About $7 million.
</P>
<P>
   All told, the Dodgers are looking at about $53 million before
they fill out the rest of their roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``No general manager operates without some constraints,''
Graziano said. ``Every general manager has constraints, even if
it's $74 million. No one is unlimited in terms of spending on
player talent. Tommy is no different, as Fred was no different.
That's the challenge.'' &QL; 
What's Miami's area code? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia Manager  &UR; Terry Francona so badly wanted to push for
several of his Phillies to be considered for the All-Star Game that
he telephoned the NL manager and left a 10-minute explanation on
his voice mail.
</P>
<P>
   After stating cases for several of his players other than  &UR; Curt
 &UR; Schilling, Francona hung up. Hours later he realized he'd called
Atlanta's  &UR; Bobby Cox. Of course, Florida's Leyland is this year's
NL manager, not Cox, who has managed four of the past six NL
squads. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at 602-444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
