<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-ARIZONA-BURKHART-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PEEP AT THE SHEEP: BIGHORN OUT ING SET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Desert bighorn sheep are unusual, fascinating
creatures. The vast majority of Arizonans have seen them only in
zoos or on TV wildlife shows.
</P>
<P>
   Being out among them in the wild is exciting.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest adventure is accompanying biologists on a sheep
capture and transfer. One method is to fly over an animal with a
helicopter and fire a net over it. Another is to bait sheep to a
certain spot, then fire a huge net over them, capturing many at
once.
</P>
<P>
   The bighorns then are examined, treated for diseases, loaded
onto trailers and taken elsewhere to be released as part Arizona's
successful program to reintroduce sheep to their historic habitat.
</P>
<P>
   Almost as exciting is to travel the Colorado River below Hoover
Dam. There is a large number of bighorns along the river here, and
they don't seem particularly concerned by boats.
</P>
<P>
   It's thrilling to look up at the rugged cliffs and see a big ram
looking down at you. It's even better when he comes to the river to
drink. The big rams are careful when they drink. It's doubtful they
could float because of their heavy horns and might drown if they
fell in.
</P>
<P>
   But few observers get that experience.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Arizona Game and Fish Department is providing a
free Watchable Wildlife Clinic, with a focus on bighorn sheep, July
17-18 in the northwest part of the state.
</P>
<P>
   The clinic will begin on a Friday at 6:30 p.m. in Kingman.
Participants will meet at Game and Fish's regional office, 5325 N.
Stockton Hill Road, where they will spend about two hours learning
about how to view wildlife, how to find it and how to photograph
it. Then the session will focus on bighorn sheep.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, participants will gather at Willow Beach
Marina on the river, where Game and Fish personnel will take them
upriver by boat to find and view bighorn sheep up close.
</P>
<P>
   Since the breeding season will be in progress, the rams should
be providing plenty of noise when they start banging heads.
</P>
<P>
   Due to limited boat availability and meeting room seating, the
clinic will be limited to 40 participants. Children under the age
of 16 won't be allowed to attend because viewing requires
considerable patience and a minimum of movement and noise.
</P>
<P>
   Those interested should make their reservations by calling the
Kingman Game and Fish office at (520) 692-7700. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Speaking of wildlife . . . &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How would you like to run around in the middle of the night,
using a spotlight to look for animals _ and be doing a service for
them?
</P>
<P>
   The Aubrey Valley near Seligman isn't too far east of Kingman,
and the Arizona Game and Fish Department is looking for volunteer
help there.
</P>
<P>
   That's where the endangered black-footed ferret was reintroduced
to Arizona. This program has produced some of the first ferrets
ever born in the wild but still is being managed intensely.
</P>
<P>
   Before the ferrets were transplanted to Arizona, biologists did
extensive surveys of prairie dog villages in Arizona to make sure
no native ferrets were present. Prairie dogs are the natural prey
of ferrets.
</P>
<P>
   Since ferrets are nocturnal creatures, walking around in a field
with a spotlight and looking for the green eyes of a ferret to
shine keeps you interested. If that's not enough, there might be a
fox or coyote staring back.
</P>
<P>
   On July 24-29, Aug. 21-26 and Sept. 25-30, biologists will be
doing surveys of the prairie dog communities at Aubrey Valley to do
a count on the ferrets. The more help, the better. That's why
volunteers are needed.
</P>
<P>
   The work will begin at sundown and last until sunrise.
Volunteers must bring binoculars, camping equipment and their own
food.
</P>
<P>
   Those interested in participating on some of the nights should
contact biologist Richard Winstead at Game and Fish's Kingman
regional office, (520) 692-7700. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at 602-444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-98 0030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
