<HEADER>
A0563 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-ITALY-NORWAY-BOS &LR;      06-28 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-ITALY-NORWAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORWAY'S EFFORTS ALL FOR NIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSEILLE _ OK, so it wasn't bellissimo. But it wasn't brutto,
either. The ``kings of 1-0,'' as the French call their blue-shirted
neighbors, did what they do best Saturday afternoon inside the
scorching cauldron that was the Stade Velodrome _ survive. Italy 1,
Norway 0. It was all still tutto bene for the Azzurri in the World
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``A very good match indeed,'' coach Cesare Maldini proclaimed,
after his side had earned a quarterfinal date with Sunday's
France-Paraguay victor. ``We didn't take many risks and had two or
three good opportunities to score. I thought we deserved to win.''
</P>
<P>
   All the Azzurri needed was Christian Vieri's goal in the 18th
minute off a classic counterattack. Then they sat back in their
half and let the overheated Norwegians trip over themselves trying
to score. It wasn't lovely, but after what they've been through
since the last Cup, the Italians aren't interested in lovely.
</P>
<P>
   They were whacked out of the 1996 European championships in the
first round. They blew their qualifying group despite blanking
England at Wembley because they couldn't beat the Georgians. So the
Azzurri had to go to Moscow and play the Russians in the snow.
</P>
<P>
   And though they won their here by 4 points, it wasn't easy. The
Italians needed a penalty kick by Roberto Baggio on a dubious hand
ball five minutes from time to tie Chile. They beat Cameroon, 3-0,
but the Africans played a man short for the second half and the
Azzurri didn't score their second goal until the 75th minute. And
they didn't put away winless Austria until the 89th minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Italy must suffer to win,'' said captain Paolo Maldini. ``But
we're ready to suffer until the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Italians were 6-2-2 against Norway, including a
10-on-11 win at the Meadowlands in 1994, they were prepared to
sweat blood Saturday. The Norwegians, after all, had beaten
defending champion Brazil with two goals in the final seven minutes
to get here after being dominated all night. ``They beat the
giant,'' shrugged Cesare Maldini.
</P>
<P>
   The Italians knew that the Norwegians were fit, patient, and
calculating. They sit back in their 4-5-1, wait for a mistake, and
storm back on the counter, looking for striker Tore Andre Flo. But
the Italians wrote the book on counterattacking, and as soon as
Norway brought too many men forward and missed, they went for the
throat.
</P>
<P>
   Here was Luigi Di Biagio, the clever midfielder from AS Roma,
launching a lovely through ball for Vieri, who dashed between two
defenders and ripped the ball past keeper Frode Grodas for his
fifth goal of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The Norwegians would have equalized in the 71st minute had
Italian keeper Gianluca Pagliuca not gotten a glove on Flo's header
just before it went over the line.
</P>
<P>
   That is how the kings of 1-0 endure _ by getting what they need,
then forcing you to come at them again and again while they throw
their sky-blue net over you. When it was done, the Norwegians
walked off shaking their heads, saying that the Italians would
never beat France. ``I'm not very impressed with Italy,'' Norwegian
coach Egil Olsen said. ``They won because we didn't play well.''
</P>
<P>
   Bello, brutto, the Italians weren't quibbling. All they knew was
that the Norwegians are going back to Oslo and they are going on to
Saint-Denis and the final eight. If this is suffering, bring the
pain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-98 0046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980628.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-28 00:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0564 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-REDSOX-MARLINS-BO     06-28 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-REDSOX-MARLINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX FLATTEN SLOPPY MARLINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ At this point, sweeping the misbegotten Marlins becomes
secondary, especially when the Floridians are so accommodating,
adding missed pop flies to a repertoire that already includes wild
pitches, passed balls, and throwing errors.
</P>
<P>
   More important for the Red Sox, who made it two in a row over
the Marlins with a 9-4 win Saturday night and matched their
high-water mark of 16 games over .500 with their third straight
win, is to escape before a Florida pitcher inflicts bodily harm.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't as easy as it may sound. Reggie Jefferson, playing
first base in place of the injured Mo Vaughn, was drilled in the
back of the head by a fastball from Marlins rookie Jesus Sanchez in
the fifth inning. An inning later, Nomar Garciaparra, who earlier
extended his hitting streak to 19 games, was struck in the back by
a breaking ball from Marlins near-rookie Matt Mantei.
</P>
<P>
   And for coming attractions, the Red Sox Sunday have to face
another rookie, Ryan Dempster, who in just 24 2/3 innings already
ranks third in the league in hit batsmen with seven.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a danger any time you're throwing the ball inside and
don't know where it's going,'' said Red Sox starter Tim Wakefield,
who wasn't exactly the picture of control himself, walking five. He
ran his rec-ord to 9-3 by checking the Marlins on six hits in 7 2/3
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, until Wakefield walked pinch hitter Derrek Lee _ ball
four escaping catcher Jason Varitek for his second passed ball that
helped lead to Wakefield's exit in the eighth _ he'd walked only
one man, Todd Zeile, but did so all four times he faced him. Was he
pitching around the Marlins' cleanup hitter, one of the few Florida
players whose time in the big leagues can't be measured by the
second hand on a watch?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Wakefield said. ``I just couldn't throw him a strike. I
don't know why.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson apparently sustained nothing worse than a terrific
headache when Sanchez's fastball caught more of his helmet than his
head on an 0-and-1 count in the fifth. He sprawled face down in the
dirt before being assisted to a sitting position by trainer Jim
Rowe, then rose to his feet and walked off the field under his own
power. X-rays were negative, and Jefferson, who returned to the
team's hotel before the end of the game, was reported to be alert
and comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that Jefferson was OK allowed the Red Sox to turn their
attention after the game to the grievous offense committed by one
of their own: Reliever Jim Corsi, who batted for only the second
time in a major league career that began 10 years ago, broke
catcher Scott Hatteberg's bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the few chances in my whole life to get a big-league
knock,'' moaned Corsi, who grounded to third to end the eighth
inning. ``And I think Hattie's mad at me because I broke his bat.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, who singled home a run in the first, walked in the
third, and singled and scored in the fifth, was struck near the
shoulder blades by Mantei in the sixth. He became the third Red Sox
in two games to be hit by a pitch, as Lou Merloni was hit by rookie
Joe Fontenot Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The evening already had been an adventure for Jefferson, who
hasn't worn a glove all season and found leather to be an ill fit
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   With Vaughn nursing a strained hamstring, Jefferson found
himself at first base. He singled and doubled in his first two
at-bats against lefthander Sanchez after having had just 12 at-bats
against lefties this season.
</P>
<P>
   But he also made errors on two of the three ground balls hit his
way. Ryan Jackson's groundball skipped underneath his glove for an
error to open the second, and Cliff Floyd's high bouncer clanked
off his glove for another error in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Ashley, who had never played first base before signing
with the Red Sox and being given a first baseman's mitt in
Pawtucket, replaced Jefferson after his beaning and showed manos de
piedra (hands of stone), too, botching Todd Dunwoody's easy hopper
in the seventh. Seldom has Vaughn resembled a Gold Glove candidate
more than when compared to the alternatives on his own team.
</P>
<P>
   But the errors were of little consequence, especially on a night
when Marlins fielders were unable to detect falling objects out of
the sky. With the Red Sox already leading, 4-1, Marlins fielders
missed pop flies by consecutive hitters after Garciaparra lined a
single to open the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   That loaded the bases, and a run scored when Jefferson was hit
by Sanchez. ``Tough way to knock in a run,'' manager Jimy Williams
said. An easier time was had by Mike Benjamin, who drew a
bases-loaded walk from Sanchez's successor, Mantei, to make it 6-1
and Darren Lewis lined an RBI hit on an 0-and-2 pitch to make it
7-1.
</P>
<P>
   An artistic triumph, it wasn't. But Williams never was one for
style points, anyway. ``It was a good win for us, as far as I'm
concerned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On deck: a sweep. Strap on your helmets, and bring plenty of
aspirin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-98 0049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
