<HEADER>
A0569 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-GARCIAPARR     06-28 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-GARCIAPARRA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAR BERTH COULD ELUDE GARCIAPARRA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Even with All-Star rosters inflated to 30 players
because of the addition of two expansion teams, a deserving
shortstop is likely to be left off the American League team.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised if it's Nomar Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even think about it,'' said Garciaparra, who was an
All-Star selection as a Red Sox rookie and has come back from a
separated shoulder to post numbers that would seem to warrant a
return trip. ``That's not why I play.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra has a 19-game hitting streak, extending it Saturday
night with a run-scoring single in the first inning against the
Florida Marlins after having his first four-hit game of the season
in Friday night's 6-1 win over the Fish. Garciaparra is batting
.407 (33 for 81) during the streak, and in his last 10 games has 10
extra-base hits: five doubles, four home runs, and a triple.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra's streak is tied for longest in the American League
with streaks by Damion Easley of the Tigers and Carlos Delgado of
the Blue Jays, and it is within one game of matching Larry Walker
of the Rockies for longest streak in the majors. Already he's on
the second-longest streak of his brief career, eclipsed only by the
rookie-record 30-game streak he had last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask anybody who plays against the guy,'' teammate Lou Merloni
said, ``and they'll all say he should be on the team.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's a chance it won't work out that way.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Rodriguez of the Mariners is a runaway leader in the
voting, and deservedly so. Rodriguez is batting .319 and, with 26
home runs and 21 stolen bases, is on track to join Jose Canseco and
Barry Bonds as the only players with 40-40 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter of the Yankees has made just three errors in 62
games, is hitting ..312 with nine home runs, and has been mentioned
frequently as an MVP candidate on the best team in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Omar Vizquel, whose manager, Mike Hargrove, will be
managing the AL stars. Vizquel may be the best defensive shortstop
in the game. He entered Saturday's game with just one error in his
last 110 games, dating to Aug. 19, 1997. And the error he made was
on the easiest of plays, as he dropped a chest-high flip from
Indians second baseman David Bell on an attempted force play.
</P>
<P>
   Vizquel, who has won the Gold Glove in each of the last five
seasons, is the most spectacular of the shortstop candidates
defensively, a master at plucking bouncing balls out of midair with
his bare hand. Hargrove would be well within his rights to reward
one of his own with an All-Star selection.
</P>
<P>
   So, where does that leave Garciaparra? Rodriguez's offensive
numbers far outrank everyone else's, of course. But Garciaparra's
batting average is three percentage points higher than Jeter's,
..317 to .312, and the Sox shortstop has two more home runs and 9
more RBIs than his Yankee counterpart in virtually the same number
of games: Jeter 62, Garciaparra 61.
</P>
<P>
   The statistic in which Jeter has a clear edge is errors.
Garciaparra has made 10, one fewer than Rodriguez has made in 80
games and seven more than Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   But the way he is swinging the bat, Garciaparra almost certainly
will have much better numbers than he had at the break last season.
He already has more RBIs (48 to 44 at last year's break), nearly
the same number of home runs (11 to 13), and a significantly higher
batting average (.317 to .291).
</P>
<P>
   Merloni played with Garciaparra in the shortstop's first two pro
seasons, in 1994 with Sarasota and 1995 with Trenton. He's seen
quite an improvement. ``In the field, I don't think anything has
changed,'' Merloni said. ``He's still making the great plays he
always has. The biggest difference is obviously the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's gotten so much stronger and hitting the ball so much
harder. Saturday night, when he got his fourth hit, guys in the
dugout started laughing, he's just so on fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was in Double A and hitting .260, you'd figure he'd
improve, hit in the .285 range while his glove would take him
anywhere. But now he's got the all-around complete game. No matter
what they throw up there, he hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``How would I pitch him? I'd try to walk him. You know how
little he likes to walk.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
