<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BURN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION DROP 8TH STRAIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ A great start couldn't do it. The return of Joe-Max
Moore and Mike Burns from World Cup duty couldn't do it. Even
playing the struggling and usually good-for-what-ails-them Dallas
Burn couldn't do it.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution took leads of 2-0 and 3-1 Saturday night but
ended up falling to the Burn, 4-3, in a shootout at Foxboro
Stadium, running their losing streak to eight games with a
three-game road trip ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Revolution coach Thomas Rongen knew the Burn were missing a
couple of their top scorers. Knew the Revolution had beaten the
Burn the last six times they'd met. And knew the Burn were coming
in off a pair of 1-0 losses.
</P>
<P>
   And he still warned that the Burn were going to be tough. And
resilient.
</P>
<P>
   They certainly were.
</P>
<P>
   They weathered the early Revolution attack. Survived an own goal
in the ninth minute. Withstood the work of Moore, who set up a pair
of first-half goals, one a highlight-film score by Raul Diaz Arce
and the other a blast by Edwin Gorter that created a 3-1 Revolution
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good to come in here and steal one,'' said Dallas coach
David Dir. ``It seems we've had a couple stolen from us.''
</P>
<P>
   No one was more resilient for the Burn than defender Ted Eck. He
played a significant role in the Dallas comeback _ after helping
create the deficit. He was charged with the own goal when he, with
Ivan McKinley pressuring, headed the ball into the Burn net as he
tried to clear a nice Gorter corner kick.
</P>
<P>
   That goal, following the one by Arce, made it 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Kreis got one back for the Burn with a direct kick blast
after a handball call on Moore.
</P>
<P>
   Gorter's goal made it 3-1 before Dallas forward Damian answered
with some pretty footwork that got him by the Revolution defense
and keeper Ian Feuer. The Revolution thought Damian was offsides.
The goal cut it to 3-2 late in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   It was Eck who tied it at 3-3 with a blast in the 56th minute.
The Burn had taken over control of the play, and the Revolution
were having all sorts of problems in their own end until Eck
stepped up, collected an errant McKinley clear that bounced off the
referee, and buried the shot.
</P>
<P>
   And then it was Eck's goal in the shootout that finished off
Revolution and boosted the Burn to a win.
</P>
<P>
   Four Dallas players got their shootout attempts past Jeff
Causey, who came off the bench to replace Feuer late in the game.
New England's Imad Baba and Burns made their shots, too, but keeper
Mark Dodd stopped McKinley's shot and Moore's went wide of the net,
and the Burn had the 1 point for a shootout win.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution now must take their losing streak on the road.
They are at Kansas City on Wednesday, at Tampa Bay on Saturday, and
at Colorado July 11. Their next game at Foxboro Stadium is July 14
against D.C. United.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams had chances late in regulation to take the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Baba, a late substitution, set up an Arce header that went just
wide.
</P>
<P>
   The Burn also had a good chance, a Damian attempt that went wide
in the closing seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line, though, the Revolution jumped out on top and then
couldn't sustain it. They had chances to widen their lead, and
didn't do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we had the 3 points (for a win),'' Moore said. ``In
the first 15 minutes, you're up, two-nothing, and you should figure
out a way to win it at that point. Once again, we let the other
team back in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Rongen thought a turning point might have been in the opening
minutes of the second half, when, with the Revolution ahead, 3-2,
Gorter and Arce worked a pretty give-and-go in close but came up
with nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive failures tell only part of the story, though. With six
goals in their two games _ they lost to New York/-New Jersey, 5-3,
Wednesday _ the Revolution's focus is squarely on the defense and
consistency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six goals in two games, and you'd like to think that anywhere
in the world those will be two Ws,'' Rongen said. ``We're working
hard and we need to work on our defense. We're giving up too many
goals and we're giving up too many soft goals.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
