<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS DRAFT DEFENSEMEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Mighty Ducks could use some immediate help on defense as
they attempt to bounce back from a disastrous 1997-98 season.
</P>
<P>
   However, they may have laid the foundation of their defensive
future Saturday by selecting defensemen with their first two picks
in the 1998 NHL Entry Draft in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   With the fifth pick of the first round, the Ducks drafted Vitali
Vishnevsky, a 6-foot-2, 187-pound defenseman from the Ukraine. With
their second-round selection (No.32 overall), they chose 6-21/2,
205-pound defenseman Stephen Peat.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ducks assistant general manager David McNab admitted
both are probably two years away from contributing at the NHL
level, Vishnevsky and Peat are the type of players the Ducks lacked
last season.
</P>
<P>
   Vishnevsky, rated as the No.2 prospect in Europe by the NHL's
Central Scouting Service, is a two-way defenseman that can
quarterback a power play and still give the Ducks a much-needed
mean streak on the blue line. His style has been compared to Darius
Kasparaitis and Vladimir Konstantinov.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys thought he was, by far, the best player after the
first four,'' said McNab, who admitted the Ducks held out little
hope that one of the top two defensemen in the draft (Brad Stuart
and Bryan Allan) would fall to them. ``He's a playmaker. He doesn't
have a big shot, but he's very physical and that's what we like.
His courage level is at the very top.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Peat is ticketed for two years of junior league play,
the Ducks expect him to eventually provide Paul Kariya and Teemu
Selanne the type of protection they sorely missed last season. Peat
is a willing fighter and accumulated 189 penalty minutes in 63
games last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every player we interviewed in the Western Hockey League said
he was toughest guy in the league,'' said McNab of Peat, who played
for Red Deer. ``But we aren't just reaching for a tough guy. We
think he can be a decent player.''
</P>
<P>
   Numerous teams made offers for the Ducks' top pick -- one
rumored deal had Colorado sending defenseman Alexei Gusarov and
draft choices to Anaheim -- but McNab said no offer overwhelmed
them, despite the team's obvious need to fill holes quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``To move the fifth pick, especially when you can get somebody
you like, is really tough,'' he said. ``You have to get somebody
back who is pretty dynamic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
