</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRL-CHEEVER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEEVER AT HOME ON VICTORY LANE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; LOUDON, N.H. _ The local TV reporter from Manchester, N.H.,
had not yet posed his first question to Eddie Cheever Jr., winner
of the 82d Indianapolis 500, when the driver anticipated it during
an interview Friday afternoon at New Hampshire International
Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me guess,'' Cheever joked. ``What do you want to talk
about?''
</P>
<P>
   Surely, Cheever thought, his victory at Indy would be the topic
of conversation.
</P>
<P>
   But the TV reporter took a different tack. Instead of asking the
obvious, he wanted to know Cheever's thoughts on other matters. On
his visit to NHIS for Sunday's Pep Boys Indy Racing League New
England 200: ``It's a great place to come to race; it's like a
mini-Indy, because the configuration of the corners are very
similar.'' The competitiveness of the IRL series: ``It's probably
the most competitive year I've had in racing, anywhere.'' And the
challenges of being an IRL owner/-driver: ``I'm having a really
great season, obviously, after having won the Indianapolis 500.
Robby Unser, our second driver, ran a strong fifth at Indy, we've
got a new sponsor for him, and our cars are running very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Three questions had been asked. None had pertained to the
biggest victory of Cheever's career. That's when the 40-year-old
Cheever deftly steered the conversation to the Indy 500 _ by
broaching the subject himself. It was, perhaps, the first time
since he's won the Greatest Spectacle in Racing that he's done so
in an interview. Ah, but it is only part of the territory that
comes with being an Indy 500 winner.
</P>
<P>
   There are numerous demands. The media requests. The photo ops.
Sponsor obligations. Corporate hospitality. Driver appearances.
Autograph sessions. And, oh yes, the occasional TV interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always expect the first question to be about Indy _
always,'' Cheever said, smiling broadly after he won $1.4 million
for his first career triumph. ``I've talked more about Indy in the
last month than I have anything in my whole life.'' Then, launching
into an imaginary, one-sided interview, he added, ```Yes, it feels
very good to be an Indy 500 winner.' `No, I have not spent all the
money.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an honor given to very few and I've raced for a very long
time and I thought I had done just about everything, but being an
Indy 500 winner is very special. It's special because it's such an
important part of America's sporting history every year. So many
people recognize it. You know who won the Kentucky Derby. You know
who won the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   And everyone knows now that Eddie Cheever Jr. won the 82d Indy
500.
</P>
<P>
   But they may not have realized the odds Cheever faced when his
primary sponsor, FirstPlus, opted to commit its resources to the
fledgling Winston Cup partnership of Bill Elliott and Dan Marino.
Cheever, however, pulled all the pieces together, landing a sponsor
in Rachel's Potato Chips, and assembling a crack crew headed by
experienced crew chief Owen Synder, and a talented apprentice
driver in Unser, the youngest son of Bobby Unser.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I jokingly told him, if I got any Unser luck in me, then
some of it probably rubbed off on him,'' said Robby Unser, who will
unveil a new Dallara this weekend at NHIS. ``But, for me, it was an
amazing experience to be a part of it in my first time at Indy.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Cheever, ``Robby did such a great job at Indy. When he got
out on the oval, it was like a duck to water. He's an Unser, which
just proves that _ genetically _ Unsers are different. They just
know ovals.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, when Cheever first began racing on the worldwide
stage of the Formula One circuit almost 20 years ago, he had
romanticized visions of winning Monaco in May, not Indy. Though
born in Phoenix and now residing in Tampa, Cheever grew up in Italy
knowing of only one series _ Formula One _ and its most glittering
street circuit, Monte Carlo. But, as his father counseled him, if
there was one race to win, it was Indy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day I won it, I wasn't really quite sure what happened,''
said Cheever, who fought off the demons of his past failures at
Indy to win going away from runner-up Buddy Lazier, the 1996 Indy
500 champ. ``I mean, I'm not an idiot. I knew I won the Indy 500,
but it takes a while to sink in. But the best recollection I had
was when I woke up that (next) morning, it was almost like waking
up the day after Christmas when you're a little kid, and you find
those presents are all still there and they haven't taken them
away. So it was exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, another present _ a victory here at NHIS _ had been
taken away. Cheever led twice for 80 laps in the Pennzoil 200 but
fell out of the lead with three laps to go when his gearbox failed.
It ushered Robbie Buhl to his first career IRL triumph. It was but
one chapter in Cheever's well-documented tome of hard luck that had
kept him winless in 133 Formula One starts and 81 starts on the
CART circuit.
</P>
<P>
   That was why winning Indy was such a liberating experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I've got a big load off my shoulders now,'' Cheever said.
``I got so tired of people telling me, `you didn't win a Formula
One race.' It almost sounded like I was playing tiddlywinks or
something. I was a Formula One driver. To those who criticized,
well, feel free to go over there and try to do it. Michael
(Andretti) tried to do it, and he's an exceptional driver, but he
didn't succeed. Danny (Sullivan) tried it and he didn't succeed. I
was probably a little too thin-skinned with people saying I hadn't
won an F1 race, which wasn't false, but it wasn't as if I wasn't
busy doing something worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been very lucky. The other day somebody told me that I'd
been extremely unlucky. But I disagreed. I think I've been very
lucky. I started racing go-karts when I was 13 years old. I had no
idea I'd become an Indy 500 winner. I wouldn't have even dreamed of
it, much less being the only American driver on the Grand Prix for
10 years. Yeah, I've lost a lot of races in the last minute, but I
did with my life what I wanted to.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cheever, who is fluent in three languages, found the
words hard to come by when he was asked to describe the emotions he
felt immediately after the race. ``It was impossible,'' he said.
``I've had a hard time over the years when things have gone bad to
stay motivated. You keep thinking, `Well, the next race will be
better; I'll win the next one.' And after a while you start to
believe it's not going to happen, so not until I had actually
finished the Indy 500 had I realized I'd won. I kept thinking,
`Well, next corner it'll stop. Next straightaway, it's gonna
break.' But when it didn't, I was almost incredulous. How can they
take it away now?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so glad this happened in a latter part in my career
instead of an earlier part of my career, because I wouldn't have
enjoyed it as much as I am now. I savor ever race I do now. I have
more races behind me than I have ahead of me, so every time I
drive, I drive with a smile on my face.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because Cheever has finally validated himself as a driver
_ ``an American driver,'' he intoned _ as a winner of the Indy 500.
</P>
<P>
   No questions asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-98 0055EDT &QL; 
