<HEADER>
A0574 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHLDRAFT-BOS &LR;      06-28 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAFT DAY NO BIG DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
 DRAFT-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BUFFALO _ The National Hockey League's entry draft, the annual
taffy pull that turns teenagers into millionaires and can turn
franchises upside down, rightside up, or stuck in the neutral zone,
went off here Saturday with little fanfare.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Lecavalier, touted as the game's next Mario Lemieux, was
selected first overall by the Tampa Bay Lightning. Only moments
later, the Lightning's new owner, Art Williams, touted the
6-foot-4-inch, 180-pound center as hockey's ``Michael Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   And if that wasn't enough Air from Williams, he also said that
Lecavalier was a ``sure-fire Hall-of-Famer.'' Williams, an
insurance magnate who only Thursday received league approval to
purchase the Bolts, tempered the Hall of Fame statement by saying
that he didn't know a lot about hockey and was learning the game
as, ``I go along.''
</P>
<P>
   Hockey 101: Talk a good game, even if you can't carry a stick.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, who gave up their first-round draft pick more than
18 months ago when they acquired Landon Wilson and Anders Myrvold
from the Avalanche, had to sit on their hands for some 3 1/2 hours
before making their first pick. The new Bostonian to be is Jonathan
Girard, a 5-11 1/2 defenseman from Laval in the Quebec League, born
May 27, 1980 _ just days before another Quebecer, Ray Bourque, was
named the NHL's rookie of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The draft, held the same Saturday every June, will come to
Boston next year and officially make Our Town the Hub of Hockey.
Two members of the FleetCenter's administration, Chris Maher and Ed
Krayer, were on hand at Marine Midland Arena, taking pictures and
making notes in preparation of the event coming some 450 miles east
next summer.
</P>
<P>
   If you're booking early, the NHL typically doesn't charge
admission to the draft. There isn't a lot of action, other than the
elbowing and jousting that occurs on the floor between the general
managers, who sit surrounded by staff members at tables that in
Boston will be spread out across the FleetCenter's floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're excited, it's a great event,'' said Maher, after
snapping pictures of press row shortly before the draft began. ``It
should tie in nicely with the Bruins' 75th anniversary year. It
gets people into the arena and keeps hockey on everyone's mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The league was expected Saturday to announce Boston as the host
city of next year's event, but official word was not forthcoming.
One source suggested that contract language had to be finalized.
The event is never a moneymaker for the host club or arena, but
does provide a boost to the local economy. A league official
estimated some 7,000 hotel rooms would be needed to accommodate the
NHL and individual club staff, media, agents, players, and their
family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   If you're already renting out your house next summer for
baseball's All-Star Game and the Ryder Cup, you might as well copy
another key for a week in June.
</P>
<P>
   Deals are usually the order of the day at the draft, but there
wasn't much of a trading wave here on the shore of Lake Erie.
Nashville jiggled up one spot, trading places with San Jose, and
selected speedy center Jeff Legwand with the No. 2 overall pick.
The Flyers unloaded smooth-skating but aging Paul Coffey on the
Blackhawks for a fifth-round draft pick. Coffey immediatley agreed
to a two-year contract with Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers and the Avalanche were at the center of the first
round's only interesting moment. Neil Smith, boss of the Broadway
Blueshirts, could be seen on the telephone, haggling with Colorado
general manager Pierre Lacroix. Think they were trading bon mots
over the Rangers trying to steal away Joe Sakic last summer with a
three-year deal that cost Colorado $21 million to match?
</P>
<P>
   Smith talked calmly into the phone. Lacroix was more animated.
The clock ran. NHL commissioner Gary Bettman implored the Rangers
to make their pick. Finally, the Rangers called time out.
</P>
<P>
   ``This better be good,'' a leatherlung in the balcony yelled,
his voice echoing among the crowd of some 8,000.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing of note happened. Smith calmly walked to the podium
and selected 6-2 center Manny Malhorta from the Ontario Hockey
League. Colorado continued on and made its four picks in the first
round, including 6-3 defenseman Robyn Regeher at No. 19, the pick
acquired from the Bruins. That trade now should read: Wilson and
Myrvold for Regeher.
</P>
<P>
   Who will turn out to be the impact player of the '98 draft? The
slick, skilled Lecavalier has the best chance. Tampa Bay coach
Jacques Demers, who works for Williams, wasn't slinging the same
hyperbole over Lecavalier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important to bring him along slowly,'' said
Demers. ``Vincent Lecavalier is not coming to Tampa to save the
franchise. We're no longer the last-placed team in the NHL, and the
reason for that is we went out and picked up Craig Janney (from
Phoenix) and Bill Ranford (from Washington). We're a better team. I
liked how the Bruins brought along Joe Thornton last year. I think
Pat Burns did a great job with him. He played some games. He didn't
play some games. When the playoffs came along, Joe Thornton looked
pretty good out there.''
</P>
<P>
   It all begins for Lecavalier in September when training camp
opens. He'll be the hottest 18-year-old in Tampa since, well, since
the Lightning made Roman Hamrlik the No. 1 pick in '92. Hamrlik now
laces 'em up for the Oilers. And so it goes.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, they're just kids. Thornton lived with a Brookline
family last season, in keeping with how junior players in Canada
live with their billet families. Demers has a son about
Lecavalier's age, and initial plans are for the young phenom to
live at the coach's house. Only in hockey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
