<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRASS SECTION DUE FOR AN OVERHAUL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fred Claire is not ready to retire. The Dodgers fired him as
their general manager last week, but Claire isn't ready to end a
30-year baseball career and wants another opportunity at running a
baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   He may get that chance. So, too, may some of the good young
assistants in the game like Minnesota's Wayne Krivsky, Florida's
Frank Wren, Cleveland's Dan O'Dowd, the New York Mets' Omar Minaya,
the Chicago White Sox's Dan Evans and the Rangers' Dan O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   Looking around baseball, there could be as many as 11 general
manager jobs changing hands between now and the start of spring
training. Some are more likely than others, and all depend on what
happens in the second half of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The rundown:
</P>
<P>
   Arizona _ Joe Garagiola Jr. does the job now, a reward for
helping bring baseball to Phoenix. But he'll probably move upstairs
in the next year or two and let Sandy Johnson, the Rangers' former
scouting director, take over. Johnson does most of the work now.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago Cubs _ Ed Lynch's job security may hang on what he does
to keep the Cubs in the pennant race. He had a good off-season, but
the Cubs still need help.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago White Sox _ The team is a disaster area. At some point,
Ron Schueler has to take the blame.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati _ The Reds don't have much money, but Jim Bowden has
not done well through drafting and player development. This
franchise has been on a downward spiral since getting lucky in
winning a division title in 1995, and there's absolutely no sign of
things getting turned around soon.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado _ The Rockies have been a major disappointment, and
it's only a question of who takes the fall: general manager Bob
Gebhard or manager Don Baylor. Maybe both.
</P>
<P>
   Florida _ Dave Dombrowski will likely abandon baseball's Titanic
and have his pick of what is available. The Dodgers are a strong
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles _ Tommy Lasorda is supposedly just the interim GM,
but he'll likely pull every Machiavellian maneuver possible to keep
the job.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore _ Owner Peter Angelos keeps Pat Gillick handcuffed,
and baseball's absolutely best general manager will likely decide
he has had enough at the end of the season. The question is if
assistant Kevin Malone goes with him or takes over.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City _ Herk Robinson will likely be forced out once the
Royals get a new owner. But nobody really knows when that will be.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle _ On one hand, Woody Woodward has built two division
champions in the past three years, which was a big improvement for
the Mariners. But he has also made several bad trades, and a
last-place finish behind the rebuilding Oakland Athletics would be
embarrassing. He may be allowed to retire gracefully.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto _ Gord Ash has made several good moves in trying to get
the Blue Jays back into contention, and they're still on the
periphery of the wild-card chase. They just haven't been able to
get their younger players going yet. He deserves more time.
\Nrailhed:The Wonder Dog It was a sad day for baseball Wednesday
when the Phillies released outfielder Rex Hudler, who is 37 and
batting just .122. All signs suggest he can no longer play, but
that doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   Rex ``The Wonder Dog'' Hudler is a joy and a treat to everybody
he comes across, one of the truly great people in baseball. Just
look at what happened when he was released.
</P>
<P>
   First, he performed his own interview for Comcast SportsNet, the
all-sports television station that carries Phillies games. Then, he
broke down in tears talking about what a pleasure it was to hear
fans thank him for signing autographs along the first-base line.
</P>
<P>
   He also thanked the Phillies for all they had done for him.
Then, after saying his goodbyes to his teammates, Hudler walked
across the Phillies' clubhouse and hugged Jon Zuber, the man who
had just taken his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only Hud,'' Zuber said.
Rocketing to 300
</P>
<P>
   When Roger Clemens pitched seven innings against the Expos on
Wednesday, it gave him 366 2/3 innings in 50 starts with the Blue
Jays. That's notable because he has an option in his three-year
contract for a fourth season if he pitches 360 innings in his first
two years _ with at least 190 this season _ or if he makes 55
starts in 1997-98. It looks like he'll make good on both.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's victory was also the 221st of his career. If
Clemens, who will turn 36 on Aug. 4, can stay healthy and
effective, he has a shot at 300 career wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year, I get closer; my wife \RDebra\S has mentioned
she'd like me to take a chance at it, if my body can do it,''
Clemens said. ``It's an attainable goal if I pitched till I was 40,
41, but I don't want to blink, come home and my two oldest boys are
headed to college. I went to Nolan Ryan's retirement dinner, and he
had one boy in college and another going in. Koby and Kory
\RClemens' two oldest sons\S like having their dad around and I
like going to their football games.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting 300 victories should not determine if Clemens is a Hall
of Famer. He should have clinched that last year when he won his
fourth Cy Young Award.
Dream team
</P>
<P>
   Let the fans pick the All-Star teams. This is my dream team, the
absolute best at their positions: C _ Ivan Rodriguez 1B _ Mark
McGwire 2B _ Craig Biggio SS _ Alex Rodriguez 3B _ Scott Rolen LF _
Barry Bonds CF _ Ken Griffey Jr. RF _ Juan Gonzalez P _ Greg Maddux
THE BUZZ
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees took three of four from the Atlanta Braves
last week, confirming what most people suspected. The 1998 baseball
season boils down to whether anybody can beat the Yankees. ...
Braves general manager John Schuerholz said he expects Mark Wohlers
to return to form and won't trade for a closer. ... Twins second
baseman Todd Walker, who was hitting .342 going into the weekend,
was a 51st-round pick by the Rangers in 1991 out of Bossier City,
La. The Rangers offered him $25,000, but he decided to go to
Louisiana State instead. ... The Dodgers need a closer and will
probably take a hard run at Reds closer Jeff Shaw, who is
overlooked but one of the best. ... Davey Lopes might finally get a
chance: He's being mentioned as a candidate for the Dodgers manager
next year. ...
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Royals had hoped to have a new owner by the
All-Star break, but the process has been delayed by at least three
months. Chiefs owner Lamar Hunt is one bidder, so is a group headed
by Royals great George Brett. But Brett's group has yet to offer
the minimum $75 million. ... Things are looking up for the
Pittsburgh Pirates. They just about have the funding in place for a
new ballpark in 2001. They also have the young talent coming
quickly that would make the ballpark a success. Brewers manager
Phil Garner says the Pirates have the best pitching staff in either
league, and highly touted Kris Benson is still in the minors. ...
</P>
<P>
   White Sox pitcher Jason Bere, who is 3-7 with a 6.34 earned-run
average, is demanding a trade now that manager Jerry Manuel has
dropped him from the rotation. Who would want him as a starter? ...
Reds hitting coach Ken Griffey left the team for one day Monday,
angry over a lack of respect. He came back Tuesday and one of his
complaints was getting pinch-hit for by manager Sparky Anderson,
when Griffey's batting average was over .300. This show of
disrespect happened in 1975. Hmmmm. ... Orioles manager Ray Miller,
fed up with his bullpen, is ready to dump veterans Norm Charlton
and Terry Mathews. ...
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers have benched Joe Randa and are going with rookie Gave
Alvarez at third base. He was acquired from the Arizona
Diamondbacks in November and had 20 homers and 58 runs batted in at
Triple-A Toledo. ... Paul Molitor went on the disabled list for the
14th time in his career when a Matt Karchner pitch nailed him in
the left rib cage. Said Molitor, ``I'm just trying to figure out
why those kinds of things don't happen to \RCal\S Ripken. Then
again, he'd probably be playing tomorrow. He'd probably hit
left-handed.'' ... The St. Louis Cardinals, desperate for pitching,
asked about Oakland left-hander Kenny Rogers but were told he
wasn't available. ... Oakland outfielder Ben Grieve of Arlington
has been invited to the All-Star game to compete in the rookie home
run derby, but said, ``I'm terrible in those things. I'm a combined
0-for-20. I did one in Huntsville \RDouble A\S and one in high
school.'' ... Phillies manager Terry Francona called Atlanta
manager Bobby Cox last week to talk about the All-Star Game and
lobby on behalf of his players. He forgot that Florida's Jim
Leyland will manage the team. ...
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies lack the pitching needed to stay in the wild-card
race, but this team is making progress, mainly because of two
off-season trades. They dealt second baseman Mickey Morandini to
the Cubs for center fielder Doug Glanville (.316) and sent
shortstop Kevin Stocker to the Devil Rays for Bob Abreu (.329). ...
The Padres' ability to handle injuries has given them an edge over
the Giants. The Padres went 10-3 while Tony Gwynn was sidelined
with injuries while the Giants are 5-10 without second baseman Jeff
Kent, who may be gone for at least three more weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
