<SLUG> BC-BOB-HOPE-LANDGRAB-2takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOB HOPE'S PROPERTIES BLANKET L.A.'S SAN FERNANDO VALLEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALEX ROTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the years after Bob Hope and Bing Crosby filmed
their classic ``Road'' pictures, the inseparable friends hiked up
to China Flat, a rugged bluff overlooking the suburban San Fernando
Valley, Calabasas and west to Malibu.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the Beverly Hills of tomorrow,'' Crosby boldly
predicted to his golfing buddy that day.
</P>
<P>
   Trusting Crosby's instincts and his own, Hope bought some of
that land. And as his career grew, he continued to buy and buy and
buy. Land near the ocean. Land in the Valley. Land that was empty
and flat. Mountainous land with goats and California walnut trees.
The way some people collect stamps or rare coins, Bob Hope
collected property.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always been very careful in spotting property,'' his
daughter, Linda Hope, said in an interview last week. ``He's always
had a real good nose for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Long a place where Hollywood's famous have chosen to live, the
Valley and outlying areas also are where many entertainment figures
have chosen to invest, and among them Hope is one of the first,
best-known _ and one of the biggest.
</P>
<P>
   In the days when the Valley was farmland and chaparral, Hope
gobbled up huge swaths, always with an eye for a profit. The
95-year-old comedian has since sold much of his holdings, except
the Toluca Lake estate he has owned since 1939. Yet even today,
Hope's fingerprints remain all over the Valley because of astute
decisions he made decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   A comprehensive list of what Hope has bought and sold over the
past six decades is impossible to reconstruct, but his real estate
dealings have included Jordan Ranch, a 3,050-home development being
built in neighboring Ventura County; part of Universal Studios, a
deal that made him a 600 percent profit; a sludge farm in nearby
Las Virgenes; and a nature preserve in Thousand Oaks, in Ventura
County.
</P>
<P>
   For a short period, an entire community bore his name. There
still is a street in Burbank named after him. And down the road he
owns a small plot on which his wife has talked about building a new
museum for the veteran entertainer and other famous comedians. With
an assessed value of $1.8million, it might be the most valuable
Christmas tree lot in America.
</P>
<P>
   In suburban Santa Clarita, Hope once owned property that's now
the site of the Friendly Valley Recreational Association, a
1,247-home senior residential community.
</P>
<P>
   His legacy also includes hundreds of acres of some of the most
beautiful open space. The irony is that Hope's priority was
business, not the environment. When Hope looked at empty land, he
tended to see golf courses and expensive homes. But by the time he
decided to liquidate much of his real estate portfolio, interest
groups wouldn't permit development without significant concessions
_ usually in the form of huge swaths of land.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now the Las Virgenes Valley has a certain beauty and
integrity,'' said Dave Brown, a former chairman of the Calabasas
Planning Commission. ``That probably wasn't Bob Hope's intention,
but that was the effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Hope's interest in the region began with his decision in 1939 to
buy the Toluca Lake home. It wasn't because he appreciated the
beauty of this still-idyllic section of the Valley, however. Linda
Hope said her father settled there for a simple reason: He liked
the Lakeside country club.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the proximity to Lakeside _ and it was near Bing's
place,'' she said. ``They could get off work quickly and head over
to the golf course.''
</P>
<P>
   As Hope's career grew, so did his real estate portfolio. The
task of seeking out buyable land fell largely into the hands of his
older brother, Jim.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would call me and say, `There's a couple of hundred acres
on so-and-so and so-and-so,''' Hope recalled in a 1993 interview
with the Daily News. ``And I'd say, `How much?' He'd say, `$250 an
acre.' And I'd say, `Buy it!'''
</P>
<P>
   Hope remembered buying a 35-acre chunk of land in North
Hollywood for $16,500. He later sold it to Universal Studios for
$1million.
</P>
<P>
   Another notable Hope holding was Corriganville _ or Hope Town,
as some people still call it. The land used to be the Corriganville
Movie Ranch, a famous set for western films and later a tourist
attraction. Hope bought it in 1966 when it fell on hard times.
</P>
<P>
   He renamed it Hope Town, but closed it after a year. Decades
later he sold it for $4.6million to a developer who planned a Hope
Town subdivision. Another developer took over and the subdivision
went through. The name, however, didn't stick.
</P>
<P>
   Several public agencies later acquired a piece of the land, and
in May a new Corriganville Park officially reopened. Nature trails,
a camping area and a revitalized western movie set are all future
possibilities for the land, said Michael Kuhn, senior planner in
Simi Valley, in neighboring Ventura County.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the acres of land Hope has owned, one of the most
intriguing pieces is a weed-covered parcel the size of a parking
lot. Sitting across the street from NBC's ``Tonight Show'' studio,
it is one of the few parcels of Los Angeles County real estate Hope
still possesses.
</P>
<P>
   For years there's been talk of putting a Hope-related museum on
the site, which sits on prime commercial real estate. Linda Hope
says the family is talking to museum consultants about creating a
shrine to prominent 20th-century comics. A restaurant and
improvisational theater also are possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the lot lies vacant, except for pumpkin sales on
Halloween and Christmas tree sales during the holidays. It's been
empty for decades, and residents near the NBC studios like it that
way. It serves as a buffer between the tourist-crammed studio and
the homes of the industry's blue-collar types.
</P>
<P>
   ``It keeps them over there and us over here,'' said Tim
Callahan, 28, an audio engineer for a post-production company.
</P>
<P>
   (2ND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Hope's most vast holdings were in the scenic, mountainous
terrain in western Los Angeles and eastern Ventura counties _ land
filled with oak trees, goats, bobcats and monkeyflowers.
</P>
<P>
   One such piece is the Micor site, named for a company that
wanted to develop it. As with some of his other holdings, Hope
figured it would become a ritzy development. Instead, it will
remain mostly open space.
</P>
<P>
   Hope owned most of the land and sold it roughly a decade ago to
a young, energetic developer. Among the people who invested money
in the project through their business managers were actress
Meredith Baxter, polio vaccine inventor Jonas Salk and actor George
Wendt, who played Norm on the TV show ``Cheers.'' The plan was to
turn the area into a gated community with million-dollar homes.
</P>
<P>
   An environmental group sued, the developer went bust and three
public agencies bought up 690 acres for $4million. Richland
Calabasas Ltd., which acquired the remaining 225 acres for
$3million, has filed a lawsuit demanding the right to push forward
with plans to build 200 luxury homes of the ``million-dollar-plus
variety,'' said Steve Thurtle, the company's vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the lawsuit's outcome, the 690 acres of public
land will remain as a trail-lined natural preserve.
</P>
<P>
   Hope also owned the adjacent land, now the site of a sludge farm
and composting facility. The Las Virgenes Municipal Water District
took the land in 1983 through condemnation proceedings.
Unfortunately for the water district, &UR;  &LR; the law requires a jury to
decide the land's value. When Hope showed up in court, his mere
presence created such a sensation with jurors that the judge
politely asked him to leave.
</P>
<P>
   The jury awarded Hope roughly $6.5million, which according to
one magazine article was double the land's appraised value.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the developers who bought Hope's land have been less
successful than others. The Zuckerman project in particular has had
a run of bad karma.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, developer Robert Zuckerman paid Hope $9.25million for
207 acres where he planned to build a shopping center and 75
large-estate homes. In the past decade, the proposal has gone
through at least 50 versions. The developer and the county still
haven't agreed on a final one. Residents fear congestion and want
to preserve the bucolic hillsides.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never worked on a more political project in my entire
life,'' said Jeff Kaplinski, the developer's project manager.
</P>
<P>
   The nearby Currey-Riach development has met with much better
luck. The project was born in 1980 when developers paid Hope
$10.3million for the land. The funnyman sold it as part of a
rolling, 10-year plan to unload most of his real estate holdings,
said Erwin Boychenko, Currey-Riach's vice president of finance.
</P>
<P>
   The land, now part of Calabasas, contains 462 single-family
homes, 600 apartments and 282 condominiums.
</P>
<P>
   The mother of all Hope-related developments is Ahmanson Ranch.
And it also is one with a particularly tortured history.
</P>
<P>
   The Ventura County project has its genesis in Hope's dream of
selling Jordan Ranch, his 2,300-acre holding near the Simi Hills,
to developers who would turn it into a Professional Golfers'
Association course. Several years, lawsuits, public hearings and
environmental protests later, the project has evolved into a plan
to build a massive development farther to the east _ also on land
once owned by Hope.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the project moved closer to realization when
developers closed a deal to buy two ranches from Hope, one near
Simi Valley and the other near Malibu. No sale price was disclosed,
but estimates have placed the combined value of the two parcels at
$30million.
</P>
<P>
   Developers envision a $1billion mini-city with 3,050 homes, two
schools, two golf courses and a 300-room hotel. Under the deal,
thousands of acres will remain open space under the control of the
Santa Monica Mountains Conservacy.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan Ranch, meanwhile, is now preserved as public parkland. In
1993, the conservancy paid Hope $16.7million for the land and gave
it to the National Park Service.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hope's real estate sales have generated millions of
dollars, he's given some land away for free. One 320-acre piece in
Thousand Oaks is called the Hope Los Robles Open Space. Hope
donated it in 1976 to the Conejo Open Space Conservation Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who hikes the oak-grove-covered trails _ a habitat for
deer, coyote, gray foxes and badgers _ should say a silent thanks
to the famous funnyman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say his perspicacity in picking the most beautiful
lands that cry out to have park signs on them is remarkable,'' said
Rorie Skei, who chairs the agency. ``He had an eye for beautiful
property, that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
