<HEADER>
A0579 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-BRAZIL-CHILE-BOS &LR;      06-28 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-BRAZIL-CHILE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL TAKES THE OFFENSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ At least one Western leader knows how to pick a winner.
Fidel Castro recently said he favored Brazil to win the World Cup,
prompting a Portuguese newspaper to speculate that President
Clinton would be cheering for Chile Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   If so, Clinton would have felt the disappointment of millions of
Chileans, who had hoped their team could pull off an upset but
watched Brazil win, 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   This game was supposed to be a scoring duel between some of the
highest-priced strikers in the world: Brazil's Ronaldo and Chile's
Ivan Zamorano, his teammate at Inter of Milan, and Marcelo Salas.
But the match was decided on scores by Cesar Sampaio, a defensive
midfielder who has scored as many goals as Ronaldo in the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Sampaio's offensive production opened the game, and Ronaldo
scored twice, and hit the post and crossbar in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil, which will meet Denmark or Nigeria in Nantes Friday,
appeared much more committed than it had in a 2-1 loss to Norway.
That was partially the result of a return to the regular starting
lineup, but mostly because of a team meeting that restored Dunga to
the role of motivator/organizer.
</P>
<P>
   Dunga seems determined to be a part of the first team to win
repeat World Cups since the legendary Brazilian teams of 1958 and
'62. He had been urged to be more diplomatic after berating Bebeto
during a 3-0 thrashing of Morocco in Nantes June 16, but his
passivity contributed to the Norway failing.
</P>
<P>
   Dunga was more vocally aggressive in this contest. And, he
contributed to the first goal with a curling free kick.
</P>
<P>
   Sampaio's second World Cup goal was similar to his first, scored
in the third minute of the tournament against Scotland. Sampaio
slipped through a mass of players to head in a Dunga kick in the
11th minute. Brazil's aggressiveness had paid off, as Rivaldo was
pulled down by Fernando Cornejo to set up the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a bit nervous at the start, but once we settled down
the team showed its experience,'' said Brazil coach Mario Zagallo.
``Then the goals came.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't stop until the final.''
</P>
<P>
   Chile continually sent high crosses toward Salas and Zamorano.
But Brazil limited those chances by controlling possession and
attacking patiently, rather than retreating onto defense with a
siege mentality.
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldo, who was to have become more involved in the offense,
seldom found room until the second half. But he played an important
part in the second goal, capitalizing on an errant pass by Cornejo,
who immediately fouled him on the right side, 30 yards from goal.
Roberto Carlos's 27th-minute free kick rebounded off Rivaldo,
standing next to the Chilean defensive wall, and went to the left
of goal to Bebeto, who rolled a perfect pass across the top of the
penalty area for Sampaio to blast a low shot into the left side of
the goal.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil soon clinched the victory. Goalkeeper Nelson Tapia tried
to cut down Ronaldo's angle, but cut down Ronaldo, who drilled the
penalty off Tapia's left hand in the 47th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Leonardo demonstrated the Brazilians' increased motivation when
he departed on a stretcher while French referee Marc Batta held a
yellow card over his body, four minutes into injury time, after a
collision with Miguel Ramirez near the halfway line.
</P>
<P>
   MetroStars' midfielder Marcelo Vega and Toluco's Fabian Estay
entered in the second half as Chile rallied. Zamorano headed off
goalkeeper Claudio Taffarel's chest. Salas took the rebound on the
first bounce and headed in midway through the half.
</P>
<P>
   But Ronaldo scored again less than a minute later after Denilson
drew the defense and laid off to the right. Ronaldo held the ball
until Tapia committed, then shot low to the far corner.
</P>
<P>
   Chile should consider its first fi-nals appearance since 1982
successful, but, except for Zamorano, the team exhibited little
confidence, even noting that South Americans consider Brazil
practically unbeatable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, we can say this is the end of a dream, not of a
nightmare,'' said Zamorano.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
