<HEADLINE>
LOCKOUT LOOMS 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ Paul Pierce will have a party Monday in southern
California to celebrate his upcoming rite of passage to the NBA.
Ordinarily, he'd board a plane the next day for Boston to see the
city, meet the press, hold up the uniform for the obligatory photo
shoot, and walk the soon-to-be hallowed floors of the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   That won't happen.
</P>
<P>
   We're going to have to wait a while to see Paul Pierce in the
flesh. While a lot of reasons factor into the decision not to come
east, there's one that supersedes all others. Pierce would no
sooner arrive here than he'd be forced to turn around and go
elsewhere. That's because at midnight, Tuesday, the Stern Curtain
will descend on the NBA and Paul Pierce will be as accessible to
the Boston Celtics as J.D. Salinger.
</P>
<P>
   We're already bored by the details of the impending lockout.
Imagine how boring it is to write about it and try to make it
interesting. There's a hard cap, a soft cap. There's the Larry Bird
exception and the Early Bird exception. The owners want protection
against themselves. The already obscenely rich players want more
for themselves. Where have we seen this before?
</P>
<P>
   There is one issue that hasn't been raised, however, which is at
the bottom of the whole, unseemly mess: the guaranteed contract.
There's absolutely no reason why the NBA should continue this
absurd practice of guaranteeing virtually every single contract.
There's also no chance that the players will settle for anything
less.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to believe that the NBA could take a cue from the NFL,
but it could and should. Less than one percent of NFL contracts are
guaranteed. Players get their money in signing bonuses, but if they
don't perform, they're gone and their salary comes off the books.
</P>
<P>
   Why should NBA rookies get 3-5 years guaranteed money when
there's no guarantee they can play? Why should Rick Pitino or any
other coach be handcuffed by guaranteed contracts for players who
can't play, won't play, or want to be elsewhere, but can't be
moved?
</P>
<P>
   Elimination of guaranteed contracts won't do anything but make
the players earn their money _ which will be there to be dispensed
_ while giving management flexibility to make changes. Somehow,
despite not having guaranteed deals, NFL players perform, get paid
handsomely, live comfortably, and life goes on. In the meantime,
when someone like Bill Parcells arrives and doesn't like what he
sees, he can make the changes he feels he needs to make.
</P>
<P>
   If you establish a hard cap at a percentage of revenues about
where it is now or slightly higher, establish a minimum that every
team must spend, and allow management to create cap room by waiving
players with non-guaranteed deals, you'd see a few things. There'd
be fewer teams able to use the cap as an alibi. There'd be more
player movement. There'd be accountability at both ends.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it won't happen. The union won't concede that having
players earn their money _ as oppose to having it handed to them
based on potential _ is a valid concept. It will point to the
average career being so short, leaving the players not much time to
make money. What the union will ignore is that the players who
deserve to be in the league do stick around and do get theirs. It's
the other ones who freeload off the system _ and you don't have to
go far down any roster, especially Boston's, to identify who they
are.
</P>
<P>
   The owners appear to be as determined as ever to right the ship
that they are responsible for almost sinking. Come Wednesday, the
battle begins in earnest. Guarantees or games, which do you want?
That's what the owners should ask.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas entourage flew out of Texas Thursday, destination
Germany. There,  &UR; Don  &LR; and  &UR; Donnie Nelson  &LR; and owner  &UR; Ross Perot
Jr. &LR;  will start the courtship of  &UR; Dirk Nowitzki &LR; . How do you say
``full-court press'' in German? Pitino was confident he could have
had Nowitzki in a Boston uniform this fall. And there are signs
that Nowitzki, who was thought to be a lock to play in Europe for
two more years, may be rethinking his position. ``The kid was
thinking of coming over here to college, so it's not like he's
reluctant to leave,'' said Celtics general manager  &UR; Chris Wallace &LR; .
``I think they have a chance to pull it off. They can sell
( &UR; Steve &LR; )  &UR; Nash &LR; , &UR;  &LR; a new arena, the NBA, and Donnie has to have
some rapport with him. The question (Nowitzki) has to ask himself
is, `Do I want to be in Bologna next year? Or Milan? Or Dallas?'
You have to have a degree of faith in these things.'' Don Nelson
conceded prior to departure that the lockout might hurt his
chances. Donnie Nelson said he thought the whole thing was ``a coin
flip.'' ... The Mavericks got ripped by some for more of Nellie's
roster reshaping. But how is Dallas not better with Nash and, soon,
Nowitzki? True, the Mavs gave up their own first-rounder next year,
but Nash alone may be worth that. However, if they do stumble, the
Suns will be the ultimate winner, getting a top pick for someone
they couldn't keep. Phoenix also has Milwaukee's first-round pick
next year, not to mention a substantial pile of cash to use in free
agency, whenever it comes ... Speaking of the Bucks, the longer
things go, the more it seems that  &UR; Chris Ford  &LR; has, for now,
survived. We hear that there is an option clause in his deal that
kicks in next Jan. 1, which means the team had better get off to a
decent start ... The Jazz wanted nothing to do with this draft,
turning aside the 13th pick and then trading  &UR; Nazr Mohammed  &LR; to
Philly after drafting him 29th. Utah wants to keep its free agent
stash intact. The Mohammed deal is lottery-protected for the Sixers
well into the next century ... Speaking of the 76ers,  &UR; Larry Brown
 &LR; is well on his way to constructing his ideal: a college team. He
has on his roster a handful of 19-year-olds, either in age or in
mind, including  &UR; Derrick Coleman  &LR; ... The Celtics were under
intense pressure from agent  &UR; David Falk  &LR; to draft Mohammed at No.
10. Mohammed is tight with Falk client  &UR; Antoine Walker  &LR; and Walker
also was hoping to see his former UK teammate in Boston. It didn't
happen, of course, and it was all the more amusing to several
general managers to see Mohammed tumble all the way to 29. It
wasn't a great night for Falk. He had earlier tried to steer  &UR; Mike
Bibby  &LR; to the Clippers at No. 1 and that didn't work, either. But
he did get  &UR; Raef LaFrentz  &LR; to Denver at No. 3 and  &UR; Michael Doleac
 &LR; to Orlando at No. 12 ...  &UR; Jerry Reynolds &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the Kings' director of
player personnel, said he feels that  &UR; Jason Williams  &LR; was the best
point guard in the draft. Better than Bibby? ``Absolutely,''
Reynolds said. ``Time will tell, of course, but that's how we feel
now.'' And what about Williams's many, er, distractions off the
court (is it any coincidence he went to the same high school as
wide receiver  &UR; Randy Moss &LR; ?)? ``There are risks, we know that,''
Reynolds said. ``But this is a lively, explosive, talented guy. We
don't have any problem with him when the lights go on at 7:30. It's
what happens when they go out. We don't see any risks on the floor.
All the risks are off the floor.'' ...  &UR; Dino Radja  &LR; has until
Wednesday to decide if he's going to opt out of his contract in
Greece. ``We still have not decided what we are going to do,'' said
 &UR; Marc Fleisher &LR; , &UR;  &LR; his agent. Given the uncertain summer in the NBA,
returning to Greece might be the safest option ... How would you
like to have been  &UR; Pete Babcock  &LR; last Wednesday night? He gets a
call informing him one of his players is about to be indicted on
drug charges. We hear he wasn't told which player it was. It turned
out to be  &UR; Cadillac Anderson &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Don Casey &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the former Celtics assistant, was in Detroit last
weekend talking to  &UR; Alvin Gentry  &LR; about joining the Pistons' staff.
Gentry is willing to give Casey two years, while his Jersey deal
has a year to run. Casey isn't eager to relocate again _ though
it's nice to be wanted _ but there are a couple uncertainties that
may make it unavoidable. First, coach  &UR; John Calipari  &LR; has an
opt-out clause in his deal that kicks in next summer. Second, there
is again talk about the team being sold. The latest proposal is to
move the club to Newark when the Meadowlands lease expires in a
couple years. However, the deal's drop-dead date apparently is
Wednesday. The prospective new boss is a deep pockets guy named
 &UR; Ray Chambers  &LR; ... All the jokes about proximity to the Diamond
District notwithstanding,  &UR; Marcus Camby  &LR; has one year to reclaim
what was thought to be a can't-miss NBA career. He got his wish to
leave Toronto _  &UR; Dee Brown  &LR; and  &UR; Chauncey Billups  &LR; have to be
envious _ and will have some teammates in New York who are
accustomed to doing things a certain way. If Camby doesn't turn it
around, he could become the  &UR; Joe Smith  &LR; of the free agent Class of
1999. The move makes a lot of sense for the Knicks, who were
exposed on the inside by the Pacers. As for Oakley, he was a big
presence on that team. You have to think he's elated to be going to
Toronto, eh? The Raptors could be even worse next year ... Wallace
believes the Lakers got themselves a real player in the second
round with the selection of Cincinnati's  &UR; Ruben Patterson &LR; . ``He
was one of the few small guys we worked out,'' Wallace said, ``and
I think he's a flat-out player. The Lakers got themselves a good
one.'' LA also got  &UR; Tony Battie  &LR; and  &UR; Tyronn Lue  &LR; for  &UR; Nick Van
Exel &LR; , &UR;  &LR; which means something has to give.  &UR; Elden Campbell  &LR; is
available, and probably will go somewhere, despite his ridiculous
salary ($7 million a year). Why any team would take on that
contract, given what we all know about Campbell, is mystifying ...
As for the high schoolers, Wallace was surprised, but not totally
shocked, to see  &UR; Rashard Lewis  &LR; slide to Seattle in the second
round. Lewis was thought to be a first-round lock, possibly a
top-15 selection, and the Celtics had him in for a workout. The
consensus was that Lewis was not aggressive enough, that he
projected as, well, someone who might not be ready for the NBA.
Gee, what a revelation. As Reynolds put it, ``I don't think the
kid's good enough to play for Duke, let alone an NBA team.'' The
NBA and the NBA Players Association could put an end to this
silliness by adopting an age limit of 20 for all players, foreign
and American.  &UR; Al Harrington &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who went 25th to Indiana, becomes
the first player to be drafted whose date of birth is in the, ahem,
1980s. Lewis and  &UR; Korleone Young &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the other high schooler who
went in the second round, were born in the 1970s ... Possible
second-round sleeper:  &UR; Bruno Sundov &LR; , &UR;  &LR; an 18-year-old Croatian
center selected by Dallas. He's listed as 7 feet 2 inches, 220
pounds, and is being coached by the same man who coached  &UR; Toni
Kukoc &LR; , &UR;  &LR; Radja, and  &UR; Zan Tabak  &LR; ...  &UR; Popeye Jones  &LR; not only has
dropped almost 40 pounds, but he also has seen his body fat lowered
from 30 percent to 13 percent. Don't worry, though. He's not going
to turn into another  &UR; Walter McCarty &LR; . One of Popeye's undeniable
assets is his sizable rear end, which he used to great advantage in
Dallas getting position. He still has that. The Celtics would like
to see him at 250 when the season starts and he re-signs with the
team. The more you hear Pitino talk about not having enough money
to spend on free agents, the more you suspect he's seen the light
and will bring back Jones and, possibly, Tabak.  &UR; Matt Geiger  &LR; isn't
going to excite anyone and isn't worth the money. Pitino's got four
of his five bases covered (for now, anyway) and can get by with his
multiple centers until something better and affordable comes along
...  &UR; Keon Clark &LR; , &UR;  &LR; whom the Celtics would have taken at No. 10 had
neither Pierce nor Nowitzki been there, could well have been a
top-five pick were it not for his checkered resume. That's what
Wallace believes. Clark had an outstanding workout for Boston, and
don't be surprised if the Celtics try to work something out with
Orlando to acquire the UNLV shot-blocker.
</P>
