<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARCELLS'S PICKOFF MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ New York Jets coach Bill Parcells always used to
assert that ``I go by what I see.'' Apparently he's developed a new
way of looking at things since he left New England.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells is a guy who hates turnovers the way Dunkin' Donuts
hates turnovers. He thinks of turnovers the way Brueggers Bagels
thinks of turnovers. In other words, he has no use for turnovers
unless his team is causing them.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's how it was until last week, when he went out and
hired the king of turnovers, free agent Vinny Testaverde, to
compete with Glenn Foley for the Jets quarterback job this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The release of Neil O'Donnell was not surprising after he
continued to refuse to rework his contract down from the $3,654,800
he was paid to finish last year as a benchwarmer. That number was
the fourth-highest paid to any player in the AFC in 1997 when base
salary and prorated signing bonuses are factored together, and it
simply could not be justified if he was going to again back up
Foley, which he seemed destined to do. So, business-wise, his
release made salary cap sense. These days that sometimes counts for
more than common sense, because, frankly, what other explanation is
there for signing Testaverde to replace O'Donnell?
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Testaverde was a salary cap bargain at $1.5 million plus
incentives, and certainly he had some big individual games against
Parcells's teams in the past, but three games against a guy is not
the same as 16 weeks with a guy, as Parcells learned the hard way
in the case of Marion Butts, for example. What one wonders, then,
is did Parcells forget that this is the same Vinny Testaverde who
has thrown more career interceptions (183) than touchdown passes
(175), or was he blinded by his personal experiences, forgetting it
was against Parcells's own weak-link defenses that Testaverde took
advantage of and now will not have the opportunity to attack?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Testaverde was a Pro Bowl quarterback two years ago in
Baltimore, when he passed for 4,177 yards and 33 touchdowns, but
his team still didn't win so it was all only numbers _ something
Parcells abhors unless the numbers are in the win column. Last
season, in fact, Testaverde couldn't keep his job because he
couldn't keep up those numbers, passing for just 2,971 yards and
only 18 touchdowns. That is why he was put on the market as a
post-June 1 salary cap casualty after Jim Harbaugh was imported
from the Colts.
</P>
<P>
   Looked upon in purely economic terms, then, swapping O'Donnell's
contract for Test-averde's makes sense because it saves the Jets
$2.75 million, but if Jet fans think O'Donnell was in Parcells's
doghouse, wait until they try to find Testaverde after a couple of
those three-INT games. You lookin' for Vinny? Try the pound.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells had to do something, however, after he let his
relationship with O'Donnell deteriorate into a sideline shouting
contest and an odd decision to go with an untested kid, Ray Lucas,
in the biggest game of the year last season rather than let
O'Donnell _ who was actually playing well in place of Foley in a
season-ending game the Jets had to win to make the playoffs _ do
the throwing. That ended whatever chance there was to convince
O'Donnell to take a financial hit for the team during the
offseason, because Parcells had publicly embarrassed and humiliated
a proud player who was only three years removed from having
quarterbacked the Pittsburgh Steelers to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Even Parcells seemed to concede that to ask a player to take a
pay cut to help a man who had humiliated him (and some say cost the
Jets the playoffs in a fit of pique) was probably asking too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed in part of the way this has gone on because I
do have a high regard for him personally,'' Parcells said when
announcing the two moves. ``If someone came in and tried to cut my
salary, I probably wouldn't like it either. He's been a good
quarterback in this league. But looking at the big picture for us,
I just felt that this was a better fit.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll feel that way until the first time Testaverde throws three
to the Miami Dolphins. Then he'll just throw a fit.
</P>
<P>
   But that is the hand he has dealt himself. And he had to do
something fast because his chosen one, Foley, has been unable to
stay healthy either at Boston College or with the Jets. Foley does
not have a complete-game victory to his credit in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Foley's injury record, coupled with his limited experience, told
Parcells the obvious _ he still needed a veteran presence even if
it wasn't O'Donnell, and Testaverde was the best available option.
Some might say, at this late date, the only available option.
</P>
<P>
   So now he's got him. He may even have him on the field this
fall, because in a fair fight in training camp, Testaverde might
very well play significantly better than Foley. He hasn't thrown
for 29,233 yards in 11 seasons without having both ability and
durability, and given a chance to showcase that, he could easily
make clear who the better quarterback is.
</P>
<P>
   But if he does, Parcells will then face another dilemma. Does he
turn a blind eye to what he sees or does he go by what he sees, as
he always claims he does? Does he try to save face or does he go
with the king of turnovers, knowing that after 11 seasons of
throwing the ball to the wrong team at the worst of times, you can
count on one thing from Vinny Testaverde.
</P>
<P>
   You can count on him doing it again when the pressure is on.
</P>
<P>
   When he does, Neil O'Donnell may start to look like Johnny
Unitas to Bill Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Difficult as it may be to fathom Parcells's willingness to bring
on Testaverde, what has just transpired in Atlanta will put it in
better perspective. With  &UR; Mark Rypien  &LR; contemplating retirement
because of illnesses to both his young son and his wife, the
Falcons last week worked out 44-year-old  &UR; Steve DeBerg  &LR; as a
possible backup. DeBerg has not played in the NFL since 1993, but
starter  &UR; Chris Chandler  &LR; has suffered with injuries through most of
his career and last season was no different. Atlanta was 7-3 in
games Chandler started and finished, and 0-6 in ones he didn't. So
with Rypien now a question mark despite having signed a two-year,
$1.85 million deal in the offseason, something had to be done, and
with the quarterback ranks depleted, it was worth considering the
 &UR; George Foreman  &LR; of quarterbacks. DeBerg seems unlikely to end up
in the NFL this fall, but just the fact that Falcon coach  &UR; Dan
Reeves  &LR; would look at him makes clear the problem Parcells and
anyone else looking for a quarterback at this late date is facing.
It's also why O'Donnell figured he could get away with playing
hardball with the Jets. In the end, O'Donnell knows he'll end up
playing football with someone ... A Las Vegas mystery woman's bid
to buy the Minnesota Vikings has been rejected as not really
legitimate, but  &UR; Shruti Misra &LR; , &UR;  &LR; a 31-year-old businesswoman who
claims vast real estate holdings in California, Nevada, and Mexico,
has raised her bid from an original $180 million to $225 million,
with reportedly $195 million of it in cash. Vikings attorney  &UR; John
Mooty &LR; , however, claimed that because of the debt a new owner would
have to assume, Misra's offer was really worth only about $150
million. But Misra may yet make a third offer by the July 1
deadline for submitting proposals. Among those expected to make
offers for the Vikings is  &UR; J. Bruce Llewellyn &LR; , &UR;  &LR; a cousin of  &UR; Colin
Powell &LR; , the former head of the Joint Chiefs of Staff. Llewellyn,
chairman of the board of Philadelphia Coca-Cola, would become the
first black to own controlling interest in a professional sports
franchise in the United States if his bid is successful. Joining
him as an investor is former Vikings general manager  &UR; Mike Lynn &LR; .
Llewellyn met with NFL commissioner  &UR; Paul Tagliabue  &LR; last week
before taking sick in New York and being hospitalized for tests.
That resulted in his having to cancel a planned session with the
Vikings' 10-man ownership group. The 70-year-old Llewellyn is
likely to be competing against Timberwolves owner  &UR; Glen
Taylor &LR; , &UR;  &LR; Viking part-owner and general manager  &UR; Roger
Headrick &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who earlier lost a bid to buy the team when author  &UR; Tom
Clancy  &LR; offered money as fictional as his books, as well as San
Antonio Spurs owner  &UR; Red McCombs &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who also bid before ...
Whispers out of Chicago are that running back  &UR; Rashaan Salaam  &LR; will
be released after reaching an injury settlement on his contract.
The former Heisman Trophy winner rushed for 1,000 yards as a rookie
in 1995 but by last season was slowed by a severely broken fibula.
When Salaam is released, it will mean both of last year's starting
backs are gone because free agent  &UR; Raymont Harris  &LR; also will not be
back. The new backfield is likely to be No. 1 draft choice  &UR; Curtis
Enis  &LR; and  &UR; Darnell Autry &LR;  ... Speaking of the Vikings, their offer
of a four-year, $22 million contract to wide receiver  &UR; Cris Carter
 &LR; is likely going to be rejected or modified. The five-time Pro Bowl
selection would become the highest-paid receiver in football, far
surpassing this season's top free agent signing of  &UR; Yancey
Thigpen &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who agreed to a deal with the Tennessee Oilers that will
pay him an average of $4.2 million. Carter is seeking a contract
averaging around $6 million instead of the $5.5 million Minnesota
put on the table last week. While all this is going on, Detroit's
perennial All-Pro,  &UR; Herman Moore &LR; , &UR;  &LR; is calmly watching, knowing the
Lions are likely to rework his deal again, as they have three times
already. Since he is arguably the premier receiver in football,
Moore knows where he should end up, but he'll wait until Carter is
done setting the market before trying to go deep again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pity poor San Diego Chargers rookie quarterback  &UR; Ryan Leaf &LR; . His
new employers seem to be taking a bit too seriously his ability to
serve as both The Savior and The Franchise. Leaf may eventually be
every bit the quarterback  &UR; Drew Bledsoe  &LR; is, but this season he'll
be throwing to a corp of receivers who couldn't be blamed if they
need to ask directions to the end zone. Of the Chargers' five young
wideouts, only two have ever scored an NFL touchdown. That doesn't
include old warhorse  &UR; Webster Slaughter  &LR; (555 career catches for
8,018 yards and 44 touchdowns), who was added to the mix this
spring despite not playing a down since 1996. With former Pro
Bowlers  &UR; Tony Martin  &LR; and  &UR; Eric Metcalf  &LR; traded in the offseason,
the Chargers lost 892 receptions and 73 touchdowns and will be
replacing that with  &UR; Brian Still  &LR; (30 career receptions in two NFL
seasons, 466 yards, no touchdowns) and rookie second-round choice
 &UR; Mikhael Ricks &LR; , &UR;  &LR; if head coach  &UR; Kevin Gilbride  &LR; sticks to his
early position on the matter. The Chargers also have  &UR; Tyrone
Brown &LR; , &UR;  &LR; acquired from Atlanta, who has 45 career catches for 523
yards and one touchdown, slot receiver  &UR; Charlie Jones &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who has 73
receptions in two seasons for 947 yards and five scores, and
second-year man  &UR; Latario Rachal  &LR; (zeros all the way) ...
Considering that the Chargers also have no No. 1 pick until 2001,
this resurrection could take a while ... It's no surprise that
Dallas's nine-year veteran defensive end,  &UR; Tony Tolbert &LR; , &UR;  &LR; was not
happy to learn he was being released for salary cap reasons. The
Cowboys saved $2.487 million on their cap and hope to re-sign
Tolbert for a significant pay cut. He is not, at least at the
moment, much inclined to accept even that, though he's coming off
double knee surgery that has the team concerned he may not be the
player he once was. If Tolbert does not return after starting 144
straight games, Dallas is faced with starting rookie  &UR; Greg Ellis
 &LR; and young  &UR; Kavitka Pittman  &LR; at defensive ends, a tandem with one
career sack. Considering that, Tolbert said last week in Dallas,
``Do you think Kavitka and those guys can get the job done?''
Apparently Tolbert doesn't ... Ex-Dallas middle linebacker  &UR; Robert
Jones &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who played on the Cowboys' three Super Bowl teams, may be
headed to the strong side slot in Miami.  &UR; Zach Thomas  &LR; is a fixture
in the middle and the strong side was trouble last year, with
 &UR; Anthony Harris  &LR; and  &UR; Dwight Hollier  &LR; both manning it at different
times ... Remember  &UR; Carlton Haselrig &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the former practice squad
player who developed into a Pro Bowl guard in 1992 and then lost
himself in drugs and alcohol? He's back in a football uniform in
Pittsburgh. It's just not a Steelers uniform. Last week Haselrig
called the semi-pro Pittsburgh Colts and asked if they could use
him. The Colts agreed to pay his health insurance but no salary,
and Haselrig will take over at both guard and middle linebacker.
The Colts play in the semi-pro National Football Federation, a
league that will have former West Virginia star  &UR; Major Harris  &LR; at
quarterback for the Huntingdon (W.Va.) Hawks.
</P>
</TEXT>
