<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITONS FEELING GIDDY ABOUT RARE DOUBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Play it again, Sam!
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly that's the theme at Wimbledon where Sam and Tim are the
leading man and lady, sort of the Ilsa and Rick of the local tennis
drama. Especially since the kid from the real Casablanca, the
dazzling shotmaker Hicham Arazi, has, alas, been beaten by a Swede,
Magnus Larsson, and deported with the usual suspects.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Casablanca'' was an all-time feel-good flick, Saturday was
a jolly good happy-ending day for the homebodies, who don't have
many of them around here. Even though the English conceived tennis,
founded Wimbledon and used to win all the titles, their day is as
gone as Bergman and Bogart.
</P>
<P>
   As time goes by, however, sparks and embers of empire do appear
as Saturday when Sam and Tim _ that's Samantha Louise Smith and
Timothy Henry Henman _ busted into the fourth round. Landing safely
among the last 16 survivors, carried over to the second week _
that's promised land stuff for a Limey. Sure, it's merely
three-sevenths of the way to titles they won't win, but it's one of
those small, satisfying triumphs like Susan McDougall getting out
of chains. A similar English double was recorded as recently as
1977 by Virginia Wade, the last native to seize the championship,
and Mark Cox.
</P>
<P>
   Henman has made his ripples in this puddled tournament _ closed
down early again by torrents _ as a preppy-looking 23-year-old
quarterfinalist the last two years. It wasn't startling that he,
ranked No. 18, beat No. 34 Black, the diminutive great white hope
of Zimbabwe, 6-4, 6-4, 3-6, 7-5, on Centre Court. Byron Black, the
doubly double-handed skitterer from a Harare avocado plantation,
had all of England in a tea time TV tizzy as he served at 5-3,
about to take it into a fifth set.
</P>
<P>
   But Henman stiffened his upper lip and forehand to carry the
day, adding to the homeland's joy at progressing in the concurrent
kickball tournament in France Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you think you'd be letting the country down if you didn't
do as well as the football team?'' an English reporter actually
asked him. Oh, well.
</P>
<P>
   You would have thought, though, that the England eleven was
facing Argentina over on uproarious Court 2 where banners and
bluster saluted the determined Miss Smith _ ``call me Sam, please''
_ in her successful assault on a champion, No. 7 Conchita Martinez,
2-6, 6-3, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
   While Smith is the No. 1 tennis player in England, this
translates to being the best golfer in Tibet. In the world she's
No. 94, so it was a totally unexpected result from a totally freaky
lady in her line of work. Henman may come from a university town,
Oxford, but Smith, 25, came in with a university degree, from
Exeter.
</P>
<P>
   Legit. No mail-order diploma. An honors graduate from one of the
land's finer schools. In women's tennis, largely staffed by grammar
school dropouts, Lindsay Davenport's high school diploma makes her
seem an Oxford don. So how is Smith regarded? Like Einstein in
drag?
</P>
<P>
   She majored in history, a bad subject for her at Wimbledon,
where she had accumulated all of two sets in five previous tries.
``But I'm coming along more solidly all the time,'' she says, ``and
I hope this inspires a lot of kids. I was inspired when I came to
Wimbledon on a school trip when I was 9. It was brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always watched the (nightly BBC-TV) highlights show, and
now,'' her green eyes gleam, ``I'll be on it. Yes, I'll be
watching.'' And she'll be seeing her face and exploits plastered
all over London's numerous Sunday papers.
</P>
<P>
   The money? She'll get a minimum of $40,160, equaling her entire
1997 take. ``It's such a lot. I can't imagine what I'd do with.''
</P>
<P>
   Named to the British Olympic team in 1992, Smith was knocked out
by hepatitis. Weakened for a time she felt, ``If I couldn't play
tennis, I could put my time to good use going to university. I'm
glad I did. I think it was good for me as a person, and eventually
for my tennis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing I'd done before this was qualify for the US
Open last year. But then I ran into Conchita (Martinez) in the
first round. It was such a shock. I was overwhelmed (6-1, 6-0).
Never played such a good player before. I couldn't handle her spin.
I felt like a beginner.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, the title-round victor over Martina Navratilova in
1994, jumped to a 4-1 lead Friday, but Sam was saved by rainfall.
``I think Conchita took me lightly when we resumed today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't ready. I didn't feel I was there,'' says Martinez,
who had no idea she'd be given a splendid fight and ignominious
last rites by this skinny foe in the dreaded cemetery of the
illustrious Court 2. As union jacks and English flags blazing with
the scarlet crosses of St. George billowed, and the crowd screamed
for her blood, Conchita was laid away by Sam's studious touch with
groundies and volleys.
</P>
<P>
   Conchita got smoked, but nothing like Todd Martin and Todd
Woodbridge, chased from Court 18 by a fire in an adjoining
apartment building. Although rain-outs are common at the Big W,
this was the first smoke-out.
</P>
<P>
   Look-alikes Sam and Tim, their brown hair cropped similarly, are
more uncommon in English terms: three wins apiece. Many a champagne
glass was lifted to them across the country Saturday night with:
``Here's looking at you, kids!''
</P>
<P>
   Could this be the start of a beautiful blendship?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
