<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON GETS DEFENSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
 DRAFT-BRUINS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Last year's National Hockey League draft was greatly
anticipated in Boston as the Bruins welcomed the No. 1 overall
pick, Sault Ste. Marie star Joe Thornton, to the fold. Sergei
Samsonov followed at No. 8 and while Thornton was brought along
slowly, Samsonov made an immediate impact on his way to winning
rookie of the year honors.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's draft had a more low-key feel for the Bruins, who had
to wait until late in the second round to make a selection. Boston
added to its depth on the blue line by taking a pair of defensemen
in Jonathan Girard at No. 48 and Boston College's Bobby Allen at
No. 52, a compensation pick for Toronto signing Kevyn Adams, the
Bruins first-round pick in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins' assistant general manager Mike O'Connell said the club
had both players projected as late first-rounders and they had
considered making a deal to move up to snag Girard and Allen.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell said the staff was very impressed with Girard's
skating.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a skilled, effortless skater,'' said O'Connell. ``If
there has been a knock it's been that he's 5-11. But he's as
skilled a defenseman as I've seen in the (Quebec) League and he can
skate.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell said the Bruins liked Allen's anticipation, which is
why they coveted him. O'Connell views both being a couple of years
away from playing in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   While Girard said he wasn't at all nervous waiting to hear his
name called, Allen confessed to being very jittery while sitting
with his parents and 12 family members who made the trek to Buffalo
for the big day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was tremendously nervous,'' Allen said. ``It's not easy
sitting in the stands and waiting for an organization to decide
your future. Being picked by the Bruins was a huge surprise. I
couldn't write a better script. I had so many hopes about being
picked by my hometown team. I'm not nervous now at all. The best
part was seeing the look on my parents' faces. They sacrificed a
lot. It's been a lot of hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen, a resident of Hull, said he was interviewed twice by the
Bruins and while he got a sense they were interested, he wasn't
certain that's what would happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an inexact science,'' he said. ``I got a feeling they
were confident in my ability but I couldn't pick out what team was
going to pick me. But this experience has been everything I thought
it would be. I figured I'd go a little earlier than I did but to be
picked by Boston, I didn't mind waiting a little longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen was the top-ranked New Englander by Central Scouting. The
Cushing Academy graduate, who turns 20 in November, was ranked 29th
among North Americans at the midpoint and wound up at 34. In his
freshman year at The Heights, he was named to the Hockey East
all-rookie team, was the Eagles' second-highest scoring defenseman
with 7 goals and 26 points in 37 games. He missed the World Junior
Tournament in Finland because of a separated shoulder and reinjured
it in the third period of BC's 3-2 loss to Michigan in the NCAA
title game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shoulder is no problem,'' said 6-foot-1-inch, 198-pound
Allen. ``It's actually probably a lot stronger than when I hurt
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen, a lefthanded shot and former Globe All-Scholastic, plans
to return to BC for his sophomore year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you can count on that right now,'' he said. ``When I
play pro all depends on my development and on what the organization
wants to do. I think being picked by Boston will actually help my
development. And it makes the situation that much sweeter that they
give college guys a chance to break into the organization.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is a knock on Allen, it's his lack of physical play.
Scouts agree he has excellent mobility, a hard shot, is a smart
player, and is effective at the point.
</P>
<P>
   Allen said his physical play didn't come up in his meetings with
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never mentioned it,'' he said. ``I can bang with the
bigger guys. I don't back down. I'll sit down and talk with (the
Bruins) and see what kind of player they want me to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Girard, 18, a righthanded shot, catapulted from a Central
Scouting ranking of 86 midway through the season to 42d. The
Joliette, Quebec, native, who played for Laval in the Quebec
League, was the league's fourth highest-scoring defenseman with 20
goals and 67 points in 64 games.
</P>
<P>
   Central Scouting considers the 5-11 1/2, 192-pound Girard very
agile with exceptional lateral movement and a player who dominates
in the defensive zone. He's an accurate passer with a booming slap
shot and is excellent in the transition game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they picked me because of my ability in the offensive
zone,'' said Girard. ``I think defensively my play is stable, but I
need to work on my play in the defensive zone. My skating and my
passing need to improve, but I improved a lot last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Girard said he plans to come to training camp and will then get
a gauge of what he needs to work on. He is most looking forward to
a trip to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been there,'' he said. ``All I know about it is
Raymond Bourque and the coach (Pat Burns). It was a young team and
they played together and had a good season. I'm real excited. I
just want to work hard and do my best in training camp.''
</P>
</TEXT>
