<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGER BLUE IS FADED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ For those who think that ownership of a major league
franchise carries with it the burden of tradition, remember the
Dodgers. And remember how easily an image built on close family
ties and organizational success can be shattered almost overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few months after the changing of the guard from the
Walter/Peter O'Malley tradition that first began in 1950 came the
Big Purge. Five key figures were replaced _ general manager Fred
Claire, manager Bill Russell, and coaches Reggie Smith, Mark
Cresse, and Glenn Gregson. A shakeup of this magnitude isn't
supposed to happen in Dodger country _ be it in Brooklyn or Los
Angeles. But it did last week, with less than half the season
played.
</P>
<P>
   Claire, 62, had 2 1/2 years left on a new contract, and was no
doubt being blamed as much for the team's sub-.500 start as for his
failure to pull off a trade for Seattle's Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Russell was asked to win with only one prime-time starter, Ramon
Martinez, who is now out for the season with a torn rotator cuff.
New GM Tommy Lasorda had to retire from managing because of the
stress. Can being a general manager in today's baseball _ and the
accompanying financial mess _ be any easier?
</P>
<P>
   Russell was replaced by former Red Sox shortstop Glenn Hoffman,
who is a good guy but has never managed in the majors. He moves up
from Triple A Albuquerque, where he was in his second season at the
helm.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, another former Red Sox, had declined an offer to manage
the Dodgers in the winter of 1996. Too much politics, he said at
the time, and he was right. The Fox move proves that even highly
regarded coaches aren't immune. Smith was offered Hoffman's job at
Albuquerque or the role of hitting instructor, which he held in the
early 90s. He declined both.
</P>
<P>
   What does this all mean? Are we to assume this is an old-
fashioned house cleaning, akin to that of the Florida Marlins,
albeit at a higher level? Or should we assume that the Dodgers are
no longer interested in the values that made the franchise unique
after the arrival of Jackie Robinson in 1947? The new owners at Fox
Corp. want success, to be sure. And now they've let it be known
they will not tolerate failure. Any baseball man will tell you
that's a faulty premise. Baseball is a game built on failure over a
162-game season. You wonder if the Fox people truly understand the
damage they have done.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody ought to tell them this isn't pro football, where you
can spruce up a franchise with cheerleaders and nightly
commercials. Baseball has its own rhythm, based as much on
intangibles as it is on gate receipts and wins and losses. For
better or worse, and this is especially true in California, it's a
game for the people, many of whom might never make it to beautiful
Dodger Stadium. They grow up with players and managers, then watch
them grow old ... like themselves. It remains to be seen if the Fox
people care as much about them as they do the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Fox hasn't really indicated what its plan is for the Dodgers,
beyond expanded exposure into the Pacific rim. But there is a lot
of speculation that the long-term goal is to ``out-Fox'' media
rival Ted Turner and, while at it, to outmaneuver the Disney clan
down the road at Anaheim, where they haven't stopped pushing since
they rode Cowboy Gene Autry out of town.
</P>
<P>
   What is more important? That the Dodgers put a winning team on
the field at all costs, or that they try to win while maintaining
their tradition? No need to answer. The trades that sent Mike
Piazza and Todd Zeile to Florida, and Hideo Nomo to the New York
Mets, spoke volumes. The deals leave a bad taste. As a point of
fact, the final elements of the six-player deal with Florida were
negotiated by Fox executive Chase Carey after Claire had
established the parameters.
</P>
<P>
   If you understand the Red Sox' history of failure, then you have
to appreciate what ``Dem Bums'' have achieved, and why this somehow
doesn't feel right. Over the last 54 years, the Dodgers have
finished first or second 36 times. The team has won nine Western
Division titles, 15 National League pennants, and six world titles.
In the 1950s, they became America's team long before the term was
invented.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s and '70s, they opened up the West for baseball with
more impact than the California Gold Rush. They won two Series in
the '80s (1981, '88) before a drought in the 1992 season (63-99)
exposed the franchise as being weak at the core. Ironically, it was
at that point that the Dodgers produced the next five rookies of
the year _ Eric Karros (1992), Piazza (1993), Raul Mondesi (1994),
Nomo (1995), and Todd Hollandsworth (1996). But one thing was
different. While the Dodgers preached they had the best
organization in the land, they came up short when it came to
results.
</P>
<P>
   Great players win awards, and the Dodgers had a handful. But it
takes great teams to win championships, and the Dodgers have hardly
produced those. They didn't underachieve; they just weren't better
than everybody anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Claire understood the Dodger plight. The team adopted an
international flavor, with stars from the Caribbean and Japan and
Korea, in an attempt to open its horizons as well as maintain the
tradition. It was probably wishful thinking that the Fox people
would wait for all of this to develop. It will take time.
</P>
<P>
   Damn the tradition and full speed ahead, Fox says. So be it.
There was no saving Claire, who, despite a significantly lower
payroll in the last four years, had teams that won. The Dodgers won
the NL West in 1995, went to the playoffs as the wild card in 1996,
and were in the race last year until the final week. In Boston,
we'd love it. But we understand tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's the right move to change horses at midstream. It's
cold and corporate, but it's the way things are done these days.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lost amid the Dodger turmoil was the death last week of their
longtime general manager,  &UR; Al Campanis &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who died of coronary
artery disease at age 81. At his funeral, it was stressed by
Lasorda and others that Robinson's onetime roommate should be
credited for advancing the cause of blacks and Latins in
professional baseball. But his legacy will forever be tainted by
racial remarks made on ABC's ``Nightline'' in 1987 when he asserted
that ``blacks lack the necessities'' to be managers and and
front-office executives. The remarks shocked a nation and made
Campanis appear crude and stupid. He was neither. He was just a
baseball man who made a bad judgment and paid the ultimate price
for tarnishing what was then called a proud ``tradition'' of equal
opportunity. Campanis died last Sunday, the same day the man who
had to fire Campanis _ Claire _ was fired for not making those
traditions work for the team's new owners. What goes around ...
Midseason trades leave most players numb, and when the Tigers'  &UR; Bip
Roberts  &LR; learned he had been dealt to the Oakland A's, he was no
exception. But he got over it in a hurry. ``At first, it didn't
register,'' said Roberts, 35. ``But then it just sunk in. It was
like, `I get to go home!''' Roberts went to Oakland's Skyline High
School and grew up watching the likes of  &UR; Bert Campa &LR; - &UR; neris &LR; , &UR; Joe
Rudi &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Sal Bando &LR; . ``I dreamed of playing there and doing
something special,'' he said. ... The rift between Reds hitting
instructor  &UR; Ken Griffey Sr. &LR;  and the team's front office last week
was brief but insightful. Griffey staged a one-day walkout last
Monday, based mostly on complaints ranging from how he'd been
treated by the organization over the years to the perception that
he was to blame for the club's weak offense and a general lack of
communication with other members of the Reds' staff. Griffey became
particularly incensed when he reported to work and saw other
coaches tutoring young players on the field. ``It's been
festering,'' he said of his decision to leave. ``All people had to
do was communicate with me.'' General manager  &UR; Jim Bowden  &LR; and
manager  &UR; Jack McKeon  &LR; issued a statement that said Griffey's
concerns had been satisfied for now. Griffey escaped a fine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
