</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRINIDAD TRYING TO PUNCH OUT KING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ Don King's empire continued to crumble last week
while he spent his days in a federal courthouse in New York
fighting to keep himself out of prison and his nights trying to
hold together a boxing stable that lost another thoroughbred
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Undefeated International Boxing Federation welterweight champion
Felix Trinidad filed suit against King Thursday and then signed an
eight-fight deal with rival promoter Dino Duva and HBO that will
likely commence with a November unification fight with World Boxing
Association champion Ike Quartey. Trinidad joined Mike Tyson, Terry
Norris, Orlin Norris, Julio Cesar Chavez, and Frans Botha among
other fighters now suing to leave King or already having left his
beleaguered promotional company, claiming their contracts were
either invalid or had ended.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad, who had been shopping his services to various
promoters for months, claims that his four-year deal with King
ended June 11. King is expected to countersue, claiming that the
contract remained in force because of a clause that says the deal
would extend two years if Trinidad became a world champion.
</P>
<P>
   King will argue that the clause applied to every one of his
title defenses. Trinidad's attorneys will counter that it applied
only to any new titles he won after the new contract went into
effect. In that regard, Trinidad had been set to fight for the
junior middleweight title but suddenly backed out a few months ago.
It is now clear he did that because to win a new title would have
activated the extension clause.
</P>
<P>
   Although Trinidad's decision seems likely to tie up him and King
in court for months, he is free to fight in the interim with money
held in escrow until the dispute is settled. That would free up a
logjam in the 147-pound division that has prevented natural
mega-events like Trinidad-Quartey and fights for either with World
Boxing Council champion Oscar De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   Those bouts could help revive the sport, which has suffered
since the suspension of Tyson's license without a major event.
Attempts to make a heavyweight unification fight between Evander
Holyfield and Lennox Lewis broke down earlier this year over money,
and all efforts to match De La Hoya in a unification bout with
Trinidad or Quartey also have proven fruitless.
</P>
<P>
   But De La Hoya has begun to agitate his promoter, Bob Arum, to
make such a match, and Arum finally reacted last week when he upped
his original $3.5 million offer to Quartey to $4.5 million. But he
was too late. By then, Quartey and Trinidad had signed an agreement
for a November match, and it is unlikely that Quartey would try to
break that agreement to fight De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   Because Duva also controls top-rated welterweights Pernell
Whit-aker and Jose Luis Lopez, De La Hoya could find himself
without a shot at Trinidad for another year, because Trinidad's new
deal with HBO provides for only one pay-per-view fight. The other
seven are to be on HBO's free cable program, ``World Champonship
Boxing,'' which is no home for a major fight like De La
Hoya-Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   It is likely Trinidad will get several of those fights out of
the way against Quartey and perhaps Lopez or Whitaker before
fighting De La Hoya, because such fights would not only earn him
millions but would also increase his leverage in any negotiation
with the Golden Boy, who Arum has said would deserve 70 percent of
a deal under present circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   That would cease to be the case, however, if Trinidad gained
strong exposure on HBO and defeated big names such as Quartey,
Lopez, and Whitaker. Judging by what Trinidad had to say at a New
York press conference announcing the new deals Friday, that seems
to be his handlers' plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I know all these big fights will come,'' said Trinidad
(33-0, 29 KOs). ``I want to send a message to all of them. When
their time comes, no more excuses. Let's get in the ring. I'll be
waiting for you, one by one.''
</P>
<P>
   That is good news to HBO, which has not had a major fight on its
network for more than a year, a circumstance a Quartey-Trinidad
match would instantly rectify.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can make Trinidad-Quartey and offer it on HBO, why
not?'' said HBO vice president for programming Lou DiBella. ``We
want to see Oscar get all the major fights he can, but we're not in
the Oscar business. We're in the pay television business.''
</P>
<P>
   Arum accused HBO of working against him and his effort to make a
Quartey-De La Hoya bout, claiming that the cable service's interest
in Quartey-Trinidad was blocking De La Hoya from getting the bout.
There may be some truth to that, because Duva could not have
afforded to sign Trinidad without the eight-fight HBO deal that
accompanied, which Duva claims could be worth $100 million to the
IBF champion.
</P>
<P>
   But what is more important is that Trinidad's decision freed him
from continuing to wallow in the kind of nonevents he has so often
been involved in with King, who last paid him $1 million in April
to defend his title against a nonentity named Mahenge Zulu in
Puerto Rico. By contrast, De La Hoya made nearly $4 million to
fight a similar opponent, Patrick Charpentier, two weeks ago in El
Paso on HBO.
</P>
<P>
   For once, though, the biggest winner should be American fight
fans, who will get a big fight in November involving Trinidad and
Quartey and soon enough have reason to believe the winner will step
in against De La Hoya in the kind of major event the welterweight
division has not seen since Sugar Ray Leonard first fought Thomas
Hearns 17 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chavez's dismal performance against light-hitting  &UR; Ken Sigurani
 &LR; Thursday night at Foxwoods didn't do anything to make you feel his
Sept. 18 bout with De La Hoya will be anything but a repeat of
their first meeting. Chavez lost the first two rounds and then had
a serious cut opened over his right eye before he went wild at the
sight of his own blood and stopped Sigurani in Round 3. Although
that provided Chavez with his 101st career victory against two
losses and two draws, it did nothing to erase the memory of a
bloodied and badly beaten Chavez being destroyed by De La Hoya when
they first met over a year ago. Chavez has grown old gracelessly,
turning from a once-fearsome fighter into a constant complainer and
excuse maker when things don't go well. And, worse, he has turned
into an old man whose reflexes are gone and whose face simply
cannot take being hit any longer. In at least a half dozen of his
most recent fights, Chavez has come out cut or badly bruised, and
that included Thursday night's bout, when he left the arena
immediately to have an inch-long cut repaired by a plastic surgeon.
Arum insisted the cut would not delay the De La Hoya fight and it
probably won't, but that's not good news for Chavez despite his
still-present bravado. ``I think a lot of people think I'm
finished,'' Chavez said. ``They think I have no chance to beat
Oscar De La Hoya. That's good. Sept. 18 will be the surprise of the
year.'' The surprise will be if Chavez isn't a bloody mess when it
concludes. Yet Chavez can see none of what is coming. He is blind
to it all, believing he is still the Chavez he once was and that De
La Hoya is none of what people think. ``I used to like the kid,''
he said of De La Hoya. ``He looked like a respectable kid. But
after he beat me, I think it went to his head. He started talking.
He can talk all the (expletive) he wants. The majority of the
fighters he fights are worth nothing. I don't have any respect for
him as a boxer. The fighters I fought long ago would have knocked
him out.'' Perhaps, but the fighter he's going to fight Sept. 18
won't ... Arum said Chavez will receive the $250,000 knockout bonus
he'd been promised if he stopped Sigurani, even though the bout was
a TKO and not a knockout ... Chavez has a fight of another kind on
his hands after being arrested in Mexico on tax charges Friday.
Chavez's attorney,  &UR; Luis Medina &LR; , &UR;  &LR; said the arrest is apparently
related to a 1996 arrest warrant on tax evasion. That case seemed
to have been settled, but Medina said Chavez's representatives had
not received a formal certificate of the settlement from the
Treasury Secretariat ... ...  &UR; Shelley Finkel  &LR; said in Las Vegas
this week he has advised Tyson to apply for reinstatement of his
boxing license next month. Tyson was suspended indefinitely for
twice biting Holyfield last June, but is eligible to apply for his
license as of July 9. There was some speculation he would wait
several months after the initial date, but it now seems likely he
will seek reinstatement next month and aim for a fight in November
... Former heavyweight champion  &UR; Bruce Seldon  &LR; is facing 364 days
in jail and five years' probation after pleading guilty to smoking
pot wth a 15-year-old girl and having ``sexual activity'' with her.
Seldon's attorneys are trying to work out a deal in which he can
serve his time in house arrest rather than returning to the prison
cell he once occupied as a teenager after he was convicted of armed
robbery. Seldon has not fought since he was destroyed by Tyson in
109 seconds Sept. 7, 1996 ... Arum's dream of making  &UR; Buster
Douglas  &LR; Tyson's first opponent on the latter's latest comeback was
turned into a nightmare by  &UR; Lou Savarese  &LR; Thursday when he
destroyed Douglas in one round. Arum claimed he had options on
Savarese, but it turns out he has only a right of last refusal.
Don't be surprised if you see Savarese in with Lewis in 6-9 months
...  &UR; Yory Boy Campas's  &LR; shot at a big payday with De La Hoya
disappeared in the midst of Trinidad's move against King. He now
will not fight De La Hoya in November, as Arum originally planned.
``Campas is out for November,'' Arum said. ``If we can't do Quartey
then we'll do  &UR; Oba Carr  &LR; or ( &UR; Frankie &LR; )  &UR; Randall &LR; .''... Although
their fight has already been announced at a large New York press
conference,  &UR; Roy Jones Jr.'s  &LR; and  &UR; Lou Del Valle's  &LR; people continue
to argue over details. Jones's camp is insisting that an immediate
rematch clause be in the contract in case he loses and that Del
Valle agree to only 40 percent of the take from a rematch even if
he wins. Del Valle's promoter,  &UR; Cedric Kushner &LR; , &UR;  &LR; said he would
agree to the 60-40 split, acknowledging that even in defeat, Jones
would be the bigger draw, but he is refusing the immediate rematch
clause ... Showtime is hoping it can stage the postponed
Holyfield- &UR; Henry Akinwande  &LR; heavyweight title fight in New York in
August.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Women boxers from the United States and Canada will fight in the
first international amateur women's meet ever held in the United
States July 10 at Lackawanna County Stadium near Scranton, Pa. USA
Boxing will run the event, using the eight winners from the
national championships to represent the US. USA Boxing says it has
900 female members ... The Fighting Foul Pole,  &UR; Andrew
Golota &LR; , &UR;  &LR; fights  &UR; Corey Sanders  &LR; (16-5) July 21 in Atlantic City
for chump change with an eye toward a bigger payday. Golota (30-3)
has won two walkover matches since being stopped in one round by
Lewis last year, and if he can defeat Sanders, he has already
agreed to a match with 39-year-old former champion  &UR; Tim Witherspoon
 &LR; (46-7) Sept. 4 at Wroclaw, Poland, for $450,000. Acknowledges the
aging Witherspoon, ``Things are very different for me right now.
I've had my ups and downs, my sads and goods. I'm going to just
train the hardest I've ever trained.'' Witherspoon said his biggest
concern would come after the fight. ``If I knock out Andrew, what
the people gonna do? When I knocked out ( &UR; Frank &LR; )  &UR; Bruno  &LR; in
London, I didn't think I'd get out of there alive.'' ...
Cruiserweight  &UR; Ramon Garbey  &LR; faces  &UR; David Izegwire  &LR; on the July 21
undercard of Golota-Sanders.
</P>
</TEXT>
