<HEADLINE>
IRL, NHIS WILL LIKELY PART WAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; LOUDON, N.H. _ Tony George smiled coyly Saturday afternoon
when asked if his blue-and-white windbreaker, emblazoned with the
slogan ``The Magic Mile,'' was his symbolic show of support for New
Hampshire International Speedway. ``Actually,'' said George,
president of Indianapolis Motor Speedway and founder of the Indy
Racing League, ``I forgot my jacket back home at Indy and I got
cold when it started raining. So I went over (to the gift shop) and
bought one for me and my son.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paid full retail, too.''
</P>
<P>
   It will likely make a perfect parting gift. When the New England
200 is staged Sunday at NHIS, it will mark the end of a three-year
contract between the IRL series and NHIS owner Bob Bahre. And,
given the event's sagging attendance and diminishing revenue, it's
quite likely it will be the last time NHIS stages such a race.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, after IRL qualifying was delayed by rain, the sun
finally poked through enabling practice to get underway. However,
there remained clouds of doubt over the IRL's future at NHIS.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Bahre expressed some concerns about extending the
contract with the series at his one-mile oval. ``I thought it would
work out better, but it hasn't been any better,'' he said,
referring to the decision to bolt from the Championship Auto Racing
Teams schedule and join the IRL as a charter venue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to Bob today and, obviously, there's a lot of
speculation around the garage area, which you might expect on a
rainy Saturday afternoon,'' George said. ``But we're on the track
running as we speak and we're looking forward to a good race
tomorrow. Hopefully, a positive result will make for some positive
discussions regarding the future.''
</P>
<P>
   George indicated those discussions would likely take place next
week. However, if the relationship is to continue, it is clear the
IRL and NHIS will have to work out a way to improve attendance,
which has declined from 24,000 two years ago to 22,000 last year.
Moreover, because he was unable to acquire a title sponsor, Bahre
indicated he stood to lose as much as $700,000.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had any solutions for making the IRL more viable at
NHIS, George said, ``I do, but I don't know how viable they are. I
think that I want to sit down with our people and various promoters
and discuss them. I wish I had a little more P.T. Barnum in me, but
I don't really believe that I do. I think there are others who have
a flair for that kind of promotion. I think there's a practical
side of me that believes if you put good minds to work on trying to
develop solutions, that any problems can be overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   So what are the chances NHIS will remain on the 1999 IRL
schedule?
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't want to comment on that question at this point
in time,'' George said. ``I think, in due course as we try to put
our schedule together for next year, we'll certainly have
discussions _ soon _ because we obviously want to release our
schedule. It has to be a decision that we reach jointly, and one
that both parties feel comfortable with announcing. We both have
agreed that our main focus is putting on an event (today) and
that's where we're at.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup points leader  &UR; Jeremy Mayfield  &LR; finally got into the
winner's circle last weekend by steering his Mobil 1 Ford
Thunderbird to victory at the Pocono 500, his first career triumph
on the NASCAR Winston Cup circuit. In doing so, Mayfield, a native
of Owensboro, Ky., passed boyhood idol  &UR; Darrell Waltrip  &LR; for the
lead and held off two-time Winston Cup champion  &UR; Jeff Gordon &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the
race runner-up. ``To pass Darrell Waltrip for the lead for my first
win and to have Jeff Gordon behind me and  &UR; Dale Jarrett  &LR; behind
him, that's a lot of heavy hitters,'' said Mayfield, who will
attempt to extend his 36-point lead over Gordon (2,208 to 2,172) in
Sunday's Save Mart/Kragen 350-kilometer race at Sears Point Raceway
in Sonoma, Calif. ``But Darrell, that's pretty wild. For someone
who inspired me to want to win and want to become who I am  &UR; today &LR; ,
that's pretty neat.'' ... Winston Cup driver  &UR; Ricky Craven  &LR; of
Newburgh, Maine, took a significant step in his recovery from
post-concussion syndrome, which has kept him sidelined since March
9, when he tested his own Busch Grand National car last week at
Watkins Glen, N.Y. ``I reestablished the hunger that maybe didn't
exist three months ago,'' said Craven, who is aiming for a comeback
to the Winston Cup circuit at NHIS for the Jiffy Lube 300 July 12.
``I'm looking to return to the focus and level of concentration I
had before. We tested for about 40 laps. It was a one-day test, but
it was really important for us.'' ... CART driver  &UR; Robby
Gordon &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who was formerly employed on the NASCAR circuit with Team
Sabco before he was discharged by team owner  &UR; Felix Sabates &LR; , &UR;  &LR; will
return to Winston Cup racing this weekend behind the wheel of a
Caterpillar-sponsored Chevrolet Monte Carlo fielded by American
Equipment Racing owner  &UR; Howard (Buzz) McCall &LR; . ``To say I'm excited
about the opportunity to drive the 96 CAT car and throw my hat back
in the NASCAR ring is an understatement,'' Gordon said. ``A lot of
people had to give the approval for this to happen, and I don't
plan on letting anyone down. I told the team to bring a few extra
sets of wheels because I plan to drive them off the car.'' ...
NASCAR president  &UR; Bill France Jr. &LR;  was the keynote speaker at the
Associated Press Sports Editors convention in Richmond Thursday.
France speculated that the series, which has grown to a rec-ord 33
events, may split before it expands again, but not anytime in the
near future. ``We don't think right now that the parts would be
worth as much as the whole,'' he said. ``If we grow too fast, I
don't think we're smart enough to handle it, to keep our arms
wrapped around it and not let things go.'' France did joke that if
he were an NBA owner, ``I'd make the players wear long-sleeve
shirts and pants with logos all over them. Can you imagine  &UR; Dennis
Rodman  &LR; selling space on his uniform?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After recording his first CART victory in Portland, Ore., two
years ago,  &UR; Alex Zanardi  &LR; returned to the scene of his momentous
triumph and duplicated the feat by winning last week's
Budweiser/G.I. Joe's 200. It was Zanardi's second win in a row and
fourth of the FedEx CART Championship series for the Target/Chip
Ganassi Racing team, giving him a whopping 38-point lead over  &UR; Greg
Moore  &LR; in the PPG Cup standings. Moore wiped out in a Turn 1
accident that collected the cars of Newman-Haas teammates  &UR; Michael
Andretti  &LR; and  &UR; Christian Fittipaldi  &LR; as well as Team Kool driver
 &UR; Paul Tracy &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who was already under probation for wrecking
Fittipaldi in Detroit. ``I passed two or three cars as I went down
to the inside of the track,'' Moore said later. ``I misjudged how
deep I went in before the Festival Curves. I made a mistake and I
feel bad for Christian and Paul.'' Said Fittipaldi: ``We are going
through a very tough time and just want to finish some races. It's
easy for Greg to say he is sorry after the fact, but here I am out
of the race. He just came over the grass out of control into me. An
apology is good between drivers, but it unfortunately doesn't
change the end result.''
</P>
</TEXT>
