<HEADLINE>
SOME OF CHARM GONE FROM GOLD CUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ The absence of Silver Charm, caused by a fever, has
diminished the importance of Sunday's $1 million Hollywood Gold
Cup, but the meeting between handicap champion Skip Away and the
talented Gentlemen should be interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm, last year's 3-year-old champion, was withdrawn
from the much-anticipated showdown with Skip Away Wednesday after
he developed a high temperature. Trainer Bob Baffert indicated that
the big gray will be out for at least a month, putting a
confrontation in the $1 million Pacific Classic Aug. 15, also
scheduled to feature Skip Away, in jeopardy as well. It could be
that the earliest Silver Charm-Skip Away meeting would be in the
Woodward Stakes at Belmont Park Sept. 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took blood and it showed that he did have a bug,'' Baffert
said Thursday. ``We'll have to give him five days off. The workout
(Silver Charm ran five-eighths in :58 3/5 at Santa Anita Tuesday)
probably brought it out. It's not a killer bug, but I can't run him
now for at least 30 days. When you lose five days with him, it's
like losing two weeks with any other horse. I'll have to sit down
with (owner) Bob Lewis and figure out a plan for him now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hollywood Gold Cup has eight horses entered, with Gentlemen
and Puerto Madero, both owned by Hollywood Park chairman R.D.
Hubbard, forming a powerful coupled entry. Floriselli, Bagshot,
Budroyale, Don't Blame Rio, and Mud Route, the last a horse with
ability trained by Ron McAnally, round out the field. All will
carry 124 pounds over 1 1/4 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Gentlemen, who will be ridden by Gary Stevens now that Silver
Charm is out, beat Skip Away in the Pimlico Special last year and
went on to win both the Gold Cup and the Pacific Classic. At that
point, the Argentina-bred horse trained by Richard Mandella was a
top contender for both Horse of the Year and handicap champion
honors. However, he ran fifth in the Woodbine Mile on the grass
Sept. 20, with a throat problem blamed for his poor performance. He
subsequently developed a fever and missed the Breeders' Cup at
Hollywood Nov. 8, which kept him from winning any Eclipse Awards,
although he still received strong support.
</P>
<P>
   Now age 6, but with only 19 career starts, Gentlemen returned to
the races with an easy victory in the San Antonio Handicap Feb. 7,
but a month later he bled and finished last in the Santa Anita
Handicap. The Gold Cup marks Gentlemen's latest comeback, and,
along with Puerto Madero, who ran a good second to Skip Away in the
Massachusetts Handicap at Suffolk Downs May 30 and who will again
be ridden by Kent Desormeaux, he should at least make Skip Away,
who will have the services of Jerry Bailey, work for his seventh
straight victory.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How big is Baffert?
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, the leading rider in the country, announced June 12
that he was going to switch his tack to New York for the Saratoga
meeting, which begins July 29, then would stay on for the Belmont
fall meeting. This caused quite a stir in the Big Apple. However,
nine days later, Stevens's agent,  &UR; Ron Anderson &LR; , &UR;  &LR; announced that
the jockey was instead staying in California and would ride the Del
Mar meet, which commences July 22. Why? Because Baffert gave
Stevens first call to ride every horse in his barn.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert, who had narrow misses in the Triple Crown the last two
years, losing the Belmont Stakes in close finishes with both Silver
Charm and Real Quiet, is the latest trainer to be elevated to the
``genius'' category, and eager owners have swamped him with
2-year-olds. ``We've been offered a position to ride a lot of good,
young horses at Del Mar and we're going to stay put and just
continue on here,'' said Anderson. ``We've been approached by Bob
Baffert with a whole bunch of young horses, which he anticipates
developing into good ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, getting to ride Baffert's entire barn means that
Stevens can guide Real Quiet, hero of the Kentucky Derby and
Preakness before losing the Belmont by a nose to Victory Gallop,
ridden by none other than Gary Stevens. If you're asking, ``Does
this mean Desormeaux was fired following his magical mystery tour
aboard Real Quiet in the Belmont?'' the answer is ``yes,'' but he
was allowed to keep his dignity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have 45 2-year-olds; 25 of them look awesome,'' said
Baffert. ``I'll need more than one rider (meaning, he'll still use
Desormeaux, whose career he was credited with reviving). I started
talking to Gary at the Preakness. He has first call on all my
horses. If that means Gary wants to ride Real Quiet, then he'll
ride Real Quiet. Gary can get out of the agreement anytime. It's
just a handshake.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens may have to chose between Real Quiet and Victory Gallop,
and many feel Victory Gallop is the better of the two, for the $1
million Haskell Invitational at Monmouth Aug. 9. Surprisingly,
 &UR; Elliott Walden &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who trains Victory Gallop, thinks that Stevens
will stay with his charge. ``I talked with Anderson on Wednesday
and he basically told me that Gary is Victory Gallop's rider,''
said Walden. ``I say that with confidence but not 100 percent
confidence. He told me he doesn't anticipate making a change, but
anything can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Walden shouldn't count on Stevens riding for him. Baffert is
just too big.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Free House, who defeated Silver Charm in the Santa Anita Derby
last year, then ran 3-2-3, respectively, in the Triple Crown races,
drilled 7 furlongs in a bullet (best of day) 1:25 2/5 at Hollywood
Park Wednesday as he continues to work well toward his 4-year-old
debut in the Bel Air Handicap July 11. Free House has not raced
since running last in the Super Derby at Louisiana Downs last
September. He had been on the shelf with muscle soreness ... Deputy
Commander, who won the Travers Stakes and Super Derby last year and
also finished second to Skip Away in the $4 million Breeders' Cup
Classic, was recently retired after suffering a suspensory tear in
his right front leg in the Californian Stakes May 31 ... Lil's Lad,
one of the top Triple Crown contenders before chipping his left
front ankle in the Blue Grass April 11, is back in training and
pointing toward a comeback race at the end of the Saratoga meeting
... Black Cash, a promising sort who finished fifth in the
Preakness, has been suffering from a lung infection but may be back
in time to make the Jim Dandy at The Spa Aug. 9 ... Orville N
Wilbur's, considered the fastest 3-year-old in California earlier
this season, will be given a vacation on the West Coast after
refusing to train after being shipped to Belmont Park to run in the
Riva Ridge Stakes June 6.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
