<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DBACKS-MARINERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOMER BREAKS D-BACKS  
 RODRIGUEZ'S BLAST IN 9TH CLINCHES IT FOR MARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Diamondbacks' first season reached its 81-game
halfway point Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to the question, is their glass half empty or
half full?
</P>
<P>
   After a 6-4 interleague loss to the Seattle Mariners at Bank One
Ballpark, the answer is half empty. More than half-empty.
Two-thirds empty, to be exact, because their record stands at
27-54.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night was a microcosm of the season _ Andy Benes
pitching well at times but not throughout, errors in the field,
baserunning blunders and the inability to get the big hit at the
crucial time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made some mistakes, and they probably cost us,''
Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   So the second half begins today with the team searching for a
way to find more victories and the respectability that comes with
it. It won't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle (34-47) and the Diamondbacks traded solo home runs by
Russ Davis and Yamil Benitez for a 1-1 tie at the end of the second
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Benitez made it 2-1 in the fourth when he drove home Matt
Williams with a single off Seattle left-hander Jeff Fassero (6-5).
</P>
<P>
   The right-handed Benes (6-8) managed to hold the lead until the
sixth inning, when the Mariners scored an unearned run.
</P>
<P>
   Joey Cora led off the inning with a line-drive single to center.
Arizona center fielder Devon White let the ball go under his glove
for a two-base error. Cora went on to score when Alex Rodriguez hit
a slow roller in front of Williams at third base. Rodriguez beat
the throw and moved to second as Williams' throw bounced past first
baseman Travis Lee for an error.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Benes was pitching at full strength at that point was up
for debate.
</P>
<P>
   When he batted against Fassero in the fifth, he popped out to
David Segui at first but hit himself in the left ankle with his
backswing. Benes said it stung but that it didn't affect him.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle took a 4-2 lead in the seventh when Dan Wilson and Rob
Ducey hit back-to-back doubles and Ducey later scored on a single
by Cora. Ducey had been caught in a rundown between second and
third on a bunt attempt in front of the mound by Fassero, but
escaped when Williams missed the tag and he wound up at third.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks pulled to within 4-3 in the eighth, and
probably should have tied it or perhaps even taken the lead, but
couldn't get the job done.
</P>
<P>
   Benitez drove in his third run of the game with a single, and
the Diamondbacks loaded the bases with two outs. But second baseman
Tony Batista grounded into a fielder's choice to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of 48,488 _ the Diamondbacks' 15th sellout of the
season _ sensed the team was still in the game in the ninth, but
the Mariners dimmed their hopes when pinch-hitter Glenallen Hill
hit a shallow single to left field with one out and scored on
Rodriguez's opposite-field home run to right, his 27th of the
season. The shot came off right-hander Bobby Chouinard, who had
replaced Benes after the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   That brought on big right-hander Heathcliff Slocumb to face
Arizona in the ninth. The Mariners' bullpen had been less than
stellar to this point.
</P>
<P>
   Slocumb walked pinch-hitter Andy Fox to lead off the inning, and
David Dellucci drove Fox home with an opposite-field single to left
to make it 6-4. Slocumb escaped trouble and earned his third save
of the season by getting Williams to ground into a 5-4-3 double
play to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   After shutting out Texas for eight innings on Monday night in
Arlington, Benes said he felt good on the mound, striking out a
season-high eight and walking just one.
</P>
<P>
   ``But their guy (Fassero) threw a great game. You have to tip
your cap to Jeff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I pitched well for the most part and have been
recently. Buck expects it, Mark (Connor, pitching coach) expects
it, my teammates expect it and I expect it. I expected to win, but
unfortunately, it didn't happen.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
