<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MENTAL MISTAKES COST D- BACKS  
 2 ERRORS ON SCORE BOARD DON'T TELL WHOLE STORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The scoreboard showed the Diamondbacks made two errors
in their loss to the Seattle Mariners on Saturday night at Bank One
Ballpark. That was the official total. Unofficially, the damage was
worse.
</P>
<P>
   Of the Mariners' runs, two might have been prevented. Meanwhile,
the three Diamondbacks runs could have been expanded upon. Did any
of that make a difference in a 6-4 game?
</P>
<P>
   ``We made some mistakes that probably cost us,'' Manager Buck
Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   For five innings the Diamondbacks demonstrated the how-to
section of the manual. Starter Andy Benes was sharp and the team
was solid. The rest of the game was on what to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The error column on the scoreboard doesn't always indicate how
you play, good or bad,'' said Showalter. ``Tonight we made some
mental errors that cost us.''
</P>
<P>
   Leading off the Seattle sixth, Joey Cora hit a sinking liner to
center field. Had Devon White let the ball bounce in front of him,
Cora would have been held to a single. White knows something about
defense and has seven Gold Gloves to prove it. But he decided to
attempt a shoestring catch. The ball skipped under his glove and
Cora ended up at third, from where it was much easier to score on
Alex Rodriguez's infield single.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Matt Williams threw the ball away on the play, but
Benes cracked down, striking out Ken Griffey Jr, getting David
Segui on a deep fly to center and, after walking Jay Buhner,
striking out Russ Davis, who had homered in the second for the
first Seattle run.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh with the game tied at 2, successive doubles by
Dan Wilson and Rob Ducey put Seattle up, 3-2. Pitcher Jeff Fassero
laid down a bad sacrifice bunt. It went directly to Benes, who had
Ducey dead off second base. Benes ran at Ducey and faked a throw to
second, then fired to Williams at third. Ducey retreated to second
base. Williams threw to shortstop Jay Bell, which caused Ducey to
change direction. Bell then threw back to Williams, but Ducey
already was running past. He avoided the swipe tag and ended up on
third.
</P>
<P>
   And Fassero was on second. So instead of the Diamondbacks having
a runner on first (Fassero) and one out, it was second and third
and none out. Ducey scored on Cora's single, making it 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   Refusing to lay any individual blame, Showalter said, ``We
created a little too much cushion,'' in allowing Ducey to make it
to third.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he didn't know what went wrong, and Bell wasn't
around to take questions. That left it up to Benes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way you execute the rundown is to make the runner commit
one way or another,'' he said. ``I take responsibility because the
guy (Ducey) was in the middle of the diamond. But, as a starting
pitcher, you're not used to running and throwing the ball. Nine
times out of 10 we get the guy out. Tonight, we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by two, the Diamondbacks scored a run in the eighth.
But they might have had more. David Dellucci led off with a single
and Williams singled to put runners on first and third with none
out. Travis Lee then topped a ball in front of the plate. Dellucci
broke for home, changed his mind and was thrown out trying to get
back to third.
</P>
<P>
   Now the tying run no longer was 90 feet from home plate. Yamil
Benitez eventually drove in Williams for his third RBI of the game,
but that was it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
