<P>
   Rankings reflect sales figures for the week ending June 20,
1998, at almost 4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 60,000
other retailers, statistically weighted to represent sales in all
such outlets nationwide. The number of titles within the two
subdivisions of non-fiction can change from week to week,
reflecting changes in book buying.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) following a book's ranking indicates that a book's sales
are barely distinguishable from those of the book above. A (b)
indicates that some bookstores report receiving bulk orders for a
book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. UNNATURAL EXPOSURE, by Patricia Cornwell. (Berkley, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kay Scarpetta contends with a killer who uses smallpox-like
</P>
<P>
   virus and cyberspace tricks.
</P>
<P>
   2. ORPHANS: BUTTERFLY and CRYSTAL, by V.C. Andrews. (Pocket,
$3.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A troubled orphan is adopted by a couple who hope she will
</P>
<P>
   become a ballerina.
</P>
<P>
   3. THE HORSE WHISPERER, by Nicholas Evans. (Dell, $7.50.)
</P>
<P>
   A woman seeks solace for her daughter and their horse from
</P>
<P>
   a wrangler.
</P>
<P>
   4. FAT TUESDAY, by Sandra Brown. (Warner Vision, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A cop and a sinister attorney's wife go on a tear in
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans during Mardi Gras.
</P>
<P>
   5. THE ANGEL OF DARKNESS, by Caleb Carr. (Ballantine, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   The pursuit of the kidnapper of a Spanish diplomat's child
</P>
<P>
   in 1897 Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   6. DIVINE SECRETS OF THE YA-YA SISTERHOOD, by Rebecca Wells.
</P>
<P>
   (Harper Perennial, $13.50.) Three generations of
</P>
<P>
   Southern women.
</P>
<P>
   7. (x) SHE'S COME UNDONE, by Wall Lamb. (Pocket, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A woman's harrowing progress from youth to middle age.
</P>
<P>
   8. BREATH, EYES, MEMORY, by Edwidge Danticat. (Vintage, $11.)
</P>
<P>
   The experiences of a girl coming of age in New York
</P>
<P>
   and Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   9. THE GOD OF SMALL THINGS, by Arundhati Roy. (Harper
</P>
<P>
   Perennial, $13.) Death and secrets haunt a once-prosperous
</P>
<P>
   family in India.
</P>
<P>
   10. PRETEND YOU DON'T SEE HER, by Mary Higgins Clark.
</P>
<P>
   (Pocket, $7.99.) A chance witness to a murder
</P>
<P>
   must live anonymously to save her life.
</P>
<P>
   11. THE NOTEBOOK, by Nicholas Sparks. (Warner Vision, $5.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A World War II veteran meets an old flame who is
</P>
<P>
   about to be married.
</P>
<P>
   12. UP ISLAND, by Anne Rivers Siddons. (Harper Paperbacks,
</P>
<P>
   $6.99.) An Atlanta woman, after a bad marriage and the death
</P>
<P>
   of her mother, seeks a new life in Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   13. THE PRESIDENT'S DAUGHTER, by Jack Higgins.
</P>
<P>
   (Berkley, $6.99.) The president of the United States
</P>
<P>
   copes with kidnappers who threaten to kill his love child.
</P>
<P>
   14. (x) THREE WISHES, by Barbara Delinsky. (Pocket, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A woman recovering consciousness in a hospital has to
</P>
<P>
   make life-changing decisions.
</P>
<P>
   15. THE NIGHT CREW, by John Sandford. (Berkley, $7.50)
</P>
<P>
   A video crew patrolling Los Angeles for news is beset
</P>
<P>
   by a series of violent deaths.
</P>
