<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-28 12:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0651 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     06-28 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, July 5.)  
 (HLW)  
 By SCOTT VEALE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ALREADY DEAD: A CALIFORNIA GOTHIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Denis Johnson. Harper Perennial, $13.
</P>
<P>
   In this creepy novel populated by a large cast of petty crooks
and wack jobs, an alcoholic marijuana grower facing the twin
threats of disinheritance and retaliation for a cocaine deal gone
bad cooks up a wild scheme with a Nietzsche-quoting drifter. ``Once
Johnson gets his hooks into you -- it takes about two sentences --
it's ... pretty much impossible to stop reading,'' David Gates
wrote here last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AMERICAN SCRIPTURE: MAKING THE DECLARATION OF INDEPENDENCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Pauline Maier. Vintage, $14.
</P>
<P>
   This feisty and highly original study, selected as one of the
best books of 1997 by the editors of the Book Review, presents the
Declaration of Independence as the embodiment of the American mind
and Colonial experience rather than as a product of Thomas
Jefferson's pen or the expression of some philosophy of natural
rights. By placing the document in the context of 90 previous
declarations issued throughout the colonies, the author ``offers
Americans a fresh perspective on their most treasured national
relic,'' Richard Alan Ryerson wrote here last year.  &UR; ANGEL IN THE
WHIRLWIND: THE TRIUMPH OF THE AMERICAN REVOLUTION &LR; , by Benson
Bobrick (Penguin, $15.95), reminds readers that the Revolutionary
War was full of amazing stories and characters -- led by a
heaven-sent hero (George Washington) and a world-class villain
(Benedict Arnold). Bobrick ``has studied his subject deeply and
writes about it with real understanding and verve,'' Frederick
Allen said in these pages in 1997. In  &UR; THE LONG AFFAIR: THOMAS
JEFFERSON AND THE FRENCH REVOLUTION, 1785-1800 &LR; , by Conor Cruise
O'Brien (University of Chicago, $15), an Irish author locates a
strain of visionary violence in Jefferson's near-religious defense
of the Revolution. In 1996, Richard Brookhiser said this ``cranky
and sweeping'' narrative ``goes a long way to show that the bust
has shoulders of clay.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHITTAKER CHAMBERS: A BIOGRAPHY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Sam Tanenhaus. Modern Library, $16.
</P>
<P>
   The accuser of Alger Hiss gets sympathetic, but not
hagiographic, treatment in this copious biography, which sheds new
light on its famously enigmatic protagonist, especially his
post-Hiss existence. Last year in the Book Review, Arthur
Schlesinger Jr. called this a ``serious and absorbing work.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEDICINE MEN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Alice Adams. Washington Square/Pocket Books, $14.
</P>
<P>
   The author demolishes the divine right of American doctorhood by
having her 40-ish heroine wonder whether her crushing headaches are
an allergic reaction to her physicians -- all of them men. Last
year our reviewer, Deborah Mason, lamented the unrelenting
doctor-bashing but said the novel ``in many ways ... is
representative of the bracing frankness and tart ironies of the
Adams oeuvre.'' The same publisher has reissued  &UR; SUPERIOR WOMEN &LR; 
($14), a melancholy group portrait that follows five mismatched
Radcliffe girls -- rich, poor, fat, thin -- through four decades of
growing disappointment and crises of midlife and identity. In 1984
in these pages, Lois Gould admired Adams' ``elegant, rhythmic
style'' and ``fine, wry logic.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE LAST GIFT OF TIME: LIFE BEYOND SIXTY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Carolyn G. Heilbrun. Ballantine, $12.
</P>
<P>
   Turning 70, a feminist pioneer and scholar looks back on the
unexpected pleasures, friendships and rewards of her 60s. This
buoyant collection of revelations and reflections is ``like a
letter to a friend, the kind you don't lie to,'' Rebecca Pepper
Sinkler wrote here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRACES: STORIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Ida Fink. Translated by Philip Boehm and Francine Prose.
Owl/Holt, $12.
</P>
<P>
   These spare, lucid tales about everyday life among the Jewish
bourgeoisie in Nazi-era Poland mix normalcy with terror, revealing
the avid need of accountants, housewives and piano students to live
fully even in the shadow of death. ``Fink's gift is for the
delicate miniature, the oblique detail that freezes the reader's
heart,'' Fernanda Eberstadt said here last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OUR GUYS: THE GLEN RIDGE RAPE AND THE SECRET LIFE OF THE
PERFECT SUBURB &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Bernard Lefkowitz. Vintage, $15.
</P>
<P>
   This disturbing account of the highly publicized rape of a
mentally retarded girl by a group of teen-age athletes suggests
that similar crimes are being committed across the nation and that
much of the fault lies in America's cult of the sports hero. Last
year in the Book Review, Russell Banks called this ``a calm,
methodical, painstakingly researched book ... that should be read
by parents and educators alike.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOWLOON TONG &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Paul Theroux. Mariner, $12.
</P>
<P>
   A British mother and her 43-year-old son living in Hong Kong
confront the imminent ``Chinese take-away'' with passive rage and
resentment in this novel. ``Theroux's astringent misanthropy and
narrative momentum are powerful propellants,'' Thomas Keneally
wrote here in 1997. Many of the 60-odd tales in Theroux's
 &UR; COLLECTED STORIES &LR;  (Penguin, $15.95) are inhabited by ordinary
no-nonsense people who find themselves immersed in Gothic
goings-on, or solitary narrators whose anonymity is threatened by
outside forces. ``Theroux displays ... a remarkable ear,'' William
H. Pritchard wrote here last year. ``He ... inhabits his sentences
in a rewardingly comic way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
