<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOW SHANGHAI BECAME A CITY OF THE 21ST CENTURY
 &HT;    With CHINA-CLINTON; CHINA-YOUTH-$ADV29.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service (at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI _ A precis of how Shanghai grew:
</P>
<P>
   1000-1800 A.D. _ Port. Shanghai expands from an obscure village
into a quiet fishing port because of its favorable location 12
miles from the confluence of the Yangtze River and the Pacific
Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   1842 _ Concession. After defeating Chinese imperial armies in
the Opium Wars, Britain imposes the Treaty of Nanking. The British
occupy the choicest sector of Shanghai as a mini-colony known as a
``concession.'' The Americans, French and Japanese soon build their
own concessions.
</P>
<P>
   1900-1935 _ Sin. Shanghai is the richest, most elegant and most
decadent city in Asia. Western businessmen and rich Chinese cavort
in 688 brothels, some the size of factories. Opium dens operate
with impunity. An upper crust of Westerners plays billiards in the
Shanghai Club on the waterfront and bets on thoroughbreds at the
Race Club.
</P>
<P>
   July, 1921 _ Stirrings. Shanghai's wretched slums incubate the
Chinese Communist Party. Mao Tse-tung and 12 other representatives
of Communist cells meet over tea in a house off Huaihai Street to
form a national communist party.
</P>
<P>
   1926 _ Protest. Marshal Sun Chuanfang begins a campaign to evict
the British, French, American and other concession-holders from
their Shanghai enclaves. He calls the concessions a ``humiliation''
because they are ``a long-standing reminder of our loss of
sovereignty.''
</P>
<P>
   1937-1945 _ Decline. Under Japanese occupation, Shanghai
withers. Silt clogs the port and nearby Huangpu River because no
one dredges it for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   May 1949 _ Takeover. Mao's troops march into Shanghai. They
impose steep taxes, destroy some of the worst slums and send off
hundreds of prostitutes known as ``sing-song girls'' for
``re-education.'' The fleeing Nationalist Chinese forces carry off
Bank of China's gold reserves to Taiwan, leaving Shanghai's
treasury empty.
</P>
<P>
   July 1985 _ Rebound. Former English teacher Jiang Zemin, China's
future president, is appointed Shanghai mayor by Beijing communist
authorities. He cultivates a populist image and brings in foreign
investment. Shanghai's economy grows by 110 percent in 1986. Jiang
is promoted to China's Politburo in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   April 1990 _ Takeoff. Ten months after the Tiananmen Square
massacre, Beijing decides to pour massive resources into Shanghai
to turn the city into an ultra-modern high-tech port. A
150-square-mile special zone on the Pudong peninsula is accorded
tax and customs privileges to draw in foreign banks and
manufacturers. Shanghai's economy starts to soar.
</P>
<P>
   Late 1997 _ Bursting. By some estimates, 20 percent of the
world's construction sites are in Shanghai. Five years ago, the
city had one 20-story building. Now it has 966, and dozens more are
under construction.
</P>
<P>
   For clients of the New York Times News Service.(at)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
