<SLUG> BC-US-CHINA-ANALYSIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AND JIANG CHANGE THE U.S.-CHINA ATMOSPHERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ORVILLE SCHELL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ President Clinton, while bantering with Chinese
President Jiang Zemin, looked out over the assemblage of
international press and high-ranking Chinese and U.S. officials and
declared:
</P>
<P>
   ``And let me say something that will perhaps be unpopular with
everyone.'' The room fell absolutely silent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have spent time with the Dalai Lama,'' he continued
insouciantly. ``I believe him to be an honest man, and I believe if
he had a conversation with President Jiang, they would like each
other very much.''
</P>
<P>
   A collective gasp of incredulity was followed by an
uncharacteristic burst of nervous laughter, and then a round of
enthusiastic applause.
</P>
<P>
   It was evident that something very unusual had just transpired.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours earlier on Saturday, Clinton's policy of
``constructive engagement'' seemed on the verge of crashing and
burning in a nightmare of recriminations by both Republicans and
some of his fellow Democrats that he was selling out to ``the
butchers of Beijing.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing on the Western edge of Tiananmen Square, as he and
Jiang reviewed a goose-stepping, bayonet-toting Chinese military
honor guard and howitzers began booming out a 21-gun salute near
the very monument where students had headquartered themselves
during the 1989 demonstrations, it was difficult to imagine how the
grim-faced Clinton was going to extricate himself from such
evocatively negative imagery.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as he walked up the granite steps into the Great Hall,
past the place where the students had kneeled with the petition of
a redress of grievances raised in supplication above their heads,
Clinton looked rather like a wild animal frozen helplessly in the
headlights of an on-rushing vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, a mere three hours later, as Clinton and Jiang appeared
together to make joint statements and answer questions, the mood
had almost completely changed.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials were flashing each other relieved smiles,
and Chinese Foreign Ministry officials and Beijing reporters were
watching with rapt attention as subjects long taboo in this shrine
to Communist Party orthodoxy _ human rights, Tibet, arrests of
dissidents and more _ were discussed with a frankness and
directness unprecedented in America's often tortured relations with
China.
</P>
<P>
   As those of us in the press corps milled around afterward,
trying to assess what we had just heard, we were further stunned to
learn that the entire event had been broadcast live over Central
Chinese Television to China's 1.2 billion people.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody familiar with China who had sat through endless
uninspired and rigidly scripted briefings and exchanges that have
usually passed for ``big leader'' dialogue could be anything but
amazed by the frankness with which these two leaders were virtually
debating with each other.
</P>
<P>
   What the exchange seemed to suggest was that the People's
Republic was edging up to an important watershed.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, attempts to discuss such sensitive issues had
usually provoked indignant allegations that the United States was
``interfering in the internal affairs of China'' or was ``hurting
the feelings of the Chinese people.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Jiang's forum suggested that the Chinese leadership was
struggling to enter a new era in which it would not only attempt to
proclaim a great power, but in which its leader would begin to
deport himself like one.
</P>
<P>
   A single robin hardly heralds springtime, and China continues to
be beset by numerous, daunting economic problems that could easily
balloon into grave political upheaval jeopardizing the present
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Jiang's apparent new confidence and the new-found
camaraderie with Clinton hint that the White House policy of
``constructive engagement'' could be leading to a closer engagement
between the two countries on issues of agreement. This enhanced
level of comfort also could help each side raise sensitive and
long-embargoed issues that have bedeviled ``the relationship''
without raising fears of causing a loss of face and derailment.
</P>
<P>
   Even though this summit accomplished no specific breakthrough,
no one who has been watching China over the past several decades
could fail to mark the occasion as anything but an event of
significance.
</P>
<P>
   What we will all be watching, over the weeks to come, is whether
this change in atmosphere will help lead to a resolution of some of
the issues that have kept the Sino-U.S. relationship from entering
a truly ``normal'' phase.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Orville Schell, dean of the Graduate School of Journalism at
UC-Berkeley, is the author of numerous books on China, including
``Mandate of Heaven'' and the forthcoming ``Virtual Tibet.'')
</P>
</TEXT>
