<P>
   INTERNET-ACTIVISTS (Undated) _ As the Internet industry prepares
to gather in Washington this week to begin planning for the future
of self-governance mapped out under the Clinton administration's
recent ``domain names'' recommendation, the role of influential
citizen-activists like David Farber and others is becoming
increasingly important. Farber and a handful of others are known
for their lists, which circulate polemics, policy positions and
cries from the heart that help frame the Internet issues of the
day. And these days, to be on the recipient lists is to be part of
the Net's constitutional convention. By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUSA-COMPUTERCITY (Dallas) _ CompUSA, the leading computer
retailer, has expanded its reach by agreeing to acquire Tandy's
struggling Computer City chain last week for $275 million. But in
view of falling PC prices, soft demand, and increasing pressure
from online computer retailing, how does CompUSA plan to protect
its profit margins? By Allen R. Myerson.
</P>
<P>
   INTEL-SUIT-REACT (Washington) _ In the weeks since the federal
government filed its suit against Intel, the world's largest
manufacturer of microprocessor chips, the company has remained
largely silent, unwilling to offer anything more than the most
rudimentary public defense. And while Microsoft representatives
have been aggressively lobbying Congress and the administration,
Intel's are nowhere to be seen _ except at the trade commission. By
Joel Brinkley.
