<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-28 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0753 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT&AMP;T-TCI-MARKETPLACE-     06-28 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-TCI-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHILE SHAREHOLDERS WILL DO WELL, TCI'S CHAIRMAN WILL GET VERY
RICH 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a mere eight days of negotiations, John Malone, the wily
chairman of Tele-Communications Inc., struck a good deal for
shareholders _ and an even richer deal for himself by agreeing to
sell his company to AT&AMP;T Corp. for $31.8 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal announced last week, the class B
shares of TCI stock, known as supervoting shares because they carry
10 votes each, will get 9.7 percent more per share in AT&AMP;T stock
than TCI's class A shares will receive.
</P>
<P>
   Malone owns an estimated 30 million class B shares, or more than
half of the outstanding 50 million class B shares, compared with
just 1.5 million class A shares, a fraction of the 472 million
outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Investors could be forgiven for not noticing just how rich
Malone's premium is because an AT&AMP;T official on Friday could not
say how many class B shares Malone owned or how many were
outstanding, and even TCI officials said they were unable to supply
definitive numbers.
</P>
<P>
   There's more for Malone, who is retaining virtual control of
Liberty Media Corp., TCI's cable programming company, which will
have a much stronger financial base. The deal allows Liberty to
sell a handful of key assets to the parent company, retain the cash
from those sales and avoid any capital gains tax.
</P>
<P>
   And if Liberty is ever sold, Liberty's shareholders, led by
Malone, will get the profit, not AT&AMP;T shareholders. Once again,
Malone is rolling in Liberty's supervoting B shares.
</P>
<P>
   How did Malone pull it off? AT&AMP;T wanted TCI's cable systems, and
it was willing to pay mightily for them.
</P>
<P>
   Based on AT&AMP;T's closing price on Friday, Malone will receive
$48.42 in AT&AMP;T stock for each class B share, or $1.4 billion. Each
class A share will be bought for $44.02.
</P>
<P>
   Making the deal even sweeter for Malone is his right to buy 14
million more class B shares from the estate of TCI's former
chairman, Bob Magness. Malone can buy at the market price any time
before June 30, 1999. The status of these 14 million shares
contributed to the confusion on Friday about the number of class B
shares outstanding. Malone is believed to have bought six million
of those shares already.
</P>
<P>
   If Malone does wind up with 38 million class B shares, he would
get $167.2 million more from the AT&AMP;T deal than would the holders
of a comparable number of A shares. Little wonder then, that
although the class A and B shares traded at roughly the same price
before the deal, by Friday's close of the stock market, the class B
shares were priced at $42.375, while the class A shares were
selling for only $38.6875.
</P>
<P>
   Neither AT&AMP;T nor TCI wanted to tamper with the structure of TCI,
which is a holding company with three separately traded units: TCI,
the cable company, Liberty Media, the programming company, and TCI
Ventures, which owns stakes in Internet, international cable and
local phone businesses. Breaking up the units would have resulted
in huge capital gains taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But AT&AMP;T did not want to buy Liberty or TCI Ventures. So AT&AMP;T
agreed that Liberty would continue to trade separately from the
parent company as a tracking stock but that TCI Ventures would be
absorbed, a slight move toward simplification. Tracking stocks
reflect the performance of a group of assets technically owned by a
parent company _ in this case TCI, soon to be AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   But the Liberty assets will be controlled by Liberty
shareholders. Malone, again through supervoting class B shares,
controls Liberty. One advantage of a tracking stock is that its
underlying assets can be swapped with assets in the parent company
without incurring taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Using this provision, Malone is transferring to AT&AMP;T several
assets under the control of Liberty and TCI Ventures, including a
stake in Teleport Communications and At Home Corp., for $5.5
billion in cash. AT&AMP;T had previously agreed to buy Teleport with
stock. It also agreed to buy Liberty's stake in At Home in cash.
The new Liberty will now get cash in both deals and avoid taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is that he has exchanged $5.5 billion of assets tax
free _ which is part of the beauty of the whole tracking-stock
issues,'' said Alan Gould, an analyst at Gerard Klauer Mattison.
``They convert these low tax-based assets and sell them at full
private market value, tax free. They had a very low tax basis in
both Teleport and At Home,'' meaning an ordinary transaction would
have led to a sizable gain.
</P>
<P>
   Malone in return gets a war chest for his use at Liberty. Though
Malone has said that Liberty will probably generate losses because
of its leasing deals, he has a history of building asset value and
then selling those assets at a markup.
</P>
<P>
   Tracking stocks have some liabilities. Should AT&AMP;T lose money,
its creditors could look to Liberty to make up the difference. But
Malone, who over the years has made his fortune selling assets, is
betting he will be able to do it again with Liberty. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-98 1607EDT &QL; 
