<HEADER>
A0758 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATENTS-NYT     06-28 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATENTS: CELL INSERTS MAY ONE DAY GROW NEW ORGANS, AVOIDING
TRANSPLANTS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Mass., Calif.) (fb) 
By SABRA CHARTRAND   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although it may sound like science fiction to suggest that human
cells can be inserted into the body and engineered to grow into new
organs, two Boston institutions have won a series of patents for
exactly such technology.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology and
Children's Hospital of Boston won three patents this month that
medical scientists hope will someday mean that patients in need of
a transplant can grow their own healthy new hearts, kidneys, livers
or other organs.
</P>
<P>
   Though the invention has the potential to revolutionize organ
transplanting, shortening waiting lists and controversy over organ
supplies, that day is by no means around the corner. The company
that licensed the three patents says it is just now preparing for
clinical trials using the new technology to grow tissues like
muscle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to try and show proof of principle in efficacy in
structural tissues first _ skin, bone, muscle,'' said Gail K.
Naughton, president of Advanced Tissue Sciences in La Jolla, Calif.
``Once medicine sees utility for these tissues, we'll go into more
complicated organs whose major functions are not structural but
systemic. The liver not only detoxifies, but makes all the protein
in the body, for example.''
</P>
<P>
   Medicine has long depended on tissue grown outside the body _
known as ex-vivo engineering _ for transplants of cartilage, blood
vessels and skin. Skin grown in a laboratory is commonly grafted to
burn victims. But skin is generally considered easy to implant.
Other tissues can be grown in a laboratory, but the ex-vivo results
are much harder to transplant to a patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advantage of in-vivo is it offers the ability to actually
treat the patient based on their condition in a way that is most
advantageous to them,'' Naughton said. ``Say you have a skeletal
muscle defect and you're missing a large part of the muscle. A
skeletal muscle has to have a certain orientation, the fibers run a
certain way, and you don't want any scarring there. It's difficult
to grow a muscle outside the body to mimic the exact type of
structure, fibers and orientation.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you put the cells inside the muscle, they can rely on
the body's own chemical signals for the pattern of the tissue, as
well as the physiological forces around the muscle, to prompt the
proper orientation and growth.''
</P>
<P>
   The three patents describe a process of growing tissue that
begins in a laboratory. Human cells are seeded on a
three-dimensional, biocompatible and biodegradable scaffolding
built from ordinary surgical suture material. Naughton said her
company usually used a dissolving suture material called
polyglycolic acid because the rate at which it dissolves can be
controlled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crux of the discovery is if you put the cells in the right
three-dimensional orientation and the right distance apart, they
are able to get oxygen and nutrients and they then form a tissue,''
she said. Tissue grown outside the body needs bioreactors to pump
nutrients and oxygen into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new patents take advantage of the ability to use the blood
and oxygen supply in the body,'' Naughton said, ``so as long as you
use the right dimension of scaffolding, the cells get immediate
oxygen and nutrients supplies from the surrounding tissues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds simple, but it's taken decades to find the right
pore size and the right rate of scaffolding dissolving,'' she
added, ``so that as it dissolves it is replaced by the new tissue.
Otherwise, the cells die.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the cells are seeded on the scaffolding, the tiny mesh
structure is implanted into the body in the spot where replacement
tissue is needed. Then it incubates and grows into tissue,
replacing diseased tissue until it is contiguous with and
indistinguishable from the patient's own, healthy tissue. Naughton
cited one hypothetical example, of a baby born with a
malfunctioning liver, and said it would take four to six weeks for
the baby to grow enough new liver tissue to solve its problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say a child is born with a metabolic disorder _ he's missing
an enzyme,'' she said. ``Right now we can grow liver tissue outside
the body, but incorporating it into the body is a very, very
difficult because the liver is a very complicated organ. But if we
grow the cells in-vivo, inside the child's own body, the blood
flow, hormones and growth factors of the child's own liver will
help those cells grow into a new liver and that new liver will
replace the enzyme. The child doesn't need an entire new liver to
get those enzymes.''
</P>
<P>
   But such a treatment would only work if a patient had time to
wait for new tissues to grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our approach is that if a patient is in an emergency situation
and needs to put a whole tissue on the body, then growing it
outside the body makes sense,'' Naughton said. Skin for burn
victims, for example, is grown in a laboratory so it will be
readily available. ``If you have more time and the success of the
transplant relies on how the implant orients itself with the rest
of the patient's body, then using these new patents makes sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Advanced Tissue Sciences has conducted animal trials using the
new patents to grow pancreas, gastrointestinal tracts, bone,
ligaments, skeletal muscle, cardiac muscle and livers. The company
hopes to begin clinical trials with human cells soon, and
ultimately to create a technology that will allow doctors to
implant cells that will grow into parts of or whole new organs.
</P>
<P>
   Naughton said she expected surgeons would someday remove part of
a liver riddled with cancer and prompt the body to grow a healthy
replacement, or implant a scaffolding bearing heart cells next to a
diseased heart and simply wait for a whole new heart to grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not science fiction,'' she said. ``What we've seen in
tissue engineering in the last few years that people might have
called science fiction has rapidly become science fact. Once we
have the scaffolding, it's no longer science fiction to see these
other possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph P. Vacanti, a pediatric surgeon at Children's Hospital of
Boston, and Robert S. Langer, a polymer chemist at MIT, won patents
5,759,830, 5,770,193, and 5,770,417.
</P>
<P>
   Patents are available by number for $3 from the Patent and
Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
