<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-28 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0767 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRAMER-PROFILE-MEDIA-     06-28 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRAMER-PROFILE-MEDIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUND MANAGER RAISES CONFLICT ISSUES AS ONLINE STOCK COLUMNIST
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV.: a photo for use with this story is being sent to NYT
photo clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by
calling 212 556-4204.) 
 (ja) 
 By LISA NAPOLI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On a white board in the newsroom of TheStreet.com, an
investment news service published on the World Wide Web, staffers
keep a running list titled the ``self-importance meter.'' The
entrants vary, but, inevitably, somewhere in the ranking is the
name James J. Cramer.
</P>
<P>
   Cramer happens to be the service's co-founder, as well as one of
its marquee columnists. He writes three daily bombastic missives,
dispatched via e-mail to 18,000 subscribers, under the rubric
``Wrong!''
</P>
<P>
   His reach extends well beyond the computer terminal and this has
made Cramer a kind of Zelig of the information age, cutting across
all media and raising the issue of his own involvement in the
market as the manager of a $350 million private investment firm.
Cramer, 43, appears as a commentator on ABC's ``Good Morning
America,'' as a guest co-host on CNBC and in print with regular
columns in GQ and The New York Observer; he also has alliances with
online ventures including America Online and Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   It is the Internet, he said, that provides immediacy to match
his freneticism, and that of the financial markets he covers.
``I've been waiting for this medium to be built all my life,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   From the offices of his investment fund on Wall Street, he
monitors the markets from a bank of computer terminals that proffer
data and news, zipping off e-mail between trades in an environment
which makes a typical newsroom appear sleepy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not capable of thinking of anything in terms other than
stocks,'' he said. He described a meeting with an executive at
Disney, which owns ABC and whose Web site TheStreet.com supplies
with financial news and for which he recently did a television
pilot. ``All I could think about was, ``Disney's stock is down
today,'` he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Cramer is betting on the notion that the rapid ups and downs of
the stock market make for compelling Internet fare, matching the
rapid-fire pace of the new medium. Cramer is hoping that the
growing sector of home investors, as well as the financial
professionals, who comprise 60 percent of the customers who pay
$9.95 a month for his wisdom, will translate into a publishing
success.
</P>
<P>
   Those who follow the world of online business news said it would
be a difficult market to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a huge number of competitors and some of them are
extremely well funded, everything from The Wall Street Journal
Online, to brokerages that are looking at ways of putting content
on line,'' said Mike Gazala, an analyst with Forrester Research in
Boston. He expressed doubt that TheStreet.com, with a staff of 30
and little brand recognition, could amass a large enough audience
to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beyond Jim Cramer, I don't think there's much there,'' Gazala
said. ``If you took away Jim Cramer, you wouldn't have too many
people visiting that `street.'''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Cramer remains the allure. Recently, he and his
co-founder, Martin Peretz, the owner and editor-in-chief of the New
Republic, received $10 million in venture capital financing from a
syndicate led by the investment firms Flatiron Partners, Chase
Capital Partners and Softbank Technology Ventures, who are now
minority stakeholders in the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very important trend,'' said Jerry Colonna,
co-founder of Flatiron Partners, of the quest for investment
information on line. He said that Cramer's cantankerous and
shoot-from-the-hip style of presentation was a major reason for the
investment.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Kansas, editor of TheStreet.com, conceded that Cramer's
involvement as manager of an investment firm presents an editorial
challenge. Some prospective employees have been concerned, he
conceded, that Cramer's dual life as a money manager and journalist
sullies the credibility of the financial news service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had people we've tried to hire who said they're not
comfortable with the perception,'' Kansas said.
</P>
<P>
   When he first conceived of TheStreet.com, Cramer said, he
approached the Securities and Exchange Commission to ask advice on
how to set up the business to avoid conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of conflicts of interest is not a new one for Cramer.
In 1995, while a contributor to Smart Money magazine, Cramer was
widely criticized for an article that he wrote recommending the
stocks of several small companies in which he owned large stakes.
The article did not make note of those holdings. As a result of the
incident, Smart Money changed its policies, restricting
contributors from writing about stocks in which they own large
positions or which are thinly traded and adding disclosures about
the stock holdings of contributors.
</P>
<P>
   At TheStreet.com, rules were instituted under which Cramer would
not have any editorial control beyond his column. All his columns,
writings and television appearances are accompanied by disclaimers
of some kind.
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean he skirts controversy, however. In January
1997, Cramer, through his fund, bought up 1.1 million shares of Dow
Jones stock, and was one of three big stockholders using their
investment to push the company to sell off Telerate, its financial
information business. He sold off most of his shares five months
later when it became clear they would not. (Cramer said he took
great pleasure in the fact that Dow Jones ultimately did sell
Telerate earlier this year.)
</P>
<P>
   For Kansas, the scrutiny of the medium in which he publishes is
a bigger issue than critics of Cramer's possible conflicts. ``To
me, the mainstream medium likes to harp on the potentially scary
issues relating to the Internet. We have to work very hard to rise
above that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
