<P>
   EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Monday, June 29. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (212-556-1927).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA:
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SUMMIT (Beijing) _ President Clinton's day: A Protestant
church service, touring the Great Wall and Forbidden City, and
dinner with President Jiang Zemin. Topping in later editions with
Monday morning speech at Beijing University. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-LAMA (Leh, Ladakh) _ The Dalai Lama reacts to the summit.
By John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   BLACKS-AIDS (Washington) _ Seventeen years after AIDS was first
recognized among gay white men in New York and San Francisco, the
disease inthis country is becoming largely an epidemic among black
people, quietly devastating families and neighborhoods, yet all but
ignored by leading black institutions. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   MCDOUGAL-LEGAL (Undated) _ The look on her face was sheer joy as
Susan McDougal savored the freedom granted her last week by a
federal judge in Arkansas. But she will have little time to
celebrate or relax. Mrs. McDougal is scheduled to be summoned to
another courtroom to face another prosecutor on July 13. And this
time the charges she faces have nothing to do with politics,
Clinton or Whitewater, but with bilking one of the most famous
names in classical music. By Jill Abramson.
</P>
<P>
   NEWHAMPSHIRE-TAX-POLITICS (Concord, N.H.) _ New Hampshire finds
itself in a fix because of its Supreme Court's ruling last December
that it can no longer fund its schools almost solely though local
property taxes. For among the politicians charged with finding a
way out of it, the mood here is one of intensive and agonizing
search for an answer; the sweat that blotches shirts doesn't come
only from the lack of air conditioning in the 182-year old State
House.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded f)
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-TCI (Undated) _ A followup on AT&AMP;T deal with TCI: a broad
look at how the world of communications is being reshaped by a rash
of deals, with the implications for consumers. Also, who is being
left out in the cold? By Steve Lohr.
</P>
