<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CLINTON-O629 _ BEIJING _ As President Bill Clinton was
trodding the Great Wall Sunday, neighboring India slammed his
attempt to use his weekend summit talks with China to cool off the
Pakistan-India nuclear testing crisis. ``India categorically
rejects the notion of these two countries abrogating to themselves
joint or individual responsibility for the maintanance of peace,
stability and security in the region,'' said an Indian Foreign
Ministry statement. It was issued first in New Delhi late Saturday
and then echoed Sunday in a second statement by the Indian embassy
in Beijing. India, which exploded five underground nuclear test
devices in early May, vented its anger at a ``presidential joint
statement on South Asia'' issued Saturday by Clinton and Chinese
president Jiang Zemin. (Albright/Kunstel , Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With CHINA-YOUTH-$ADV29 _ BEIJING _ China's new graduates are a
rare tribe _ more informed, more free, more pampered and more
job-pressured than any generation since the 1949 communist
revolution. They herald a new round of university students unbowed
by the burden of their country's tumultuous recent past, as they
take their turn at molding its future. (Albright, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   With CHINA-HISTBOX-$ADV29 _ Shanghai history, from a scummy
colonial city with 600 brothels to a 21st-century mega-city.
(Albright , Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Main to move, sidebars to be resent by 1:30 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: The main will be topped or inserted with Clinton speech on
China at Beijing University, expected sometime between 8 p.m and
10:30 p.m. Sunday EDT. (Clinton scheduled to start speaking about
10 p.m. EDT, but there is some prospect of getting an advance text
at 8 p.m. EDT. Clinton's speech will be followed by a Q&AMP;A with
Beijing University students, probably about 11 p.m EDT. The Beijing
University speech may or may not be televised in China, we still
don't know.)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   SIERRACLUB _ The Sierra Club, one of the nation's leading
environmental groups, conjures images of California's pristine
mountains. But the tax-exempt foundation also strikes fear in the
hearts of many incumbents around the country as one of the most
aggressively negative issue advertisers in elections. This year,
the Sierra Club is targeting 18-20 districts around the country,
from North Carolina to California. New ads begin airing June 29.
(Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GOP-ENVIRONMENT _ Tired of their bad image on the environment,
Republicans are hoping to turn around public perception with the
help of a new group that intends to mount issue ads in the fall
elections. (Sherman, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-MAIN _ The World AIDS Conference opens in Geneva with
opening speeches. (Kim, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-VACCINE _ An AIDS vaccine is the only way to completely
halt the epidemic, say researchers. But a working vaccine is at
least 10 years away. Sunday the International AIDS Vaccine
Initiative unveils its blueprint for accelerated vaccine
development, which calls for intensifying government and private
sector efforts, at the World AIDS Conference in Geneva. Other
highlights of the gathering of 11,000 researchers, community
leaders and drug company representatives from about 150 countries
worldwide. (Kim, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   PEDOPHILE-PRIESTS _ JEMEZ SPRINGS, N.M. _ Where Highway 4 bends
through the canyon between mesas and ponderosa pines, a half-hour
from Los Alamos, the Catholic church
</P>
<P>
   tried for four decades to treat some of its worst pedophile
priests. New Mexico became ground zero for an explosion of sexual
abuse cases. (Moffett, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
