<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TASTER-ICECREAM-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMONG TASTE-TESTERS, HE'S THE (ICE) CREAM OF THE CROP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSAN PHINNEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Harrison gets paid for eating ice cream _ a sweet
occupation he pays for with chubby cheeks and taste buds that need
constant pampering.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison, official taster for Dreyer's Grand Ice Cream, avoids
coffee, onions, garlic or other strong flavors that might dirty his
palate. He doesn't smoke or drink. A pepperoni pizza on Friday
night is a big deal for this guy.
</P>
<P>
   By Sunday, however, he's back on the bland wagon, especially if
he's tasting on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison's family has been in the ice cream business for four
generations. Seventeen years ago, Dreyer's, based in Oakland,
Calif., lured him away from his father's flavoring company to
become their ``flavorologist.''
</P>
<P>
   As the company's official taster, he tests samples at three
different stages of a production run, 60 ice creams per tasting. He
also trains other tasters and sales people and travels the country
educating people about ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   It's a subject he knows well. His great grandfather had ice
cream stores in New York City. His grandfather had a dairy co-op in
Tennessee and his dad owned Dari-Tech, a Georgia company that made
ice cream flavorings.
</P>
<P>
   Ice cream was always the topic of family conversations. And it's
almost always on the tip of his tongue, from tasting all the way to
national production problems. Yesterday's report that ice cream
prices were rising because of an increase in the price of milk fat
wasn't news to him.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison grew up in Memphis, Tenn., working in his uncle's ice
cream factory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned all the nuances at an early age _ what fresh cream
really tastes like and what yeast and mold do to the flavor of ripe
strawberries,'' he says. ``I don't have blood in my veins, I have
40 percent heavy whipping cream.''
</P>
<P>
   A degree in chemistry and a stint with Borden honed his skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to work for your family right away. You want
them to invite you,'' he says of his time at Borden. Eventually he
did go to work for his dad, selling to ice cream makers throughout
the West. Dreyer's was a client.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got to know me and hired me a couple of years later,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   The job isn't all Cookies 'n Cream (a flavor he says he
invented). Harrison keeps a 55-gallon trash barrel at his side when
he tastes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to swallow to taste,'' he explains delicately.
</P>
<P>
   He first checks the ice cream for eye appeal _ ``it has to look
inviting.'' Then he dips in with his official gold tasting spoon.
Plastic or wood would affect the taste, and silver tarnishes, he
says.
</P>
<P>
   He goes into what he calls his ``swirl, smack and spit'' routine
_ swirling the sample around his mouth, smacking his lips rapidly
to warm it up, then spitting it into the barrel.
</P>
<P>
   He says he treats ice cream tasting like wine tasting _ starting
with the vanillas or whites and working his way up through the
``Bordeaux'' of ice creams (mint chocolate chip, for example).
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, he cleanses his taste buds with warm water. If
that doesn't work, he goes to a salt-free soda cracker. If someone
walks into the tasting room with noticeable perfume or after shave,
Harrison is done for a while.
</P>
<P>
   If a sample doesn't look good, isn't taste balanced (the right
blend of cream, sugar and flavoring), or the texture isn't smooth
and creamy, it is donated to an area food bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have all our eggs in one basket,'' Harrison explains. A
snafu could lead to a national recall. That's why he has a back-up
taster in case he has a cold or other illness.
</P>
<P>
   There haven't been any national recalls under his palate, but
Bay area food banks did get 500,000 gallons of Dreyer's Grand last
year _ ice cream that was very edible, but not quite up to the
Harrison/Dreyer's standards.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison doesn't just educate people about the product. He also
has a few parlor tricks.
</P>
<P>
   Dreyer's recently commissioned a study to determine what flavor
preferences divulge about one's personality. Tell Harrison your
favorite flavor, and he'll define you. Like coffee ice cream?
Harrison says you're colorful, a risk taker, an impulsive type.
Prefer Macadamia Nut Brickle? You're conservative, a perfectionist,
a take-charge kind of person who is detail-oriented.
</P>
<P>
   To keep ice cream flavors at their peak, he suggests:
</P>
<P>
   _ Consume ice cream within three days.
</P>
<P>
   _ Store away from the refrigerator/freezer door and away from
the ice maker.
</P>
<P>
   _ After dipping, pat plastic wrap over the top of the remaining
ice cream. It helps maintain quality and prevents ice crystals from
forming.
</P>
<P>
   _ For long-term storage (2-3 months maximum), use a deep freeze.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
