<SLUG> BC-FOOD-COLUMN-OWEN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMOKED SALMON PENNE FOR A TASTE OF ITALY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cast of characters would have been appropriate for a mystery
novel by Agatha Christie or P.D. James.
</P>
<P>
   There was the Anglican vicar and his quiet wife. His animated
conversation usually ended with an explosive giggle, but a stranger
sensed some inner pain.
</P>
<P>
   There was tall, stately Harry the Purser, who had spent a career
handling the finances _ and the first-class passengers _ aboard
ships in the Cunard fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the figure who became known as The Weasel. He was
a little man with a broad, East End London accent. Englishmen of
his age have spent a lifetime standing in queues. Not this man. No
matter where or how he arrived at a buffet line or at a crowded
coffee bar, he quickly and mysteriously insinuated himself to the
front of the crowd and pulled his frowning wife along with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't think I didn't notice you weaseling your way into the
queue, you terrible little man!'' The Chief Inspector's voice
occasionally boomed out.
</P>
<P>
   The Weasel would flash a sly smile and say something cryptic
like, ``Ah, now, don't say anything bad on your birthday or you'll
be bad all year long.''
</P>
<P>
   No, the cast had not been assembled on the Orient Express or the
Q.E. II. And no crime had been detected, except for the failure of
Italian waiters to deliver, ``a nice cup of tea'' as quickly as it
was desired. The Brits were touring Umbria, Tuscany and the
Dolomites along with a few Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The vicar did, it turns out, harbor a deep hurt. One of his most
vivid and enjoyable memories concerned a backpacking trip he had
taken on the Olympic Peninsula just after divinity school. But his
hiking days now seemed to be behind him. He was cursed with the
gout and he decried the English stereotype that suggests it
afflicts only those who overindulge in 40-year-old port and
expensive cigars.
</P>
<P>
   One of the interesting facts we learned was the existence of a
holy relic in a church we visited in Mantua. It was the result of
some skepticism until Pope Pius II visited in the 15th century. The
pope declared the relic genuine because it miraculously cured him
of gout, which is more than it did for the Anglican vicar in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Chief Inspector (actually the retired police chief of
Newcastle) admitted that he watches TV mysteries involving
Inspector Morse and Scotland Yard Cmdr. Adam Dalgliesh. But he said
he really preferred the old ``Hill Street Blues'' even over the
newer American series ``NYPD Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   As for crimes in the Yorkshires, he recounted how amateur
gardeners in his area slept near their gooseberry bushes and leek
beds on nights before judging was conducted at the local fairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes an intruder will sneak up in the night to slash a
rival's prize leek,'' he informed us in a tone that might have been
describing a serial murder.
</P>
<P>
   No gooseberries and few leeks were served to us in Italy. But
dishes like these forgave all crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon Penne
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces smoked salmon
</P>
<P>
   8 thin spears asparagus
</P>
<P>
   One-and-one-half cups cream or low-fat evaporated milk
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 pound (or 4 cups) small penne pasta tubes
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Fill a large skillet with just enough water to cover the
asparagus. Add one-half teaspoon salt and one-half teaspoon sugar.
Bring to a boil, cook 1 minute, then remove from the heat. Let the
asparagus sit in the hot water.
</P>
<P>
   Cook the pasta in boiling salted water until done to the tooth.
</P>
<P>
   While this is happening, remove the asparagus from the water and
cut into 2-inch pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the water out of the skillet, put the pan on the heat and
add the oil and garlic. Pour in the cream, reduce slightly, then
add the salmon and asparagus. Simmer for 2 minutes, then add
drained pasta to the skillet and moosh everything around. Sprinkle
with cheese plus salt and pepper to taste and this should serve
four.
</P>
<P>
   Liver Venetian
</P>
<P>
   Three-quarters pound calves liver, sliced
</P>
<P>
   Flour
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup cream or evaporated milk
</P>
<P>
   3 teaspoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons minced parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Season some flour with salt and pepper. Dredge the liver slices
in this mess, then saute in heated olive oil 2 minutes on each
side. Remove to a dish in a 200-degree oven.
</P>
<P>
   Add the butter to the same pan. Then saute the onions until
soft. While this is happening, combine the cream or milk, the
mustard, parsley and lemon juice. Stir this muck in with the onion
and cook another minute.
</P>
<P>
   Serve the sauce over the liver and this should serve two.
</P>
<P>
   On second thought, one crime was committed during our trip. The
Weasel shoved his way into the wrong queue and had his pocket
picked in Florence.
</P>
<P>
   John Owen writes ``The Intermediate Eater'' weekly for the P-I.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
