<DOCNO> NYT19980628.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-28 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0794 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REBELS-525&AMP;ADD     06-28 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REBELS-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBEL COMMANDER SAYS AIM IS TO UNIFY ALBANIANS IN ONE STATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By CHRIS HEDGES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLOGOVAC, Yugoslavia _ A Volkswagen Golf bearing a yellow
license plate issued by the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army sped along
the dirt road near this town in the Drenica Hills, snaking back and
forth to avoid Serbian snipers.
</P>
<P>
   The car spun screeching into a small farm village and turned
down a narrow road between whitewashed mud-and-wattle houses. The
rebel officer inside wearing an American army uniform had an AK-47
assault rifle next to him and a Russian sniper rifle across the
back seat.
</P>
<P>
   The car bounced past fields where farmers were stacking their
hay. At a rebel checkpoint, two teen-age girls wearing the black
uniforms and berets of the rebel police and armed with assault
rifles, sat on a bench in the shade of a black locust tree. They
diligently wrote down the make and registration number of each car,
truck and tractor that went by.
</P>
<P>
   The officer was waved forward by young men wearing red arm
bands, and he drove past village children who clutched homemade
wooden weapons and who raised clenched right fists to their
forehead in the rebel salute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are changing the salute,'' said the officer, as his car
jostled down the rutted track. ``We want our troops to use the
traditional salute of Western armies.''
</P>
<P>
   The rebel army in the Serbian province of Kosovo, which has a
population that is 90 percent ethnic Albania, was dismissed in
January by the American envoy to the region, Robert Gelbard, as a
``terrorist organization.'' The rebel group was described as
recently as a month ago by the ethnic Albanian leader Ibrahim
Rugova as ``a creation of the Serb security forces.'' But it has
emerged as the most powerful ethnic Albanian movement in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Gelbard's decision to meet rebel representatives in Switzerland
this week implicitly recognizes the force as the province's new
power brokers and signals the waning influence of Rugova, a
committed pacifist.
</P>
<P>
   But as the rebels consolidate their hold on about 40 percent of
Kosovo and struggle to unify their command in the ``liberated
zones,'' the outside world is scrambling to discover who leads the
movement, who speaks for it and what it wants.
</P>
<P>
   It is not always clear that the rebels themselves know the
answers to these questions. But days of criss-crossing the villages
and back roads under the control of the fighters give the
impression that the Serb nationalist movement that brought Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic to power in Serbia a decade ago, and
triggered the wars in Croatia and Bosnia, has found its corollary
in the ethnic Albanian insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels vow to fight until the Serbian authorities, and
implicitly the Serb minority of 150,000 people in Kosovo, are
driven out of the province. They call not only for an independent
Kosovo, but for a greater Albania that stretches into Macedonia and
Montenegro to embrace the ethnic Albanian minorities in neighboring
states. Serbia and Montenegro are the two republics remaining in
Yugoslavia. Macedonia is now an independent nation.
</P>
<P>
   Most ominously, the rebels say that the time for dialogue with
the Serbs has ended and that they will achieve their aims with
violence.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One of about five regional command headquarters, based in a
captured police station, is on a remote hilltop in central Kosovo.
On a recent day, a red Albanian flag with its black double-headed
eagle flapped in the breeze on a white metal flagpole. A satellite
dish was positioned on the roof of the red brick single story
building. Rebel soldiers dressed in German army fatigues and
carrying assault rifles guarded the gate and iron fence that ringed
the building.
</P>
<P>
   In the front room, a group of about a half dozen fighters sat
idly surrounded by machine guns, cartridge belts and ammunition
boxes. Rows of assault rifles lay neatly lined up in wooden racks
once used by the Serbian police.
</P>
<P>
   The commander of the Drenica region, who would give only his nom
de guerre, Salim Suleman, and who said that he is 28, was dressed
in a short-sleeve, Swiss Army camouflage uniform. He said that he
had worked for several years with Adem Jashari, one of the founders
and leaders of the Kosovo Liberation Army, who was killed in March
when Serb forces attacked the village of Prekaz, an assault that
left more than 80 dead and triggered the current rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   Suleman and about four other leaders appear to make up the
command structure of the guerrilla force. No leader appears
predominant. Regional and often local commanders are able to carry
out the war in their zones with a great deal of autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels say they are organizing local volunteers, as well as
fighters and weapons smuggled over the border from Albania, to
build a force that will drive the Serbs out of the province. They
say that they have no interest in establishing a cease-fire and
that they are unwilling to remove their barricades on main roads to
give American mediation efforts with Serbia a chance, arguing that
they no longer trust the Serbs or the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have learned from the wars in Croatia and Bosnia that the
outside world cannot solve our problems for us, that we must fight
for our own freedom,'' Suleman said. ``There is a de facto Albanian
nation. The tragedy is that the European powers after World War I
decided to divide that nation between several Balkan states.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now fighting to unify the nation, to liberate all
Albanians, including those in Macedonia, Montenegro and other parts
of Serbia. We are not just a liberation army for Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   The fighting that has claimed several hundred lives since March
threatens to escalate as the 50,000 Serbian special policemen and
troops deployed in Kosovo position themselves around rebel
enclaves.
</P>
<P>
   An attack on rebel enclaves, which this commander predicted was
``imminent,'' could cause the fighting to spread to other parts of
the province and into the provincial capital, Pristina. Suleman
said that guerrilla units were being moved into ``new areas'' in
anticipation of a Serbian assault.
</P>
<P>
   The commander said that Serbs who wanted to live in ``the
republic of Kosovo'' would be welcome, but only those who respected
``the culture and heritage of the Albanian people.'' He conceded
that Serbian villages, where he said there were armed groups, were
being attacked by the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbs who have blood on their hands will have to leave
Kosovo,'' he said, ``but the others can stay if they are willing to
be loyal citizens of the state. The Serbian churches and
monasteries will always be respected. Our forces surround a
monastery not far from here and it has not been harmed.''
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke a woman in a black uniform entered the room and
placed orders for the commander to sign on the table. He picked up
a pen and scribbled his name at the bottom of the sheets. A heavy
gold ring flashed in the sunlight that streamed in through the
window.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time for America and Europe to forget this plan to give
Kosovo some kind of autonomy and help us in our struggle for
liberation,'' he said. ``If the Americans and the Europeans do not
help us we will find others who will. We will never betray our
people.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
