<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNNY-ADE-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNNY ADE: DANCE MUSIC, EVEN FOR DANCING 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By PETER WATROUS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two hours into King Sunny Ade's show at Tramps on
Wednesday night, Ade and his 17-piece band had played about all
that modern orchestral dance music can do.
</P>
<P>
   There were riffs, by talking drums, or guitars, or pedal steel
guitar, or by the band's chorus. There were stop-time breaks. Ade
layered three or four different types of drums to create waves of
sound. There were solos; Ade sang to the audience, and the people
who had space to dance, danced.
</P>
<P>
   Ade, from Nigeria, doesn't play New York very often, and his
shows are events. At every one, people who went to his first
concert in New York, sometime in the mists of the early 1980s, muse
about the power the music held.
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived then, playing an extraordinary and revelatory
show, the cultural makeup of music in New York changed. Suddenly
world music existed; Ade and the effort that Island Records took in
trying to make him the next Bob Marley have plenty to do with the
current local interest in pop music from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   It helps that Ade has one of the great orchestras working, equal
to the best bands in the Caribbean. On Wednesday night, it chugged
along like an unstoppable and intelligent machine.
</P>
<P>
   The three guitars spewed clanging, metallic riffs that
interlocked with the various drums. The chorus chanted bits and
pieces, or sang long, gently waving lines. Two talking drums,
taking the lead instrument role, plowed up the music. And on tune
after tune, the band members, along with Ade's two female dancers,
shaped their bodies to the rhythms, giving a tactile response to
music.
</P>
<P>
   Ade was in New York to celebrate the release of a new album,
``Odu'' (Atlantic), playing tunes from it and older pieces. He sets
his material up as suites, and each piece had movement, with drum
parts giving way to guitar figures, which gave way to choral
sections.
</P>
<P>
   Tempos changed and new rhythms flashed abruptly across the
music's screen. And during transition sections, new sounds drifted
through the music, like fog through reeds. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
