<HEADER>
A0797 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STODA-COLUMN29-COX     06-28 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STODA-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ex-Marlins swap demolition derby for show biz
 &HT;    By Greg Stoda
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   They only thought they were escaping the madness.
</P>
<P>
   And, really, how could they have known they weren't? How could
Gary Sheffield, Bobby Bonilla, Charles Johnson and Jim Eisenreich
possibly have known that by leaving the Florida Marlins to hook up
with the Los Angeles Dodgers they were going from one strange purge
to another?
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers? Purged?
</P>
<P>
   The blue-capped, blueblooded, blue-heaven-on-earth Chavez
Ravine, Dodgertown Dodgers of O'Malley famed family ownership?
</P>
<P>
   The same. And not the same at all.
</P>
<P>
   Because now, for all practical purposes, they're the Los Angeles
Foxes.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield, Bonilla, Johnson and Eisenreich were shipped to the
West Coast just more than a month ago as the Marlins, deep into
destroying their own World Series championship team of 1997, took
sledgehammer to the demolition process.
</P>
<P>
   But two months before that trade, the Dodgers had been sold to
Australian bajillionaire Rupert Murdoch and his conglomerate. And
ever since the Fox Group invaded the Dodgers' henhouse, feathers
have been flying.
</P>
<P>
   It is worth noting here that the O'Malley family, which
purchased the Dodgers in 1950, had held the longest ownership of a
major league baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   So, even when the O'Malleys announced in January 1997 that the
team was for sale, well, the assumption was any transfer would be
rooted in some kind of stability. Six months later, though, the
Dodgers received permission from the Major League Baseball
Ownership Committee to continue discussions with Fox, and
subsequently reached agreement on a sale on Sept. 4 of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Uh-oh.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Foxes pulled off the huge swap with the Marlins
featuring, on the L.A. side, slugging coverboy catcher Mike Piazza
and third baseman Todd Zeile coming to Florida. Piazza, of course,
has since left to become a New York Met where one of the new
pitchers happens to be ex-Dodger headliner Hideo Nomo.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, Bill Russell was fired as manager of the Dodgers
and Fred Claire was bounced as the team's general manager. Both
were 30-year men within the organization.
</P>
<P>
   That's entertainment, folks, and that's Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Claire had much say in things recently, anyway (see:
Piazza trade). Swept into the manager's position was Glenn Hoffman,
accompanied by ex-Dodgers manager Tommy Lasorda in Claire's vacated
spot.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda, who has felt discombobulated on the Dodger fringe since
his own retirement/ouster as field boss in favor of Russell a
couple of years back, found a way back into a position of
influence. Lasorda fits the Fox television profile. He's noisy.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, he was willing to do the dirty work when three
coaches were booted Wednesday night. Lasorda's explanation was that
the coaches were offered other positions, which in Fox
corporatespeak translates to a take-it-or-leave-it proposition.
</P>
<P>
   It has reached the point,Dodgers first baseman Eric Karros has
been quoted as saying, ``You just go to the park and hope you still
have a uniform to wear.''
</P>
<P>
   About those duds, Eric.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers aren't wearing their white shirts for home games
these days. They're wearing their blue batting-practice jerseys.
The plan is to autograph them and auction them off.
</P>
<P>
   What's next?
</P>
<P>
   Melrose Place inning-card girls?
</P>
<P>
   Hey, Gary and Bobby and Charles and Jim, don't laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Stoda writes his column for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
