<HEADLINE>
MEDIA TALK
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Conn., N.J., N.Y., Wash.)  (fb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   READER'S DIGEST SELLS ART PIECE BY PIECE
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is not easy to part with great art, but Reader's
Digest Association Inc., under financial pressure, is apparently
forcing itself to face facts. In a meeting with employees, the
newly appointed chief executive officer, Thomas Ryder, told his
staff that the company had sold Van Gogh's ``Flowers in a Vase,''
Monet's ``Landscape'' and Georges Braque's ``Sunflowers,'' part of
the enormous collection built up by DeWitt Wallace and his wife,
Lila, when they ran the company, according to a transcript of the
staff meeting,
</P>
<P>
   Ryder did not reveal the prices, but the company later said the
Van Gogh brought $3.7 million at a Sotheby's auction in May and the
Monet fetched $2 million. The Braque was sold privately and no
price was disclosed. Ryder said the company ``is going to be under
enormous pressure _ and we should be _ to be rational about our
ownership of a whole lot of valued art.''
</P>
<P>
   The company, which has watched its stock sink and has slashed
its dividends as the circulation of its crown jewel, Reader's
Digest, has fallen, is finally biting the bullet. But not very
hard. So far this year Reader's Digest has bought 200 photographs,
though a company spokeswoman would not name a price for them. Still
it sounds like the company is at least giving up some of the high
life and comfortable corporate headquarters for which it was
famous.
</P>
<P>
   It has to. Ryder also told staff members, ``Our cash reserves
have declined by several hundred million dollars in the last few
years. The Easter Bunny will not bring back those resources. We
will not win the lottery. We will have to bring the resources back
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   But if that takes too long, the company, with a bulging art
collection, could always sell off more art. Ryder at least seems
willing to consider it.
</P>
<P>
   FEWER REPORTERS COVER MORE NEWS AT STATE CAPITALS
</P>
<P>
   Tighter budgets and a penchant to offer softer, more
reader-friendly news stories and features has led more and more of
the nation's newspapers to pare their coverage of state government,
according to a report scheduled to be released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The reduced emphasis on covering the affairs of state
governments comes at a time when television has also pared back its
reporting, and when state governments, backed by Washington, are
exerting more power, enacting more legislation and spending more
money than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   The report, which appears in the July-August issue of American
Journalism Review, is the third in a series underwritten by The
Project on the State of the American Newspaper, which is supported
by a grant from the Pew Charitable Trusts.
</P>
<P>
   Since the early 1990s, the report found, newspaper staffing at
the statehouse level has declined in more than half the states: 27
states _ including Connecticut, New Jersey and New York _ now have
fewer full-time reporters covering state government. Over the same
period, newspapers in 14 states have increased the size of their
reporting staff. Newspapers in nine states have not changed the
size of their staffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't try and say that more bodies mean better coverage,''
Thomas Kunkel, editor and director of the project, said. ``But this
is an important barometer.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff cuts at Gannett and Knight-Ridder, the two chains whose
newspapers have the highest circulation in the country, have been
particularly pronounced. The number of statehouse reporters at
Gannett newspapers has been pared by 14 percent, the report found.
At Knight-Ridder, the number of full-time reporters covering state
government has been cut by 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   MEN'S JOURNAL ENCOUNTERS PROBLEMS ON MOUNT RAINIER
</P>
<P>
   It is no easy task keeping a magazine's content timely.
</P>
<P>
   In the June-July issue of Men's Journal, a magazine that focuses
on sports, fitness and adventure, the title of an article on
mountain climbing blared: ``Climb Mount Rainier: A Serious
Mountaineering Challenge with Minimal Risk of Headline-Making
Deaths. Call it Everest for Everyman.''
</P>
<P>
   The June-July issue hit newsstands in late May. Flash forward to
June 12, when newspaper headlines around the country reported the
death of a climber who was caught in an avalanche on Mount Rainier.
Four days later, new headlines appeared about the plight of two
climbers who were stranded near the summit of the mountain by a
whiteout.
</P>
<P>
   ``An unfortunate coincidence is probably the best way to
describe it,'' said David Willey, a senior editor at Men's Journal,
which is owned by Wenner Media. There are three months between the
time the magazine's staff produces an issue and when it goes on
sale, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, Willey defended the headline and the article, saying
that Mount Rainier, in Washington state, has had the fewest deaths
of any major peak in the lower 48 states. (Rainier is the second
highest peak in the lower 48 states, at 14,410 feet. Mount Whitney
in California is the highest, at 14,495 feet.) If approached with
the proper attitude and preparation, Willey said, Rainier does not
pose a serious threat to the less-experienced mountain climber.
</P>
<P>
   John Krambrink, the superintendent of Mount Rainier National
Park, was more cautious. ``Even on the most popular routes up the
mountain, which people would consider the easiest to climb, you can
face situations where the conditions make it very treacherous,''
Krambrink said. ``We have the most accidents and fatalities on the
popular routes. Rainier is one of the most physical climbs. It
takes tremendous stamina and mental strength.''
</P>
<P>
   UNIVERSITY PUBLISHING LEAVES ITS IVORY TOWER
</P>
<P>
   The ivory tower of scholarly publishing is not quite such an
ivory tower anymore. Just ask the top-of-the-line outside
publicists who have been hired for a couple of major university
press titles this fall, books whose 20,000-copy print runs are 10
times bigger than the usual runs. Books that could slip very nicely
onto a commercial publisher's lineup.
</P>
<P>
   These signs show that the upheavals in bookselling and trade
publishing are being felt within academia. So much so that the
Association of American University Presses, meeting in Washington
over the weekend, chose ``Seismic Shifts'' as its theme.
</P>
<P>
   The scholarly mission has not changed, but some of the
publishing realities have. Library budgets for scholarly monographs
have shrunk. Publishing more books that could be sold in retail
bookstores was one solution. But in a bookselling world that is
consolidating, fighting for position is harder than ever. Every
publisher must brandish a few titles that can lead its list through
the chain doors.
</P>
<P>
   Although Tina Weiner, the associate director at Yale University
Press, emphasized that every book on her fall list ``is rock solid
in its academic contribution,'' she said it was ``the most
ambitious trade list we've ever had.'' That is coming from the
publisher who has sold 60,000 copies of ``The Encyclopedia of New
York.'' Yale is starting this September with 20,000 copies of ``The
New Encyclopedia of the American West''; at least 15,000 copies of
Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan's analysis of American government
secrecy, called ``Secrecy'', and in October, a similar number of
``My German Question,'' Peter Gay's memoir of growing up Jewish in
Nazi Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   Among the lead titles at Princeton University Press is ``The
Life of Birds'' by David Attenborough, which will have a
50,000-copy print run and accompany a 10-part PBS series, and ``The
Shape of the River,'' an examination of race as a factor in
university admissions co-written by Derek Bok, president emeritus
of Harvard and William Bowen, a former Princeton president.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Lippincott, the director of Princeton University Press,
said, ``I wouldn't want to do too many of these books, because
there's such an element of risk.'' But then, these are risky
publishing times. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
