<HEADLINE>
PRIZES CREATED TO HONOR WRITER J. ANTHONY LUKAS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Mass.)  (fb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A series of awards has been established in honor of
J. Anthony Lukas, the Pulitzer Prize-winning author who died last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The awards will include an annual prize of $10,000, to be given
to a book that covers an important aspect of American social or
political life, and a grant of $45,000 for a work in progress on
similar subject matter. In addition, the organizers of the award
plan a series of annual events for students and young journalists
that will focus on nonfiction writing.
</P>
<P>
   The awards were conceived by Linda Healey, his widow, and Arthur
Gelb, one of his former editors at The New York Times, and they
will be administered by the Nieman Foundation of Harvard University
and the Columbia University Graduate School of Journalism.
</P>
<P>
   The project will be financed by the family of the late Mark
Lynton and will include the Mark Lynton History Prize, an annual
award for a work of popular history. Lynton, a senior executive at
Hunter Douglas in the Netherlands, had a love of nonfiction
writing.
</P>
<P>
   Gelb is president of The New York Times Company Foundation, and
Healey is a vice president and senior editor at Pantheon Books. The
prize committee includes several other friends and associates of
Lukas, who committed suicide. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
