<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-DANCE-FESTIVAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANCE REVIEW: AIRBORNE CREATIVITY FLIRTING WITH PAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (fb) 
By JACK ANDERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.C. _ Elizabeth Streb does not throw her dancers to the
lions. At least she hasn't done so yet. She doesn't have her
dancers engage in gladiatorial combat, either, though one could
almost imagine her deciding to give such duels a try. She has
already created dances that resemble boxing and wrestling matches.
</P>
<P>
   Streb specializes in extremely demanding, and even exhausting
and potentially dangerous, choreography. Appearing as part of this
summer's American Dance Festival on the campus of Duke University
here, her company, which she calls Streb, proved to be a troupe of
disciplined daredevils. Yet the performance on Saturday night in
Page Auditorium was an ordeal as well as a show.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Streb's choreography derives from gymnastics, and she
emphasizes the arduousness of her acrobatic stunts by amplifying
the stage so that whenever a dancer's body touches a surface,
thunderous noises ring out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drop,'' a world premiere, was typical of Streb's efforts. With
cords attached to their bodies, Hope Clark and Matthew Stromberg
plummeted head downward from above the stage, then began to swoop
wildly from side to side, sometimes nearly colliding. It was as if
they had been transformed into human slingshots.
</P>
<P>
   Other dances were based upon similar mind-boggling tricks. In
``Fly,'' a woman tied to a huge lever swung about in the air while
other dancers scurried beneath her. The dancers in ``Look Up'' wore
harnesses that permitted them to walk up and down a wall. Everyone
in ``All/Wall'' slams against the side of a wall in choreography
that threatened to break their bones.
</P>
<P>
   People kept rising and falling on moving platforms in a two-part
dance called ``Across,'' and in ``Breakthrough'' a dancer crashed
through a windowpane. A company representative said that it was
made of stage glass, a synthetic substance used by theatrical
designers that is less unpredictable when it breaks than real
glass. Yet one miscalculated move through this pane could still
have left the dancer in pain.
</P>
<P>
   Streb sent people bounding buoyantly on a trampoline in ``Up''
and on a surface with springs in ``Bounce.'' But joyousness is not
one of her major themes. She thereby differs from some of the
choreographers who in recent years have used acrobatic movements to
suggest that through training people can acquire a sense of
nimbleness, playfulness and grace. Streb's choreography, in
contrast, is dominated by images of pain. Therefore, despite their
intense physicality, her dancers do not celebrate the body. Rather,
they can be related to an American puritan tradition that regards
the body as something to be punished, not glorified.
</P>
<P>
   In only one piece did the choreographic pain serve a genuine
purpose: ``Little Ease,'' a solo in which Streb thrashed about
inside a tiny coffinlike box. By creating a remarkably
claustrophobic sense of imprisonment, she made the work an implicit
protest against oppression.
</P>
<P>
   Streb, who has been dancing ``Little Ease'' since its premiere
in 1985, gave her final performance of it on Saturday. Other
dancers will continue to do it in the future. It remains one of
Streb's few works to inspire a theatergoer to think as well as
gasp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
