<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: UPTOWN HORNS; LITERARY LIGHTS; CANADIAN COOL;
CURTAIN RAISER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Unicorn Tapestries, one of the great surviving
artworks of the Middle Ages, are about to sample life on Fifth
Avenue. On view for 60 years at the Cloisters, the Metropolitan
Museum of Art branch in Fort Tryon Park, the seven hangings
depicting the hunt and capture of the elusive mythical beast are
taking up temporary residence at the main building of the museum
beginning on Wednesday. Designed in Paris and woven from 1495 to
1505, the tapestries, made of wool, metallic threads and silk, will
be shown there through Sept. 6 while repairs are made to the
Cloisters. Information: (212) 535-7710.
</P>
<P>
   LITERARY LIGHTS
</P>
<P>
   CROWBOROUGH, England _ The game will definitely be afoot
beginning on Friday in Crowborough, an East Sussex community some
50 miles southeast of London. With Sherlock Holmes and Dr. Watson
(actually local school principals), the village will be the site of
the third annual Sherlock Holmes Festival. Through July 10, the
event includes a talk on Arthur Conan Doyle and a visit to his home
from 1907 to his death in 1930, a crime-writing workshop with talks
by seven authors, and a Victorian street market (with Holmes books
and memorabilia) where some townspeople wear period dress. The area
was also home to Rudyard Kipling, A.A. Milne and James Joyce, and
the weekend retreat of the Bloomsbury Group. Information:
011-44-1-892-66-39-06.
</P>
<P>
   CANADIAN COOL
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Hockey season is over, and the city goes this week
from the ice cold to the cool and hot with the opening on Wednesday
of the 19th Montreal Jazz Festival. More than 100 indoor concerts
and 300 free open-air events are expected before the music ends on
July 12. Attractions of opening week include Puerto Rican
saxophonist David Sanchez with Cuban piano virtuoso Chucho Valdes;
a George Gershwin centennial tribute starring Michael Feinstein;
Wynton Marsalis and the Lincoln Center Jazz Orchestra; Roberta
Flack, and an evening with Ray Charles. Information: (888)
555-0515.
</P>
<P>
   CURTAIN RAISER
</P>
<P>
   SANTA FE, N.M. _ In the foothills of the Sangre de Cristo
Mountains, the Santa Fe Opera is scheduled to open its 42nd season
Friday with something old and something new. The old is Puccini's
``Madame Butterfly.'' The new is a 2,126-seat theater designed by
James Stewart Polshek and Partners of New York. In its nine-week
season ending Aug. 29, the Santa Fe Opera will also present
Mozart's ``Magic Flute,'' directed by Jonathan Miller; Berlioz's
``Beatrice and Benedict''; a revival of Richard Strauss'
``Salome,'' and ``A Dream Play'' by the Swedish composer Ingvar
Lidholm. Information: (800) 280-4654.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
