<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980628.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-28 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0808 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT&AMP;T-ARMSTRONG-ART-77     06-28 1296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-ARMSTRONG-ART-775&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T CHIEF SAYS HE CAN DEFEND DEAL FOR TCI 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ko) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T chief Michael Armstrong is getting his first taste of the
criticism that can come with remaking a corporate icon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just been a crazy few days,'' he said Friday in an
interview in his Basking Ridge, N.J. office. ``The disinformation,
its incredible. I've never seen anything like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither had a lot of people in the business world before
Wednesday, when AT&AMP;T, the nation's largest phone company, announced
a deal to acquire the nation's No. 2 cable television company,
Tele-Communications Inc., for $31.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Since then AT&AMP;T's stock, the most widely held in the nation, has
lost more than 13 percent of its value. Investors are confused and
worried about the full ramifications of the deal; the AT&AMP;T of old
was not so aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   But Armstrong, AT&AMP;T's chairman and chief executive, is nothing
if not aggressive. The TCI deal follows AT&AMP;T's agreement in January
to acquire Teleport Communications Group, a competitive local phone
provider, for $11.3 billion. And other bold moves may be in the
offing, including an alliance with a major overseas telephone
company.
</P>
<P>
   Whether investors and competitors view this flurry of activity
as exhilarating, worrisome or downright scary, it should not be
surprising.
</P>
<P>
   After all, on the day he was named the new AT&AMP;T leader eight
months ago in a ceremony that seemed a lot like a coronation,
Armstrong made clear that he would be no mere caretaker of the
company, one of the world's best known.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a lot of adrenaline flowing,'' he said that day last
October. ``I don't think I'm going to let that adrenaline stop for
the rest of my career.''
</P>
<P>
   When Armstrong arrived last fall from running the Hughes
Electronics unit of General Motors Corp., AT&AMP;T resembled a
dyspeptic giant, disoriented and grouchy. In an industry that is
one of the world's largest and most dynamic, AT&AMP;T, under the
now-retired chairman Robert Allen, had no visible strategy for the
future.
</P>
<P>
   After joining AT&AMP;T, Armstrong spent three months quietly
assessing his options. He broke his silence in January by
announcing the Teleport deal, which was to be the cornerstone of
AT&AMP;T's expansion into the business-customer side of the local phone
market.
</P>
<P>
   The TCI deal is Armstrong's bid to break into the residential
segment. AT&AMP;T, like MCI Communications Corp., its main competitor
in the long-distance business, has essentially given up on trying
to enter the local market by reselling the phone service of the
local Bell companies.
</P>
<P>
   The next and last big piece of the strategy would be
international. Armstrong says that in the next few months the
company will announce a major plan for its global business.
Armstrong offered no specifics, but there is strong suspicion that
AT&AMP;T is forging an alliance with British Telecommunications PLC,
now that British Telecom has seen Worldcom Inc. sunder its deal to
acquire MCI.
</P>
<P>
   The Times of London reported Sunday that AT&AMP;T and British
Telecom are in ``advanced negotiations'' for some sort of alliance;
AT&AMP;T declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Before he can drop another bomb on the industry, however,
Armstrong must convince investors of the wisdom of acquiring TCI's
cable operation and combining it with AT&AMP;T's consumer business as a
new subsidiary. So far, such convincing has not been easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strategically, he's doing the right things,'' said Stephanie
Comfort, head telecommunications analyst for Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter. ``I think where people are worried is that he's throwing a
lot of dollars around, and there's a lot of transformation that has
to happen. You're basically transforming a company that has had a
traditional value-based investor focus. The perception on the
Street that's building is that he's very good but he's shooting
from the hip a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   While Armstrong denies that he is acting rashly, he freely
admits that he feels compelled to move quickly. He said that after
divesting itself of its local operations as part of the 1984
federal antitrust settlement and then spinning off its computer and
equipment business in 1996, AT&AMP;T has a lot of catching up to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to be bold because I'm working against time and the
forces of industry, of change, of technology and of competition,''
he said. ``Had AT&AMP;T over the last 10 years been ramping to this
threshold, terrific. The facts are that AT&AMP;T was accomplishing its
breakup, then its tri-vestiture, so it was consumed with a lot of
things internal. Now we have to be consumed with a lot of things
external, so maybe that's why it comes as a step-function rather
than as evolution.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But in the absence of specific details about the company's
technical plans for TCI, and in light of the deal's bewildering
complexity, Armstrong and his chief financial officer, Daniel
Somers, made the unusual move on Friday of holding an impromptu
conference call with financial analysts. Still, the call did not
keep AT&AMP;T's shares from continuing their slide, ending the day at
$56.75, down $1.625.
</P>
<P>
   Armstong said that AT&AMP;T hoped to sell local phone service and
high-speed access to the Internet to 30 percent of TCI's 10.5
million cable customers within five years of completing the
acquisition. Armstrong is also about to start negotiating deals
with TCI's affiliated cable systems to get them to carry AT&AMP;T's
service.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of upgrading cable systems to carry voice and
Internet-style data traffic will be $400 to $500 a line, Armstrong
said. The necesssary technology, however, is not expected to be
ready for perhaps two years. In markets where the company wants to
move especially quickly, AT&AMP;T could deploy technology that more
closely resembles a traditional phone system, at a cost of about
$750 a line.
</P>
<P>
   Once TCI has been updated and integrated into AT&AMP;T's operations
by early next decade, though, the company predicts that the new
venture will enable the corporate parent to report earnings growth
of nearly 20 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   A big outstanding question is the ultimate fate of Liberty
Media, the television programming unit of TCI. After the deal John
Malone, TCI's chairman, would continue to control Liberty and AT&AMP;T
would have no finanical stake in the unit. Some people on Wall
Street wonder whether the structure of the new AT&AMP;T would allow
Malone to spin out Liberty Media in a tax-free deal after the
AT&AMP;T-TCI merger closes.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said he had no idea if Malone was planning such a move
and added that it would be illegal for AT&AMP;T and TCI to agree to a
merger with a future spin-off in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why you just don't have those sorts of discussions,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said he had not yet decided which of TCI's cable
markets would be the first to receive new services from AT&AMP;T. He
would not say what he expected the new services to cost but added
that within metropolitan areas the services would be offered in
both high- and low-income areas.
</P>
<P>
   His experience with Hughes' DirecTV direct-broadcast satellite
television products was that high-income households did not
necessarily buy the service more often than families with less
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will sacrifice to enjoy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that goes for shareholders as well as customers remains
to be seen, but Armstrong continues to radiate confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``My experience, and maybe also history's experience,'' he said,
``is that you're remembered more for how it ends up as to how you
got there.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
