</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEAMSTERS-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS APPEAR TO BLOCK FUNDS FOR TEAMSTER ELECTION
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With a federal monitor complaining that he cannot supervise the
Teamsters' presidential election because Congress has cut off his
funding, Republicans in Congress are finding themselves in a
pickle.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do congressional Republicans appear to be blocking a
monitor whose job is to prevent election corruption in a union
synonymous with corruption, but the funding cutoff is alarming
James P. Hoffa, the front-running candidate who is considered
friendlier to the Republicans than the union's current leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The Hoffa forces fear that the decision to bar funding could
delay the vote for months and could result in an election that is
run by anti-Hoffa incumbents rather than the federal monitor. ``We
don't trust the current administration to conduct a fair
election,'' Thomas Pazzi, Hoffa's campaign manager, said in an
interview. ``There is no evidence they would do so.''
</P>
<P>
   The International Brotherhood of Teamsters is now headed by Tom
Sever, the secretary-treasurer, who was elected on the slate with
Ron Carey, the union president who has taken a leave of absence
while under investigation in a campaign-finance scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Carey narrowly beat Hoffa in the 1996 race, but that victory was
nullified and a new election was ordered when federal monitors
discovered that Carey aides embezzled more than $700,000 in
Teamster funds to help his campaign. In the new election, ballots
are scheduled to be mailed out in September and counted on Oct. 14.
But Michael Cherkasky, the federal monitor, said he has so little
funds that vendors will not sign contracts with his office to do
needed activities, like print the ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, he filed an urgent request with Judge David
Edelstein of Federal District Court in Manhattan, asking him to
order the federal government and the union to agree on a plan by
Tuesday to fund his office. Cherkasky asserted that the funding
crisis would jeopardize the long-standing federal effort to clean
up the Teamsters.
</P>
<P>
   In his appeal, he wrote, ``It would be astounding, and a
stunning waste of decades of effort spent fighting organized crime
and labor racketeering, if the current paralysis over funding
resulted in the abandonment of this law enforcement effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Under a 1989 consent decree that the Teamsters signed to settle
a racketeering lawsuit, the union agreed to hold elections every
five years and to allow government supervision of the union and its
elections.
</P>
<P>
   The consent decree required the federal government to pay for
supervision in the 1996 election. But congressional Republicans,
led by Rep. Pete Hoekstra of Michigan, were so angry about the
Carey campaign-finance scandal and about having taxpayers finance a
union election that they barred funds for supervision. Ever since
Carey was first elected in 1991, Republicans have disliked him
because he made the Teamsters aggressively pro-Democrat after the
union had long supported the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Some Teamster officials say that in orchestrating the funding
prohibition, Hoekstra was trying to hurt the Carey camp and bolster
Hoffa, who is also from Michigan. But the cutoff has hurt Hoffa
instead.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Trossman, a spokesman for Hoffa's main opponent, Tom
Leedham, said, ``It's ironic that congressman Hoekstra, with the
Hoffa forces cheering him on, has made a mess of funding this
election.''
</P>
<P>
   In the funding standoff, the Federal Court of Appeals in
Manhattan has ruled that the government must pay to conduct the
election if it chooses to supervise the vote. The court left the
alternative that the government could choose not to supervise the
election and let the union conduct and pay for it. That alternative
is opposed by Cherkasky, the Justice Department, the Teamster
incumbents and Hoffa.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials say they are lobbying Congress to
agree to provide the $8.6 million Cherkasky says he needs.
</P>
<P>
   Upset that such a relatively small sum is creating such big
problems, Pazzi said, ``They accidentally move decimal points in
Congress that wipe out more dollars than this.''
</P>
<P>
   Some officials who follow the funding negotiations said that
congressional Democrats who originally supported the funding for
the monitor's office have been strangely quiet about the money.
These officials suggest that the Democrats are happy to see the
Republicans stew over the issue and that the Democrats also want
the Teamster vote delayed so that Carey's allies can remain in
charge until after the congressional elections in November. That
way the union might continue backing Democratic candidates. But
congressional Democrats deny any such strategem.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Hoekstra said he was reluctant to make
funding available because Cherkasky, in his view, has not done
enough to stop Teamster officials from using union resources and
money to help their preferred candidates. He has also indicated he
would like Cherkasky to remove Sever from office for participating
in the campaign-finance fraud. Teamster officials deny Sever has
any involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Cherkasky has said that he has no power to suspend Sever and
that he was already working hard to prevent the misuse of union
resources in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But Hoekstra is skeptical. ``My concern here is with the
taxpayer,'' he said. ``The system is not yet in place to conduct a
fair election. I don't want to pour another dollar or $8 million
into an election that in three or six months we'll have to overturn
again. That sounds pretty dumb to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
