<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-28 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0820 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-SPORTSWEAR-NY     06-28 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-SPORTSWEAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION'S CONTRADICTION: WOMAN AS OBJECT OR AS DOER
</HEADLINE>
  (Column) 
 By MARGO JEFFERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For all the talk about the male gaze _ the way of
seeing that perpetually turns women into fixed objects of men's
desires and needs _ when it comes to fashion, the demands of the
female gaze can be just as potent and ruthless.
</P>
<P>
   For women, fashion is an esthetic, a competition and a spectator
sport. Like all of these, it includes eros, envy, status strivings
and the pleasures, pure and impure, that come from watching how
flesh, forms, fabrics and temperaments meet.
</P>
<P>
   To walk through ``American Ingenuity: Sportswear, 1930s-1970s,''
the exhibition at the Metropolitan Museum of Art's Costume
Institute, is to see how women who designed clothes turned their
gaze upon women who bought them, and how together they devised
socially desirable and at times socially daring representations of
what an American woman was supposed to mean and be. (There are
important men designers in the show, too, but the focus is a group
of women who began to give American sportswear a Parisian-free ease
and forthrightness in the 1930s and 1940s.)
</P>
<P>
   The witty writer and designer Elizabeth Hawes wrote in 1938 that
fashion was a complete anachronism, a deformed thief; designers
like Claire McCardell, Clare Potter and Vera Maxwell set out to
banish that thief from their realm. They were followed by Anne
Klein, Bonnie Cashin and Anne Fogarty, among others, then by Donna
Karan and Diane Von Furstenberg, the youngest designers in the
show. (Karan will surely be remembered for the quality of her work,
and Von Furstenberg will surely be remembered for the quality of
her marketing.)
</P>
<P>
   How did these designers represent American women? As fresh-faced
but never fresh teen-age girls, as vigorous but graceful suburban
wives and mothers, as clever but never strident career women.
Fashion has to work by cleverly manipulating these dualities; its
job is to make what is dangerous and marginal seem desirable and
natural. And so a prostitute's stiletto boots and torn fishnet
stockings become wittily vulgar and bold, while hip-hop clothing,
so funky, so black and so Latino, becomes jaunty, white and very
Tommy Hilfiger, too. That's why we are so repelled by clothes that
have just fallen out of fashion. We feel like Titanias who've been
caught in the clutches of jackasses or like the jackass that has
been cast off by Titania.
</P>
<P>
   The ``American Ingenuity'' clothes are filled with these
contradictions. They are opulent but pragmatic. Cost and function
attest to certain social privileges (ah, that golf dress and those
leisure-time day ensembles), but they bestow certain democratic
prerogatives as well (modest cottons and denims, clothes to do
house or factory work in, shapes that adapt to all kinds of
bodies). Some seem made for what Isadora Duncan, the early-1900s
dance pioneer, called the ideal woman of the future: ``The highest
intelligence in the freest body.'' Others see that ideal woman as a
handsome, movable fetish object.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone walking through the show will follow the same zigzag
course; modern fashion can't help being a catalyst for
autobiography, too. (Why don't more men write about their relation
to what they wear, used to wear and still long to wear?)
</P>
<P>
   If you were a girl in the 1940s or '50s, did your mother dress
you in Emily Wilkins-esque dresses with smocking, ruffled collars
and bows or flowers at the waist? Did you like them? And if you
belong to the ``Free to Be You and Me'' generation, do these
dresses look preposterous, hazardous to the health of the teen-age
and preteen-age female psyche, or do they possess a certain allure
that reason cannot assuage?
</P>
<P>
   When I came upon lithe black evening culottes by McCardell from
1934, I recalled the thrill of being allowed to wear my own modest
daytime pair to high school 30 years later: it combined slightly
defiant revelation (they were pants) with still-flirtatious
disguise (they looked like a skirt).
</P>
<P>
   Some clothes made great demands, physically and psychologically.
Like the Cashin jumpsuit, with those ``Look at me, I'm daring and
adorable'' olive and orange stripes, or the dark, discreet one by
Geoffrey Beene, which signals, ``I'm so offhandedly classy that
you'll have to do a double take before you realize that I'm daring,
too.'' But Vera Maxwell's trim 1944 Rosie the Riveter jumpsuit,
made for women in wartime factories, sends just one message:
physical competence and concentration are essential and elegant.
</P>
<P>
   The show's curator, Richard Martin, stresses the structural ways
in which these designers made clothing for women more useful and
modern. They built pockets and purses into skirts and jackets,
dispensed with elaborate, hard-to-reach fastenings, designed
separates that were easy to combine and then recombine and adapted
men's fabrics and tailoring techniques. But the shifts in attitude
also come through in cheeky, displays of wit. Cashin takes the
traditional WASP country club colors of green and pink and turns
them into a city lights midriff-baring dress of jersey and suede,
while McCardell converts the man in the gray flannel suit into a
woman in a gray flannel swimsuit.
</P>
<P>
   We make sharp, clear distinctions between fashion that looks
dated and fashion that looks timeless, and unless we're cultivating
a retro look, ``dated'' is a nasty word. But it doesn't have to be.
Many of the dress-and-coat ensembles from the 1960s look dated to
me: carefully shaped and cut, the lining of the coat usually
matching the pattern of the dress. It's fun to look at them in a
museum, as you look at period furniture or statuary, and it's fun
to imagine how some women might look in them today; but it's not
very interesting to imagine how women would act or move in them.
These clothes have symmetry but they do not have dynamism.
</P>
<P>
   McCardell does, though, and that is what makes her the
revelation of this show. McCardell savored the contradictions of
the female body: she knew how to disclose or conceal its parts
without making either process ostentatious. She did this by making
clothes that a woman could adapt to her body in all sorts of ways:
a belt or no belt, dress strings tied around the waist or just
below the breasts, the adjustment of the wrapped bodice of an
evening gown. Severe fabrics and lines characterize her beach wear,
while delicate ornamental touches appear on the most easygoing
workaday dresses.
</P>
<P>
   McCardell's calculated modesty can be visually underwhelming
compared with some of the clothes here. Some of those plaids are
just too drab; the denim-derived topstiching on dress pockets, suit
jackets and tops can look too self-conscious about its own
sportiness. But keep looking.
</P>
<P>
   Edith Wharton, who knew so much about female constraints, once
called the face the theater of varied human emotions. McCardell's
designs undermine our fixed social readings of clothes and give the
body that same privilege.
</P>
<P>
   All of which has to do with why we want to call certain artists
timeless. They let us live in the past and the present
simultaneously; they make us eager to imagine the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-98 1849EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980628.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-28 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0822 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-NEXTWAVE-FESTIVAL-     06-28 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NEXTWAVE-FESTIVAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROOKLY ACADEMY ANNOUNCES LINEUP FOR '98 NEXT WAVE FESTIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Brooklyn Academy of Music will open its 1998 Next
Wave Festival on Sept. 9 with the American premiere of ``Eclipse,''
the latest spectacle from the French equestrian troupe Zingaro. The
production features 26 horses, 18 riders, dancers and acrobats and
a seven-member folk-music ensemble performing dreamlike sequences
based on the contrast between black and white. The troupe, which
made its U.S. debut in ``Chimere'' in 1996, will present 41
performances at Battery Park City through Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The festival, in its 16th season, will move to its Brooklyn home
on Oct. 8 with the New York premiere of the Bill T. Jones/Arnie
Zane Dance Company's ``We Set Out Early ... Visibility Was Poor.''
Divided into three sections, the work combines ballet, modern,
social and ethnic dance forms set to music by Stravinsky, Cage and
the Lithuanian composer Peteris Vasks.
</P>
<P>
   Ballett Frankfurt will make its first New York appearance in
nearly a decade in the U.S. premiere of William Forsythe's ``Eidos:
Telos,'' based on the tale of the spider woman, Arachne, who flouts
time by spinning a web. Other dance performances include the local
premieres of Ballet Preljocaj's ``Romeo and Juliet,''
Chandralekha's ``Raga _ In Search of Femininity'' and Susan
Marshall's ``Most Dangerous Room in the House.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Wilson's and Philip Glass' opera ``Monsters of Grace,'' a
three-dimensional, computer-animated 70-millimeter film with live
music and vocals, will be given its New York premiere, as will
Steve Reich and Beryl Korot's ``Hindenburg.'' The first part of a
documentary video opera to be completed by 2001, ``Hindenburg''
explores the impact of new technology on the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   The violinist Gidon Kremer will lead his Kremerata Musica in
Astor Piazzolla's tango opera ``Maria de Buenos Aires,'' written
with and narrated by his lifelong collaborator, Uruguayan poet
Horacio Ferrer. ``Powder Her Face,'' Thomas Ades' opera about the
scandalous life of Margaret, the Duchess of Argyll, will be
performed by the Brooklyn Philharmonic in a semistaged version
conducted by Robert Spano.
</P>
<P>
   Spano will also lead the orchestra in ``AB&AMP;C,'' a program of
works by John Adams, Luciano Berio and Elliott Carter, presented in
honor of Carter's 90th birthday. Other music events include a
25th-anniversary celebration by the Kronos Quartet and the U.S.
premiere of Schubert's ``Winterreise,'' produced by Christian
Boltanski, Jean Kalman and Hans-Peter Cloos. Don Byron returns as
the host of ``Jazz _ the Next Wave'' with Latin masters Tito Puente
and Giovanni Hidalgo.
</P>
<P>
   Two theater productions will also be given their U.S. premieres:
``Anna Karenina,'' presented by the English company Shared
Experience, and Vasilios Calitsis' and Tasos Roussos' ``World
Mysteries: The Mysteries of Eleusis,'' inspired by the Greek myth
of Demeter and Persephone.
</P>
<P>
   The festival is sponsored by Philip Morris Co.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
