<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-28 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0833 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASIA-ECON-NYT &LR;      06-28 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIA-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUBIN DELIVERING TOUGH MESSAGE TO STRUGGLING ASIAN ECONOMIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MARK LANDLER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia _ Visiting China may pose thorny
political issues for President Clinton. But for Treasury Secretary
Robert Rubin, who peeled off from the White House delegation Sunday
to visit Asian countries with troubled economies, China could turn
out to be the smoothest part of his trip.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving here Sunday evening, Rubin had to face a fresh volley
of criticism of the United States from Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad, who accused the American government of plotting
with Wall Street to take over Asia's economies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They accuse us of practicing cronyism,'' Mahathir said in a
speech at a political gathering here on Saturday. ``The cooperation
between the U.S. government and Wall Street is cronyism.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahathir, a relentless critic of the West, drew world attention
last October when he delivered a strident denunciation of George
Soros and the fraternity of global financiers. He blames the
financial crisis on currency traders, who he says played havoc with
the region's currencies. And he says the U.S. government is
standing by while Wall Street buys Asian companies at fire-sale
prices.
</P>
<P>
   For Rubin, a Wall Street executive before he took his job in
Washington, such charges are a painful reminder that the Asian
financial crisis is generating intense frustration among some of
the region's leaders. The message Rubin is expected to deliver in a
meeting with Mahathir on Monday is unlikely to soothe his feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The international community has a great deal of work to do,''
said Rubin, in a briefing during his flight from Beijing to Kuala
Lumpur. ``These problems are not going to be solved quickly, but it
is absolutely imperative that we deal with these problems and work
with the countries that are affected.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin's trip began on a positive note, with assurances from
Chinese leaders that they do not plan to devalue their currency,
the yuan. But now he is in southeast Asia, which has already
suffered a wave of crippling devaluations. In addition to Malaysia,
he will travel to Thailand and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin declined to discuss specific remedies for Malaysia before
his meetings on Monday. But the Treasury Department generally
favors the International Monetary Fund's economic prescription for
Asia, which calls for tight fiscal and monetary policy, coupled
with a wholesale reform of the banking system and the often-corrupt
relationships between business executives and government officials.
</P>
<P>
   Critics contend, though, that the cure has actually worsened the
pain in Thailand, South Korea and Indonesia. By insisting that
these countries maintain a stable currency, even if it means
raising interest rates, they say the IMF has choked off credit to
businesses. The economies of all three countries contracted in the
first quarter of 1998, and analysts say they are sliding into a
severe recession.
</P>
<P>
   Malaysia has not asked for the IMF's help, though it has adopted
a reform plan with features like those the fund requires. Like its
neighbors, Malaysia's economy shrank in the first quarter _ a 1.8
percent contraction that was all the more traumatic because it
followed 6.9 percent expansion in the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden reversal in fortunes has sparked a remarkable public
debate at the top levels of government. On one side is Mahathir,
who argues that the central bank should lower interest rates to
jump-start the economy. On the other side is Deputy Prime Minister
Anwar Ibrahim, who opposes such a step because he fears it would
erode Malaysia's currency, the ringgit.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar has long been regarded as Mahathir's probable successor,
but political experts here said the dispute had frayed their
relationship. Last week, Mahathir named Daim Zainuddin, another
close adviser, to a new Cabinet post overseeing the economy.
Economic trouble-shooting had been Anwar's brief, and it is unclear
how he will emerge from this shake-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The debate over interest rates is really part of a broader
debate over globalism vs. nationalism,'' said one business
executive here who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``Anwar still
has faith in the global markets, while Mahathir is playing to
nationalist sentiments.''
</P>
<P>
   As a leading emissary for the global economy, Rubin will have to
wade into this debate, if only for a day. He met briefly with Anwar
on Sunday evening and will hold separate meetings with Anwar and
Mahathir on Monday. Zainuddin will participate in at least one of
the sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Malaysia's internal tensions have been aggravated
by the turmoil in nearby Indonesia, where President Suharto was
forced out after economic hardship led to riots and looting. Though
Malaysia's situation is nowhere near as dire as that of Indonesia,
analysts said that Mahathir is deeply concerned about the social
unrest that can stem from deprivation.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Rubin said he would focus on the issue of a
``social safety net,'' which he said was critical ``so that you can
maintain your public and political support for what needs to be
done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got wrenching changes in countries that are in very
difficult circumstances,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
