A0836 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUMMER-COLUMN29-COX     06-28 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUMMER-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Although not graceful, Klesko is the perfect outfielder
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In all the usual ways, the Braves won the first game
of the second half Sunday. You know the constants by now. Stand-up
starting pitching from Tom Glavine and errorless outfield play by
Ryan Klesko.
</P>
<P>
   The sameness of it all was monotonous. Every pitch had a
purpose. Every fly ball had a place to go and have a little fun.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time _ oh, say last Monday _ when equating Klesko
with defense would have been like pairing Dennis Rodman with an
Amish barn-raising. But after 82 games and 0 errors, might it be
time to adjust? Or at least give a little notice to the
leftfielder-in-progress who has made noticeable, if sometimes
reckless, strides.
</P>
<P>
   ''Don't know if he'll ever be a Gold Glove outfielder,'' said
Glavine, ''but Ryan has done a great job improving out there. He's
far better than the days when a fly ball went out there and
everybody in the stands closed their eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There have been a lot of years (four-plus, actually) working
at getting better. A lot of years of people saying I couldn't play
the position,'' Klesko said. ''They seem to forget it's not my
natural position. It has taken a lot of work.''
</P>
<P>
   He had spent the preceding four games at his more genetically
compatible station, first base, while Andres Galarraga nursed a bad
back. He enjoyed it immensely, but it took much away from the
ambiance of a Braves game.
</P>
<P>
   With Randall Simon dispatched to first, we were warmed to see
Klesko back at his leftfield outpost Sunday. It had been so bland
out there without him. There was no edge. No tightrope-walking,
bomb-defusing, dark-alley sense of danger. Where's the fun, after
all, in the routine fly ball?
</P>
<P>
   Seems cruel to keep him penned up at first base. All was right
with Sunday's victory by the fourth inning, when Toronto's Shawn
Green hit a slicing drive toward Klesko's quadrant. As is custom,
Klesko seemed momentarily puzzled by the trajectory, his heartbeat
of hesitation lending the usual drama to the moment. Then, he threw
himself in the alleged direction of the ball, covering a surprising
amount of ground in a one-man stampede. Fully extended, full-speed
ahead, Klesko and ball became one.
</P>
<P>
   That freed him to make this proud claim: He was the only man to
catch anything Green hit Sunday. Green was the single outstanding
Blue Jay, with two home runs and a single in the 10-3 loss.
</P>
<P>
   Klesko's is the knack of making it all look as hard as it really
is. He'll run into walls, crash face-first into the sod like a
heavy bomber with one wing on fire, slide after foul balls long
after they have landed in the seats, and generally have a nice time
out there in his own little private pasture.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's not Andruw Jones out there. He's not swift and sleek.
He's a big, rumbling type of guy. He's not going to look good doing
it, but the bottom line is that the results are a lot better,''
Glavine said.
</P>
<P>
   While there's a chance, we pause now in rare appreciation of the
Braves leftfielder. With a style of defense as refined as a mosh
pit and a swing as subtle as a waterspout, Klesko makes baseball
even more a game of extremes. For the time being, life is quite
good (he's hitting .382 for June).
</P>
<P>
   ''I keep playing hard and eventually I will make an error here
or there,'' he said, lest fly balls to left no longer set off
calliope music in our heads and we begin to expect simple
perfection.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Hummer's column appears in the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
