<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-MEXICO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO FACES GERMANY IN SECOND ROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT-DENIS, France _ They were called the ``Tritanic,'' a
disaster waiting to happen, a ship sure to sink. But somewhere en
route to hitting bottom in Lyon, or Bordeaux, or Saint-Etienne,
maybe all three something extraordinary occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Tricolor,'' Mexico's national soccer team, tossed aside
all the negatives that had burdened it since the start of spring
can't score, can't win, can't play with any of the style and charm
expected south of the border and became this World Cup's version of
the cardiac kids.
</P>
<P>
   A comeback victory over South Korea, followed by astonishing
rallies to draw with Belgium and the Netherlands, has captured the
imagination of the throngs that have gathered in France for these
championships, and it has stirred confidence in the Mexican squad
heading into today's second-round battle with Germany at
Montpellier's Stade de La Mosson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we are Columbus' three small ships, about to come into
port,'' said Manuel Lapuente, the once-beleaguered Mexican coach.
``I think we are getting close to our best, but there are no
limits. The sky's the limit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mexicans have been talking championship since rallying to
beat the Koreans in their opener June 13 in Lyon. It seems a most
unlikely scenario, but each time they find themselves in serious
trouble as when they fell behind, 2-0, to the Belgians and the
Dutch a hero emerges to save the day.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, it's Luis Hernandez, ``El Matador,'' who scored twice
to beat South Korea, 3-1, then flicked home the decisive goal in
injury time to earn a 2-2 tie with Holland. His striking partner,
Cuauhtemoc Blanco, did the job against Belgium with a stunning
volley to complete the comeback. And Ricardo Pelaez, the aging
forward who comes on when Lapuente goes to a four-attacker
formation, has pitched in with two fine headers, goals that started
the rallies against South Korea and Holland.
</P>
<P>
   The Germans, clear favorites to advance to a quarterfinal
pairing with Romania or Croatia, promise they won't underestimate
the Mexicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made up a two-goal deficit against Holland,'' Germany
goalkeeper Andreas Koepke said. ``They are a good team, and we will
have to watch them. No team is easy at this stage of the
competition, and we have a difficult game coming up.''
</P>
<P>
   How difficult may be determined by the impact of Ramon Ramirez's
absence from the Mexican lineup. The left winger, with captain
Alberto Garcia Aspe Mexico's most influential player, will sit out
the match, serving a two-game suspension for using abusive language
after a Blanco goal was canceled by an offsides call near the end
of the game with the Netherlands. It was a foolish error Ramirez
already had a first-round yellow card and faced suspension with
another and it could prove costly.
</P>
<P>
   Germany, seeking its fourth World Cup crown, has twice
eliminated Mexico twice in the previous five tournaments, a 6-0
rout in 1978 and a penalty-kick win in Mexico in the 1986
quarterfinals. The Mexican media has played up the revenge factor,
but Lapuente won't play along.
</P>
<P>
   ``The talk of controversy and revenge is your business, it's all
part of the pre-match hype,'' he said. ``We're not thinking of
revenge. We just want to go forward. The Dutch and Germans are
among those fighting for the title, and we want to be up there with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Dutch defender Jaap Stam thinks that's conceivable. ``The
Mexicans are true fighters,'' he said. ``Their technique is not
very good, but they compensate for that with their mental approach.
They play from the heart.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an element that has been missing from the German game. They
won Group E on the strength of the 2-0 victory over the United
States in their opener, but despite fine work from their striking
tandem Juergen Klinsmann and Oliver Bierhoff, both with two goals
and a defense led by Christian Woerns, they haven't yet looked like
title contenders.
</P>
<P>
   That might mean nothing Germany is notorious for starting slow
and getting stronger as the Cup proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it is all or nothing,'' Klinsmann says. ``We are capable
of moving up a gear. ... We can beat any team here.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexico shares the attitude. The world will learn this afternoon
if the Tri can back it up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
