<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-28 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0839 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDS-VACCINE-COX     06-28 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-VACCINE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Report calls for government, private companies to do more for
AIDS vaccine
 &HT;    (EDS: Moves on (a) general news and (i) international
categories.)
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ The only real cure for AIDS will be a vaccine, most
AIDS researchers agree. But a working vaccine is at least 10 years
away, and the search still moves slowly.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to galvanize vaccine research into an urgent hunt,
the International AIDS Vaccine Initiative (IAVI) Sunday released a
blueprint for AIDS vaccine development. The report calls for both
government-funded research organizations and private drug companies
to invest much more time and money in vaccine research, and urges
that existing vaccine candidates be speeded into testing in humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only a vaccine has any chance of ending a global AIDS
epidemic,'' said Dr. Seth Berkeley, founder and president of the
non-profit IAVI.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will put us on the fast track toward accomplishing our
goal.''
</P>
<P>
   IAVI and other vaccine advocacy groups have criticized the
slowness of the vaccine testing pipeline. IAVI's blueprint suggests
that several vaccines should be in testing simultaneously, instead
of sequentially.
</P>
<P>
   The blueprint also recommends creating three to six product
development teams of researchers and drug manufacturers, with
representatives of both industrialized and developing countries.
</P>
<P>
   IAVI also suggests that vaccines should be tailored to the
various strains of HIV, the virus that causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Since much of the current vaccine research is being done in the
U. S., the AIDS vaccine candidates that have been tested so far are
designed for the HIV strain that is most common in the U. S.
</P>
<P>
   But 90 percent of the 30.6 million people who are HIV-positive
live in developing countries, where other types of the virus are
prevalent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paternalism has kept products from being tested in developing
countries,'' Berkeley said.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1997, President Clinton announced the creation of a
vaccine research institute at the National Institutes of Health,
and declared the goal of having a working vaccine by 2007.
</P>
<P>
   But that's unlikely to happen, say some vaccine experts. While
more than 40 AIDS vaccines have been tested, only one, VaxGen's
AIDSVAX, has been approved for testing in a large number of people.
The first of 5,000 volunteers received an AIDSVAX innoculation last
week in Philadelphia. Researchers estimate it may be two years
before the next vaccine candidate is ready to move into large-scale
trials.
</P>
<P>
   IAVI says this process must be speeded up, even if it means
testing vaccines that may not provide immunity for 100 percent of
recipients. Every test teaches researchers more about the nature of
HIV.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to be afraid of failure,'' said Dr. Jaap
Goutsmit of the Netherlands, a member of IAVI's scientific advisory
committee.
</P>
<P>
   The plan outlined in the IAVI recommendations would cost about
$350 million to $500 million, above what is currently being spent
on vaccine research and development, over the next nine years.
</P>
<P>
   IAVI also announced Sunday that Microsoft CEO Bill Gates and his
wife, Melinda, have contributed $1.5 million through the
billionaire's William H. Gates Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
