<DOCNO> NYT19980628.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-28 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0840 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-TAIWAN-625&AMP;ADD-     06-28 1273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TAIWAN-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN NERVOUSLY TOASTS CLINTON'S VISIT TO CHINA
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: CHINA-SUMMIT, CHINA-CHURCH, CHINA-LAMA, CHINA-HILLARY,
CHINA-U.S.) 
(ja) 
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan _ As the festivities and pomp of President
Clinton's state visit unfold on the other side of the Taiwan
Strait, the mood here is sullen and profoundly nervous.
</P>
<P>
   The Foreign Ministry has set up a 24-hour situation room to
follow moment-by-moment developments of Clinton's trip, the
government has impaneled an interagency task force to monitor it,
and thousands of Taiwanese have signed petitions or taken to the
streets to warn the United States not to sacrifice the people here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are afraid that Americans will betray us,'' said Lin
Fong-lan, a 48-year-old housewife who was apprehensive enough to
take part in a sit-in Saturday outside the United States'
quasi-embassy in Taipei. ``Americans may think about their own
interests and sacrifice Taiwan.''
</P>
<P>
   Disagreements about Taiwan have been hovering over the
Chinese-American summit meeting, for Washington's ties with Taiwan
remain a central obstacle to improved relations between China and
the United States. China regards Taiwan as a renegade province and
would like the United States to curtail its unofficial relations
and arms shipments to the island.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan officials were enormously reassured when Clinton and
President Jiang Zemin of China concluded their statements and news
conference in Beijing without talking about arms sales or raising
other matters affecting Taiwan. At a luncheon Saturday with several
senior officials, there were beaming faces and toasts all around
when word came that the Clinton-Jiang news conference had ended
without any unpleasant surprises about Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're relieved so far,'' David Lee, the deputy foreign
minister and head of the interagency task force monitoring the
Clinton trip, said as he tucked delightedly into the lunch. ``At
least from the public information so far, we haven't heard anything
alarming.''
</P>
<P>
   From an American perspective, Taiwan's anxieties might seem a
bit overwrought, for the Clinton administration keeps repeating
that its Taiwan policies will not change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's obvious that there will be no change in our
position one way or another on this trip,'' Clinton said Friday of
relations with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for people in Taiwan, biting their lips as they watch
Clinton gallivanting around the mainland with Jiang, the assurances
of continuing American affections have not removed the heartache.
</P>
<P>
   The perception here is that over the last couple of years, the
Clinton administration has been distancing itself from Taiwan,
narrowing its options and pressing it not to cause trouble for
Chinese-American relations.
</P>
<P>
   All that has been painful for a country whose people brim with
enthusiasm for the United States _ the island's most popular radio
station broadcasts in English and is ostentatiously American, and
people occasionally embarrass American officials by suggesting that
Taiwan would make a great 51st state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been America's star pupil _ we've built democracy and
freedom just as America wanted,'' said Huang Chao-yuan, a physics
professor who heads an academic organization that set up a
demonstration Saturday to warn the United States against any
agreement with China that would hurt Taiwan. ``So why are you
prepared to turn your backs on us?''
</P>
<P>
   The underlying challenge for people here is simply that China is
becoming increasingly powerful in the world today, and so China is
gaining leverage and Taiwan is losing its own, with nearly all
countries now recognizing Beijing over Taipei. That trend is
evident in the pattern of state visits: China is hosting Clinton,
and Taiwan last week had to settle for the president of Sao Tome
and Principe, a tiny African island nation with 105,000
inhabitants.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``To be candid, I don't think we have much leverage to prevent
Clinton from doing something about Taiwan, because we're so
dependent on America,'' said Parris Chang, chairman of the defense
committee in Parliament. ``But we will try to use moral persuasion
to shame Clinton so that he does not appease a Communist
dictatorship by sacrificing a democratic country like Taiwan.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason for apprehension in Taiwan is that when Clinton met
Jiang in Washington last fall, the State Department spokesman,
James Rubin, described Washington's Taiwan policy in a way that
some people here felt was more formal and restrictive than before.
</P>
<P>
   The essence of that statement, here dubbed the ``three no's,''
was that the United States does not support Taiwan independence,
does not support a two-China policy or a ``one China, one Taiwan''
policy and does not support Taiwan's membership in international
organizations whose members are sovereign countries.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan officials are exultant that Clinton has not mentioned a
formulation of the ``three no's'' so far during this trip.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, partly because of concerns raised by Taiwan's many
friends in Washington _ Taiwan has a formidable lobbying
organization in the United States _ administration officials have
been falling over themselves lately to reassure Congress that
improved relations with China will not come at the expense of
Taiwan. And indeed, when China conducted missile tests in 1996 in
an effort to intimidate Taiwan, Clinton reacted forcefully by
sending two aircraft carriers to the area.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Taiwan is still the ugly duckling of international
diplomacy, its investors welcome but its leaders grounded. Taiwan's
president, Lee Teng-hui, who holds a Ph.D from Cornell, has been
effectively barred from visiting the United States since he was
granted a visa in 1995 to visit Cornell, enraging China. The United
States also bans top Taiwan Cabinet members from visiting
Washington or most American Cabinet members from visiting Taiwan,
for fear of upsetting relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   Thus as people here hear Clinton talk about the need to build a
better relationship with China, they wonder anxiously whether the
tide of history is running against Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is never easy for a lesser power to confront the fact that
it is a lesser power,'' Michel Oksenberg, a political scientist at
Stanford University, said of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all Taiwan's citizens are ethnically Chinese, but the
island has been ruled by mainland China for only four years in this
century. It was a Japanese colony until the end of World War II in
1945, and then in 1949 it became the refuge of Chiang Kai-shek when
he fled there with his Nationalist troops.
</P>
<P>
   For many years after that, Taiwan was the seat of ``Nationalist
China'' while Beijing was the capital of ``Communist China.'' The
two rival governments insulted each other while each insisting that
it was the legitimate ruler of all China.
</P>
<P>
   One of Taiwan's most ubiquitous slogans used to be ``Recover the
Mainland,'' but now many people feel their own separate identity
and would not want to recover the mainland if they had a chance.
Instead, many simply want an independent country, separate from
China.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Lien Chan emphasized in a nationwide radio show
Saturday that Taiwan is not against better relations between
Washington and Beijing, and that in fact such improved ties may
help moderate China's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want relations between the U.S. and the Chinese Communists
to develop smoothly,'' Lien said. ``But we don't want that process
to hurt our own interests.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
