<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOW MALONE DID SO WELL ON AT&AMP;T'S TAKEOVER OF TCI
</P>
<P>
   John Malone, the chairman of Tele-Communications, made a
lucrative deal for himself when he agreed to sell his cable company
to AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   The class B shares he owns will receive 9.7 percent more a share
in AT&AMP;T stock than TCI's class A shares will get. Malone will also
retain control of Liberty Media, TCI's programming company, and can
sell a handful of key assets to AT&AMP;T. If Liberty is ever sold,
Liberty's shareholders, not AT&AMP;T shareholders, will get the profit.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUSA IS CHANGING THE INDUSTRY
</P>
<P>
   CompUSA's chief executive, James Halpin, came in and saved the
company in 1994 when it was on the brink of collapse. But the
computer retailer faces strong competition from direct marketers
like Dell Computer that take orders on the Internet or over the
phone and offer more megahertz for the money. Now Halpin has agreed
to acquire CompUSA's chief rival, Computer City, from Tandy for
$275 million and has just started selling computers on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   INTEL CHOOSES THE SILENT APPROACH
</P>
<P>
   Intel has decided not to debate the Federal Trade Commission's
antitrust suit in public. One reason for the silence is that the
chip maker believes Microsoft hurt its antitrust case by hiring
lobbyists and issuing sharp denunciations of the government.
</P>
<P>
   HEARST REJOINS PUBLISHERS BUREAU
</P>
<P>
   Hearst Magazines announced that it had rejoined the Publishers
Information Bureau, the trade group that tracks magazines'
advertising pages. The magazine company had resigned from the
bureau to protest its decision to count the ad pages in Conde
Nast's supplement Currency.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTATOR PREFERS THE INTERNET
</P>
<P>
   James Cramer appears as a commentator on ABC's ``Good Morning
America,'' as a guest co-host on CNBC and in print with regular
columns in GQ and The New York Observer; he also has alliances with
online ventures including America Online and Yahoo. But he prefers
the immediacy the Internet gives him as a co-founder and columnist
for the online service TheStreet.com.
</P>
<P>
   RESEARCHERS WIN THREE PATENTS
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology and
Children's Hospital of Boston won three patents that medical
scientists hope will someday mean that patients in need of a
transplant can grow their own healthy new hearts, kidneys, livers
or other organs.
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION BACKS COMPUTER FILTERS
</P>
<P>
   An Oklahoma congressman won preliminary support for legislation
that would require public schools and libraries to use filters on
their computers as a way to keep children from seeing sexually
explicit material on the Internet. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
