A0846 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAN-CAVEDWELLERS-ART     06-28 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-CAVEDWELLERS-ART-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAN'S CAVE DWELLERS HAVE WATER, ELECTRICITY AND NOT MUCH ELSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map of Kanduvan is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO  
 &HT;     
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANDUVAN, Iran _ There is not much evidence of the Islamic
Republic in the caves of Kanduvan.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty miles southwest of Tabriz, hidden in the side of a deep
valley with only one access route, is an odd honeycomb of caves
that hundreds of people call home.
</P>
<P>
   The Turkish-speaking herders who live in the damp dwellings dug
into the steep, strangely shaped cones of porous volcanic rock do
not talk much about politics. In fact, they don't talk much at all
_ at least not to foreigners or Persian-speaking city folk from
Tehran.
</P>
<P>
   These cave dwellers are not like their sophisticated
counterparts in the rugged Goreme Valley in the Cappadocia region
of Turkey, one of that country's most popular tourist spots.
</P>
<P>
   The largest caves there have been made into bars and
restaurants, and there is even a 16-room cave-hotel. A Goreme
address is now considered to be healthy, even fashionable.
</P>
<P>
   Villagers in Kanduvan have a much tougher life.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, there is a breathtaking view of the green Sahand
Mountains on the other side of the valley. And most of the cave
dwellers have at least minimal electricity _ tapped from the main
electrical lines below _ and cold running water pumped up from a
spring.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, the government paved the road leading into
the village. And a health clinic is an easy donkey ride away.
</P>
<P>
   But most people live in only one room. They can try to expand by
digging deeper, but at their peril.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be careful not to dig into our neighbor's house,''
one villager said. And the walls of a cave that is too big can
crack and collapse.
</P>
<P>
   The caves that are not inhabited by people belong to sheep,
goats and roosters. The villagers bake their bread and cook their
meals _ stews mostly _ in outdoor clay ovens.
</P>
<P>
   There are no telephones, although the villagers have formally
petitioned the government to install telephone lines. At least one
cave dweller has a television, but the reception is not very good.
There is no local newspaper, mail delivery, nearby mosque or call
to prayer, and three years seems to be the average extent of
education.
</P>
<P>
   Women cover their heads in colorful scarves, less to be
religiously observant than to keep out the thick dust kicked up
from the crumbling stone.
</P>
<P>
   The only light in the caves comes from one or two bare light
bulbs, tiny windows that also serve as an outlet for smoke and
cracks in the heavy wooden doors, which are three to five feet
high.
</P>
<P>
   The most difficult time is during the brutally long winters,
when heavy snow and wind come and there is never enough heat. To
try to keep warm, the people use makeshift heaters in which they
burn dried manure, the same fuel they use for cooking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a hard, hard life,'' said one woman who had moved to
Tabriz and was back to visit her family. ``I don't plan to come
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Another challenge for the cave dwellers, although not the
highest priority, is bathing. The local authorities shut down the
village's only communal bath several months ago, branding it a
health hazard. So the villagers have rigged up makeshift outdoor
showers. They say they bathe once or twice a month.
</P>
<P>
   Behind wooden doors, open pits swarming with flies serve as
toilets. Every once in a while, the waste is covered with ash,
emptied and dried to make more fuel.
</P>
<P>
   The walls are painted white to brighten the dim spaces. Thin,
brightly colored woven carpets serve as floor coverings and
seating. Dusty, thin mattresses are laid out when it is time to
sleep. Bookshelves and closets have been chiseled into the tufa
stone.
</P>
<P>
   People have lived here since pre-Islamic times _ more than 1,300
years ago _ but Kanduvan is scarcely mentioned in guidebooks on
Iran. Shah Mohammed Riza Pahlevi tried to avoid drawing attention
to the remnants of Iran's folkloric past, which he believed smacked
of backwardness, preferring to spotlight the symbols of the
2,500-year-old Persian empire instead.
</P>
<P>
   And when revolution and violence gripped Tabriz, the capital of
Azerbaijan Province, in the late 1970s, the cave dwellers of
Kanduvan were largely untouched.
</P>
<P>
   In the home of one family that a foreign guest stayed in, a huge
electric clock with a portrait of the late Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini, the father of Iran's Islamic revolution, hung on the
wall. But the owner, Hassan, said he knew little of politics.
</P>
<P>
   When asked how Iran's reform-minded president, Mohammad Khatami,
was doing, he confused him with Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, Iran's
conservative spiritual leader. Then he added, ``Whoever brings
security to the country and low prices, we like him.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it had never occurred to him to leave Kanduvan. ``When
you are born in a place, your spirit is born there too, and your
spirit wants to stay,'' he said. ``Even if we were not happy here,
where are we supposed to go? How would we survive in a city like
Tehran?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Not everyone here is content with the status quo. A few years
ago, Hashem Akbari, 35, who owns a triplex cave, bought a choice
plot of real estate along the road at the base of the hills. He
built an austere five-room, three-story guesthouse and put in a
kitchen on the ground floor to cook stews and kebabs for guests. He
taught himself Persian so he could communicate better.
</P>
<P>
   But he does not know what to charge for the rooms, since he has
not had many customers yet. And since there is a school in
Kanduvan, but no teacher, he has taken to spending the school year
with his wife and three children in an apartment in Tabriz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is so difficult here,'' he said. ``We can make money if
more tourists come. But it is no place to live.
</P>
<P>
   But the shopkeeper next door who sells biscuits and locally
bottled Pepsi prefers to keep things just the way they are.
</P>
<P>
   In a tiny shop filled with more flies than customers, he laughed
when an Iranian visitor said that maybe some of the American
tourists who have begun to discover Iran would come and he would
make enough money to build a great restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no, don't do that,'' he said in Turkish. ``Don't let that
happen. If I make money, the Islamic Republic would come and take
it away.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
