<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-DENMARK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENMARK ROUTS NIGERIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT-DENIS, France _ Playing like the ``old, famous Danish''
teams of the past translation: brilliantly Denmark ended Africa's
World Cup hopes Sunday and spoiled a long-anticipated matchup,
stunning Nigeria, 4-1, at the Stade de France.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Moller and Brian Laudrup scored goals in the first 10
minutes, and the Danes better known these days for their fight and
spirit than for their skills advanced to a quarterfinal Friday
against Brazil in Nantes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why we play like this suddenly is impossible to explain ...
,'' Denmark coach Bo Johansson said. ``Now we play the best team in
the world. We know, so far, we are not the best team in the world,
but we have to try.''
</P>
<P>
   Many figured it would be Nigeria that would be taking on the
Brazilians in what promised to be an attractive, attack-minded
game. But the Danes struck quickly, and goalkeeper Peter Rufai let
down the Super Eagles again and again, killing their chances to get
back into the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody dreams to be world champion,'' said Bora
Milutinovic, Nigeria's coach. ``To be world champion you need to
have so many things to be best in the world. We go through (to the
second round) like no one in Africa, (but) it's very difficult. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Team lose today. Team win yesterday. This is the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Danes, looking more like the superb 1986 team that thrilled
audiences in Mexico, finished things off early. The first strike
came in the second minute, from a pass out of midfield that found
Michael Laudrup, Brian's brother, behind the Nigerian defense. He
squared the ball to Moller, who bent the ball around Rufai and
inside the right post.
</P>
<P>
   Eight minutes later, Moller took a blast off a 27-yard free
kick; Rufai stopped it but surrendered a rebound, and Brian Laudrup
raced in to knock it home.
</P>
<P>
   With a strong defense led by Peter Schmeichel, perhaps the
world's top goalkeeper, the Danes owned the result.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles didn't give up, and their attack primarily through
the work of Jay-Jay Okocha put plenty of pressure on Denmark's back
line. Nwankwo Kanu ended up 1-on-1 with Schmeichel in the 16th
minute, but the netminder grabbed the ball off his foot; poor
shooting doomed Nigeria's other chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not that good, so we can't keep the pressure (up)
against a team like Nigeria all the time,'' Johansson said. ``We
know we have to fight very hard also to have victory. Nigeria is a
very good team, and that says much about our performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebbe Sand set a World Cup record scoring just 22 seconds after
coming on as a substitute in the 59th minute, a nifty little
sequence from a Michael Laudrup scoop in which he headed the ball
past Taribo West and then fired past Rufai then took advantage of
another Rufai error to help set up Thomas Helveg in the 76th.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria got one back two minutes later, a superb Okocha pass
from midfield leading to a Tijani Babangida strike.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
