<SLUG> BC-CHINA-HILLARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS CHINA'S LEGAL SYSTEM GROWS, SO DOES LEGAL HELP FOR WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: This story is scheduled to be topped between 9 and 10
p.m. Sunday night, after Hillary Clinton's visit.) 
(fb) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ From its tiny office just outside the South Gate of
Beijing University, the Center for Women's Laws Studies and Legal
Services, which Hillary Rodham Clinton visited Sunday morning,
operates at the leading edge of China's developing legal system,
tackling a range of controversial issues that affect women.
</P>
<P>
   Their activities include representing the family of a girl who
died after having been raped by her high school principal, as well
as a woman who sued an employer after it had fined her heavily for
having a first child without permission.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our cases you can see the problems of Chinese women
today,'' the executive director of the center, Guo Jianmei, said in
a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   The two-year-old center, affiliated with the Beijing University
law school, is in many ways an anomaly: an aggressive legal aid
center in a country whose emerging justice system remains riddled
with flaws. An organization run by outspoken women in a country
where discrimination against women is rampant. A nongovernmental
organization in a country where the government ultimately calls the
shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're doing some really difficult work against tremendous
odds, since the legal system is still quite weak and they're
representing people who have neither power nor money,'' said
Phyllis Chang, a legal expert with the Ford Foundation in Beijing,
which helps finance the center. ``Given that, I think they've been
surprisingly effective.''
</P>
<P>
   The center's very existence is evidence of the progress achieved
by China's decade-old effort to reform its legal system.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese government is showing increasing interest in legal
aid work and legal aid centers for the poor have sprung up all over
China in the last two years, generally under the Ministry of
Justice. There are currently 180 mostly tiny centers, with about
half of them set up in the last six months.
</P>
<P>
   American assistance for the Chinese legal aid system is among
the initiatives announced during Clinton's state visit. So it was
not surprising that the first lady, Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright and the president's special adviser on the White House's
rule of law initiative, Paul Gewirtz, came here to learn what such
centers can and cannot accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   Guo, the center director, says its goal is to use the law to
improve the lot of women in China. But it also seeks to promote the
development of China's emerging legal system, publicizing and
trying to resolve its many remaining flaws and contradictions.
</P>
<P>
   Although Chinese legislators have drafted a number of new laws
over the last decade aimed at protecting personal rights, many are
vague or are ignored by often poorly trained judges. The courts,
which are paid by the local government, tend to favor authority.
And court judgments are hard to enforce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our 1992 law of the protection of women's rights is quite
comprehensive, but it is not always carried out,'' Guo said. A
sampling of the center's current cases illustrate her point:
</P>
<P>
   _ The center assisted the prosecution of a high school principal
in Chengde who raped a 16-year-old girl, who later died in
childbirth. The principal was found guilty of a lesser charge of
``hooliganism'' and put on probation. The center said the judge
never received all the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   _ The center brought a class action suit against a Beijing
factory on behalf of its workers, rural migrants whom the factory
had not paid in months.
</P>
<P>
   _ The center has been representing women engineers whose
employer forced them to retire earlier than their male colleagues,
even though a national regulation prohibits such discrimination.
Although a judge has found in the women's favor, the company has
refused to give them their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, the center has taken up the case of Sun Lili, a
former banquet-organizer at a state-owned hotel, who sued her
employer over the huge fine it had imposed when Sun and her husband
had their first child, without the company's approval.
</P>
<P>
   Urban employers are charged with enforcing the national family
planning policies and determine when their employees can give
birth, but Sun and the legal center held that the penalties the
hotel imposed on her for having a child without permission far
exceeded the guidelines in the family planning regulations.
</P>
<P>
   In a country where most citizens still go to great lengths to
avoid controversy, Guo, a lively, articulate lawyer, does not mind
jumping into the fray.
</P>
<P>
   She said that the center's staff of young lawyers, law students
and volunteers have won more than half of the cases they have taken
on. Sometimes they win in the courts, but often they appeal to the
press or senior government officials if they feel the courts have
not provided justice for their clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not only trying to help women,'' said Chang, of the
Ford Foundation, ``but also to move China to a rule of law.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-98 1937EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
