<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-28 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0851 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-ENVIRONMENT-COX     06-28 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-ENVIRONMENT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Republicans try to `green up' their image on environmental
issues
 &HT;    (EDS: May run with SIERRACLUB-COX.)
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With a ``green'' name, logo and money, Republicans
are trying to recast themselves as protectors of the environment in
this congressional election year.
</P>
<P>
   The Coalition of Republican Environmental Advocates, or CREA,
which has the support of Speaker Newt Gingrich (R-Ga.), stands for
the idea that local and free-market solutions often are better than
Washington rules.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Colorado Attorney Gale A. Norton, a protege of former
Interior Secretary James Watt, and Gingrich ally Grover Norquist,
CREA intends to run issue ads, funded by unlimited contributions
from undisclosed sources, in key congressional districts in which
GOP candidates are being attacked as foes of the environment.
</P>
<P>
   The group also is casting an eye on 2000, when Vice President Al
Gore may be the Democratic nominee for president and Gingrich may
be vying to be his opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans won't surrender to Al Gore on the environment,''
said Norton, who worked unsuccessfully to open the Arctic National
Wildlife Refuge to drilling in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent Washington dinner that raised $100,000 for CREA,
Gingrich blasted Gore for ``pandering'' to environmentalists on the
crisis du jour.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what this is really about on the left. It's the newest
excuse to build a bigger government to run your life,'' Gingrich
said.
</P>
<P>
   But before CREA takes on Democrats, it has to contend with
Republican detractors who fear that the group's logo featuring
mountains, a stream, the sun and a healthy infusion of cash will
confuse voters and dilute the potency of environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Marks is a Republican Lake County, Ill., commissioner who
also heads REP America, another GOP environmental group. But her
organization believes that under Gingrich's lead, Republicans ``are
on the wrong side of the issue and are looking bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Calling CREA a ``green scam,'' Marks said, ``They are a Who's
Who of anti-environment Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Kansas Gov. Mike Hayden, also a Republican, is chairman
of the League of Conservation Voters, which grades members of
Congress annually by noting their votes on environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The voting record of some (CREA) members would indicate that
these people would not show much concern for the environment,''
Hayden said.
</P>
<P>
   CREA's list of congressional supporters includes Republican
Reps. Don Young of Alaska and Helen Chenoweth of Idaho, both known
for their often caustic views of environmentalists and
environmental causes.
</P>
<P>
   Chenoweth once held a salmon bake to mock environmentalists'
concerns about fish, and Young has called environmentalists his
``enemies'' and ``not Americans.'' Chenoweth and Young each got 6
percent on League of Conservation Voters' scorecard for 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The group's Georgia representatives, Rep. Saxby Chambliss and
Sen. Paul Coverdell, received grades of 13 percent and 0,
respectively, in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans, perhaps predictably, don't like the League's
scorecard or the votes it uses to grade them.
</P>
<P>
   CREA came into being, in part, to counter the League and the
Sierra Club, another long-standing environmental organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a need to change the public misperception that
Republicans don't care about the environment,'' said Italia
Federici, CREA's president.
</P>
<P>
   By handing out ``Teddy Roosevelt'' awards and touting personal
responsibility over heavy-handed government regulation, CREA hopes
to ``green up'' the GOP image without significantly changing the
party's issues on the environment.
</P>
<P>
   The effort is not enough for Rep. Sherwood Boehlert, a New York
Republican with a strong environmental record.
</P>
<P>
   His name is nowhere to be found on CREA's membership rolls. ``Oh
gosh, no,'' Boehlert said. ``I belong to a respectable
environmental organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
