NYT-06-28-98 1940EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980628.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-28 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0852 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIERRACLUB-COX     06-28 1512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRACLUB-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sierra Club's political muscle flexed in close congressional
races
 &HT;    (EDS: May run with GOP-ENVIRONMENT-COX.)
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ New political advertisements set to the tune of
``America the Beautiful'' begin playing today in five states around
the country, courtesy of the Sierra Club, the nation's oldest
environmental group.
</P>
<P>
   But the ads will not likely conjure images of amber waves of
grain or purple mountains majesty for Sen. Gordon Smith (R-Ore.).
Smith blames the Sierra Club for sinking his first Senate campaign
in Oregon's 1996 special election after the club launched a
blistering advertising assault on his environmental record.
</P>
<P>
   ``They busted my chops pretty good,'' says Smith, who
subsequently was elected to Oregon's other Senate seat later in
1996. ``It's an organization with a warm and fuzzy name that
engages in real brass knuckle tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   Now in its 106th year, the Sierra Club has become one of the
most aggressive players in the crowded field of political issue
advocacy.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing on its IRS tax exemption and 500,000-strong membership,
the club collects and spends millions each election cycle to elect
pro-environment candidates and oust those whose voting record on
the environment is poor.
</P>
<P>
   Club activists distribute voter guides ranking candidates on the
environment, a pioneering technique later adopted by the Christian
Coalition. Members trained in the tactic of ``bird dogging'' appear
at rallies and heckle candidates over their environmental records.
In the last election, the club's political action committee (PAC)
distributed $372,000 to federal candidates, 94 percent of whom were
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   And in an era when voters say they are increasingly turned off
by negative campaigning, the Sierra Club remains convinced that
negative advertising works. A radio ad running today in Seattle
will tell voters there that Rep. Linda Smith (R-Wash.), a candidate
for U.S. Senate, and Rep. Rick White (R-Wash.) voted to make it
``harder to clean up air pollution in Mount Rainier National
Park.''
</P>
<P>
   The club's political activism in 1996 so angered congressional
Republicans that the Senate committee investigating campaign
finance abuses subpoenaed the club for information about potential
abuse of its IRS tax exemption, a line of inquiry that ultimately
went nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Sierra club is targeting some $6 million at
congressional races in Washington, Nevada, New Mexico, Wisconsin,
New York and Illinois, mostly on behalf of Democrats. North
Carolina, featuring a close Senate race between Sen. Lauch
Faircloth (R-N.C.) and attorney John Edwards, could join the list,
says Sierra Club President Chuck McGrady, who acknowledges the
club's testy relationship with the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans are critical of the Sierra Club because we've been
sharply critical of a large number of Republicans,'' McGrady says.
``It's not a partisan matter though. It's a matter of what the
voting record is of these members. So if they are Republicans or
Democrats, if they've got a voting record which evidences their
desire to gut our environmental laws we're going to be critical and
they are probably not going to be happy with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Sierra Club is trying to reach out more to the GOP.
McGrady, a registered Republican who was elected Sierra Club
president in May, says he doesn't want pro-environment Republicans
to view the club as a ``first cousin of the Democratic Party.''
</P>
<P>
   In each of the three rounds of issue advertising that the club
has launched this year, one or two ads have praised Republicans for
their environmental voting records. A 30-second television spot
that aired in Maryland recently, for example, lauded Rep. Connie
Morella (R-Md.) for supporting clean air legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to be fair. We're trying to give Republicans
credit for good things and be critical of Republicans when they are
not doing good things,'' says McGrady, former president of
Georgia's Sierra Club chapter.
</P>
<P>
   Former Kansas governor Mike Hayden, a Republican who chairs the
League of Conservation Voters, says the Sierra Club must use the
symbolism of its new, Republican president to portray a more
bi-partisan face and avoid the perception that it supports only
candidates ``on the far left.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important that they stay balanced,'' says Hayden.
</P>
<P>
   Political activism and paid, issue advocacy are deeply entwined
at the Sierra Club. Founded in 1892 by environmentalist and thinker
John Muir, who explored the richness of California's Sierra
Mountains, the Sierra Club started as a kind of explorers
fraternity composed of scientists who set about mapping the area
that was to become Yosemite National Park.
</P>
<P>
   As a California-based conservation group, the Sierra Club fought
efforts to dam major western rivers. In 1963 the Johnson
administration proposed damming the Colorado River above and below
the Grand Canyon, and the Sierra Club went on the attack.
</P>
<P>
   In 1966, it ran four newspaper advertisements, two in the New
York Times, opposing the dams. The day after the ads appeared, the
IRS notified the club that it could no longer guarantee its
tax-exempt 501(c)(3) designation, which allowed members to deduct
their contributions.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club officially lost its tax exempt status as a
charity in 1969 and became primarily a 501(c)(4), which doesn't
permit members to deduct contributions but exempts the club's
endowment from taxes. The 501(c)(4) designation also allowed the
club free rein to lobby and wage issue advertising campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1960s, the Sierra Club has sharpened and refined its
issue advocacy. Many special interest groups run generic
advertising that avoids mention of specific candidates. Unlike
those groups, however, the Sierra Club targets most of its issue
advertising to specific congressional districts that feature close
races.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the late '70s and early '80s it became clear that it was
all well and good for us to be out there lobbying legislators to do
good things, but the fact was every two years we needed to be out
there supporting our friends and frankly get some changes in some
of the congressional delegations,'' says McGrady.
</P>
<P>
   Money raised and spent on the ads is so-called soft money,
unregulated by federal campaign finance laws and exempt from public
disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   The ads don't tell voters to vote for or against a particular
candidate, but leave little doubt which one the club prefers.
Earlier this year, the Senate attempted to regulate such
advertising on the grounds that it allowed special interest groups
an unfair advantage. The measure was killed as part of broad
campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're complying with the law with the way it is,'' says
McGrady. ``I suspect that the club is strongly supportive of
changes in our campaign finance laws. And if those laws change,
we'd be among the first to try to run different sorts of campaigns
than the ones we are running.''
</P>
<P>
   Convinced that this year voters aren't as concerned about
national issues, the Sierra Club has tailored its issue advertising
to local environmental concerns in about 18 congressional districts
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Subhed here in bold
</P>
<P>
   A radio ad that played recently in New York blasted Sen. Alfonse
D'Amato (R-N.Y.) for trying to weaken clean air and water laws at
the expense of the Hudson River. An ad targeted against Sen. Ben
Nighthorse Campbell (R-Colo.) cited Denver's worsening smog and air
pollution problems. An ad running in Illinois praised Rep. Lane
Evens (D-Ill.) for protecting agricultural runoff laws that
particularly impact large hog farms common in his district.
</P>
<P>
   The club's new round of advertising take 7 members to task for
recently voting against a Democratic amendment that would have
required separate votes on environmental riders, legislative
provisions affecting the environment attached to larger bills.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Club political director Dan Weiss says House Republicans
have sought to use riders to avoid votes affecting the environment.
A vote against the amendment was a vote against environmental
protections, Weiss says, so it was fair game.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, Weiss and media consultant Kim Haddow met in a
Washington studio to cut the new spots. Henry Strozier, an actor
and Atlanta native, was hired to read the ad scripts.
</P>
<P>
   Strozier hit a snag when he got to the spot featuring Reps.
Smith and White in Washington. No one in the studio knew if Mount
Rainier was pronounced Rainier like ``rain'' or Rainier like
``deer.'' The wrong pronunciation would alert listeners that the ad
was the work of an outside special interest -- a fatal mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Deciding to figure it out later, Strozier read the script both
ways, allowing his deep, gravely voice to flow over the lines like
a Washington trout stream.
</P>
<P>
   ``A thing of beauty,'' said Haddow. ``I think that was a home
run.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
