u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-CHURCH-1STLD-WR     06-28 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CHURCH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON VISIT AND SPEECH DELIGHT WORSHIPERS AT BEIJING CHURCH 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Eds.: new 7th graph, adding the Clintons' church membership.) (See also: CHINA-SUMMIT, CHINA-LAMA, CHINA-HILLARY, CHINA-TAIWAN,
CHINA-U.S.) 
(fb) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ President Clinton's visit and short speech to a
crowded Protestant church in Beijing on Sunday morning may not have
converted many Chinese across this nation of 1.2 billion _ his
attendance at the services was not even mentioned on the national
television news Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   But it was certainly appreciated by more than 2,000 members of
the Chongwenmen Church, who lined up as early as 6 a.m. to get
seats for the 9:30 service. Many of them emerged from the ceremony
_ complete with Bible readings, hymns, a sermon by one of the
Chinese pastors on ``unity'' and, on Sunday, brief comments by a
visiting American president _ with the hope that Clinton's visit
would somehow advance the cause of Christianity in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``His coming here today is very encouraging to us,'' said Hu
Guorong, a 33-year-old businessman, who said he became a Christian
two years ago ``by the work of the Holy Spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Wang Wenxiang, a middle-aged man who has attended this church
for the last eight years, said: ``We expect that this visit will
help spread Christianity in China.''
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton and his wife are like brothers and sisters
to us,'' his wife added.
</P>
<P>
   Before they headed home through the narrow alleys surrounding
the steeple-less gray-brick church, a group of excited, curious
worshipers cornered an American reporter, ignoring the scores of
plainclothes policemen who milled, watching and listening, through
the departing crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does President Clinton go to church every Sunday?'' they
wanted to know. ``Are all the members of his family Christians?''
``Is he a Baptist or a Methodist?'' (The president is a Baptist,
the first lady, Hillary Rodham Clinton, a Methodist.)
</P>
<P>
   This church, like virtually all government-approved Protestant
churches, is nondenominational, part of a hybrid ``patriotic''
church founded after the Communists, who are officially atheist,
took control of China in 1949. Like the Chinese Patriotic Catholic
Association, which does not recognize the leadership of the pope,
it is supposed to be independent of foreign organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very moved by the fact that President Clinton is a
Christian,'' said Zhang Shuhuan, a middle-aged woman. ``As far as
we know, many heads of state are not Christian.''
</P>
<P>
   As the comments of many worshipers suggested, Christianity in
China today is at once thriving and constrained, and even many who
attend the approved churches may sometimes feel a bit beleaguered.
</P>
<P>
   Since the extreme persecution of religion during the Cultural
Revolution of 1966 to 1976, the Communist government has permitted
the rapid growth of the official Protestant and Roman Catholic
churches. Under the rules, personal worship is free but public
evangelizing, outside church walls, is banned.
</P>
<P>
   Still, outside experts believe the number of Protestants in
China may now surpass 20 million and the number of Catholics total
10 million, including those in legal and illegal churches.
</P>
<P>
   The Chongwenmen Church in east-central Beijing is the largest of
eight officially sanctioned Protestant churches in Beijing, which
together serve tens of thousands of members.
</P>
<P>
   But there are also numerous small, illegal ``house churches'' in
this city, as around the country, where Christians who reject
government controls, often Evangelical Protestants, gather. These
groups, along with Catholics who insist that the pope is their
leader, often face police harassment, fines, or arrests.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is said to have pressed the case for more religious
freedom with President Jiang Zemin, but in his comments at the
church on Sunday he was circumspect. He expressed pleasure at the
reported growth in numbers of Christians here and said: ``I believe
our faith calls upon us to seek unity with people across the world
of different races and backgrounds and creeds.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Chongwenmen Church this Sunday, like every Sunday, only
800 people, fewer than half those attending, could sit in the main
hall. Hundreds crowded into a side chapel, and another thousand sat
in the basement, watching the services on closed-circuit
television.
</P>
<P>
   While the number of churches around the country is steadily
growing, it has not kept pace with the rise in believers, and
overcrowding is common. The government closely controls the
construction of new facilities, arguing that there are not enough
trained pastors to staff them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope President Clinton will urge our leaders to build more
Christian churches in Beijing,'' said He Jiazhen, a 70-year-old
woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 70, about the same age as President Jiang Zemin,'' she
continued. ``I pray all the time, hoping that Jiang Zemin will be
converted,'' she said. ``If everyone in China were Christian, then
China would live in peace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
