<HEADER>
A0857 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKIN-THEATER-REVIEW-A     06-28 1428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKIN-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SKIN OF OUR TEETH': 5,000 YEARS OF SUBURBAN FAMILY'S FORTITUDE
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes at end of review. The use of `Ms.' is
correct, an effect intended by the producers.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(fb) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They seemed, at that moment, to be Everycouple, an
embodiment of the aspirations of the audience watching them. They
had endured much, and now, trying to make their way to another
place, they found themselves wandering Ishmael-like, up stairs and
down, as a forbidding green light stung their eyes. It was funny
but touching, too, and even a little suspenseful. Although you knew
what the outcome would be, you still asked yourself if this
venturesome man and woman would finally prevail.
</P>
<P>
   This vignette occurred last Thursday during a preview
performance of Thornton Wilder's ``Skin of Our Teeth'' at the
Delacorte Theater in Central Park, and it captured the spirit of
the 1942 play, a wry paean to the tenacity of the human spirit.
</P>
<P>
   It happened, however, not on the stage but just in front of it,
when an elderly pair of theatergoers decided to make an early
departure between scenes and found their search for an exit turned
into a public performance.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, this all felt perfectly appropriate to a comedy that
deliberately blurs the boundaries between actors and spectators.
But it is not a good sign when an unscripted moment becomes the
high point in the production of an elaborately constructed play.
The New York Shakespeare Festival's revival of ``The Skin of Our
Teeth,'' which officially opened Sunday night, does stir your
sympathies on occasion, especially when the actors have to wear
heavy coats and sweaters and pretend it is the Ice Age instead of
sweltering summertime in a big-city park.
</P>
<P>
   But as staged by Irene Lewis, the artistic director of Center
Stage in Baltimore, the production often seems to be scratching its
head, wondering, like that couple, where to go and how to get
there. It has some definite assets, including a snazzy set by John
Conklin and a game, industrious cast led by John Goodman, a fine
actor best known as a star of the sitcom ``Roseanne.'' What it
lacks, all too clearly, is any governing point of view.
</P>
<P>
   Wilder once described himself as a blend of poet and
schoolteacher, and both elements are much in evidence in ``Skin.''
This allegorical fable, which takes one archetypal American family,
the Antrobuses, through the millenniums, does indeed suggest the
work of a passionate professor with a touch of the ham. Based in a
generic suburban home in Excelsior, N.J., the Antrobuses make it
through the Ice Age, a flood (the one that put the animals on the
ark) and an annihilating war.
</P>
<P>
   They get knocked down, but they get up again. Along the way,
Antrobus ( Goodman), whose first name is (yes) Adam, invents the
wheel, the lever and the alphabet; his wife, Eva Antrobus (Frances
Conroy), keeps the fires burning at home with their two children: a
destructive little boy called Henry (John Ortiz), whose original
name was Cain, and a daughter with the refreshingly nonsymbolic
name of Gladys (Brienin Bryant). They also have a maid, Sabina
(Kristen Johnston), who is the Lilith-like temptress to Mrs.
Antrobus' stalwart mother and who slides out of character to
address the audience.
</P>
<P>
   When ``Skin'' first opened in November of 1942, Broadway had
never seen anything like it, at least not from an American
playwright. It wasn't just the anachronistic stew of time periods
that startled, and the mixture of philosophical earnestness with
broad comedy, but also its insistence on tearing down the wall
between audience and performance. This was something Wilder had
experimented with in his earlier ``Our Town'' but took to far
greater lengths here. For a country newly thrust into world war,
the identification with the immortal strugglers onstage assumed a
special poignancy.
</P>
<P>
   In the succeeding years, the play, which won a Pulitzer Prize,
has turned out to be much less resilient than its characters. What
once seemed clever now feels exceedingly precious, and without the
jolt of novelty, most of the work's history-lesson jokes can be
anticipated long before they reach their punch lines. The
adaptability of humankind may be an eternal theme; the idea,
however, of an eternal triangle in which Man the Inventor needs
both the Nurturing Woman and the Inspirational Sex Goddess is a
little harder to put over these days.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis has brought no revitalizing perspective to this material;
often, she seems to have brought no perspective to it at all. When
you arrive at the Delacorte, you're greeted with the hopeful sight
of Conklin's bright cartoon setting, which crosses the domestic
uniformity of Levittown with a sense of cosmic geometry, suggested
by grid-lined trapezoid platforms decorated with spheres,
rectangles and triangles. Yet there's nothing in the performance of
the play to match the sharp sensibility of the set.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the production itself feels bafflingly shapeless and
doesn't even take advantage of the obvious, emotion-tugging rhythms
at which Wilder was so adept. The program identifies the time of
the play as ``the present and the 1940s,'' and there's a pair of
scene-setting, jitterbugging dancers (Michael H. Fielder and Maria
Torres) to establish a period mood. But there has been no attempt,
aside from a few updated theatrical in-jokes in Johnston's speeches
and a bizarre use of sign language in the third act, to create a
dialogue between the two eras. What's worse, there is very little
sense of connection among the individual actors, a feeling
compounded by the erratic amplification of their voices.
</P>
<P>
   The sassy Sabina, who keeps interrupting the play to comment on
its faults, has always been the key to ``Skin.'' The role was first
portrayed (and to some degree shaped) by Tallulah Bankhead, who is
still perceived as owning the part, though Vivien Leigh, Mary
Martin and Elizabeth Ashley all received glowing notices for it.
Johnston, the charming actress from ``Third Rock From the Sun'' on
television, is simply miscast. Despite her curvaceous form and
raspy voice, she registers less as a crafty but hapless vamp than
an overgrown, ever-ingenuous cheerleader.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman does some appealing comic embroidery on the business of
shifting in and out of character, but mostly he is a surprisingly
tentative presence here, as though he were trying on different
personae to see which the audience might like best. Most of the
supporting cast members seem to be treading water, though Lola
Pashalinski stands out as the understandably exasperated stage
manager of the play within the play.
</P>
<P>
   Among the leading actors, only Conroy gives an authoritative and
consistently focused performance, and she brings Mrs. Antrobus into
the 1990's by slyly suggesting acrid undercurrents of frustration
in her homebody character. She also finds an astonishing number of
very funny levels in the speech she delivers at a Darwinian
convention of the species in Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, maybe it's a Darwinian effect that Lewis is aiming
for, the idea of throwing a group of actors onto a big stage in an
urban jungle and seeing how they fend for themselves. As a
consequence, this planet comes across as a lonelier and more
isolating place than even Wilder might have imagined.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE SKIN OF OUR TEETH'
</P>
<P>
   By Thornton Wilder; directed by Irene Lewis; sets by John
Conklin; costumes by Candice Donnelly; lighting by Mimi Jordan
Sherin; sound by Dan Moses Schreier; choreography by Willie
Rosario; fight director, J. Allen Suddeth; production dramaturge,
John Dias; production stage manager, James Latus. Senior director,
external affairs, Margaret M. Lioi; associate producer, Wiley
Hausam; artistic associate, Brian Kulick; associate producer,
Bonnie Metzgar; general manager, Michael Hurst. Presented by the
Joseph Papp Public Theater/New York Shakespeare Festival, George C.
Wolfe, producer, Rosemarie Tichler, artistic producer; Mark Litvin,
managing director. At the Delacorte Theater, Central Park West,
enter at 81st Street, Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   With: John Goodman (Mr. Antrobus), Kristen Johnston (Sabina),
Frances Conroy (Mrs. Antrobus), John Ortiz (Henry), Brienin Bryant
(Gladys), Novella Nelson (Fortune Teller), Lola Pashalinski (Ms.
Fitzpatrick) and J.R. Horne (Announcer).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
