<SLUG> BC-TEN--ROBERTSON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Anyone for tennis in a Wimbledome?
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Dale Robertson
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ After decades of practice, the BBC
producers have the drill down pat.
</P>
<P>
   First they show the angry, roiling clouds.
</P>
<P>
   Then they cut to one of the players on the court, anxiously
glancing skyward.
</P>
<P>
   The next shot is of stone-faced Alan Mills, Wimbledon's referee,
balefully staring down the heavens.
</P>
<P>
   Once sprinkles are visible on the TV screen, the camera returns
to Mills, who is speaking somberly into his walkie-talkie.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes a close-up of the players gathering their rackets,
followed by a wide-angle view of the grounds crew scurrying forth
to pull the tarp over the court.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, and the one before that, those blokes got more air
time than Pete Sampras. The conditions this summer haven't been
quite as miserable, but that isn't to say it has been balmy and
pleasant, either.
</P>
<P>
   If there's a more maddening experience in all of sports than
watching one tennis match drag on for three days, starting and
stopping and starting and stopping because of the whims of what has
to be the world's most capricious and confoundedly erratic climate,
I'm not aware of it.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, the defending Wimbledon champion who has developed the
patience of Job here, was supposed to play Thomas Enqvist in
Friday's feature match. They finally got on court late Saturday,
and after three rain stoppages, the match was suspended at 5-all in
the second set after Sampras had taken the first in about four
minutes, slapping six aces in a row past the hapless Enqvist at the
outset.
</P>
<P>
   Poor precedent for Pete
</P>
<P>
   Well, so much for Pete's momentum. He had sagged appreciably
once they returned for the second set. Now they're supposed to
resume play at noon today, almost 72 hours after their originally
scheduled starting time. And more rain, as always, is forecast.
</P>
<P>
   The only match Sampras has dropped at Wimbledon since 1992, his
loss to eventual champion Richard Krajicek in 1996, dragged on over
48 hours. That quarterfinal was memorable for reasons other than
the rare Sampras defeat. When the cover was being pulled on, a
groundsman tripped and became trapped beneath it. His rescue
required removing the just-laid tarp, which, of course, caused the
court to be soaked, necessitating the carry-over into the following
day.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Swimbledon, a tournament only a duck, or an umbrella
salesman, could truly love. Rain Britannia! Forget anything Kipling
wrote. The real mantra, if not motto, of Wimbledon is, ``Ladies and
gentlemen, play has been suspended.''
</P>
<P>
   When I passed through English customs, the agent asked me what
my business in her country was. After I said I was a journalist
covering Wimbledon, she smiled a knowing smile and replied in kind:
``Oh, indeed. Cover's on; cover's off. Now they're playing; now
they aren't. Bloody fun, Wimbledon.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the record shows that since 1914, only a dozen days
have been total washouts at Wimbledon, and the only time it has
happened back-to-back in the 20th century was in 1997, requiring
the All England Club to open the gates to the unwashed masses on
the middle Sunday for just the second time ever.
</P>
<P>
   Despite innumerable delays to date, the current tournament is
lurching along at a normal _ for Wimbledon, anyway _ pace, and it
wasn't deemed necessary to let the serfs visit for another
``People's Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Wet grass doesn't cut it
</P>
<P>
   The problem with grass, tennis' most anachronistic surface, is
rain is its ultimate bane. The slightest bit of drizzle makes the
court slippery and, hence, unsafe for the players. That's why Mills
wastes nary a moment in calling for his covers. A temporary staff
of 140 stands ready for the order.
</P>
<P>
   At Roland Garros, on the other hand, the terre battue handles
the moisture well. Some dampness actually improves how the clay
plays. They will play through mists in Paris that routinely shut
down Wimbledon for an hour or more.
</P>
<P>
   Logically then, if there's one stadium on the face of the earth
that should have a dome, or at least a retractable roof, it's not
the new ones in Houston, Phoenix or Seattle, or the old one in
Toronto. It's Wimbledon's Centre Court.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Wimbledome.
</P>
<P>
   But this country is just a tad tradition-bound, so it will never
happen. We won't see that roof in our lifetime, nor will our
children in theirs. The tennis will continue to sputter along,
making everyone just a little bit crazy.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the Centre Court streaker of two years ago? I'm certain
it was the precipitation that made that poor young lady go starkers
in more ways than one.
</P>
<P>
   As the All England Club's official statement in response to the
incident said: ``Whilst we do not wish to condone the practice, it
did at least provide some light amusement for our loyal and patient
supporters, who have had a trying time during the recent bad
weather.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
