<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-MAIN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glavine gets 11th win in Braves' 10-3 win over Toronto
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A team that hasn't laughed for two weeks let out a
giggle Sunday. They dropped a quick seven-spot on the Toronto Blue
Jays, closed out a short 2-3 homestand with a 10-3 runaway and then
the Atlanta Braves set themselves for tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ''What happened with the Yankees is in the past,'' said catcher
Javy Lopez, his club still smarting from the three losses to New
York last week. ''Now we just have to keep playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as Greg Maddux bore the flag Saturday night with a shutout,
Tom Glavine (11-3) walked the point in this one, allowing five hits
in seven innings while driving in three of the first seven runs
himself. Rookie first baseman Randall Simon, freshly arrived from
Richmond, delivered three more RBI while the club mounted a 14-hit
attack, its biggest outburst since the Baltimore series three weeks
ago. The victory gave the Braves two straight after the team had
dropped seven of nine. They had not won consecutive games over a
stretch of the last 10.
</P>
<P>
   ''We needed a couple, that's for sure,'' said manager Bobby Cox.
The club has today off before opening a three-game set in Tampa Bay
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you want to take momentum for a team,'' said right fielder
Michael Tucker, ''you have to take it from them early.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan precisely. The Braves sent 11 men to the plate in the
first inning and punished Jays starter Chris Carpenter (4-3) for
five runs on six hits, three of them two-out singles coming in a
row. Then in the third, Glavine sent an oppossite-field double
twisting into the left field corner, the team's only extra-bases
hit of the day scoring two men for a 7-0 lead and relieving all
anxiety from the 44,185 who sweated through the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a pick-me-up,'' said Cox, ''tyring to get back on the
right track.''
</P>
<P>
   From there, Glavine glided to his seventh win in 10 starts. He
yielded a solo home run to Shawn Green in the sixth but dropped his
ERA to 2.71 while joining Maddux as the league's lone 11-game
winners. In the 35 games Maddux and Glavine have started thus far,
the Braves have won 24 times (.686).
</P>
<P>
   ''You're not trying to just let them hit it but you try not to
walk anybody,'' Glavine said of working a run-away. ''My mindset in
a game like today is a whole lot different than it is normally. I'm
not really trying to work the ball on the corners, I'm not changing
speeds a whole lot. I'm just trying to throw fastball on the
inner-half or the outer-half. That's not the way I normally pitch.
But you have to guard against getting complacent.''
</P>
<P>
   Not much time for that. After the Devil Rays comes the
three-game series with the second-place New York Mets, when the
Braves learn who gets to laugh during the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
