<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-SIDEBAR29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Simon says he aims to stay in Atlanta
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Randall Simon arrived at Turner Field on Sunday,
perhaps half a season later than he and most Braves officials
anticipated. For Simon, however, now could be the best opportunity
for an extended stay in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Simon, a 23-year-old first baseman from Curacao, went 2-for-4
with two runs and three RBIs in Atlanta's 10-3 win over Toronto on
Sunday, his first appearance in the majors this season.
</P>
<P>
   While it certainly was a good initial impression, Simon is
probably having a tough time forgetting about his record-breaking
performance with Class AAA Richmond on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   In that game, a 15-5 win at Charlotte, Simon went 4-for-5 with a
double, three homers and 10 RBIs. He became just the second
Richmond Brave to hit three home runs in a game, joining Miguel
Sosa, who did it in 1985. Simon also broke the club's RBI record,
formerly seven.
</P>
<P>
   ``In two days, he's had two home runs, about eight hits and 13
RBIs,'' Atlanta manager Bobby Cox said. ``That's not too bad. It
was a boost to have a new face like (Simon) out there today. He's
somebody that everyone likes and he plays with a lot of energy. I
really like him.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon is one of the organization's top prospects, hitting for
both average and power on all levels of the minor-league system.
After hitting .429 in 13 games with Atlanta in a September call-up
last year, Simon was expected to make the team as a backup to first
baseman Andres Galarraga.
</P>
<P>
   That was before outfielder Curtis Pride outplayed Simon in
spring training. After hitting only .254 with two homers and three
RBIs in Grapefruit League play, Simon was headed back to the
minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just looking at the overall picture,'' Cox said.
``Curtis could steal a base and play in the outfield. We had
Galarraga at first base, who plays everyday. We had (left fielder)
Ryan Klesko, who could fill in at first. Curtis was more of a fit,
that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   In 75 games at Richmond this season, Simon hit .254 with 10
homers and 46 RBIs in 287 at-bats. He was promoted to Atlanta after
Pride was placed on the 15-day disabled list Saturday night. Pride
received 10 stitches in his right index finger, which he split open
slamming a bat against a concrete wall inside a tunnel behind the
dugout in a 2-0 victory over Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   With Galarraga out since Tuesday with an ailing back, and the
Braves' pinch-hitters batting only .207 this month, Simon might be
in Atlanta to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Richmond manager Jeff Cox) pulled me aside last night and
told me I was getting called up,'' Simon said. ``He told me to go
and never come back. I'm just going to play hard and do everything
I can to spend the rest of the season here.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
