<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CRITICS SAY HE DIDN`T GO FAR ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CHINA-SUMMIT, CHINA-CHURCH, CHINA-LAMA, CHINA-HILLARY,
CHINA-TAIWAN) 
(ko) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Clinton administration officials praised the
president for his performance in Beijing, where he spoke out on
human rights in a televised news conference with the Chinese
leader, Clinton's critics said Sunday that he had done only the
minimum required and that his words were largely empty.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and the national security
adviser, Sandy Berger, speaking to reporters in Beijing and to
American television audiences at home, called Clinton's exchanges
with President Jiang Zemin of China ``remarkable,''
``extraordinary'' and ``unprecedented.''
</P>
<P>
   Those judgments were echoed, though with less enthusiasm, by
some Democratic legislators and China scholars. They regard the
real importance of the Beijing meeting as twofold, an opportunity
to normalize high-level visits between the two countries after a
sometimes dangerous break following the 1989 Tiananmen Square
crackdown, as well as a way to enable American and Chinese leaders
to speak more bluntly to a larger Chinese audience about their
differences over political and religious values while they
cooperate on regional security issues.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's critics, most of them Republicans, continued to attack
his China policies as wrongheaded and his performance as
perfunctory.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Fred Thompson, R.-Tenn., said he was glad to see Clinton
speaking out at his news conference on human rights and on the
killings in 1989 of Tiananmen Square protesters. ``He needed to do
that,'' Thompson said on ``Fox News Sunday.'' ``But it frankly was
the least he could do under the circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Christopher Cox, R.-Calif., spoke in similar terms on
``Face the Nation'' on CBS-TV, saying, ``There's no question we
were all pleased by the news conference, and that was, frankly,
necessary to make up for what otherwise would have been a very,
very bad, worldwide television image'' of Clinton's welcome in
Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   ``But notwithstanding rhetorical progress,'' said Cox, who is
leading an investigation into the reported transfer of American
missile-guidance technology to China, ``not much substantively has
changed.''
</P>
<P>
   A Democratic Party critic of the president's China policy, Rep.
Nancy Pelosi of California, said, ``On human rights President
Clinton has said just enough for U.S. domestic consumption and not
enough to produce results for the Chinese people.''
</P>
<P>
   She called the meeting a victory for Jiang, who made few if any
concessions on trade, proliferation or human rights but ``has
accrued all the benefits of standing side by side with the
president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   For the president of the conservative Family Research Council,
Gary Bauer, the meeting's lasting symbol will be Clinton's
honor-guard welcome at Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will be a haunting image as things unfold in China,''
Bauer said. ``The very cautious handling of human rights in the
wake of the roundup of dissidents makes it look like another kowtow
summit. Even this is modest for an American president, who has an
obligation to put American values front and center.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bette Bao Lord, the Shanghai-born writer who is chairwoman
of Freedom House, a human rights group, said both Clinton and Jiang
``did what they had to do'' for their dual audiences, those
watching in China and in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a piece of choreographed theater for domestic
consumption on both sides, to dampen the decibels of criticism,''
said Mrs. Lord, who is on the broadcasting board of governors for
the Voice of America and Radio Free Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton ``said all the right things and touched all the
right bases,'' Mrs. Lord said, ``I would have liked him to do more
of what he does so well, which is to put his heart in it.''
</P>
<P>
   There was an element of role reversal, she said, with ``Jiang's
trying to sound like a good old American pol, and Clinton's trying
to look reserved and controlled, the way a foreign devil thinks the
Chinese want to see a foreign statesman.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Washington director of Human Rights Watch, Mike
Jendrzejczyk, the Clinton-Jiang exchange on human rights was
extraordinary. Jendrzejczyk gave ``credit to Clinton for laying out
a specific agenda'' like talking to the Dalai Lama and reviewing
the cases of those sentenced for counterrevolutionary activities.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was particularly good at rebutting Jiang and arguing
that real stability in the 21st century would ``require high levels
of freedom,'' Jendrzejczyk said.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's words, he added, ``must be matched by results that
go beyond a dialogue or training some judges or lawyers or even a
few individual releases of dissidents.''
</P>
<P>
   The director of the Sigur Center for Asian Studies at George
Washington University, David Shambaugh, said the visit was an
important marker. In the Cold War a strategic partnership with
China was aimed at a common enemy, the Soviet Union. Now, he said,
Clinton and Jiang are trying to avoid an unnecessarily adversarial
relationship, while reaching for a different kind of partnership _
``complicated, messy, hard nosed and realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement at the meeting for the two countries to stop
aiming their nuclear missiles at each other is only symbolic,
especially given that China's strategic rockets are stored without
their liquid fuel or their warheads, meaning that retargeting is
the least time consuming of China's war preparations. But the
symbolism is important nonetheless, Shambaugh said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's symbolic of a nonadversarial relationship, and that's
fundamental to both sides now, to insure that the relationship does
not slide into confrontation.''
</P>
<P>
   Morton Abramowitz, senior fellow at the Council on Foreign
Relations, said Clinton had ``handled this exceedingly well,'' even
if his domestic critics were not satisfied. ``The critics seem to
want him to go there and start a war,'' Abramowitz said.
</P>
<P>
   To Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D.-Conn., ``the most important aspect
of the Beijing meeting is that it occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've regularized our relations, and I hope Jiang returns here
next year,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the substantive accomplishments were few, he added,
``it's better to have some good small agreements than one big bad
agreement, made from weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, he said, ``that will mean less to criticize by
the critics and less to defend by us, so both parties can appear
strong.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
