<HEADLINE>
ANTI-SMOKING GROUP TO FILE COMPLAINT AGAINST INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky.)  (nk) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An anti-smoking organization plans to file a
complaint Monday with the Federal Election Commission accusing the
major tobacco companies of making illegal corporate campaign
contributions by promising to run political advertisements on
behalf of Republican senators.
</P>
<P>
   The prospects are remote that the complaint will have any
effect. It appears primarily to be an effort to generate bad
publicity for the cigarette makers and for Republican politicians
who voted to support them.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint, prepared by the Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids,
refers to news media accounts of a comment made by Sen. Mitch
McConnell, R-Ky., at a private meeting on June 17. According to the
accounts, McConnell told his Republican colleagues that if they
voted to kill comprehensive tobacco legislation, the cigarette
manufacturers would run television advertisements supporting them.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours after that meeting, the Senate fell three votes
short of approving a motion to cut off debate on the tobacco bill.
Forty of the 42 votes against ending debate came from Republicans.
The effect of the vote was to scrap the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell is not only a leading opponent of strong anti-smoking
legislation; he is also the chairman of the campaign committee that
raises money for Republican senators' re-election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rarely is the connection between a campaign contribution and a
vote on a critical issue so blatantly linked,'' the complaint
states, arguing that the promise to run political advertisements
violates campaign finance legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint was written by Matthew Myers, executive vice
president of the Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids. He gave a copy to
The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Williams, a spokesman for the tobacco industry, said that
he could not comment because he had not seen the complaint. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
