<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    American League week in review
 &HT;    By I. J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Yankees 5-1 (55-19), Blue Jays 5-2 (41-41), Red Sox
3-4 (47-32), Devil Rays 3-4 (34-46), Orioles 1-6 (37-45).
</P>
<P>
   _ Interleague records: Yankees 10-2, Blue Jays 7-6, Red Sox 6-7,
Devil Rays 4-8, Orioles 4-9.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: The Yankees are playing at a .743 clip and at
their current pace would finish with 120 wins. The Red Sox are
battling the Rangers for control of the wild-card spot. Meanwhile,
things only seem to be getting worse in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: Red Sox shortstop Nomar Garciaparra has a
20-game hitting streak.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: Blue Jays closer Randy Myers passed Rollie
Fingers on the all-time saves list and moved into fifth place with
342.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: The Blue Jays are ready to deal third baseman
Ed Sprague, feeling prospect Tom Evans is ready to take over the
spot.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: Orioles pitcher Scott Kamieniecki could miss the
rest of the season with a disk problem that is causing nerve
irritation.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: Devil Rays owner Vince Namoli denies a report that
he had to fight an attempt by two minority owners to force him out.
Namoli has been criticized for the way he handled fans and local
government officials.
</P>
<P>
   CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Indians 5-2 (46-33) Royals 5-2 (35-45), White Sox 4-3
(33-47), Twins 3-4 (38-42), Tigers 3-4 (30-48).
</P>
<P>
   _ Interleague records: Indians 8-5, Royals 7-6, Twins 6-7, White
Sox 6-7, Tigers 5-8.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: The Indians are running away with the division,
with an 8 1/2-game lead, and are tied for second in the league in
hitting (.282), but their pitching is what is carrying them. They
have a league-leading 3.81 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: The Indians are the only team in the majors with
at least one extra-base hit in every game.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: The Tigers called up reliever Matt Anderson, the
first player taken in the draft last year. He was at Class AA
Jacksonville, where he had a 0.66 ERA in 12 games. Saturday, his
fastball was clocked at 100 mph.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: Comiskey Park's Saturday crowd of 22,100 was
only the fourth home crowd of more than 20,000 for the White Sox in
39 games this season.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: The Twins placed veteran pitcher Mike Morgan on
the disabled list with a strained rib cage muscle.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: In a start last week, five pitches by Cleveland's
Bartolo Colon were clocked at more than 100 mph.
</P>
<P>
   WEST
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Rangers 4-3 (46-35), Angels 4-3 (48-32), A's 3-4
(36-44), Mariners 3-4 (34-48).
</P>
<P>
   _ Interleague records: Angels 9-4, Rangers 8-5, A's 6-7,
Mariners 5-8.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: This may end up being the best division race,
with the Angels holding just a 2 1/2-game lead over the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: A's rookie Ben Grieve has nine hits in his last
13 at-bats and eight RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: Mariners starter Ken Cloude is winless in his
last 11 starts. Two Anaheim pitchers (Omar Olivares and Chuck
Finley) are among the group of five AL pitchers with an ERA under
3.00.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: The Mariners are just 13-14 when Ken Griffey
homers. Griffey has 32 homers to lead the league, five more than
the player behind him, teammate Alex Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: The Rangers activated second baseman Mark
McLemore from the DL and sent left-hander Matt Perisho to Class
AAA.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: The 119-game errorless streak for Rangers center
fielder Roberto Kelly ended Saturday night.
</P>
