<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NATIONAL LEAGUEWEEK IN REVIEW
 &HT;    By I. J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Phillies 4-3 (40-39), Marlins 4-3 (28-53), Expos 3-4
(33-47), Braves 3-4 (53-29), Mets 3-3 (42-34).
</P>
<P>
   _ Interleague records: Mets 7-5, Phillies 7-6, Braves 6-7, Expos
6-7, Marlins 6-7.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: The Yankees ripped through the two best teams
in the division, taking five of six from the Braves and Mets going
into Sunday's game at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: Phillies outfielder Bobby Abreu has the best
average of any hitter in the division at .324.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: Mets starter Hideo Nomo is winless in his last
10 starts while Greg Maddux won game No. 100 with the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: The Phillies released utilityman Rex Hudler,
costing them $800,000, while starter Curt Schilling has allowed 25
hits in his last two starts.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: The Mets announced that catcher Todd Hundley
will begin a 20-day rehab assignment Wednesday at Class A Port St.
Lucie (Fla.). Also, the club put starter Al Leiter on the DL.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: Word around the league is the two relievers the
Braves have targeted are Mark Leiter of the Phillies and
Cincinnati's Jeff Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Brewers 6-1 (42-37), Reds 4-3 (34-49), Astros 3-4
(49-32), Cardinals 2-5 (39-41), Pirates 1-5 (38-43), Cubs 1-6
(42-39).
</P>
<P>
   _ Interleague records: Astros 8-3, Brewers 7-4, Pirates 5-5,
Cubs 5-8, Reds 4-5, Cardinals 4-7.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: Since winning 10 in a row, the Cubs have lost
13 of 18 and the Brewers have passed them for second place. Cubs
outfielder Sammy Sosa has 19 home runs this month, a major-league
record for any month.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: Cardinals first baseman Mark McGwire has 36
homers, matching the most by any St. Louis player in a full season
in 49 years.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: The Brewers have replaced closer Doug Jones with
Bob Wickman, who has converted seven saves in a row.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: The Cardinals are only 15-16 in games in which
McGwire has homered. Astros center fielder Carl Everett has been
caught stealing two more times (10) than he has stolen (eight).
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: The Cubs placed center fielder Brant Brown on
the DL with an injured shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: The four-year, $3.5 million contract the Cardinals
have given second-round pick Chad Hutchinson (48th overall) has
upset other team executives, feeling the signing bonus bar has been
raised again.
</P>
<P>
   WEST
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Padres 4-3 (53-29), Giants 4-3 (48-35), Dodgers 3-3
(39-41), Rockies 4-3 (36-47), Diamondbacks 3-4 (28-54).
</P>
<P>
   _ Interleague records: Padres 5-5, Giants 6-4, Dodgers 5-5,
Rockies 4-6, Diamondbacks 5-8.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: The Dodgers cleaned house, firing manager Bill
Russell and general manager Fred Claire. The Padres went 25 games
over .500 for the first time in their history.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: The Padres are tied for the best record in the
league despite being are ninth in the league in hitting (.258).
They are fourth in pitching (3.48).
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: Dodgers starter Ismael Valdes threw a one-hitter
Saturday, beating the Pirates 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: Giants manager Dusty Baker is pushing former
Dodgers teammate Davey Lopes for the managerial job in Los Angeles.
Colorado starter Darryl Kile is winless since May 4.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: The Rockies put right-hander John Thompson on
the DL with a blister on his pitching hand.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: When Claire was asked if he would do anything
different if he takes another GM job, he said, ``Yes, I won't trade
Pedro Martinez.
</P>
