<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-NETHERLANDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAVIA WILL FACE A NETHERLANDS TEAM UNITED AT LAST
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST.-ETIENNE, France _ Five hours ahead of time, the orange crush
of Dutch fans began to gather for last Thursday's World Cup match
with Mexico. They wore orange hats, orange dresses, orange
shoelaces, orange hair, orange sombreros. They carried plastic
orange hammers and plastic orange clogs and plastic orange hands
and even plastic orange Eiffel Towers.
</P>
<P>
   ``At home they are crazy,'' said Rene Gielians, 26, a
quality-control manager for an electronics company in Vroomshoop,
the Netherlands. ``They have orange houses, orange cars, orange
fries, orange mayonnaise.''
</P>
<P>
   Gielians had driven 10 hours to the match with a friend, Willem
Eising, who also considered painting his car the color of a highway
cone. ``But after the World Cup, you have an orange car,'' Eising
said, explaining why he decided not to.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the Netherlands is consumed by soccer's world
championship, but orange is as much the color of caution as of
celebration. Every four years, the Netherlands brings one of the
deepest, most talented teams to the World Cup, and every four years
it goes home unfulfilled. Inevitably, the team shatters into a
collection of petulant individuals. Failure is routine and
predictable, a sort of clockwork orange.
</P>
<P>
   These are the Buffalo Bills of international soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always have the feeling we are going to win, but in the
back of your mind, you think, `No,''' Eising said.
</P>
<P>
   Gielians said: ``This year will be different. I am sure of it.''
</P>
<P>
   This Dutch team is being compared with the squads of 1974 and
1978, which reached the World Cup final. Perhaps, finally, the
Netherlands will shed itself of the backhanded compliment of being
the best team never to win a world championship. The Netherlands
will learn quickly about its chances with a second-round match
against Yugoslavia on Monday in Toulouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the talent to win it all,'' said Steve Sampson,
coach of the Americans, who lost to the Netherlands, 2-0, in a
pre-World Cup exhibition match in February. ``Individually, they
have tremendous skill and strength and power. They have great
talent at every position and great balance. If there is a weakness,
the Dutch tend to beat themselves before anyone else does.''
</P>
<P>
   Hope has been resurrected by the return of striker Dennis
Bergkamp, who won the player of the year award in the English
Premier League playing for Arsenal, but who missed the end of the
season and the English F.A. Cup final because of a recalcitrant
hamstring injury. For seven weeks, trainers have worked on his
wheels. He returned tentatively in the scoreless World Cup opener
against Belgium, but shanked a certain goal from 10 yards out.
</P>
<P>
   In the next match, he delivered a brilliant goal, fox-trotting
between two defenders and blasting a shot that opened the
floodgates in a 5-0 victory over South Korea. So humiliating was
the defeat for the losers that Cha Bum Kun was fired as coach of
South Korea before it played its next match.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they keep playing like this, I think they will win the
World Cup,'' Cha said about the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, in a 2-2 draw against Mexico, Bergkamp was
brilliantly ubiquitous. He ranged across midfield to retrieve the
ball and place it in attack. He headed a pass two perfect strides
ahead of his teammate Phillip Cocu for a goal in the fourth minute.
And he threatened to score himself on defense, stealing a pass and
heading the ball just wide of the right post. Still not completely
fit, though, Bergkamp left the game 11 minutes from the end. The
Netherlands seemed to deflate like a balloon, allowing Mexico to
retrieve a 2-2 tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can control the ball at great speed and he has a great work
rate,'' said Sampson, the American coach. ``And he's a great
opportunist in front of the goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Bergkamp is, however, not great at flying. This fear of airplane
travel developed during or shortly after the 1994 World Cup in the
United States. Bergkamp, who is intensely private, does not like to
talk about this phobia. Dutch journalists are not certain of the
origins, either, but they list three possibilities: Bergkamp became
alarmed after a Dutch reporter joked that he had a bomb on a flight
during the 1994 World Cup; he had a scare while playing for Inter
Milan in the Italian League; he feels the grave weight of
fatherhood.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Bergkamp declined to fly to a World Cup qualifying
match in Turkey, and the Netherlands lost, 1-0. He also missed a
team training camp in the United States. While the Dutch have been
flying around France during the World Cup, Bergkamp has been taking
trains and cars.
</P>
<P>
   At the other forward spot, Patrick Kluivert has seen his career
burn fiercely and then fade like a comet. In 1995, at the age of
18, he scored the decisive goal for Ajax Amsterdam against A.C.
Milan in the European Champions League title game. But he was later
involved in an accident in which the car he was driving killed a
prominent Dutch theater director. Kluivert was fined and sentenced
to community service, and his soccer career has never regained that
early magical promise.
</P>
<P>
   He had a disappointing season at A.C. Milan this year, then was
ejected from the Netherlands' first game in the World Cup after
elbowing the Belgian defender Lorenzo Staelens. Kluivert was
suspended for the next two matches, against South Korea and Mexico.
He told a Dutch newspaper that he reacted because Staelens called
him a ``rapist,'' a reference to an investigation of allegations of
a sexual offense in which Kluivert was cleared earlier this year
for lack of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Kluivert is eligible to return against Yugoslavia, but Coach
Guus Hiddink said Sunday that he would put Kluivert in a reserve
role and retain the creative partnership of Bergkamp and Cocu. As
always with the Dutch, attitude is a more urgent concern than
personnel. The players are always great; their demeanor is not.
</P>
<P>
   They missed repeated chances to score against Belgium and
relaxed with a 2-0 lead against Mexico, surrendering two goals for
the draw. Four years ago, the Netherlands waited an entire half
before deciding to attack against Brazil, erasing a 2-0 deficit
before losing, 3-2, in the quarterfinals when it could have won
with earlier determination.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to play for 90 minutes, not 60,'' the captain Frank
DeBoer said after the tie with Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   So far, at least, there has been no evidence of the internal
squabbles that have wrecked this team in recent years. Midfielder
Edgar Davids was sent home from the 1996 European Championships
after he accused Hiddink of favoritism. The star striker Ruud
Gullit refused to join the team for the 1994 World Cup. When the
Dutch are cooperating on the field and off, they have the
capability to win any tournament. Against Mexico, they made 15
passes in one mesmerizing sequence before Bergkamp flicked the ball
to Cocu for a shot that rang off the crossbar.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new start; we don't talk about the past,'' DeBoer
said. ``We have our noses pointed in the right direction. We know
we can go very far, but we must remain friends.''
</P>
<P>
   The Netherlands won the 1988 European Championship, but a decade
has passed now since any substantial crown sat on the Dutch head.
There has been nothing to replace the nostalgia for the 1970s, for
Johan Cruyff, the most famous Dutch player of all, and for the
teams that lost to host Germany in the 1974 World Cup final and to
host Argentina in the 1978 final.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won the European title in 1988, and I think the World Cup
will be next,'' said Annemiek Kuyer, a 19-year-old medical student
from Maastricht. ``It's time, don't you think?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-98 1954EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
