u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-FREE-AGENCY-NYT &LR;      06-28 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FREE-AGENCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS FACE FREE-AGENCY SEASON FILLED WITH DOUBTS
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With the entry draft over and the free-agency season
about to begin, General Manager Neil Smith presides over a Rangers
roster filled with deficiencies and doubts.
</P>
<P>
   Consider his top three centers, the spine of any team. First is
Wayne Gretzky, a superstar gradually and gracefully fading into his
20th and possibly final season in the National Hockey League. The
second is another veteran, Pat LaFontaine, whose recovery from yet
another career-threatening concussion is uncertain. The third is an
unproven rookie junior, Manny Malhotra, who Smith says might play a
regular role at age 18.
</P>
<P>
   Behind center, the big concern is Brian Leetch, the captain and
star defenseman, who will try to improve upon a poor season as he
heads into what may be his walkaway year _ the last of his contract
before unrestricted free agency.
</P>
<P>
   Behind him, goalie Mike Richter will be an unrestricted free
agent on Wednesday to sell his services to the any team.
Technically, the expansion Nashville team drafted him on Friday,
but once Richter signs with another team, that would give the
Predators only the right to compensation in next summer's entry
draft.
</P>
<P>
   As was the case with the captain Mark Messier last summer,
Richter and the Rangers say they would like to make a deal. As with
Messier and others in this category, money will always talk and
free agents will often walk.
</P>
<P>
   John Muckler, who took over as coach late last season, said that
the Rangers cannot win with the roster they had at the end of last
season, when they missed the playoffs and squandered all of that
ticket revenue for Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Muckler also said he did not see much immediate help from the
farm system, built by Smith, who could get active in the free-agent
market. But Smith has hinted that he might not make a big bid for a
top talent, the way he did last summer with his unsuccessful effort
to sign Colorado's Joe Sakic to a three-year $21 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   So how will Muckler get the players he needs? It was interesting
to watch the coach and the general manager at the draft table on
Saturday afternoon on the floor of Marine Midland Arena in Buffalo,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Before Smith chose Malhotra with the seventh pick over all, he
was on the phone with Colorado General Manager Pierre Lacroix,
discussing a possible trade. Muckler, anyone could clearly see, was
up from his chair, speaking forcefully. Asked afterward what
Muckler was talking about, Smith brusquely replied that he had no
idea and that Muckler was not responsible for the selection.
</P>
<P>
   Muckler has recent experience as a successful general manager,
and his communication with Smith could be an important factor in
the rebuilding of the Blue Shirts.
</P>
<P>
   With Craig MacTavish, Charlie Huddy and Keith Acton, Muckler has
a staff of assistants loyal to him. Among general managers in the
sport, Smith holds seniority, beginning his 10th season. But after
building the Stanley Cup champions of 1994, the Rangers have
experienced four seasons of decline and drift. How many more will
the current corporate ownership accept?
</P>
<P>
   Smith isn't the only local boss with a full summer agenda. Lou
Lamoriello of the Devils could lose center Doug Gilmour to
unrestricted free agency the same way Smith could lose Richter.
</P>
<P>
   But Lamoriello's franchise has a strong farm system and more
depth at all positions. His problems will come in Group 2, the
restricted category of free agency where players signing offer
sheets from other teams can be retained through matching bids.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative is to accept draft choices as compensation.
Until last summer, this category saw little action. That changed
with Sakic, Sergei Fedorov and Chris Gratton. Among this year's
Group 2 palyers, Lamoriello could lose defenseman Scott Niedermayer
and centers Bobby Holik and Peter Sykora.
</P>
<P>
   Lamoriello is a tough and shrewd bargainer who sometimes gets
good players to sign for less than market value. If he can do it
with these three, the league should cast in bronze the Lou
Lamoriello Trophy and award it to him for negotiating brilliance.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Islanders, so much is unclear. Mike Milbury has
survived as general manager, but it remains to be seen how much his
influence has been reduced in contract matters. With Zigmund
Palffy, Trevor Linden and Kenny Jonsson enjoying the leverage of
restricted free agency, the new ownership must settle with them
before it can sell many more season tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another version of the uniform is not enough to draw a
crowd. As for coaching, Milbury has that title, too, but he still
seeks a strong associate for a major role. Ted Nolan, out of work
for a year, turned down the job, then hinted this past weekend that
he might want it after all. But he never formally approached
Milbury to apply.
</P>
<P>
   When Nolan coached Buffalo and Muckler was the general manager,
both helped to build a good team. But they lost their jobs in a
bitter, franchise-wide civil war over power and personality.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, both men were visible last weekend on the shore
of Lake Erie, trying to improve their situations with rival
franchises based in the opposite corner of the Empire State. On the
opposing islands of Manhattan and Long, theirs would be a rivalry
worth watching. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
