u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-MAGS-MEDIA-NYT     06-28 0280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-MAGS-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARST MAGAZINES REJOINS PUBLISHERS' AD GROUP
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hearst Magazines announced last week that it had rejoined the
Publishers Information Bureau, the influential trade group that
tracks magazines' advertising pages.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine company is a unit of Hearst Corp., which publishes
Cosmopolitan and Esquire. Hearst Magazines resigned from the bureau
last month to protest the bureau's decision to count the ad pages
in Conde Nast's recent supplement, Currency, a personal finance
magazine that was sent along with the company's 15 other magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst's withdrawal was considered significant by the industry
because it involved an important publishing company breaking ranks
and because it seemed to add fuel to a longtime rivalry between
Hearst and Conde Nast Publications, which is owned by Advance
Publications Inc. and publishes Vogue, Glamour and GQ, among
others.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the Hearst pullout, the bureau's council voted
unanimously last week to approve a new format for reporting figures
on magazine ad dollars and ad pages that are collected by
Competitive Media Reporting, a unit of VNU NV. In addition to the
customary overall magazine totals, the new reporting structure will
also identify ad pages and dollars that appeared in scheduled
issues of a magazine, unscheduled issues and supplements.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau also asked K. Robert Brink, a Hearst executive vice
president, who had resigned his post as chairman of the bureau's
council, to resume his service through the remainder of his term,
which ends in October. A Hearst spokesman said Friday that Brink
had accepted. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-98 2001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
