</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AIDS conference opens with myriad of emotion
 &HT;    (EDS: May run with AIDS-VACCINE-COX. Moving on (a) general news
and (i) international categories.) By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ The 12th World AIDS Conference _ the largest symposium
to deal with the deadly disease _ opened Sunday both bouyed with
optimism and shrouded with despair.
</P>
<P>
   About 13,000 researchers, activists, community leaders and media
are in Switzerland this week to hear scientists present thousands
of scientific papers ranging in topic from drug therapies to
fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Despite much progress against AIDS, ``there is news so
devastating that few in this room could have predicted or imagined
it a decade ago,'' Dr. Peter Piot, head of the United Nations AIDS
program, told delegates at the opening session.
</P>
<P>
   His organization estimates 12 million people around the world
have already died of AIDS, and 31 million are alive but infected.
Each day, 16,000 people catch the virus.
</P>
<P>
   Yet rather than dwell on disappointments, the leaders of the
conference who spoke Sunday encouraged continued hopefulness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now is the time for us to embrace a new realism and a new
urgency in our efforts,'' Piot said. Researchers have been warning
that the prevalent feeling at this year's conference would be far
less optimistic than at the last one, in Vancouver, British
Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, exceptionally good results from drugs called
protease inhibitors had persuaded many that they were winning the
battle against the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers and people with AIDS still sing the drugs' praises,
but less jubilantly since they were linked to several debilitating
side effects, including kidney stones, high cholesterol levels and
a bizarre redistribution of body fat called ``buffalo hump'' in
which fat collects on the back and shoulders or midsection.
</P>
<P>
   Also, reports that some people are increasingly returning to
risky sexual practices, such as condomless sex, are worrying HIV
prevention experts.
</P>
<P>
   Conference leaders obviously are pushing to brighten the tinge
of depression.
</P>
<P>
   Piot focused heavily on recent triumphs, including stablizing
HIV infection rates in many countries, new prevention methods such
as the female condom and recent research that definitively shows
administering anti-HIV drugs during pregnancy can sharply reduce
the number of HIV-positive babies born to HIV-positive women.
</P>
<P>
   Piot summed it up by saying, The biggest AIDS gap of all is the
gap between what we know we can do today, and what we are actually
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The extreme cost of combination drug therapy, considered the
best option for people with HIV, is a continuing sore spot among
activists who point out that the $10,000 to $15,000 annual price
tag for a single patient equals the yearly budget of some hospitals
in poor countries.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
