<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-28 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0884 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT&AMP;T-TCI-ART-970(2TAK     06-28 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-TCI-ART-970(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHONE MERGER AIMS TO CONTROL ELECTRONIC PIPELINE OF FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mass.)  (See related stories: AT&AMP;T-ARMSTRONG, AT&AMP;T-TCI-MARKETPLACE) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ko) 
 By STEVE LOHR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Billions of dollars and a bold high-tech vision are fueling AT&AMP;T
Corp.'s plan to buy Tele-Communications Inc. The merger, announced
last week, is the latest in a rising wave of corporate deals
sweeping up telecommunications, cable television and media
companies as these industries become increasingly dependent on the
digital technology of computing.
</P>
<P>
   The business logic behind the trend is that companies now face a
once-in-a-corporate-lifetime choice of getting in early to become
leaders in the new markets of the information age or being
relegated to also-ran status. Earlier this month, two major media
companies _ Walt Disney Co. and the NBC unit of General Electric
Co. _ applied that logic in making significant investments in
popular sites on the Internet's World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Whether any of these deals make sense, or make money anytime
soon, will depend largely on the economic behavior of people like
Charles Vandagriff of Oakland, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Vandagriff, his wife and two daughters are the kind of well-off,
technologically fluent family earmarked first by phone, media and
computer companies in their consumer marketing campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Someday, AT&AMP;T wants families like the Vandagriffs to turn to the
company for one-stop shopping for not only all of their telephone
and cable television services but new information services as well.
And AT&AMP;T's purchase of TCI, the nation's second-largest cable
television company, is seen as a big step toward realizing AT&AMP;T's
vision of becoming an all-in-one digital delivery system.
</P>
<P>
   Vandagriff, 49, is a furniture designer, and his wife, Kathy
Sinsheimer, is a psychotherapist. Their household has three
personal computers, four phone lines, a cellular phone and two
pagers.
</P>
<P>
   There are 16 million such wired families in America, typically
with incomes of $70,000 or more, at least one PC and often more
than telephone line, according to Yankee Group, a research firm.
``No new technology or technology marketing plan will succeed if it
doesn't succeed first with families like that one,'' observed
Howard Anderson, Yankee Group's managing director.
</P>
<P>
   By acquiring TCI's cable-television system, AT&AMP;T gets a faster
network for sending telephone, video and Internet services directly
into consumers' homes, including 1.3 million TCI customers in the
San Francisco area like the Vandagriffs. It was this vision of a
phone-entertainment-Internet supercarrier that AT&AMP;T chairman
Michael Armstrong and TCI chairman John Malone were extolling
Wednesday when they announced their $31.8 billion deal.
</P>
<P>
   Vandagriff remains skeptical. ``I'm sure these companies are
trying to think ahead, but it's not clear to me what they are going
to try to sell us really,'' he said. ``I have so many services now
_ Internet, cable, phone, cellular and pagers _ that I can't
imagine I want any more. I'll wait for the future to arrive.''
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications and media companies do not believe they have
the luxury of waiting. The rapid advances of technology, they say,
are forcing them to act now. The main engine is the spread of
digital technology that enables text, sound and video all to be
expressed and distributed in the form of the elemental building
blocks of computing, the electronic 1's and 0's called bits (short
for binary digits).
</P>
<P>
   Though all forms of information can be reduced to bits, text
requires the fewest bits, while sound and video consume many more.
One letter in a word can be rendered in eight bits, while a few
seconds of movie-style video may require millions of bits. Most of
the new services companies hope to market eventually _ including
video phones and movies on demand _ are expected to be multimedia
offerings that require high-speed connections into homes.
</P>
<P>
   So today, companies are puzzling over both how to carry more
bits into homes and how to package those bits into new
entertainment, information or shopping services that people may
actually want. In simple terms, telecommunications companies can be
thought of as the pipes and media companies as the programmers.
</P>
<P>
   It will be costly and time-consuming to upgrade the existing
bit-delivery mechanisms. Phone lines are skinny pipes, but they are
two-way networks that can both send and receive data; cable systems
offer fat pipes, but must be converted from one-way to two-way
systems. It will, for example, take AT&AMP;T nearly five years and $9
billion to upgrade the entire TCI network, estimates the Yankee
Group.
</P>
<P>
   As with most new technologies, businesses will be able to pay
for high-speed Internet service first, before it becomes
commonplace in homes as costs come down.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts predict the impact will be sweeping. Nicholas
Negroponte, director of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology
Media Laboratory, insists that for all the attention the Internet
has received, the power of the technology is still not understood.
``The Internet is wildly underestimated,'' Negroponte said. ``It
will grow to be the enabling technology of all media, TV, radio,
magazines and so on.''
</P>
<P>
   A longtime Internet enthusiast, Negroponte advises many of the
nation's leading media and telecommunications companies. What gives
his counsel added weight, though, are the recent trends in
household computer and Internet use.
</P>
<P>
   By January 1998, the share of American households with personal
computers reached 42 percent, up from 31 percent in 1995, according
to Odyssey L.P., a research firm in San Francisco. Over the same
three-year span, the percentage of households online has increased
to 23 percent from 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few years ago, the Internet was a geek network,'' noted Kate
Delhagen, an analyst at Forrester Research Inc., a technology
research firm. ``Now, the Internet equals consumer network,
something that is increasingly part of day-to-day life.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As more people go online, the Internet attracts more
advertisers, increasing the potential for electronic commerce. For
example, online purchases of airline tickets, hotel rooms and other
travel services tripled last year to $654 million, Forrester
estimates. By 2001, it projects online travel sales of $7.4
billion.
</P>
<P>
   With new-media startups beginning to attract large audiences to
their sites on the Internet's World Wide Web, the established media
companies are taking notice, starting to move beyond experiments to
make sizable investments. Two weeks ago, for example, Disney
announced that it would buy 43 percent of the Infoseek Corporation,
an online directory service, in a complex deal worth about $900
million.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular properties online, including the Yahoo
directory service and America Online Inc., are likely takeover
candidates, industry executives say. Indeed, AT&AMP;T did talk to
America Online recently, though the overture was rebuffed. The
Internet media business is expected to follow the pattern of cable
television, where entrepreneurs created CNN, ESPN and MTV and were
later bought out by Time Warner Inc., Disney and Viacom Inc.,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's inevitable that you will see increased concentration in
the new-media field as it matures, just as you did in every other
media business in history,'' said Mike Slade, chief executive of
Starwave Corp., the Web developer that built Disney's ESPN and ABC
News sites.
</P>
<P>
   Someday, people will look back on the recent telecommunications
and media deals as either shrewd or premature, depending on how
quickly the anticipated new business develops. History, both recent
and more distant, suggests some caution is in order.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1992, Malone of TCI declared that as early as 1994
his company would install digital compression technology enabling
customers to receive as many as 500 channels on their televisions
and many of the interactive shopping and information services that
people are today saying will be delivered via a supercharged
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, television was declared the engine of the so-called
information highway. ``Television will never be the same,'' Malone
said. ``Our ability to deliver program services is limited only by
our imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   Following a slightly different avenue of technology, Malone may
be proved correct, though his timetable was overly optimistic. Over
the years, the technologies that have truly transformed the way
people live required some time to spread.
</P>
<P>
   For example, it took 70 years from the first consumer sale of a
telephone in 1876 to the year when half of the nation's households
had phones, in 1946, according to a study by Technologic Partners,
a research firm in New York. It took the automobile 29 years, from
1895 to 1924, to reach half of American families, while it took the
television only 8 years, from 1946 to 1954.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you keep some technology history in mind, you are
setting yourself up for disillusionment,'' said Richard Shaffer, a
principal of Technologic Partners.
</P>
<P>
   Shaffer's own guess is that it will be 5 to 10 years before most
Americans will find that communications or media offerings have
changed markedly.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, analysts expect that combinations like AT&AMP;T-TCI
will focus on consolidated marketing of existing services. Such
telecommunications supercarriers want to offer local and
long-distance phone and cellular service, cable TV and Internet
access _ all on one bill with a price discount for buying all these
services from one company.
</P>
<P>
   Now that is an innovation that intrigues Vandagriff in Oakland.
``If they could simplify all this, put it on one understandable
monthly bill and then offer me a discount of 20 percent or so, I'd
say, `OK, you've got my attention,' '' he said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
