<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TALKERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T READ TOO MUCH INTO LIVE BROADCAST, CRITICS SAY  
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While applauding President Clinton's remarks on
human rights, critics of his trip to China cautioned Sunday against
reading too much into Chinese President Jiang Zemin's decision to
allow their discussion to be broadcast live.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's criticism of the 1989 Tiananmen massacre, which
prompted Jiang to defend the crackdown on pro-democracy activists,
was characterized as one of the few positive developments of the
trip.
</P>
<P>
   Although the two leaders struck agreements on the targeting of
nuclear missiles and the faltering Asian economy, no deals were
made on reducing Chinese trade barriers or enhancing human rights
or religious freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not much has substantively changed,'' said Rep. Christopher
Cox, R-Calif., chairman of a House committee investigating the
sales of U.S. satellite and other high-tech equipment to China.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president was able to deliver some message,'' Rep.
Christopher Smith, R- N.J., said on CNN's Late Edition. ``I'm happy
for that, but we should be very, very careful not to gush and do
the victory lap prior to seeing some real and substantial deeds.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Chinese leaders have held live news conferences in the
past, they have never permitted uncensored debates with a foreign
leader. The Saturday session featured Clinton and Jiang offering
their views on such sensitive subjects as the Tiananmen crackdown,
the detention of dissidents and the exiled Dalai Lama.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mon., who is traveling with Clinton, called
the televised news conference a ``turning point'' in U.S.-China
relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision by President Jiang to televise that press
conference nationwide is an indication to me that he, too, knows
the future for China is going to be more political freedoms and
more political expression,'' Baucus said. ``The genie is out of the
bottle with that press conference.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer of the Family Research Council dismissed the event as
``one flower'' in a long winter. ``One of the problems we've got
with our overall relationship with China is that we are unduly
affected by a symbolic moment like this,'' the conservative
Republican said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a one-dimensional policy with China. Trade has been
everything, not an element of it, it's been everything,'' Bauer
told CNN. ``First we sacrificed human rights to it. And I think
we've seen in recent months that even national security was
sacrificed.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to allegations that U.S. technology transfers
approved by Clinton may have helped the Chinese improve missile
guidance systems. The firm that benefited from the waivers is owned
by a major Democratic Party donor.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Lee, a leading pro-democracy activist and head of Hong
Kong's Democratic Party, expressed surprise over Jiang's decision
to broadcast the news conference in China, but sees it as an
indication the Chinese president faces no immediate threat from
within his government.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he believed that there would be any problem, I'm sure
wouldn't have allowed it,'' Lee said. ``So I think he must think
that he is in a pretty good position to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   And while it was astonishing to see Clinton and Jiang in a
virtual debate on human rights, Tibet and religious freedoms, Lee
said he ``would be truly happy if these sensitive issues could be
freely debated by ordinary Chinese people.''
</P>
<P>
   Past attempts to discuss such sensitive issues have provoked
indignant assertions by Chinese leaders that the U.S. was
interfering in China's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The dean of Chinese dissidents, Wei Jingsheng, said was
``delighted'' with Clinton's admonition to Jiang, although he
believed that Clinton could have pressed harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I don't think that it is enough,'' said Wei, who
lives in New York after being expelled from his homeland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
