u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK29-COX     06-28 0318
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves Notebook
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the space of two at-bats, Tom Glavine generated
enough offense to personally beat Toronto Sunday. Then he threw
down the gauntlet to Greg Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   With a one-run single in the first and a two-run double in the
third, Glavine recorded the first three-RBI game of his career, the
final two runs giving the Braves a 7-0 lead that pretty much closed
the book on this one. The day gave Braves pitchers a combined .188
average and 16 RBI this season, an RBI coming every 10.1 at-bats.
That is beyond respectable, considering that Andruw Jones, who
generally hits in front of the pitchers, generates an RBI ever 6.5
at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine has had a three-RBI game in the playoffs (Game 7 vs. St.
Louis of the 1996 NLCS) but this was his first in the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's something we all work hard on around here, so that when
the opportunity arises, hopefully we can do something about it,''
said Glavine, who leads Braves pitchers in RBI (5) and doubles (3).
''Not that you always will but you don't want to go up there
feeling like you're an automatic out. That was fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Not as much fun as Maddux is having. After setting out to finish
with a high batting average than ERA, Maddux is hitting .302
(13-for-43), far and away the class of the pitching staff. Glavine,
for one, is not impressed and is not about to concede the pitchers'
batting title.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm coming after him,'' he stated afterwards. ''I'm not laying
down. It's kind of like a golf handicap. I've spotted him his lead
and now I'm going to go after him. I don't know if I'm going to
catch him in average (.182) but I'm going to catch him in hits
(6).''
</P>
<P>
   Replied Maddux, ''He's got a long way to go, baby, a long way to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
