<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SUMMIT-610&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, IN FINAL CHINA SPEECH, CALLS FOR DEFENSE OF PERSONAL
FREEDOM
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: will be topped with Monday morning speech at Beijing
University.) 
(See also: CHINA-CHURCH, CHINA-LAMA, CHINA-HILLARY, CHINA-TAIWAN,
CHINA-U.S.) 
(fb) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ President Clinton on Monday proclaimed personal
freedom the ``mandate of the 21st century'' in a broad defense of
human and economic liberty at Beijing University.
</P>
<P>
   In his last public appearance in the Chinese capital, the
president said that the United States does not seek to impose its
vision of society on China or any other nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we are convinced that certain rights are universal,'' the
president said in remarks prepared for delivery and released by the
White House in advance of the speech. ``I believe that everywhere,
people aspire to be treated with dignity, to give voice to their
opinions, to choose their own leaders, to associate with whom they
wish, to worship how, when and where they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials have called Monday's speech the
rhetorical centerpiece of Clinton's nine-day visit to China, a
philosophical discourse addressed directly to the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to several hundred students and faculty in a freshly
painted auditorium at China's premier university, Clinton sought to
broaden his audience from the Chinese leadership, with whom he held
talks over the weekend, to a new generation that will shape the
future of the most populous nation on earth.
</P>
<P>
   He said that liberty was not a luxury to be enjoyed only by
wealthy nations, but a necessary element of human and economic
development. Acknowledging China's centuries-old fear of internal
disintegration, he said that all societies crave stability.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, personal freedom strengthens a nation's security,
rather than undermining it, as the Communist government has long
maintained.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the global information age, freedom is a powerful engine of
progress,'' Clinton said. ``China's greatest source of strength
resides in the minds and hearts of its citizens. It is profoundly
in your interest _ and the world's _ that those minds be free to
reach the fullness of their potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hailed the rapid economic growth that has swept across
China in the past decade, as the government has loosed controls on
private entrepreneurship and begun to close down its inefficient
state-owned enterprises. He said that growing incomes brought more
options to the Chinese people _ foreign travel, access to cable
television and the Internet, new career opportunities, a higher
standard of living.
</P>
<P>
   ``Economic security is an essential element of freedom,''
Clinton said. ``In China, the extraordinary strides you have taken
in nurturing that liberty and spreading freedom from want will be a
source of strength for your people in the 21st century. But true
freedom must mean more than economic opportunity. In America, we
believe that freedom itself is indivisible.''
</P>
<P>
   The Beijing University speech offered a coda to a remarkable
series of weekend discussions with Jiang Zemin, the president of
China, and other top government leaders here.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday evening, Clinton and Jiang continued their dialogue at
a private three-hour dinner, exploring in greater depth the growth
of the United States-China relationship and the possible paths of
China's future.
</P>
<P>
   The dinner was the last meeting of the two presidents on
Clinton's five-city visit to China, which has seen a significant
step forward both in relations between the two nations and between
their leaders. Aides who attended called the evening ``very casual
and very lively.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday began with a service at Beijing's largest Protestant
church and ended with the private dinner attended by the
Presidents' wives and a handful of top advisers. The day also
included an afternoon of touristic diversions to the Forbidden City
and the Great Wall.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The dinner, in a ceremonial house in the lakeside Zhongnanhai
compound for Beijing's government elite, included discussion of the
Asian financial crisis, dvelopment of an independent judiciary in
China and American movies. Jiang recalled enjoying ``Gone with the
Wind'' several years ago in Shanghai, according to a United States
official who attended.
</P>
<P>
   ``They went way beyond what people thought were the
possibilities of having this kind of discussion,'' Madeleine
Albright, the secretary of state, said of the two days of meetings
between the two presidents. ``We have moved the relationship into a
qualitatively and quantitatively different direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright and other American officials were still clearly elated
by the press conference Saturday in which Clinton and Jiang engaged
in an animated debate on subjects that for years were not the
subject of public discussion _ religious freedom, Tibet and the
role of the individual and the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The press conference was a truly remarkable event and one that
is going to have long-term repercussions _ positive ones,''
Albright said in a session with reporters at the Diaoyutai state
guest compound at Diaoyutai. But in a reminder that not everything
has changed in China, American security officials had posted a
notice on the wall of the room where Albright spoke reading, ``The
walls have ears.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright and two other senior American officials _ Samuel R.
Berger, the national security adviser, and James Sasser, the
ambassador to China _ said Monday that 600 million Chinese had seen
the news conference, carried live on China Central Television, the
government's national network.
</P>
<P>
   But that number seemed a significant exaggeration, given that
there are an estimated 300 million television sets in China and
there was no advance notice that the midday Saturday news
conference would be carried live. It was difficult to find Chinese
who had seen the news conference live, and state television
rebroadcast only selected portions of it over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Sunday, the Clintons attended services at Chongwenmen
Church, the largest Protestant church in Beijing with nearly 3,000
members.
</P>
<P>
   The congregation presented Clinton with a bilingual Bible and
invited him to speak to the overflow crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``We celebrate with you the growth of the practice of our faith
in China,'' Clinton said in remarks that lasted less than five
minutes. ``I believe our faith calls upon us to seek unity with
people across the world with different backgrounds and races and
creeds.''
</P>
<P>
   Added the President, ``I believe Chinese and Americans are
brothers and sisters as children of God. We come here in that
spirit today.''
</P>
<P>
   The church service was briefly disrupted by a woman who rushed
to the front of the room in an apparent attempt to speak to the
president. The woman, who later gave her name as Chen Anbi, was
hustled out of the church by security agents. She said outside, ``I
just wanted to see him,'' referring to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said later that she was ``very emotional'' and only
wanted to thank him for attending the service.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons and their daughter, Chelsea, spent the afternoon
touring the Forbidden City and the Great Wall. Authorities cleared
the Forbidden City for the Clintons, only the third time they have
done so, American officials said. The previous times were for a
tour by President Richard Nixon and for the making of the film
``The Last Emperor.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called the wall ``quite unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing to imagine that it was done so long ago. They've
even had bricks here for 400 and some odd years,'' the president
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
