<SLUG> BC-GLF-SHOPRITE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SORENSTAM SIZZLES TO WIN BY FOUR STROKES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABSECON, N.J. _ Annika Sorenstam, the premier player in women's
golf, was so busy picking up pine needles at the first green Sunday
that she joked she would need a vacuum cleaner for the final round
of the ShopRite LPGA Classic. She drew a laugh from the gallery,
then proved for the rest of the round that a few pine needles would
be the only obstacles she shied away from.
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam sizzled again on the Bay Course of the Seaview
Marriott Resort, shooting her second consecutive six-under-par 65
and capturing the ShopRite event by four shots over Juli Inkster
with a total of 17-under 196.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second consecutive victory for Sorenstam, whose game
has apparently returned to the standard that helped her capture the
U.S. Women's Open two years in a row before she missed the cut last
year. This year's Open begins Thursday at the Blackwolf Run Golf
Resort in Kohler, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy with my game now that my putting has come
around,'' Sorenstam said. ``I'm very pleased the way I'm playing
going into the Open next week. I was playing well going into the
Open last year, but I put too much pressure on myself. I learned a
lot from that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam mastered the Donald Ross-designed course, a links-type
layout that requires intelligent managing. Players raved about the
way Sorenstam played, especially Inkster, who shot 67 playing with
Sorenstam in the last group of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``She just doesn't make any mistakes,'' Inkster said. ``She's
always in the fairway, hits the greens and makes the putts. She is
the best player in the world, and I needed to play a perfect round
to beat her.''
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old Sorenstam registered 18 birdies and just a
single bogey in the tournament, on the 12th hole on Saturday when
she three-putted. She started the day with a two-shot lead over
Inkster, who bogeyed the second hole. But three consecutive birdies
by Inkster, starting at the fourth hole, brought her within one
shot, as Sorenstam managed just one birdie after seven holes.
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam birdied the eighth with a 15-footer to go 13 under and
widen the gap to two shots again, but Inkster responded with a
birdie on the ninth to close the gap to one again.
</P>
<P>
   It was the closest Inkster could come, however, because
Sorenstam finished with birdies in the last four holes while
Inkster managed just one more birdie.
</P>
<P>
   Lori Kane shot 66 and finished third with a total of 203 on the
6,024-yard course. Lisa Walters (68) was next at 205, followed by
Dina Ammaccapane (67), who finished at 206.
</P>
<P>
   Carrie Webb of Australia broke the course record Sunday morning
with seven-under 64 with plenty of help from the first hole-in-one
of her career. It came with a 6-iron at the par-3 seventh, which
played 169 yards Sunday instead of the usual 182.
</P>
<P>
   Webb, 23, has nine victories, including two this season. She won
four tournaments in her rookie season in 1996 to become the rookie
with the most victories behind Nancy Lopez, who won nine
tournaments, including a record-setting five in a row, in her first
full season on the LPGA tour in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Webb's course record, played in a slight wind Sunday morning,
included six birdies and two bogeys besides her hole-in-one.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the bad bounces the first two days turned into good
bounces today,'' Webb said. ``I got the breaks at the right time,
but I also hit some good shots. Putting is my main concern going
into the Open next week, but hopefully it will come around by
Thursday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
