<SLUG> BC-CHINA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: AMERICAN PUBLIC NOT LIKELY TO BUY WHITE HOUSE PITCH ON
SINO-AMERICA RELATIONS   

</HEADLINE>
 ANALYSIS-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ After two days of high-level talks with Chinese
leaders, the Clinton administration is confident that when it comes
to Sino-America relations the glass is at least half full.
</P>
<P>
   But as President Clinton and his official party move on Monday
to Shanghai for the trade and economics part of the trip, they are
equally aware that for critics of his China policy back home the
glass remains no better than half empty.
</P>
<P>
   Before Clinton began his nine-day journey through the world's
most populous nation last week, U.S. Ambassador James Sasser,
predicted the visit ``will indicate that relations between the
United States and China have normalized.''
</P>
<P>
   That may now be true in the White House's mind _ and there will
be a decent public relations effort to sell the high points of the
journey _ but it is likely to take years for that view to settle in
with the American public.
</P>
<P>
   The administration takes the line that improvement in relations
with China will be gradual, and that a dramatic governmental change
or collapse of the present regime, such as occurred in the Soviet
Union, is unlikely. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; And while gradualism may be a tough sell back home, where
polling indicates a significant animosity toward China, the White
House contends the summit meetings Saturday and Sunday with
President Jiang Zemin and Premier Zhu Rongji proved Clinton's
determined effort at dialogue was correct.
</P>
<P>
   ``Engagement with the Chinese can advance America's interests
and its values,'' said Clinton's national security adviser Samuel
``Sandy'' Berger. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Some of the best moments of the summit, in the view of the
Clinton administration, were atmospheric _ how things were handled
more than the substance of what was agreed or even said.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who specialized in
totalitarian regimes as an academic, was struck by Jiang's demeanor
in the news conference with Clinton that was broadcast live
throughout China.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it had some dynamics of a debate and a real
engagement instead of ... one person says his piece and the other
one says his piece,'' Albright said Sunday. ``I thought in that
regard it was quite remarkable.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Berger, for all his exuberance after the Clinton-Jiang joint
appearance, also conceded some limits to warming Washington-Beijing
ties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not forming an alliance with China,'' Berger said. His
statement came in the context of how other Asian allies of the
United States _ including some Washington has sworn to protect with
nuclear weapons if necessary _ should view the chummier
Sino-American relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know that an improving relationship with China is not
directed against any of them, but that stability in China and
bringing China into the global and regional regime is to their
advantage,'' Berger said. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; So in the United States and Far East, the Clinton
administration must still convince doubters of the correctness and
viability of the White House approach.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told President Jiang Zemin, as their talks opened
Saturday: ``I know that I speak for the vast majority of the
American people when I say that this effort to improve and
strengthen our relationship is welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be true in the sense that it's better than a dangerous
deterioration of relations, but recent polling in the United
States, of which the White House is keenly aware, shows a great
deal of ambivalence, and some animosity, toward China.
</P>
<P>
   When asked in early June about Clinton's handling of relations
with China, a sample for ABC News found 40 percent approve and 39
percent disapprove. On the respondents' impression of China, 34
percent said it was favorable and 52 percent said it was
unfavorable.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-six percent said China was not a threat to the U.S.
national security, 38 percent said it was.
</P>
<P>
   Another survey pointed to a specific wariness on the part of the
American people. A sampling for the Stimson Center, an arms control
group, found that China was the nation seen as posing the greatest
nuclear threat to the United States, ranking only behind terrorist
groups.
</P>
<P>
   That view is one reason the administration pressed so hard for
the symbolic detargeting agreement reached Saturday, in which the
United States and China said they would not point intercontinental
nuclear missiles at each other.
</P>
<P>
   Several experienced China observers, including former U.S.
Ambassador James Lilley, said the best way to judge the success of
the Clinton-Jiang meetings would be what they accomplished on the
India-Pakistan nuclear standoff.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of specific joint actions that Washington and Beijing
are prepared to take in light of the troubling South Asian
developments is not likely to be taken as a good sign. Although
China's participation in the global debate after the nuclear tests
this spring is a step forward, Beijing is still a bit standoffish.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is that China believes she gains by being there (in
the debate) but is the one least willing to be drawn into group
initiatives'' said Bruce Larkin, a political scientist at the
University of California at Santa Cruz.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is aware of the sometimes halting progress that will be
part of any dealings with China.
</P>
<P>
   In his toast to Sino-American relations at the state dinner
Saturday, Clinton called for a commitment from both sides ``to keep
moving forward, turning small steps into giant strides for our
people, our nations and the world.
</P>
<P>
   And he couldn't resist an old Chinese proverb: ``Be not afraid
of going slowly, be only afraid of standing still.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
