<SLUG> BC-SOC-FRANCE-PARAGUAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH DEFENDER BEATS STUBBORN PARAGUAYAN DEFENSE
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LENS, France _ Jose Luis Chilavert, the Paraguayan goalkeeper,
was face down on the grass with his gloves over his eyes: not a
customary position for a loud, proud leader of men. But the
game-winning shot that the French defender Laurent Blanc had just
driven past him in the 113th minute was enough to deprive even the
big and agile Chilavert of his sense of balance.
</P>
<P>
   For 90 minutes of regulation time and nearly two periods of
overtime in their second-round World Cup match Sunday, Chilavert
and his Paraguayan teammates had managed to impose their
revisionist brand of soccer on the more talented, aggressive and
frustrated French.
</P>
<P>
   The Paraguayans had stalled. They had spread out cleverly in
their own half, counterattacked selectively and dared the French to
do their worst in the absence of Zinedine Zidane, their suspended
playmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Zidane would be sorely missed by his teammates on this bright,
windy afternoon as they struggled to find rhythm and each other in
front of the Paraguayan goal. As the minutes and squandered French
opportunities ticked by, it began to look likely that this long,
often ugly match would come down to penalty kicks _ precisely what
Paraguay and its excellent goalkeeper were craving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we would have had a very good chance if we could have
gotten to that stage,'' said Paraguay's coach, Paulo Cesar
Carpeggiani.
</P>
<P>
   But the French, despite all their ineffectual offensive play,
still had other plans. Robert Pires dribbled down the right wing,
as he had done frequently since replacing Thierry Henry in the 64th
minute because of Henry's sprained ankle. This time, Pires managed
to get past two tiring defenders and cross the ball into the
penalty area. David Trezeguet leaped and headed it toward the
streaking Blanc, who had charged forward from his customary
position in central defense and who scored the only goal of the
match with a single swipe of his right foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a fox on the field,'' said Blanc's fellow defender,
Marcel Desailly. ``He told me, `I'm going up,' and it all turned
out fine.''
</P>
<P>
   In previous World Cups, there would have been seven more minutes
to play, but this is the first year of the ``golden goal'' or, as
Americans prefer to call it, sudden death. While the French team
rushed to engulf Blanc, the Paraguayan players slumped to the turf
as if they had been hit by some sort of fast-acting chemical
weapon.
</P>
<P>
   They had delighted their small nation and surprised soccer
aficionados by qualifying for the second round at the expense of
Spain, but they would not reach the quarterfinals. The team that
will face Italy on Friday in St.-Denis will be, as expected,
France, and Zidane will be back in the lineup after his two-game
suspension for a red card. The injured Henry, France's leading
scorer in this World Cup, may be missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, Zidane might have been the happiest of us all,'' the
French coach, Aime Jacquet, said after he had finished kissing
Blanc on the cheek and hugging every other player he could get to.
``The goal rewarded the better team. Often in matches like this,
there is injustice at the end, but we got through because of our
great defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense is also Paraguay's strength, and its leader is
Chilavert, the only real star on an overachieving team. Sunday, he
strutted onto the field and, as usual, placed his good-luck charm _
a medallion honoring the Madonna of Lourdes _ on the grass inside
his goal.
</P>
<P>
   But the player who would decide the game was Blanc, a reserved
man who chooses extroverted friends, such as Eric Cantona, the
charismatic star who never got to play in a World Cup because of
France's spectacular failure in the qualifying rounds in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   When Bulgaria's Emil Kostadinov scored to knock Cantona and the
French out of the 1994 World Cup, it was Blanc who had the last
shot at stopping him.
</P>
<P>
   He announced his retirement from the national team after that
experience, but Jacquet persuaded him to return, and Blanc can now
say that he has repaid his debt to French soccer. ``What a
moment,'' Blanc said. ``I promised myself I'd score in the World
Cup, and I kept my promise.''
</P>
<P>
   The match was Blanc's 72nd for France, which equals the total of
Michel Platini, who was watching next to Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin. Both Platini and the prime minister leaped to their feet
after Blanc's dramatic goal, and before long, Chilavert regained
his feet, too. One by one, he approached his fallen teammates and
lifted the smaller men off the ground. The Madonna of Lourdes had
not brought him good fortune this time.
</P>
<P>
   But then, isn't Lourdes in France?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
