A0910 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-TOURIST-HNS &LR;      06-28 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TOURIST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA-TOURIST 
  
PRESIDENT AND FAMILY DO THE TOURIST THING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds: HAS OPTIONAL TRIM) 
 
By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ As symbols go, nothing beats China's Great Wall, the
3,000-mile fortress against outsiders. But, a better symbol of the
new China may be the relentless T-shirt vendors capitalizing on the
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, following in the footsteps of three other
U.S. chief executives, trekked up the steps of the stone fortress
as he and his family turned into tourists on Sunday, viewing a
section of the Great Wall and the Forbidden City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe this wall now is a symbol that China shows to the
rest of the world; not a wall to keep people out. It sort of
unifies the country for over 7,000 kilometers,'' Clinton told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Nixon made the first presidential visit to the tourist
attraction in 1972 and proclaimed it, indeed, a great wall. But at
least he wasn't hassled by aggressive venders hawking ``I Climbed
the Great Wall'' T-shirts, calendars, key chains and other
souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   At the base of the fortress at Mutianyu, more than a dozen
vendors are lined up in stalls _ all selling the same items with
the shouting frenzy of a bazaar. A popular seller: the green caps
with a red star that were required attire during the era of Mao
Tse-tung.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, accompanied by first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and
daughter Chelsea, drove the 40 miles from Beijing to Mutianyu where
the wall snakes through the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even more magnificent than I had imagined it to be,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   The first family and their entourage took a cable car up the
steep mountainside to avoid having to climb to the top on a steamy
China day. The president made the standard pose for photographs
with the wall zigzagging in the background.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Mike McCurry took a look at the 1,000
steps up the steepest portion of the wall and remarked: ``Wouldn't
want to roller-blade it.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the Clintons visited the Forbidden City where Chinese
authorities, despite promises to the contrary, closed the palace
compound to the 10,000 tourists who visit each day.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The president began his tour at the Imperial Palace, the ornate
backdrop to the movie The Last Emperor and viewed emperor's chamber
where China's ancient rulers sat on a gold throne below a glass
ball that legend said was one of the heavenly forces keeping the
emperor in power.
</P>
<P>
   The Forbidden City is the place where the rulers during the Ming
and Qing dynasties lived. The massive compound in the heart of
Beijing has 9,999 buildings. Construction started in 1406. Emperors
lived there for 491 years, until 1925.
</P>
<P>
   But the Great Wall is even more ancient, construction having
started in the 3rd century. And, because of Nixon's historic visit,
is probably the most visible symbol of China for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Other presidents visited Badaling, which became so crowded with
tourists that China developed the Mutianyu site. At Badaling,
vendors have actually set up shop on top of the wall as well as at
the base.
</P>
<P>
   The ride on the cable car at Badaling costs 55 yuan, the
equivalent of $7. To walk on the wall once you get off the cable
car costs another 25 yuan.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's a small price to see the results of the labor of
more than 1 million people, many of them political prisoners,
ordered to work on the structure by the emperor Qin Shihuang 2000
years ago. Qin was the first leader to unify the many kingdoms and
ruled with an iron hand.
</P>
<P>
   It was his burial site that Clinton visited in Xi'an, his first
stop in China. Qin also ordered craftsmen to build the terra-cotta
army of 6,000 soldiers that were buried near him to protect his
afterlife.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
