<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIMBLEDON AWAITS A WILLIAMS-VS.-WILLIAMS SISTER MATCH
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ There is so much about Wimbledon, starting
with rules, regulations and rain, that just bugs the Williams
sisters. Venus, 17, who knows that everybody around here knows
exactly who she is, gets annoyed when the security guards insist on
checking her plastic pass with their electronic scanners, recording
her every entrance and exit, all of them applauded by fans eager to
get a close look at the biggest _ but possibly not the best _ of
the beaded ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only scan once a day,'' was her unsolicited advice to the
keepers of the peace at the All England Club. ``I'm not into all
that scanning.''
</P>
<P>
   And 16-year-old Serena, who has not yet exhibited a trace of
ingenue awe in her first appearance at the staid Grand Slam event
that was around a hundred years before she was, was indignant when
she discovered that Center Court and every other court were
off-limits for practice on this middle Sunday, when Wimbledon
traditionally goes as dark as the theater district.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just found out that you can't even practice here,'' Serena
said. ``That really went right over my head. I would say that's
being traditional.''
</P>
<P>
   Serena, like her sister, has dropped just nine games through two
rounds, and the two appear headed for a much-anticipated collision
in the Round of 16. The last time Wimbledon played host to a
sisterly spat was 1966, when Australia's Gail Sherriff defeated her
sister, Carol. In the only other confrontation between a pair of
sisters, Maud Watson, the younger of Britain's Watson girls,
defeated Lilian in the 1884 final.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far in their fledgling professional careers, the Williams
sisters have stuck to the tradition put into practice often in the
last decade by the trio of tennis-playing Maleeva sisters, ceding
the victory to the older sibling. When they met in the second round
of this year's Australian Open, where Serena was making her Grand
Slam debut and Venus was seeking to reprise her surprise sprint to
the 1997 U.S. Open final, Venus pocketed the victory, just as she
did last month at the Italian Open and again when the two, along
with their partners, squared off in the mixed-doubles final at the
French Open.
</P>
<P>
   But Serena Williams has been basking in the attention she has
received since the splash debut she enjoyed on grass two weeks ago
at Eastbourne, where she reached the quarterfinals. Her performance
there had such experts as Steffi Graf, the seven-time Wimbledon
champion, and Monica Seles, the winner of nine Grand Slam events,
commenting that her grass court game may be superior to her
sister's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a little bit that Serena has a better chance here than
Venus,'' said the sixth-seeded Seles, one of the five top-ranked
victims who helped Serena zoom from No. 453 in the ranking last
October to her current career high of No. 20. That it took Serena
Williams just 16 professional matches to tally five upsets against
players from the top 10 broke the record set by Seles, who needed
33 matches to accomplish it in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Seles also said it was too bad that one sister would have to
cancel out the other in the fourth round. But before that can
happen, the seventh-seeded Venus must get past Chanda Rubin in the
third round and Serena must win her first meeting with 47th-ranked
Virginia Ruano Pascual of Spain.
</P>
<P>
   According to Venus Williams, whose own Wimbledon debut was a
``terrible'' opening-round exit last year, the Williams-Williams
clash is a virtual lock. She was a little less definite on whether
she could keep her undefeated streak against her sister, who
clearly shows no signs of being intimidated by her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has all the muscles,'' Venus Williams said. ``Serena's
definitely a juggernaut, and the only way to handle it is to become
a bigger one yourself. I guess you have to become the nemesis.''
</P>
<P>
   But Venus Williams is already playing from a position of power.
She set a record when she fired a serve of 125 mph in her
second-round match, breaking the mark of 123 mph set here last year
by Brenda Schultz-McCarthy. Williams said she has added nine mph to
her serve in the last year, and her record-breaker here put her
just nine mph behind Greg Rusedski's tournament-leading serve of
134 mph. Only six men have served faster at Wimbledon than
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeepers,'' Serena Williams said when informed of her sister's
new record. ``She's much bigger than I am, she's taller, and she
might have more power. I really don't know if I can catch up with
that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Serena has made it clear that, with Venus already the proud
possessor of two 1998 Grand Slam championships _ mixed-doubles
titles she won at the Australian and French opens with her partner,
Justin Gimelstob _ this might be the time and place for her to
start playing catch-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's already won a slam before I have,'' Serena said. ``She
has two, but we really don't talk about it. Maybe I can catch up.''
</P>
<P>
   But the rivalry is limited to the court. Serena thinks her
sister would be perfect if she were about four inches shorter than
her height of nearly 6 feet 2 inches. And Venus Williams has no
complaints about Serena, who always takes care not to mimic the
color configuration of her beaded hair.
</P>
<P>
   As advocates, and as adversaries, the two figure to have a
lengthy future, and their future at Wimbledon has only just begun.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-98 2041EDT &QL; 
