u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-SPENDING-NYT     06-28 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SPENDING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOOD OF COOPERATION IN WASHINGTON MASKS DEEP DIVISIONS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Miss., Ga.)   (Washington column) 
(ko) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress has left town for its Fourth of July
recess, seemingly content that the annual negotiations over how to
spend the taxpayers' money will resolve themselves to everyone's
benefit in this election year.
</P>
<P>
   But battles loom over a number of issues, some of them old, like
home heating assistance for the poor, and some new, like how to
conduct the census in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   There are only 35 legislative days before Congress adjourns on
Oct. 9, and even less time before the next fiscal year begins on
Oct. 1. By then, the 13 different spending bills must be signed
into law to keep the U.S. government running.
</P>
<P>
   Views vary as to how it will all come out. The Clinton
administration likes to portray the Republicans in the House as
extremists, ready to throw the government into chaos at a moment's
notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The placid surface conceals a very, very turbulent time
ahead,'' said one negotiator on the Democratic side. ``We're not
headed toward an easy exit.''
</P>
<P>
   But many others involved with the spending bills on Capitol Hill
say there is little appetite for chaos in an election year. Even
the conservatives, who one said are ``ready to pick a few more
fights,'' seem reluctant to shut down the government, as they did
to disastrous political effect in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sherwood Boehlert, a moderate Republican from Utica, N.Y.,
said, ``The wingers _ the right wing, the left wing _ are getting
most of the attention, but the moderates are shaping public
policy.'' Still, he said, to try to draw conclusions now about the
course of the spending bills is as pointless as guessing the ending
of a baseball game after two innings.
</P>
<P>
   House and Senate committees are still working separately on the
bills and have not begun to negotiate their vast differences. They
have to do that before presenting their final proposals to the
President, who has his own set of priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the early skirmishing has a familiar ring.
</P>
<P>
   As they have since they came to power in 1995, the Republicans,
whose strength derives from the South and West, have proposed
lopping off programs that benefit urban dwellers in the Northeast.
This includes financing for Amtrak, which is again on the hit list.
</P>
<P>
   They have proposed cutting heating aid for the poor, summer jobs
for disadvantaged youth, and several environmental and education
programs dear to President Clinton's heart. They would also knock
out AmeriCorps, the national service program, and the Legal
Services Corp., which provides lawyers for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   But this year offers some new twists.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest change is that both Congress and the
administration are living under a virtual freeze on new spending
because of last year's balanced-budget agreement. The spending
limits are the guiding principle _ not the projected budget surplus
and strong economy, which, along with talk of tax cts, give the
false impression that Washington has lots of extra money on its
hands.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, the budget agreement barely allows for inflation.
And tax cuts can come only from entitlements, not from the
discretionary spending that is the subject of the 13 appropriations
bills. So spending _ a favorite election-year activity _ is limited
this year, prompting members to be especially creative.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have shown that, despite their complaints about past
Democratic pork-barrel spending, they are just as eager to direct
money to hometown projects.
</P>
<P>
   The spending bills include billions of dollars spread across
most districts and states for local projects like refurbishing
courthouses, controlling floods and beach erosion, providing
construction work for the Army Corps of Engineers, keeping open
military bases that the administration wants to shut and financing
22 projects, like better dining halls, at various military
installations. Most are in the home states of members of the House
and Senate appropriations committees.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans have also included big-ticket items for
high-ranking individual members, including money for a helicopter
carrier to be built by Litton Industries in a shipyard in
Pascagoula, Miss., the hometown of Sen. Trent Lott, the Republican
leader, and millions of dollars for cargo planes to be built by
Lockheed Martin Corp. in Marietta, Ga., the hometown of Speaker
Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans have earmarked new money for basic medical
research, granting the National Institutes of Health a whopping
increase of 9 percent over its current budget. They would provide
more money to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, more
for anti-drug programs to counter their failure to pass
anti-tobacco legislation, would expand Federal mortgages for
low-income home-buyers and raise the size of Pell grants for
low-income college students.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have not complained about these priorities as much as
they have complained about the Republican cuts. Most notably, they
have highlighted the conservatives' recurring attempt to block
money for the National Endowment for the Arts. But Republican
moderates in the House have joined with Democrats to keep the money
in, signaling that the moderates _ 40 to 60 members of the House,
depending on the issue _ could have a strong say in the final
spending proposals.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most contentious issues shaping up is not a spending
matter at all but one of the many policy rulings that are often
tucked into the spending bills. This is the question of the census.
Republicans want an exact head count. Democrats want to use
statistical sampling, which would make up for people who are hard
to find, like blacks in the inner city, Hispanic migrant workers
and the homeless. This matters hugely to both parties because the
census determines Congressional boundaries for the next decade of
elections and determines how much Federal aid each region receives.
</P>
<P>
   It is too early to tell how these conflicts will be resolved.
That depends largely on the political dynamics as the November
elections approach.
</P>
<P>
   But some central questions are clear:
</P>
<P>
   How deeply split will the Republican Party be? Will the
conservatives and the moderates be prepared to compromise with each
other and the administration and leave Washington on an up note as
they head home to campaign?
</P>
<P>
   Or, with analysts predicting that the strong economy has lulled
most voters into complacency, will Republican leaders risk a more
confrontational strategy to inspire conservative voters, who are
perceived as paying attention and likely to go to the polls?
</P>
<P>
   Finally, how much sway does President Clinton have on Capitol
Hill? How readily will he meld his views with those of the
Republican majority? And perhaps most important, which issues will
he be willing to fight for?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
