<DOCNO> NYT19980628.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-28 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0920 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     06-28 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILUTINOVIC WILL BE BACK, AND SPEAKING ANOTHER LANGUAGE
</HEADLINE>
   (See related stories: SOC-NIGERIA-DENMARK, SOC-FRANCE-PARAGUAY,
SOC-NETHERLANDS) 
(ja) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST.-DENIS, France _ Perhaps today he is browsing in a bookstore
in Paris, poking through the dictionaries. He picks up a Japanese
dictionary. ``I'm a soccer coach,'' he said Sunday night. ``I don't
know what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Bora Milutinovic will be back. Oh, yes, he will be back in the
year 2002, hoping to be the first soccer coach to handle five
separate teams in the World Cup, and not only that, but to guide
all five into the second round. His career has twirled and curled,
risen and dipped like a cannonball free kick.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, the Nigerian team he had coached for all of six
months went down to defeat by Denmark, 4-1. The Nigerians had
captivated the World Cup in the first round by playing open,
opportunistic soccer, but that will take you only so far.
</P>
<P>
   It had taken him weeks to persuade most of the European-based
professionals to even listen to him. He was as much of an itinerant
as they were. This was not like the United States, where he coached
for four years and caught the Balboas and the Harkeses at their
peaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the U.S., the team was like my boys,'' Bora said last week,
as direct as he ever allows himself to be. ``Here, it's different.
I feel like more of a professional. It's a different sentiment but
still big satisfaction. I am very proud for these players and for
the people of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always seem to end up with a good team,'' he added. ``I
always feel lucky. I'm just that way: a good soccer coach and a
lucky man.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, his luck ran out. The Danes are something of a joy
themselves, on the field and in the stands. Their jolly legions of
fans dress themselves in red and white and call themselves
``Roligans,'' a goofy reference to the vile hooligans of other
nations. The players run precise patterns like wide receivers in
American football. Afterward, the only thing left was the Bora news
conference, always a delight. The folks in the World Cup provided
an English-speaking moderator (the Danes do it mostly in English
anyway) and a French translator, but that is never enough for Bora.
He is the latter-day version of Charles Dillon ``Casey'' Stengel,
the manager of the Yankees and Mets, who swerved conversational
corners in his own unique language known as Stengelese. Bora does
it with smidgens of languages borrowed from all his ports of call.
This time he refrained from a little Hausa, a little Ibo, a little
Yoruba. So many languages. So little time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mi equipo'' _ my team _ the Serb who lives in Mexico said,
starting in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody asked whether the Nigerians had limitations that the
Danes had exploited.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excuse me, are you ask me?'' Bora replied.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody asked him how he would compare Peter Schmeichel, the
towering goalkeeper for Denmark, who spends his regular seasons
with Manchester United, to Peter Rufai, the Nigerian keeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to make comperations,'' Bora said, in vintage
Stengelese. ``He don't have so much luck, but this is the life.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody in the interview room knew that Bora and Carlos
Alberto Parreira, who was sacked after two losses by Saudi Arabia,
have both coached four teams in the World Cup. In 1986 with Mexico,
Bora lost a quarterfinal shootout to Germany. In 1990, he
unexpectedly brought Costa Rica to the second round. In 1994, he
guided the United States to a 1-0 loss to Brazil in the round of
16. And now he lost in the second round with Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   Was Bora getting frustrated with not progressing?
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you something,'' he said. ``In this world there are 2
million people'' _ presumably he meant something higher _ ``and I
am soccer coach, and four times I go for it, so I don't feel, how
you say, frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he went over it again in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Some reporters badgered him about his plans. It was well known
that Bora had signed on only through the World Cup, for a $100,000
bonus and a monthly salary of $35,000, untaxed, and a bonus of a
reported $50,000 for reaching the second round, but now his
contract is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am soccer coach, I go with family,'' Bora said.
</P>
<P>
   Would he accompany the team back to Lagos?
</P>
<P>
   ``I stay at World Cup,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Did this mean he was saying goodbye to the Nigerian team?
</P>
<P>
   ``My English not good but I never say goodbye,'' Bora said.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody asked why Nigeria had deteriorated from the 3-2 victory
over Spain in its first game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect your opinion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bora, who returned for another stint as Mexican coach last year,
was asked whether he would root for Mexico against Germany Monday.
He replied: ``In this World Cup, I had four teams _ Nigeria and the
U.S. and Mexico and Yugoslavia. Now Mexico plays an excellent team.
I sent my best wishes to the Mexican people.''
</P>
<P>
   Somebody tried to pin Bora down one more time about his plans
for coaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am soccer coach,'' he said. ``I don't know I will do in the
morning. Really. I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody asked Bora about the opening that is sure to come with
the American team when Steve Sampson is dropped in the next month.
The United States could do far worse than go back to Bora, but he
is going for the record _ five teams, five Cups. A Berlitz course
today in Hindi. A saturation course tomorrow in Korean. Maybe a
little Russian. You never know.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-98 2050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
