<HEADER>
A0926 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT     06-28 0418
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Repeating for all needing)  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, June 29, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call 212-556-4204.) 
(ja) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The injection of very warm, humid air into the Ohio Valley and
southern Great Lakes will lead to the development of at least two
clusters of strong thunderstorms early Monday. One complex of
storms will race southeast from southern Ohio toward the Smoky
Mountains. Damaging winds and flash flooding are especially likely
with these storms. A second area of thunderstorms will form near
Lake Ontario and move rapidly across western and central New
England. Sections of Vermont will be particularly vulnerable to
flooding.
</P>
<P>
   The leading edge of sultry air will stretch from low pressure in
southern Ontario to near New York City. Showers and thunderstorms
will attend a warm front as it moves into the Northeast. Onshore
winds in New England will temper the vigorous storms. High level
winds from the northwest will direct clouds and showers into the
Middle Atlantic region and Carolinas, but most of the rain will
dissipate before reaching the Southeast Coast. Record heat is
expected from South Carolina to northern Florida.
</P>
<P>
   A broken line of potent thunderstorms will sprout from western
Missouri to eastern Kentucky Monday afternoon as a cold front
approaches. Isolated tornadoes are possible. Moisture associated
with a weakening tropical wave will spread heavy showers inland
across Texas. Thick clouds will keep temperatures near seasonal
levels. Extreme heat will persist in the southwest Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the West will stay sunny with continued warming inland.
A few showers will mark a new cold front at the border states.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Seat of Heat
</P>
<P>
   The center of the nation's hottest weather was located in the
southwest high Plains on Saturday. The morning minimum temperature
at Pueblo, Colo., at an elevation of nearly 4,700 feet was 70
degrees, the highest minimum reading ever recorded. Under blazing
sunshine, the mercury rose to 108 degrees at Amarillo, Texas, about
300 miles to the southeast of Pueblo, tying the all-time maximum in
that city. A dome of high pressure and associated very hot air has
slowly migrated westward last week from the Southeast states to the
Plains. The seat of heat will stay in this region much of this
week. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-98 2101EDT &QL; 
