<HEADLINE>
VP MCKINNEY THINKS CHANGE WILL BE GOOD FOR SONICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ When he's in Seattle and not racking up sky miles
faster than a jet pilot, Billy McKinney sits in his office,
plotting.
</P>
<P>
   For McKinney, the future of the Sonics is always at stake, so
plot and travel and evaluate he must.
</P>
<P>
   ``People sit next to me at a game and ask me if I'm associated
with the Sonics,'' McKinney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them I'm the vice president of basketball operations,
and they say, `Yeah, right. You never clap. You never get upset.'
But my job is to evaluate what we do every night. If I get
emotional, you don't make the best decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal of an NBA coach is to win now, McKinney said. But the
vision of an NBA front office is to win now with a critical eye on
how to sustain winning, too.
</P>
<P>
   That is why, for the past four years _ up until this last NBA
draft day when the Sonics, based on McKinney's exhaustive
evaluations, took Vladimir Stepania, Rashard Lewis and Jelani McCoy
_ McKinney must have felt a certain pang of heartache.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, McKinney has flown upwards of 150,000 miles. He has
embarked on harrowing Checkpoint Charlie car rides across war-tense
borders. He has watched more NCAA and European league basketball
games than Dick Vitale and Billy Packer combined _ all in search of
the perfect future NBA star.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, despite all this effort and necessary work, McKinney
understood that as long as George Karl was the Sonics' coach, all
that traveling and work was basically for nothing, because rookies
and mistake-prone young players never got a chance to learn and
grow in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``George could have gotten us there (to a championship.) He did
a great job,'' McKinney said. ``But the thing that's changed (with
Karl's departure) is that there's an open-mindedness to the talent
being brought in here. You take these young guys and add them to
the players available in free agency, that's a pretty potent mix.''
</P>
<P>
   McKinney has a certain affinity for underdogs, mind you. A
sixth-round draft pick out of Northwestern in 1978, McKinney earned
his place in the NBA with coach Cotton Fitzsimmons' Kansas City
Kings when he beat out first-round draft pick Mike Evans to become
an 18.7 minute-per-game backup point guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because he's young doesn't mean he can't play,'' McKinney
said. ``If Cotton Fitzsimmons had taken that philosophy, I
guarantee you I wouldn't be here today.''
</P>
<P>
   The lack of open-mindedness is, in part, one of the reasons Karl
is gone. Karl's system, his regular-season win record, his quirks,
his dominating, paranoid and creative personality were shown the
door by Sonics' president Wally Walker.
</P>
<P>
   If Karl was condemned by Walker for his gargantuan personality
and his leaky media relations, then the burden is squarely left to
Walker and McKinney to demonstrate that their experience, their
style and their vision can be the successful force behind
concocting a contending team.
</P>
<P>
   That is why beneath the rancor and wonder about what Karl's
departure will mean, there is a certain sense of relief and renewal
inside Sonics headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's the fun before the fall, if the Sonics fail to win
with Karl's regularity. For now, though, there's a sense that
improvement is as much possible as collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``For four years, Wally has done some great things he doesn't
get credit for. People talk about Shawn (Kemp) leaving, but we were
a better team without him,'' McKinney said, suggesting perhaps that
Karl's departure might not lead to the same result.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like in Detroit, where Chuck Daly was coach for nine
years and (GM) Jack McCloskey was there for 12 years. There was a
resistance to change. I knew we had to get younger, so with Dennis
Rodman, there was a chance to trade an asset. If you don't trade
Rodman, you never get Grant Hill. Defining moments for any
franchise are tough.''
</P>
<P>
   McKinney has 19 years of NBA playing and management experience.
At Minnesota, he was brought in to start the expansion
Timberwolves. Next, in Detroit, he was hired to rebuild the aging,
former champion Pistons.
</P>
<P>
   So McKinney understands certain things about trying to put a
winning team on the floor. He also understands first-hand the
inherent tension that can cause a breakdown or a breakup between
coach and management.
</P>
<P>
   Karl never put much faith or respect in the way Walker and
McKinney did their end of the business, so surely it will be with a
certain amount of relief and pride that Walker and McKinney have
enlisted new coach Paul Westphal to help carry out their plan.
</P>
<P>
   Time, though, is not exactly on their side. In fact, with the
NBA lockout coming Wednesday, the league will likely be shut down
all summer and into fall. McKinney understands as well as anyone
the implications of this labor war, since anything that impedes the
Sonics' chances to put a championship contender on the floor next
season while also not ransoming the franchise's future, could spell
disaster for the men, other than Karl, left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for McKinney, he's been through the NBA grist mill
before. He understands the degree of difficulty in the task at
hand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
