<SLUG> BC-GLF-CADILLAC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DICKSON WINS CADILLAC IN SUDDEN-DEATH PLAYOFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLIFTON, N.J. _ It had been 25 years since Bob Dickson won a
professional golf tournament. And because he missed a 50-foot putt
Sunday, he finally captured another one.
</P>
<P>
   Dickson was 29 in 1973 when he won the Andy Williams-San Diego
Open on the PGA Tour. Sunday he still showed a youthful exuberance
as he won the Cadillac NFL Golf Classic, a Senior PGA Tour event.
He won it on the first hole of a sudden-death playoff with a
20-foot birdie putt, beating Jim Colbert and Larry Nelson, who
missed shorter shots.
</P>
<P>
   To snag the $165,000 first prize, Dickson survived a mental
lapse by him and his caddie on No. 17 that brought them face to
face with the unforgiving rules of golf. Dickson was making a late
charge in a tight field at the time.
</P>
<P>
   On the par-3, 215-yard hole, he left himself with a 50-foot putt
after his drive. The hole was in the shadows and so far away that
Dickson did not realize that his substitute caddie had not removed
the pin. If a putt hits the flagstick, it is a two-stroke penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I left the putt five feet short,'' he said after winning. ``If
I had knocked it in, I wouldn't be sitting here now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we fell asleep at the switch at the same time,'' he
added, taking the onus off his caddie, Brian Deasy. ``I honestly
did not see the flag. That's a first for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Deasy, an experienced caddie, also said it was a first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got caught up in the moment,'' Deasy said. ``Even
though Bob was being kind to me, I fell asleep.''
</P>
<P>
   So where was Dickson's regular caddie, Mark Bolick?
</P>
<P>
   He was helping his parents celebrate their 50th wedding
anniversary in Hickory, N.C., and took the weekend off.
</P>
<P>
   Colbert said he looked at the pin and could not believe Dickson
was hitting the putt. He said he wanted to rush over and remove the
pin as the ball was rolling.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I saw the putt was going to be short and I left it
alone,'' Colbert said. ``It was a good thing I did, too, because
one of the officials told me that if I touched the stick while
someone was hitting, I would have been subject to a two-stroke
penalty myself.''
</P>
<P>
   To force a three-way playoff, Nelson birdied the 590-yard, par-5
18th hole, while Dickson and Colbert made par. It gave each of them
a three-day total of 9-under 207 on the par-72 course at the Upper
Montclair Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   They played No. 18 again in the playoff, and Nelson reached the
green in three, leaving only a six-foot putt. Dickson, meanwhile,
had hit his third shot to about 20 feet from the pin. Colbert was
about 12 feet out, on the fringe of the green.
</P>
<P>
   After holing out for his rare victory, Dickson recalled that in
1973, someone asked him what winning a tournament felt like.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said it was like wild, animal joy,'' he said. ``It's
fabulous. And to be honest, I didn't think it would happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   After Dickson's pro tour career ended, he worked in golf
marketing. The game had too many highs and too many lows, he said,
and he decided to forget about trying to make a living at it.
</P>
<P>
   Then, four years ago, he decided to try it again.
</P>
<P>
   And had he thought about giving it up once more?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he said. ``As late as last week.''
</P>
<P>
   CHIP SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   _ Arnold Palmer shot a 1-under-par 71 for the second straight
day to finish at 217. ``I was going so poorly, and I'm not going to
continue that,'' he said. ``Yesterday and today were very
encouraging, and these rounds will keep me going.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Mike McCullough, who had a 1-stroke lead going into the final
day, soared to a 77. He predicted that he would have trouble with
the course, which favors right-to-left hitters. He was in constant
trouble in the right rough. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
