r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     06-28 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX BECOMING LAUGHINGSTOCK OF BASEBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last thing the guys who run Fox, and the Dodgers, need is
some sportswriter telling them what to do. They sort of made that
clear when they fired the general manager, one-time sportswriter
Fred Claire.
</P>
<P>
   But everyone can appreciate a little advise, a glimpse into what
people are thinking about them. We're all human, and therefore a
little bit insecure, like the guy who asks his doctor for Viagra,
you know, just in case.
</P>
<P>
   So here's a snippet, fellas. Take it graciously.
</P>
<P>
   Some people are laughing at you.
</P>
<P>
   Many fans are angry at you.
</P>
<P>
   And those who aren't chuckling or mad are prepared to blow you
off.
</P>
<P>
   All this is the result of what you have done to the Dodgers
since taking over the operation of the team this spring. At that
time, your first official act was to assure everyone, from fellow
owners who OK'd the sale to the little guy sitting in the pavilion,
that you would handle the team and its image as if it were a
Faberge Egg.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, you've scrambled everything. If one didn't know better,
one would think Ally McBeal is making these scatter-brained
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The people laughing at you are your intimates, the
Steinbrenners, Turners and Disneyites. They're the fellas who
provided you with some of your motivation and desire to buy a
baseball team and trump them at their own game.
</P>
<P>
   They really didn't want to see you get your hands on the
Dodgers. They've seen how successful you've become in creating a
fourth TV network and gobbling up regional cable sports. They
feared the potential positive impact an aggressive Fox might have
on the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they're laughing at the way you've screwed up the best
thing going in baseball. They can barely contain their glee over
your flop sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Peter O'Malley only was losing money because he was a
cash-and-carry guy. He didn't like debt. And whatever O'Malley's
losses were could be traced to baseball's ignorance, not his own.
Steinbrenner and Jerry Reinsdorf were costing him money.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers basically have been a cash cow for years. In the
last 20 years, since 1978, the Dodgers topped 3 million in home
attendance 12 times. In five other years, they topped 2.5 million.
The only years they didn't hit either figure were the strike years
of 1981 and 1994, and 1992, when the team lost 99 games.
</P>
<P>
   Now why would you do anything to confuse or anger that kind of
fan support? People talk about the Dodgers' on-field malaise since
1988, the last World Series win, but one could actually say they've
had just one good year since 1982. Your friends in New York would
be the first to add, too, that the 1981 World Series win was
strike-tainted.
</P>
<P>
   Disney would kill a rat for this kind of loyalty. Even with a
renovated stadium and team in a pennant race, the Angels have had
only three sellouts this season. The Yankees still have cachet in
baseball, but the reality is that George Steinbrenner's team can't
draw like it once did. Four of the last seven years, the Yanks,
world champs in 1996, couldn't crack 2 million in home attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Your losses are their guffaws.
</P>
<P>
   The people who are angry at you are among the loyal 3 million.
They have been attending Dodgers games for 20-to-40 years in part
because they liked the team's image. It meant something to be a
Dodger fan, something beyond the team's place in the National
League standings.
</P>
<P>
   Call it nobility, call it loyalty, call it naive. Whatever it
was, it worked for the Dodgers up until now. Fans were loyal to the
Dodgers because they weren't the Yankees. The
once-a-Dodger-always-a-Dodger philosophy has always carried weight
in baseball, even among those who consider it arrogant.
</P>
<P>
   Now, that philosophy has has been trashed. Steve Garvey may have
left the Dodgers as a free agent, but he'll always be a Dodger. Can
we say that now about Mike Piazza? Can we ever look Gary Sheffield
in the eye and not see Piazza?
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers needed to make some changes on the field, but I
doubt if most fans thought the changes should start with Piazza and
Hideo Nomo and include Bobby Bonilla and Greg McMichael as
replacements.
</P>
<P>
   It may be dandy to have the characters in ``Melrose Place''
screwing each other, too, but watching the Dodgers do it watching
Tommy Lasorda become GM at the expense of career Dodgers like
Claire and Bill Russell leaves one bleeding Dodger blue.
</P>
<P>
   (I guess we now know why Lasorda didn't question Fox's
upper-level decision to trade Piazza to Florida. He obviously
wanted to stay on your good side in hopes of getting the job he
wanted. The saddest part of Lasorda's rise is the way he's turned
on people he said he loved.)
</P>
<P>
   Even if half of the 3 million felt Claire and Russell weren't
cutting it, they would have voted for a respectful transition.
</P>
<P>
   Dodger Stadium has been a cathedral and 3 million came to mass
every year. In light of this 180 degree turn of events, many fans
may start humming R.E.M.'s ``Losing My Religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Which leads us to those who will blow you off.
</P>
<P>
   This is another area where Los Angeles is different. It is
loyal, but not blind. It has seen its share of carpetbagger owners
and worse, and it responds accordingly in the way which hits home
quickest: It ignores you.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit A would be the Los Angeles Rams. Exhibit B would be the
Los Angeles Raiders. They both left to sounds of silence. Few
hearts were broken.
</P>
<P>
   Dodger fans do not want to hear a player they love complain
about his contract. They do not want to see favorites shuffled to
other cities. They do not want management to exercise its privilege
with heavy hands. They do not want to see bloody knives of internal
chaos. They do not want the image that they have adored for 40
years cracked in a day.
</P>
<P>
   If it's enough to know people are talking about you, then Fox
should be happy. My advice would be to listen to what is being
said, too, lest you wake up one day and find out that no one cares.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-98 2117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
