<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-28 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0945 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-RUSSIAN-ENTREPRENE     06-28 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RUSSIAN-ENTREPRENEUR-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN ENTREPRENEUR THRIVES, DESPITE RUMORS OF SHADY PARTNERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of Felix Komarov is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 By RALPH BLUMENTHAL  
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Felix Komarov isn't actually everywhere doing
everything. It can just seem that way.
</P>
<P>
   In barely six years in the United States, Komarov, a portly
Russian whirlwind who favors black leisure ensembles by his friend
Bijan, has built a multimillion-dollar art and jewelry business out
of a Fifth Avenue gallery and three workshops that render the
designs of some of Russia's top artists.
</P>
<P>
   He has become a patron of culture and charitable causes, founded
a weekly Russian-language newspaper in New York and started a
Rolls-Royce dealership in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   And just this month, he opened a lavish three-story Russian
cabaret-restaurant on Manhattan's East Side. Earlier this year, he
celebrated his 50th birthday with a party for 500 in the cabaret's
unfinished space. The guests included Russian entrepreneurs and
aristocrats and the country's pre-eminent living poet, Yevgeny
Yevtushenko.
</P>
<P>
   One thing he cannot seem to do, however, is lay to rest
questions that have publicly dogged him since FBI court papers
linked him to a man federal prosecutors called the Russian
godfather in the United States, Vyacheslav Kirillovich Ivankov, and
to other Russian organized-crime figures.
</P>
<P>
   With patient if wary good humor, Komarov says he has met and
talked to Ivankov and others named by the FBI, but he dismisses the
encounters as inconsequential and innocent.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI office in New York said it would have no comment on
Komarov, who holds a green card and has never been charged with a
crime in the United States. Police authorities in Russia said they
had no information to share on Komarov.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews in his Russian World Gallery and his Club Moscow,
Komarov sought to dispel the air of mystery that even friends say
clings to his entrepreneurial ventures. All the while, however, he
managed to invite only more questions about his associations and
his wealth, which he says grew out of import-export trading as the
Soviet Union was collapsing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not someone divine or supernatural,'' he said in Russian
through a bilingual American associate. ``I'm a real person. Of
course, I have my shortcomings, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends of Komarov praise his generosity but say they know
little of his financial affairs. ``Behind the mirror is a mirror,''
recited Zoya Boguslavskaya, the Russian writer and critic, who flew
to New York in January for Komarov's birthday party.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Komarov shuttles between his gallery and his
nightclub, furnished with folk artifacts, czarist antiques and
hundreds of horseshoes that Komarov collected and personally nailed
to the walls for good luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very, very real Russia,'' he said in English as a spirited
troupe of costumed musicians and dancers entertained one recent
night. ``This no show. This culture!''
</P>
<P>
   His only partner in the enterprise, he said, was Simon
Millerman, who owns a minority share and who came to Komarov after
managing tennis clubs in Brooklyn and working at a McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   Komarov's Fifth Avenue gallery, which opened in January 1997,
displays jewelry, ominous balloon-head paintings by Oleg Tselkov
and whimsical silver carnival figures by Mihail Chemiakin, another
leading Russian sculptor who also designed the gallery's series of
palm-size carnival figurines in precious metals, gems and lapis
lazuli, costing up to $53,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   Komarov also produces the Golden Elf statuette, designed by
Neizvestny and presented to winners of Russia's leading cultural
prize, the Triumph Awards. He put the gallery's gross sales in a
year and a half at about $5.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   It's been quite a journey, by his account, from proletarian
origins. His father served the military as a professor and his
mother was a doctor. He said he quit a government engineering job
when he found that associates were reporting on him to the
ministry. He said he then worked in construction, dealt on the side
in fruits and vegetables, worked for theatrical producers and built
up a clothing import business.
</P>
<P>
   After two visits to scout business opportunities in New York and
Los Angeles in 1990, he said, he came for good in 1992, leaving his
wife and their grown son, Roman, in Moscow. With a nest egg of
$300,000 and a $150,000 advance payment against future clothing
shipments to trading partners in Russia, he said, he bought a
$400,000 co-op apartment on Manhattan's East Side. He spent up to
$800,000 decorating it, he has said, and later bought a $450,000
apartment in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, he joined with Peter G. Terian, the owner of Rally
Motors, a BMW, Mercedes-Benz and Rolls-Royce dealership on Long
Island, to open a Rolls-Royce salesroom in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   In an affidavit in support of a wiretap application in the
Ivankov investigation in 1995, Lester R. McNulty, an FBI agent in a
squad formed to combat Russian organized crime, quoted German law
enforcement officials and unnamed informants as stating that
Komarov was laundering money for Ivankov and that Ivankov and two
criminal associates owned three-quarters of the Moscow Rolls-Royce
dealership as a front to launder criminal proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   Ivankov was convicted in 1996 of trying to extort $3.5 million
from two Russian emigre businessmen and faking a marriage to enter
the country, and was sentenced to nine years and seven months in
prison. Komarov was not charged or called as a witness.
</P>
<P>
   Terian said in a telephone interview that he had first met
Komarov as a customer. They agreed to become partners in Moscow,
Terian said, along with a former Rally Motors salesman who no
longer plays a role in the business. He said that Komarov's son,
Roman, ran the dealership but that heavy import taxes had hurt
sales, raising the cost of a Rolls-Royce in Moscow to about
$400,000.
</P>
<P>
   Terian said he had never heard of the FBI affidavit, which
quoted informants alleging that Ivankov and two other Russian
organized crime figures each held 25 percent interests in the
Rolls-Royce dealership and that that it was ``merely a front'' used
by Ivankov ``to launder proceeds from illegal activities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``None of it comes here,'' Terian said when told about the
affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   Terian said that he did not know Ivankov or the two others but
that if the allegations were true, ``I would have to disengage
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Komarov dismissed the allegations as baseless, saying Terian was
his only partner.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The allegations in the affidavit were disclosed last September
in an article in The Washington Times as Komarov was about to serve
as host of a gala party and concert at Carnegie Hall celebrating
Moscow's 850th birthday. ``I was really very upset,'' Komarov said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he first met Ivankov at a crowded banquet several years
before Ivankov's arrest in June 1995. He said they had met since
and that Ivankov called him several times from prison, ``but we
never had any one-on-one and we never had any joint business.''
</P>
<P>
   As for FBI allegations that he had Ivankov's phone number and
called him in February 1994, Komarov said, ``It's quite possible.''
Besides, he said, ``I had no reason not to call him.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what they had talked about that day, Komarov said, ``I
have no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivankov's lawyer, Barry I. Slotnick, said his client would have
nothing to say about Komarov.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At other times, Komarov joked about the matter, describing some
of his gallery's carnival figurines as ``Mafia production,'' and
grumbling: ``Hmf, Mafia! If they work like I do 24 hours a day, it
would be a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he applied in his own name for the club liquor license
to show that he had nothing to hide. He got the license. He denied
one FBI agent's account that he had employed a bodyguard in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me?'' he said, ridiculing the story.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1997, through contacts with American friends, he said,
Komarov attended President Clinton's second inauguration in
Washington. Could he have gone, he asked, if any cloud hung over
his name?
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Komarov said, he has been scouting the city for
promising sites for a Russian cultural center and library he wants
to establish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really get a rush from life. I love life,'' he said. ``I do
what others dream about but perhaps can't.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
