<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-28 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0952 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-COACH-MACKEY-1     06-28 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-COACH-MACKEY-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER SHARP RISE AND SHARPER FALL, A COACH LOOKS FOR A BREAK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By IRA BERKOW    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   That terrible night, that terrible period, can never be wiped
away, or excused, or ignored. Kevin Mackey understands this.
</P>
<P>
   Mackey was once called the king of Cleveland and a civic
treasure, rising to prominence when his underdog Cleveland State
basketball team upset Bob Knight's powerful, methodical Indiana
Hoosiers in the first round of the 1986 NCAA tournament. A few
years later, Mackey's wondrous world collapsed in a welter of
alcohol and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   He has been trying to put it back together ever since, in places
like Argentina, South Korea, Portland, Maine, and Atlantic City,
N.J., where he is now coach of the minor league Seagulls. The team
had the second-best record in the U.S. Basketball League this
season and was playing in the semifinals Sunday night in Asbury
Park, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Mackey, 52, hopes to return to big-time college basketball one
day, or to get a shot in the NBA as an assistant coach or a scout.
So far, all doors have been closed to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy for the opportunity to be in the USBL,'' he said
recently, ``but it's like being in the witness protection program.
No one knows if you're still alive, and no one cares.''
</P>
<P>
   When he has sat down with a prospective employer, one who is
considering using his proven skills as a basketball coach _ as was
the case last winter with Ken Gross, the owner of the Seagulls _
Mackey has brought up his past immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a mistake,'' he tells the person across the desk. ``It
was nobody's fault but my own. I've been paying for it. I'm clean
now. The problem and the answer is in the mirror.''
</P>
<P>
   Mackey, a ``squatty guy,'' by his definition, with a shock of
gray at the front of his short, dark hair, possesses the gift of
glibness, and he speaks directly about the past that has caused him
so much anguish for the last eight years.
</P>
<P>
   On an early July evening in 1990, the police stopped a blue
Lincoln Continental weaving down a street in a squalid area of
Cleveland's east side. The driver was Kevin Mackey, then 43, the
respected local college coach, married, the father of three
children, who lived in a large brick house in a leafy section of
town. Mackey was coming from a crack cocaine house, where he had
spent the previous five hours.
</P>
<P>
   Five days earlier, Mackey had signed a two-year contract with
Cleveland State worth $300,000. ``It was all blue skies and green
lights,'' he recalled. There had been recruiting violations under
Mackey, but that was a thing of the past.
</P>
<P>
   But then, five days after the arrest, he was fired.
</P>
<P>
   Mackey had begun drinking as a 16-year-old in Somerville, Mass.,
a suburb of Boston. It escalated, and he went from that to drugs to
his crash in 1990. ``It was a descent into hell,'' he said. Despite
making a good salary, he regularly asked friends for money. When
they expressed bafflement, he made excuses about unexpected
recruiting expenses.
</P>
<P>
   When his dark double life was finally discovered, it seemed a
relief. After pleading no contest to charges of cocaine abuse and
driving under the influence of alcohol, Mackey was ordered to spend
60 days in a drug and alcohol rehabilitation center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' he said, ``I can try to get my life back in order.''
</P>
<P>
   He is doing it the way he knows best. By coaching.
</P>
<P>
   Even after his arrest, Mackey never really left the profession.
Shortly after his firing, John Lucas, a former NBA player and then
the coach of the San Antonio Spurs, called Mackey. Lucas is a
recovering drug alcohol addict who had a rehabilitation center in
Houston and reached out to sports figures. He invited Mackey to
spend time with him. Mackey was in rehab there and in another
center, and, he says, it changed his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only did I confront my addiction there,'' he said, ``but
John Lucas was instrumental in getting me back into coaching.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas helped get Mackey an assistant's job with Atlanta of the
USBL just a season after he had been dismissed at Cleveland State.
One month later, the Miami Tropics hired Mackey to be their head
coach, and he went on to win a division championship with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of anyone who has a better eye for talent than
Kevin Mackey,'' Lucas said. ``As a coach, he's demanding, a
disciplinarian. I have a lot of respect for him. When I went to
Philadelphia to coach the 76ers, I considered Kevin as one of my
assistants. But with me and one or two other guys who had had drug
and alcohol problems, the timing just wasn't right, and I was
advised by management not to go ahead with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mackey began moving around the globe in pursuit of work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the low point was in Argentina, where the bus went for
two days from one town whose name I couldn't pronounce to the
next,'' he said. ``We'd sleep on the bus, and some of the players
were difficult. They'd say: `I don't have to play defense. I'm a
national star. Get someone else to do it. I shoot.' But then you'd
get a win, and everything is good again. That never changes
wherever you are in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Mackey went to the Continental Basketball League and coached the
Albany Patroons to a second-place finish. He was coach of the year
with the Fayetteville, N.C., team of the Global Basketball
Association. Last season he coached Atlantic City to the USBL
championship and was named coach of the year. Last fall he was a
consultant for a team in Seoul, South Korea. This fall he will
coach a team in Ohio in the International Basketball Association.
</P>
<P>
   For now, his attention is on the Atlantic City job, for which he
is paid $25,000 to coach the Seagulls in the eight-week summer
league.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic City defeated Atlanta, 118-107, on Saturday to advance
to last night's semifinal game against Jacksonville. The
championship game is Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like playing for him,'' said Paul ``Snoop'' Graham of the
Seagulls, a guard who formerly played for the Atlanta Hawks. ``He
knows how to relate to players, which is the most important thing
in the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   Mackey said: ``We root for each other. Every player has had
someone in their family, or a friend, or themselves, with an
addiction problem. These guys don't come from the moon. We
understand each other.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-98 2134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
