<DOCNO> NYT19980628.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-28 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0953 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-COACH-MACKEY-2DTA     06-28 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-COACH-MACKEY-2DTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: each other.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the court, Mackey is intense, directing his players with
shouts and then grabbing the ubiquitous Diet Coke on the scorer's
table and draining it like a parched man in a desert.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in front of his bench, Mackey shouts at his players,
who are trotting back on defense: ``Get back! Get back!'' When the
team gets a defensive rebound, he shouts: ``Hurry it up! Hurry it
up!'' His aggressiveness for both defense and offense is a
trademark of his style that goes back to when he began his coaching
career.
</P>
<P>
   He won state championships with Don Bosco High School in Boston.
He was an assistant coach and a marvel of a recruiter for six years
with Boston College, bringing in players like Michael Adams and
John Bagley, whom few others thought could make the big time.
</P>
<P>
   He did the same at Cleveland State, a school that had a string
of losing seasons before he arrived in 1983, but which he built
into a nationally ranked team that averaged 20 victories for seven
seasons, got as far as the NCAA tournament's Round of 16 and twice
played in the National Invitation Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Mackey worked hard recruiting players whom no one else wanted.
``I'd scour the playgrounds, the AAU games, wherever there were
players, looking for guys who had either gone to the wrong school,
had the wrong coach, or went to the wrong summer basketball camps.
I've got a place in my heart for guys caught with the end of the
stick.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those players, Ken ``Mouse'' McFadden, a 5-foot-10-inch
guard from New York City, had dropped out of high school but got a
general equivalency diploma and became one of Mackey's best players
at Cleveland State. He starred in the 83-79 victory over Indiana,
which Mackey said ``put Cleveland State and me on the map.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Mackey is trying to find his place on the map again. He is
separated from his wife, but after reconciliation is in contact
with his three grown children. And he is still coaching winning
teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done a great job for us,'' said Gross, the Seagulls
owner. ``He's great with the players, the fans and the press. And
no one works harder at his job.''
</P>
<P>
   Gross said he had ``made some calls for Kevin, trying to get him
hooked up. So far, no luck.''
</P>
<P>
   John Nash, general manager of the Nets, has attended some of the
Seagulls' homes games, played in the 2,500-seat Atlantic City High
School sports complex, and observed Mackey as coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ken Gross recommended Mackey to me,'' Nash said. ``But John
Calipari is the coach, and he hires his assistants, and he knows
Kevin. And his staff was set. I do think Kevin is qualified to be
an NBA assistant coach or scout. No question about it. He's coached
successfully on the pro level, and he's coached successfully on the
college level. And he has to be a good evaluator of talent to put
together those teams. We just don't have any openings.''
</P>
<P>
   Mackey, sitting recently at breakfast in the coffee shop of the
hotel he is living at in Atlantic City, was asked whether he
thought he was being blackballed. ``If it happens, it would be more
on the college level than the pros,'' he said. ``The pros want to
win, and a lot of them have had addiction problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's a buddy network up there, and people hire their
friends. Like a big fraternity. It happens that I've had a lot of
friends _ so-called friends _ not return my phone calls. But I
still have hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'd be willing to be tested. Please, test me every day.
I'd waive any rights to prove I'm clean.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did wrong, and I expected to pay for it. And I have. But
it's been eight-plus years. How long must that punishment go on?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
