r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN     06-28 0451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHBURN MAINTAINS CONFIDENCE LEVEL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Angels manager Terry Collins marvels at the
confidence of 23-year-old pitcher Jarrod Washburn. But Washburn,
who improved to 4-0 with seven strong innings Sunday against the
Padres, said it hasn't always been that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through a very tough first half of the season at
(Double-A) Midland last year,'' Washburn said. ``I was getting hit
all over the place. My confidence went down a lot and my ERA was
around seven. After games, I'd be all (ticked) off. About halfway
through the season, I said, `Screw it. I can't worry about it
anymore.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since then I've kept the same confidence level. If I have
a bad game, I forget about it and get ready for the next one. My
confidence level right now is the same as it would be if I was
0-4.''
</P>
<P>
   Routine but fancy: Second baseman Justin Baughman and first
baseman Cecil Fielder teamed up to make a play Sunday against the
Padres that certainly will be shown on the highlight shows for a
while. But it didn't have to be such a tough play.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres' Tony Gwynn hit a chopper toward second that Baughman
charged. He tried to short-hop it, but he dropped it. Baughman then
flipped the ball off the ground with his glove to Fielder, who
caught it with his bare hand for the final out of the seventh
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Gwynn) doesn't run well, but I tried to hurry,'' Baughman
said. ``If I just played it on a hop, I would have been OK. But
Cecil make a great bare-handed catch.''
</P>
<P>
   Swings for Salmon: After taking today off, the Angels will begin
a six-game homestand against the Giants and A's. One of the best
things about being at home, Collins says, is the fact that the
Angels get to use the designated hitter Tim Salmon.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon had a cortisone shot in his sore left foot last Monday
and appeared in only one of the five games at Dodger Stadium and
Qualcomm Stadium, drawing a walk in Sunday's game in his only plate
appearance. But he will hit in his usual cleanup spot again Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody can say or write whatever they want about the DH, but
that's our game,'' Collins said. ``Is it fun to manage with the
pitcher in the lineup? You bet. But I can't wait to have Tim Salmon
back in the lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   Versatile Olivares: When Salmon walked in his appearance Sunday,
Collins had pitcher Omar Olivares pinch run. Olivares went to third
on a double by Darin Erstad and scored on a single by Craig
Shipley.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can do a lot of things,'' Collins said of Olivares. ``He
can hit, he can run. He's been playing a long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
