<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS ROOKIES LEAD THE WAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Justin Baughman and Jarrod Washburn are rookies with
the Angels, which means they are meant to be seen and not heard.
</P>
<P>
   But given the opportunity to express themselves on the field,
they are making plenty of noise.
</P>
<P>
   Baughman and Washburn, both of whom started the season in the
minors, teamed up to lead the Angels to an 11-3 victory over the
San Diego Padres on Sunday afternoon before 41,574 at Qualcomm
Stadium, avoiding a series sweep.
</P>
<P>
   For the Angels, the win was No.21 in the month of June, the most
they've had in any month in the history of the franchise. Their
48-32 record matches the Angels teams in 1970, '89 and '95 as the
best after 80 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels increased their AL West lead over Texas to 2{ games,
while San Diego's lead over San Francisco was reduced to 5{ games
in the NL West.
</P>
<P>
   Both Baughman and Washburn have played well since becoming major
leaguers, but Sunday the Angels needed it most. After playing big
games against the Rangers, Mariners and Dodgers recently, the
Angels were flat in losing the first two games of the series to the
Padres. But the rookies gave the team a jump start.
</P>
<P>
   Baughman went 4 for 5 with two RBI and a run scored to pace the
Angels' 14-hit attack, while Washburn improved to 4-0 after giving
up two runs and eight hits in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels also got home runs from Cecil Fielder (No.14) and
Garret Anderson (No. 9).
</P>
<P>
   Washburn, who did not walk a batter, has made six starts with
the Angels since being called up June 2 to replace the injured Jack
McDowell, and the Angels have won all six games.
</P>
<P>
   Baughman, called up May 16 to replace the injured Randy Velarde,
raised his average to .274 with his first career four-hit game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justin Baughman last year was in (Single-A) Lake Elsinore, and
Jarrod Washburn was in Double-A (Midland),'' Angels manager Terry
Collins said. ``You look at all the people we have up here that are
home grown. It's a tribute to what our scouts and
player-development people have done.''
</P>
<P>
   Baughman and Washburn have lockers next to each other in the
Edison Field clubhouse, so they are able to lean on each other when
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rookies aren't always allowed to talk,'' Washburn said, ``so
we talk to each other. It's great.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard sometimes,'' Baughman said. ``Sometimes you have to
watch what you say or watch what you do off the field. He's been a
help to me and I've been a help to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Washburn got some help from pitching coach Marcel Lachemann
between starts, which helped correct a flaw in his delivery and
resulted in Washburn giving up no walks on Sunday. But his best
attribute is the way he handles the spotlight, according to
Collins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing, his presence on the mound,'' Collins said.
``He's got great composure. He knows what he has to do and he never
gets away from that. You never see him, when he gets in trouble,
overthrow the ball or try to throw such a nasty curveball it
bounces in the dirt.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had spent time during the weekend complaining about
the National League strike zone, and finally third baseman Dave
Hollins had seen enough. After being called out on strikes on a
ball that was low and inside in the third inning, Hollins argued
with plate umpire Mark Wegner long enough to get ejected.
</P>
<P>
   But the strike zone was not a factor the rest of the way for the
Angels. The Angels led 1-0 in the third when Padres starter Joey
Hamilton (5-9) hurt his own cause by making two errors in the
inning. It led to two unearned runs and a 3-0 Angels lead.
</P>
<P>
   Fielder's second homer of the series made it 5-0 in the seventh,
and Baughman's RBI double later in the inning put the Angels up
6-0.
</P>
<P>
   Washburn allowed a two-run double to Andy Sheets in the bottom
of the seventh, but the Angels put the game away with five runs in
the eighth, three coming in on Anderson's homer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; !end! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
