<SLUG> BC-NY-TOURIST-SHOT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN SHOOTING AT ANOTHER HITS TOURIST
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)   (ja) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A tourist from Florida was shot in the leg in midtown
Manhattan Sunday morning by an apparently deranged man who was
firing at someone else _ a homeless man who had asked him to quiet
down, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting occurred shortly before 10 a.m. as the tourist,
Pamela Turk, 41, a mother of two from Boca Raton, was walking on
the Avenue of the Americas near 56th Street en route to a museum,
the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The man suspected in the shooting, John Palmer, 58, of
Manhattan, was walking down the street muttering to himself and
yelling when he was confronted by the homeless man, who was not
identified by the police. A police investigator who spoke on the
condition of anonymity said that the homeless man asked Palmer,
``What are you mumbling about?''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer cursed at the man, told him to shut up, then pulled out a
.380 caliber revolver and fired five shots, the police said. None
hit the homeless man, but one hit Mrs. Turk. Not immediately
realizing that she had been struck, she ran for cover into a deli
on the corner, said her husband, Jonathan Turk, in a telephone
interview from Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Turk had just left her hotel, the St. Moritz on Central
Park South, said her husband, who was preparing to fly to New York
Sunday afternoon. ``She was walking around with a friend when they
heard a couple of pops,'' he said. ``They went inside to a store or
restaurant and then they saw she was shot.''
</P>
<P>
   J.H. Park, who works at the deli, Chambord Royale, said he heard
the shots and saw Mrs. Turk stumble into the store with her friend,
weeping and holding the back of her leg. As he gave Mrs. Turk some
napkins to stanch the bleeding, he said, the police came. Mrs. Turk
was taken to Bellevue Hospital, where she was in stable condition
Sunday. ``It was so fast,'' Park said. ``It all happened in two
minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer was then chased down by two police officers from the
Midtown North precinct who were on routine patrol: Officers John
Powers, a 15-year veteran, and Dennis Lane, who has been on the
force for six years.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer was carrying a .380 semiautomatic pistol and had 26
rounds of ammunition crammed in his pockets when he was arrested,
the police said. Palmer told detectives that he had carried the gun
for two years, ``just in case'' someone annoyed him, the
investigator said.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer, who rents a room on the Upper West Side, has an arrest
record dating back to 1963, said Officer Leslie Cardona, a Police
Department spokeswoman. Palmer was being held on charges of
attempted murder, assault, reckless endangerment and weapons
possession.
</P>
<P>
   Turk said that he had no harsh words for New York City. ``These
are things that happen throughout the whole country,'' he said.
``There are just too many handguns out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who has often credited the city's
falling crime rate with drawing record numbers of tourists, visited
Mrs. Turk in Bellevue Hospital Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said that Palmer appeared to have psychological
problems. ``He was walking along the street at about 10 in the
morning making a lot of noise, yelling and screaming,'' the mayor
said.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer was arrested in 1963, 1964, 1972 and 1977 on charges
ranging from burglary and attempted grand larceny to harassment,
the police said. Neighbors at Palmer's rooming house at 139 E. 78th
St., where he rented a room on the top floor for $235 a month, said
they were stunned by the shooting. Abraham Szmidt described Palmer
as a loner who kept to himself. ``I never heard him bother
anyone,'' he said. ``A gun? Never.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-98 2200EDT &QL; 
