<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-28 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0970 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-GAY-PARADE-NYT &LR;      06-28 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GAY-PARADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATEMENTS AT GAY PARADE RANGE FROM PASSIONATE TO PASSIVE
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By WINNIE HU   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jani Carlson didn't wear an eye-popping costume or
wave a rainbow-hued flag to show her gay pride. She came with her
lesbian partner, and didn't even reach for her hand.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Carlson marched Sunday alongside hundreds of thousands
of people _ some in flamboyant costumes, some in ordinary street
clothes _ during the city's annual gay pride parade down Fifth
Avenue from 52nd Street to Greenwich Village.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here because we want to make a statement,'' said Ms.
Carlson, an engineer from Brooklyn. ``We're lesbians and that's OK.
We're just like anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gay and Lesbian Pride March captivated spectators with
startling costumes, booming music and showy dancing, as it has done
for the past 28 years. Nearly 100 lesbian and gay motorcyclists
roared down the avenue. Transvestites clattered behind in clingy
evening gowns and stiletto heels.
</P>
<P>
   But the parade also brought out a quieter spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Carlson pointedly ignored the transvestites and turned to
her partner. ``That's not us, is it?''
</P>
<P>
   The parade, which was organized by Heritage of Pride, capped off
a series of events across the country in recognition of Gay Pride
Week. Afterward, countless revelers danced at a street festival in
the West Village and at Pier 54 near 13th Street.
</P>
<P>
   In a tense moment, 17 men and three women confronted Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani around 12:45 p.m. as he marched with gay
Republican supporters in front of the New York Public Library at
41st Street.
</P>
<P>
   The activists, who were chained together, wore white T-shirts
that read, ``Rudy Get Out of Our Parade.''
</P>
<P>
   They yelled and laid down across the avenue, forcing Giuliani to
stop for 10 seconds and then go around them by walking onto the
sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   After Giuliani passed by and rejoined the parade, police
officers dragged the activists into a van. They were charged with
disorderly conduct and resisting arrest, and later released, the
police said.
</P>
<P>
   Joneil Adriano, who helped organize the protest, said his group,
Take Back the March, wanted to point out what he called Giuliani's
lack of action on violence against gay people and mandatory AIDS
education in schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're upset that after attacking our community the entire
year, he feels he can just waltz in and march with us,'' Adriano
said.
</P>
<P>
   Other politicians joining the parade were the city comptroller,
Alan Hevesi; Mark Green, the city's public advocate and a candidate
for U.S. Senate, and Lt. Gov. Betsy McCaughey Ross, who is seeking
the Democratic nomination for governor.
</P>
<P>
   The parade's grand marshals were Councilman Philip Reed, who
represents parts of Manhattan and the Bronx, and Councilwoman
Margarita Lopez, who represents the Lower East Side. Both are gay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time when people believe you can only be elected in a gay
district is over,'' Ms. Lopez said. ``It's irrelevant if you're gay
or lesbian or transsexual. The question is: Which candidate goes
down to City Hall and fights for truth and justice?''
</P>
<P>
   For many marchers, homosexuality was neither a political nor a
social issue but was a deeply personal side of their lives that _
for one day _ they revealed to friends and strangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't come out dressed like this every day, but it's part of
my life,'' said Simone McKay, a RuPaul look-alike in a short black
sequined dress.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Ewall, a businesswoman from Long Island, rode a big purple
Honda as a member of the Sirens Motorcycle Club.
</P>
<P>
   She hasn't missed a parade since 1992, she said, and she didn't
plan to miss this one, even though she broke up with her partner
the day before.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a hesitation when someone asks you whether
you're seeing someone,'' said Ms. Ewall, who wore rainbow-colored
socks and displayed gay pride flags on her handlebars. ``It depends
on how well you know them whether you're going to say something or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Tanner, a Catholic who lives in Brooklyn, twirled a
rainbow-colored umbrella as he marched with Dignity New York Inc.,
a group of lesbian and gay Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   He said he planned to attend a religious service after the
parade. ``We're showing that you can be gay and Catholic,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Lavender Light Gospel Choir showed off their
spirituality in loud, gutsy tones. Karen Gamble, a member of the
choir, said the gay and lesbian singers have performed in the
parade for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This allows people to know God loves us, whether we're gay or
not,'' she said. ``We still worship Him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
