<HEADER>
A1000 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-UNIVERSITY-BO     06-28 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-UNIVERSITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEIJING UNIVERSITY STUDENTS MUCH DIFFERENT FROM 1989 CLASS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The choice of Beijing University as the site of
President Clinton's address Monday on the future of democracy and
progress in China carries a symbolism that goes beyond symmetry
with Chinese President Jiang Zemin's speech at Harvard last year.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing University _ referred to as ``the Harvard of China'' _
was the birthplace of nearly every revolutionary and liberal
movement in China this century. From the May 4 movement of 1919 to
the June 4 movement of 1989, students at ``Beida,'' as the
university is called for short, have led the uprisings that
dramatically and irrevocably shaped modern China.
</P>
<P>
   Some advocates of democracy in China wish that current-day Beida
students would take up that leadership again, pushing for further
reforms and openness. But the Beida to which Clinton preached
Monday is a campus greatly becalmed since the heady, and ultimately
tragic, days of the student-led demonstrations that ended in the
1989 Tiananmen Square massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Monday's Beida students are more concerned about their
grades and their economic future than they are about pressing
leaders for change. Many have been convinced by the government that
June 4 leaders were misguided, and that cooperation with
authorities, rather than the spirited dissidence that is Beida's
legacy, is the best way to promote reform.
</P>
<P>
   Nine years since their predecessors were treated by the world as
martyrs and by Chinese authorities as criminals, many Beida
students espouse pragmatic and individualistic values, like other
Chinese youth. Thanks to economic progress and a message drummed
home by the government that prosperity is impossible without
stability, these young people have turned their attention to
getting rich. Political change, they say, will come in time and the
government knows best how to achieve it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since June 4, students here don't care as much about politics.
We try to study and be more practical,'' said Liu Hai, 27, a law
student at Beida. ``June 4 was a failure for the students and it
didn't help the country. Economic development is the most important
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   A third-year math student, who spoke on the condition that her
name not be used, said she and her friends ``live in a different
generation, a different society'' than their activist predecessors.
``These days, university students care more about how to improve
ourselves, our potential, our abilities. We care more about
building ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether she considered that a betrayal of Beida's history
of political activism, she retorted, ``That's what society is like
now. That's the atmosphere we're in.''
</P>
<P>
   On the grassy campus that is home to multi-colored traditional
Chinese architecture as well as modernist concrete blocks, Beida
students said Sunday they were looking forward to Clinton's visit,
though few would be able to hear his remarks. A limited number of
tickets were distributed by teachers, and students interviewed knew
of no plans to broadcast the speech.
</P>
<P>
   Students were interested in Clinton's suggestions on how to
modernize China, but they said they would not take his Western
values as gospel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beijing University students are famous for being open to new
ideas, and we want to learn from Clinton,'' said Li Donghua, 20, a
computer science student. ``We will adopt some of those ideas, not
all.''
</P>
<P>
   New ideas have been a hallmark of Beida's history. Founded 100
years ago last month, the university was the scene of protests in
1919 against the government's signing of a treaty that gave Chinese
territory to Japan after World War I. That patriotic fury expanded
into a movement to modernize China through science and democracy _
referred to as ``Mr. S and Mr. D'' _ and spawned an outpouring of
literature that set the tone for intellectual thought.
</P>
<P>
   Beida was also the breeding ground for some unpleasant chapters
of history, starting with the anti-rightist struggle of 1957. The
school also was the site of the first ``big character'' poster that
set off the Cultural Revolution, a devastating 10-year crackdown on
intellectuals and liberals. At least 60 Beida professors were
persecuted and died during that struggle.
</P>
<P>
   But by 1979, Beida students had changed their tune, and figured
prominently in the ``Democracy Wall'' protests. A decade later,
students outraged at government corruption launched hunger strikes
in Tiananmen Square that galvanized millions nationwide. In the
aftermath of the massacre, Beida's president was fired, political
debate on campus was suppressed, and students reportedly were
forced to participate in military drills and political
indoctrination meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Beida since has been restored to the government's good graces,
as evidenced by the glowing official media coverage during the
school's 100th anniversary and President Jiang's praise-filled
centenary campus address. But suspicions of this onetime
revolutionary hotbed remain. Campus security guards stopped a
reporter Sunday, saying journalists were not permitted on campus.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Leo Ou-Fan Lee, a professor of Chinese culture at
Harvard and a specialist on the May 4 movement, lectured at Beida,
and his admonition that ``Beida's tradition is to keep a critical
distance'' from any regime caused a stir.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Beida of Monday has lost most of that tradition,'' Lee
said sadly. ``As far as I could see, the younger the students were,
the more patriotic they are, whereas the Beida I knew was very
critical ... They criticized the government in the name of the
national good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' Lee said, ``nationalism means you have to agree with
the government _ that's a tremendous difference.''Monday
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to Mao Zedong's warning that ``anyone who suppresses
student movements will never have a good ending,'' this government
Mondayappears to have won over youth. Monday's students, Lee said,
``see only the failure of June 4....''
</P>
<P>
   Beida students do see a government they feel is more responsive
and that shares their ideals. The government has invested in
``educating university students about politics so we don't go
wrong,'' said Liu, the law student.
</P>
<P>
   Li, the computer science student, said: ``The government is
playing a good role now. They think we should use science and
technology to help the country, and we students think that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   He and his friends praised Prime Minister Zhu Rongji for
reforming government and saving money by eliminating departments
and officials. ``That really shook the thoughts of people. It made
us realize the government is not just saying things, but actually
doing them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
