<SLUG> BC-CHINA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA-MAIN 
 &HT;     
 CLINTON EMPHASIZES PERSONAL FREEDOM IN SPEECH TO STUDENTS  
 
 
 
BY CRAGG HINES
</HEADLINE>
 MAIN-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   BEIJING _ President Clinton, appealing to China's determination
to sustain its economic boom, today declared freedom ``a powerful
engine of progress'' that could bolster the commercial surge in the
world's most populous nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Economic freedom is an essential element of freedom,'' Clinton
told an audience of students at Peking University. ``But freedom
must mean more than economic opportunity. In America, we believe
that freedom itself is indivisible.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comments came as he made a persistent pitch &UR;  &LR; for
American values in a speech capping his three-day visit to the
Chinese capital and talks with the nation's Communist leaders,
including President Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not seek to impose our vision on others,'' Clinton told
the college audience. ``But we are convinced that certain rights
are universal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that everywhere people aspire to be treated with
dignity, to give voice to their opinions, to choose their leaders,
to associate with whom they wish, to worship how, when and where
they want,'' Clinton said. ``These are not American rights or
European rights or developed world rights. They are the birthrights
of people everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the extraordinary Clinton-Jiang joint news conference on
Saturday, the U.S. leader's speech was carried live on Chinese
state-owned television. Clinton stood before a backdrop of mounted
U.S. and Chinese national flags.
</P>
<P>
   A White House official said Clinton's remarks were intended to
``focus on the things China needs to do to assure its success in
the 21st century,'' one of Clinton's favorite rhetorical
references.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you build a new China, America wants to build a new
relationship with you for a new century,'' Clinton said. ``We want
China to be successful, secure and open _ working with us for a
more peaceful and prosperous future.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted some critics of his China policy who remain to be
convinced of the wisdom of engagement with the authoritarian
regime, but said: ``Everything we know about the way the world is
changing and the challenges your generation will face tell us that
our two nations will be better off working together than apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's emphasis on how personal freedom can enhance economic
achievement was directed at the Chinese leadership as much as the
students.
</P>
<P>
   The Communist leaders have made it clear that they do not share
Clinton's belief that human rights and economic prosperity go hand
in hand.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang, in his appearance with Clinton on Saturday, renewed his
defense of the government crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators
at Tiananmen Square nine years ago in which hundreds of protesters
were killed by the People's Liberation Army, declaring:
</P>
<P>
   ``Had the Chinese government not taken the resolute measures
then, we could not have enjoyed the stability that we are enjoying
today.'' The Chinese leadership equates ``stability'' with economic
progress.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's audience for today's speech almost certainly included
China's future leaders, as the 100-year-old university is the
nation's most prestigious. About 20,000 students attend the school.
</P>
<P>
   Also called Beida, the university has often been a hotbed of
ideological unrest _ of varying kinds. The campus spawned not only
the Red Guards, who led the reactionary movement known as the
Cultural Revolution, but also the pro-democracy movement of 1989
that ended in the bloody Tiananmen crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   In the last nine years, students and Western observers agree,
the main thrust of the student body has been to prepare for life in
a more financially aggressive and prosperous China. One student
said the grassy area known in 1989 as ``Democracy Lawn'' is more
apt these days to be occupied by couples with romantic interests.
</P>
<P>
   There were echoes of the repression nine years ago when the
school celebrated its centenary earlier this year. Invitations for
the ceremonies were strictly limited, bypassing some alumni whom
the government considered trouble-makers, and security forces were
present in force, students said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton praised the ``extraordinary strides'' China has made in
``nurturing'' freedom, ``and spreading freedom from want will be a
source of strength for your people in the 21st century.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The president said he would like to see the current
``productive'' Sino-American relationship ``blossom into a fuller
partnership for the new century.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If that is to happen,'' he said, ``it is important that we
understand each other better _ our common interests and aspirations
and our differences.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said his ``open, direct exchange'' with Jiang in a news
conference Saturday was the kind of session which ``can both
clarify and narrow our differences and, more important, can change
lives for the better.''
</P>
<P>
   In an unprecedented step, Chinese officials allowed the
70-minute session, in which Clinton and Jiang sparred politely but
pointedly about a range of issues including the Tiananmen massacre
and human rights, to be broadcast live on a government-own channel
which reaches all over the vast nation.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright estimated Sunday that the
broadcast was ``probably seen'' by more than half China's 1.2
billion people.
</P>
<P>
   After his speech to the students, Clinton went to a lawn outside
the university's library to present the school's American studies
program with 547 volumes on Western civilization and U.S. history
and life, including ``Total Baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   The books were selected and purchased by the U.S. Information
Agency at a cost of approximately $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   The gift also included the Encyclopedia Britiannica,
Encyclopedia Americana, Great Books of the Western World and 325
other references works, such as African-American Writers,
Hispanic-American Almanac, Encyclopedia of American Prisons and
Vital Statistics of the Presidency: Washington to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
