<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-28 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1005 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-JIANG-BOS &LR;      06-28 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-JIANG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER ROCKY START, TWO LEADERS DEVELOP RAPPORT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ When President Clinton and Chinese leader Jiang Zemin
first met at an economic summit in Seattle nearly five years ago,
Clinton asked a polite question about the Chinese economy, and got
in return a scripted 45-minute lecture on the virtues of communism
and Jiang's accomplishments back home.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufbitelabel &LR; Newsanalysis
</P>
<P>
   Flash ahead to last night, to a graceful government-owned villa
on a picturesque Chinese lake. Clinton, accompanied by his wife,
daughter, and mother-in-law, excitedly recounted his tour of the
Great Wall for Jiang. Later, in a casual conversation about movies,
Jiang recalled watching ``Gone With the Wind'' in Shanghai a few
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   How the relationship between the two presidents has transformed
from rigid to relaxed is a story of heady policy motivations in
Washington and political intricacies in Beijing. As the two leaders
have gained experience and confidence in office, they have tried to
forge a bond that may eventually serve as the foundation for a
transformed diplomatic relationship as well.
</P>
<P>
   At no time has that bond been more apparent than during this
summit, from the extraordinary debate at Saturday's press
conference, where sharp points were sheathed in silken gestures, to
the state dinner later that night, when Clinton and Jiang jokingly
prodded each other to take the conductor's baton and lead the
People's Liberation Army band.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials point to a strategy in friendship. It is a
fact of international diplomacy that personal relationships
influence official ones. A stronger personal bond, officials said,
has allowed Clinton to repeatedly raise the issue of human rights
with Jiang, in venues private and public, without causing the
diplomatic relationship to collapse.
</P>
<P>
   US officials maintain that Chinese leaders insist on respect,
and President Clinton is willing to provide it with the assumption
it will further US policy goals, such as improved human rights and
fairer trading policies. Critics have charged that Clinton is
granting Jiang respect while receiving virtually nothing in return.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials and other analysts said Saturday's press
conference, televised live across China at Jiang's behest, was the
ultimate indication that the bond was beginning to pay dividends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a much easier relationship now,'' said Winston Lord, a
former ambassador to Beijing under President Bush and an assistant
secretary of state under Clinton. ``They can debate the most
sensitive issues in front of a world audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, the two leaders have crossed a cultural
divide _ and a language gap _ to engage in a steady stream of
banter. Their conversations are often casual, officials said, an
observation borne out by the constant sight of Jiang making small
talk with Clinton, waving his arms and laughing out loud.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you see in public is what you get in private,'' said
Michael McCurry, White House spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship on display during this summit represents a
significant amount of work by both sides. Clinton left that dismal
meeting in Seattle infuriated that the Chinese president had
squandered so much of his time and political capital with a
pointless harangue. At the time, Clinton was putting aside his
fiery campaign accusations that Bush had coddled Chinese dictators
in an attempt to develop a bond.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been difficult for Clinton to establish a relationship
with Jiang,'' said Robert Ross, a professor of political science at
Boston College and an associate at the John King Fairbank Center
for East Asian Research at Harvard University. ``Jiang has talking
points just on how to relax.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time the two leaders gathered at Lincoln Center in New
York in October 1995, the rigidity gave way to mere formality,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, their relationship was still clouded by a prickly
give and take among senior aides. The Chinese first insisted that
any meeting take place in Washington, as part of an official
summit, rather than as a sideshow to a UN visit by Jiang. The White
House refused, which, in turn, prompted the Chinese to spurn
Clinton's luncheon invitation. Eventually, they settled on Lincoln
Center as the site of a meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of the long lecture, this was a conversation back and
forth, and you could see Jiang was ad-libbing and departing from
script,'' said Lord, who was present in the first five meetings
between the two. ``There were jokes.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not until October, in Washington, that Clinton and Jiang
made significant strides in forging a bond. On the night Jiang
arrived in the capital, Clinton invited him to the White House for
a personal and impromptu meeting. Over orange juice and snacks,
they discussed human rights. Clinton later gave Jiang a guided tour
of the White House, including the living quarters. When they came
upon Lincoln's handwritten Gettysburg Address, Jiang recited from
memory the first few lines.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, the two clashed on the issue of human rights at a
now-famous news conference. But the bond between them was strong
enough that the relationship proceeded with little apparent
personal animosity, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, in the Great Hall of the People, the two tangled
over human rights, Taiwan, and Tibet. But despite the heady
content, at the end of the news conference, Clinton said that if
the Dalai Lama, the spiritual leader of Tibet, and Jiang met face
to face, ``they would like each other very much.'' With that, both
leaders smiled broadly and left the stage together.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
