<DOCNO> NYT19980628.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-28 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1008 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDS-VACCINE-BOS &LR;      06-28 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-VACCINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIDS VACCINE EFFORT RAISES ETHICAL, POLITICAL AND SOCIAL ISSUES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ With the human immunodeficiency virus infecting someone
in the world every 11 minutes, frustrated proponents of AIDS
vaccine development are pushing for accelerated human trials of
experimental vaccines, despite debate over what an AIDS vaccine
should contain.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we in the West had a 25 percent infection rate among our
adults _ the way Namibia, Botswana, and parts of South Africa do _
we wouldn't be having this debate about testing of experimental
vaccines already proven safe,'' Dr. Max Essex of the Harvard AIDS
Institute said in an interview here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Essex's exasperation with the slow pace of vaccine development
is widely shared among AIDS researchers and specialists attending
the 12th World AIDS Conference, which opened here last evening.
</P>
<P>
   The conference's theme, ``Bridging the Gap,'' might equally
refer to the chasm between rich and poor nations in access to
costly AIDS treatment, or the large gaps in scientists' knowledge
about the essential qualities of an anti-HIV vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two strategies to developing an AIDS vaccine,'' said
Dr. Jaap Goudsmit, a Dutch researcher. ``One is to figure it all
out first and the other is to do human testing to determine a
vaccine's efficacy. There's an abundance of good ideas out there.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 40 experimental AIDS vaccines have been developed so
far, but only last week did the first enter large-scale human
tests. Critics say the US government is too cautious about human
AIDS vaccine experiments, preferring to concentrate on more test
tube research first.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it were just a matter of developing a vaccine for the
United States and Europe, I'd say fine, let's wait and be sure,''
said Margaret Johnston, a leading vaccine specialist. ``But there's
too much urgency.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubaramira Ruranga, a major in the Ugandan Army, added a
personal note of urgency. ``I have lived with HIV myself for 13
years,'' he said. ``I don't fear HIV because I already have it, but
I live in fear for my sons and daughters. How long will we have to
wait for a vaccine?''
</P>
<P>
   Noting recent success in suppressing the AIDS virus with costly
drugs, Ruranga said such measures would do little good in places
like Uganda. ``Drugs have never stopped an epidemic,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston, formerly the federal government's chief AIDS vaccine
adviser, is principal author of a report issued Sunday by the
International AIDS Vaccine Initiative, a group formed two years ago
at the time of the last global AIDS conference in Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   The report, billed as a blueprint for AIDS vaccine development,
is intended to ``put us on a fast track toward the goal,'' said Dr.
Seth Berkly, the group's president. It calls for spending $300
million to $500 million above current levels over the next nine
years.
</P>
<P>
   Berkly announced that the chairman of Microsoft, Bill Gates, and
his wife, Melinda, have pledged $1.5 million to his group's program
to set up vaccine development teams in developing nations.
</P>
<P>
   The US government has increased its commitment to AIDS vaccine
research and is implementing some of the ideas suggested in the
critics' report, said Dr. Anthony S. Fauci, leader of the federal
government's AIDS research efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The quest for an AIDS vaccine, first promised 14 years ago by
the Reagan administraton, has proved far more difficult than anyone
imagined. Many doubt that researchers can meet the 2007 goal for an
effective vaccine set a year ago by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons are complex, involving scientific, ethical,
political, and economic obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having this debate now because AIDS activists aren't
putting on pressure the way they did to get drugs to save their
lives,'' Essex said. ``And companies that make AIDS drugs are
satisfied with the $1 billion a year they will lose if we had an
effective vaccine.''
</P>
<P>
   The AIDS virus ``is a uniquely difficult target for vaccine
development,'' according to Norman L. Letvin of Beth Israel
Deaconess Medical Center, because it has evolved ways to thrive in
the face of vigorous immune-system attack.
</P>
<P>
   Vaccines against most diseases work by stimulating the
production of antibodies. But recent research suggests antibodies
alone will not stop HIV; and perhaps antibodies will not even be
partially protective because the virus wears a sugar coating to
mask the proteins that an antibody could recognize.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, scientists now know that laboratory-grown strains of
HIV stimulate the production of antibodies that are totally
ineffective against ``wild'' strains recovered from infected
patients.
</P>
<P>
   This insight has forced VaxGen, manufacturer of the vaccine that
entered human trials last week, to reformulate its product to
include components of a ``wild'' strain.
</P>
<P>
   But the VaxGen vaccine does not stimulate the immune system
defense, called cellular immunity, that kills cells already
infected with HIV. Thus, many researchers doubt it will protect
people against the virus.
</P>
<P>
   Vaccines that stimulate cellular immunity, or both cellular and
antibody defenses, are in various stages of development. But these
vaccines so far are either complicated to make, elicit only modest
or weak immune responses, or are possibly dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Another knotty problem is that different types of HIV
predominate in North America and Europe, Africa, and Asia. If a
vaccine made against the North American ``B'' subtype were tested
in Africa, it might not work, leading many to conclude that a
vaccine is not possible.
</P>
<P>
   But if a company developed a vaccine against the African type,
it would run the risk of marketing a product that no nation could
afford. The Vaccine Initiative is trying to persuade the World Bank
to set up a $1 billion fund to purchase an AIDS vaccine for
developing countries as a lure to manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond all these problems, scientists, policymakers, and AIDS
activists are beginning to ponder the ethical issues that will
accompany large-scale vaccine trials, especially in poor nations.
</P>
<P>
   These issues were aired at an often-contentious meeting here
last week by UNAIDS, the United Nations AIDS agency, involving more
than 100 representatives from around the world. The group
identified 10 levels of agreement on a wide range of issues, ``from
unanimity to total chaos,'' said Dr. Donald Burke, a Johns Hopkins
University vaccine specialist.
</P>
<P>
   The attendees agreed that it would be ethical to compare an
experimental vaccine to a placebo, or inert substance, to determine
efficacy. But they could not agree on whether participants in
vaccine trials who became infected with HIV should be guaranteed
expensive drug treatments indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``If triple-drug treatment will continue forever, who is going
to pay?'' asked Ruranga, the Ugandan Army officer. And, putting
himself in the position of a vaccine trial subject who gets
infected and subsequently infects his wife, he added, ``Am I going
to get triple-drug treatment while my wife is not?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
