<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-28 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1013 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RABBI-MESSIAH-2TAKES-     06-28 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RABBI-MESSIAH-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME FOLLOWERS OF DECEASED RABBI PROCLAIM HIM THE MESSIAH
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By JIM YARDLEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Four years after the death of Rabbi Menachem Mendel
Schneerson, the charismatic Hasidic leader, his Lubavitch movement
finds itself embarrassed by a persistent group of his followers,
mostly in Brooklyn, who stubbornly proclaim the rabbi as the
Moshiach, or Messiah, and eagerly await his resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   During a weekend in which several thousand people commemorated
Schneerson's death by visiting his granite mausoleum in Queens,
Lubavitch officials dismissed these followers as a fringe group
whose views are not representative of Lubavitch, a Hasidic group
centered in Crown Heights, Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   But some Lubavitch rabbis worry that the messiah controversy
could reinforce negative stereotypes of Hasidim and undermine the
credibility of Lubavitch at a time when the group is aggressively
expanding and trying to reach out to Jews around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to keep our eyes on the primary goal, which is to
educate more Jews, promote more Judaism and bring more goodness and
kindness,'' said Rabbi David Eliezrie, an ``emissary'' who runs a
Lubavitch Center in Yorba Linda, Calif. ``That would be the way to
bring the messiah.''
</P>
<P>
   The anniversary of Schneerson's death, as calculated by the
Hebrew lunar calendar, fell on Saturday. But during four days of
commemoration events, the messianists, as they are known among
Lubavitchers, held a separate ``Moshiach'' congress in Crown
Heights honoring Schneerson, called the rebbe, or spiritual leader.
People sold Moshiach tapes, posters and candy bars and attended
messiah-related lectures. Others handed out business cards _ one
for Jews, another for Gentiles _ promoting the ``Moshiach
Campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe,'' said Rabbi Yosef Carlebach, who attended the
messianists' congress, ``that every Lubavitcher believes in his
heart of hearts that the rebbe is the Moshiach.''
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to douse this messiah fervor began about two years ago
after messianists placed a ``King Moshiach'' billboard near the
George Washington Bridge. Lubavitch officials countered with
newspaper advertisements and predicted that the passage of time
would change such thinking. Earlier this year, though, the highest
Lubavitch rabbinical court felt compelled to issue a statement
denouncing ``the deification of any human being'' as contrary to
Jewish belief. The statement also said the rebbe himself would
disapprove of being identified as the Messiah.
</P>
<P>
   Lubavitch officials do not deny that a messiah is coming; to the
contrary, that is a tenet of Jewish belief. But in a statement this
weekend, Rabbi Yehuda Krinsky, once a close aide to the rebbe,
criticized the messianists.
</P>
<P>
   He said: ``We must pray for the arrival of Messiah, increase our
personal goodness and kindness and encourage an awareness and
anticipation of our redemption. No one can know with certainty, and
clearly should not ``campaign'' about, who Moshiach may or may not
be.''
</P>
<P>
   With an estimated 200,000 followers worldwide, Schneerson led
Lubavitch for 44 years. Until his death at age 92, he was
considered among the world's most influential Jewish leaders,
courted by American and Israeli politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some Hasidic leaders, Schneerson preached engagement,
though not assimilation, with the non-Orthodox Jewish world. He
established an international network of Chabad Houses, or Jewish
learning centers, to offer prayers, readings and classes open to
all Jews. Today, Lubavitch officials say there are 2,400 Chabad
Houses in 48 countries.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
