<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-28 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1015 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-JEWISH-LEADER-2NDT     06-28 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-JEWISH </SLUG>
 -LEADER-2NDTAKE-NYT  
 NEW YORK: 48 countries. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Zalman Schmotkin, a Lubavitch spokesman, said the messiah
controversy had not hampered the growth of Lubavitch. The group's
budget has risen to $600 million, much of it from Jewish
philanthropists, he said. As further evidence of popularity,
Schmotkin said roughly 800,000 Jewish students worldwide now attend
Lubavitch schools.
</P>
<P>
   But Schmotkin said that the local schools in Crown Heights had
become something of a controversy. At the United Lubavicher
Yeshivas, the Crown Heights Hasidic school system, many teachers
lead students in daily chants of ``King Moshiach.''
</P>
<P>
   ``After we pray every morning, we sing, `Long live the rebbe,
King Moshiach for ever and ever,''' said Israel Benchoun, 10, a
fourth grader.
</P>
<P>
   Schneerson's presence still dominates Crown Heights. In becoming
the seventh grand rabbi, or rebbe, of the Lubavitch, he succeeded
his father-in-law. But childless, he left no successor. Now,
bookstores offer volumes of his writings or a collection of his
letters. For the anniversary weekend, one of his previously
unpublished scholarly treatises was released. Video tapes and audio
tapes are for sale in many stores on Kingston Avenue. Along
residential streets, a sprinkling of homeowners tack his photograph
above their front doors, many with slogans proclaiming him the
Messiah.
</P>
<P>
   In Cambria Heights, Queens, Rabbi Abba Refson, a Lubavitch
official, lives in a house near Montefiore Cemetery, keeping watch
over the 20-square-foot mausoleum in which the Rebbe is buried
beside his father-in-law. According to Jewish belief, the soul of
the deceased lingers above the grave, and throughout the weekend,
buses arrived with followers from Crown Heights. Outside the house,
people sat at long tables writing notes to leave atop the graves.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew overturned a
decision that would have allowed about 1,000 Lubavitchers to spend
Friday night in an elementary school near the grave site. After
complaints from neighbors, Crew revoked the permit, saying that
public schools had never been used for overnight lodgings except in
emergencies or disasters. The Lubavitchers instead stayed at a
Jewish center about two miles away, and Sunday the police said the
weekend passed without incident.
</P>
<P>
   The reverence for Schneerson was evident Thursday afternoon, as
followers left their shoes outside the open-air mausoleum and
stepped inside. A group of Hasidic men silently mouthed prayers,
holding worn Hebrew prayer books, swaying slightly at the edge of
the graves. A handful of women stood slightly apart, praying. The
only sound was the tearing of the notes _ a custom favored by
Schneerson _ and the occasional jet descending toward John F.
Kennedy International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel strongly affected by it,'' Refson said of the
visits. ``I'm more moved by the people who are not so religiously
inclined who when they come here, they come out very moved and very
motivated personally.''
</P>
<P>
   A different scene unfolded Thursday night as about 200 people,
mostly men, gathered in the steamy upstairs auditorium of the
Brooklyn Jewish Center on Eastern Parkway in Crown Heights to open
``the Third International Moshiach Congress.'' These messianists
listened to lectures and watched videos of an aged Schneerson
speaking into a microphone.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the auditorium, Yossi Schwartz, 29, a medical student,
sold cassette tapes under the auspices of ``the Moshiach Awareness
Project.'' Cheery and eager to talk, Schwartz said that many
ordinary Lubavitchers were leery of admitting their belief.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask a person privately, he might say, `Of course, I
believe the rebbe is the Messiah,''' Schwartz said. ``I would say
that 99 percent of the people are of that mind set. The big issue
is whether or not to publicize it to the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Chaim Adelman said he spreads the messiah message at his
Chabad House in Amherst, Mass., and he accused Lubavitch officials
of being ``afraid it might turn people off.'' Lubavitch officials,
several of them from Chabad Houses around the country, say the
messianism is almost completely confined to Crown Heights. Another
fierce debate between the two sides is whether the rebbe suggested
that he was the Messiah in vague statements made near the end of
his life. The messianists believe he did; Lubavitch officials
fiercely say he did not, accusing messianists of distorting the
rebbe's words.
</P>
<P>
   But messianists like Adelman say they consider it their mission
to spread the message of the imminent arrival of the Messiah. One
woman, Rivky Shvey, spent Thursday selling Messiah posters, tapes,
candy bars and tambourines. Just as women played tambourines as
Moses led the Jews through the Red Sea, Ms. Shvey said she kept a
small tambourine in her carrying bag in readiness for the arrival
of the Messiah.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just in case I'm on the subway and Moshiach comes,'' Ms.
Shvey, 33, said, ``I'll have one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
