<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-28 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1016 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LA-FILMS-FOURTH-LADN     06-28 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-FILMS-FOURTH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD TRADES FIRECRACKERS FOR BLOCKBUSTERS ON HOLIDY WEEKEND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
BURBANK -- Now that ``Godzilla'' has died a premature death, the
industry's last chance for a true summer blockbuster is widely
believed to be The Walt Disney Co.'s ``Armageddon.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   And if it does become the quarter-billion-dollar movie that
analysts predict, ``Armageddon'' will reaffirm a Hollywood truism
of the '90s: The Fourth of July is hot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Studios have realized that the Fourth is the type of holiday
where families like to do things together, like go to the movies,''
said Robert Bucksbaum, president of the Reel Source forecasting
service.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the July 4 weekend has been the launching
ground for such blockbuster movies as ``The Firm,'' ``Men In
Black'' and, of course, ``Independence Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Cruise's ``The Firm'' took in $32.5 million during the 1993
holiday weekend on its way to a $158.3 million domestic gross.
``MIB'' grabbed $84.1 million of its $250.1 million domestic gross
on its opening weekend and ``ID4'' took in $85 million during the
long weekend on its way to $306.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any studio would love to have a film in this slot,'' Bucksbaum
said, ``but you have to put in a movie that others won't
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney has already succeeded on that level: No other major
movies are being released this upcoming weekend.
</P>
<P>
   For those few who have managed to avoid the onslaught of
publicity leading up to Wednesday's release, ``Armageddon'' stars
Bruce Willis as the leader of oil drillers trying to nuke an
Earth-menacing asteroid. Its plot, augmented by spectacular special
effects, including the destruction of New York's famed Chrysler
Building, is fairly recognizable: Call it ``The Dirty Dozen in
Outer Space'' or maybe ``Independence Day Meets Apollo 13.''
</P>
<P>
   The $50 million worth of special effects make ``Armageddon'' the
most expensive movie in Disney history. That makes it a significant
departure for the entertainment giant, which prides itself on
cautious financial conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a little out of character for Disney to spend this much
but they've kind of had to do it because this one is the
spotlight,'' said Salomon Smith Barney analyst Jill Krutick. ``As
we all know, in the film business, it's a matter of no guts, no
glory.''
</P>
<P>
   Bucksbaum believes ``Armageddon'' should take in $75 million
during the first five days -- about $10 million short of what ``Men
In Black'' and ``ID4'' took in during similar periods, but quite
respectable just the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be the top movie of the summer,'' he said. ``There's
strong interest from young adults, kids and women.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, some worried that Paramount's ``Deep Impact'' -- in
which Robert Duvall leads a team of astronauts trying to blow up a
comet menacing the Earth -- would detract from ``Armageddon,'' but
those concerns have evaporated.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it opens, there will not have been a real action movie
since `Deep Impact' and `Godzilla,' so I think it will do well,''
said Drew Devlin of the Independent Marketing Edge consulting
service. `` `Deep Impact' seems more cerebral than `Armageddon,'
which looks like a real slam-bang movie. By the Fourth, people are
really ready for a wham-bam film.''
</P>
<P>
   The analysts note that the film has a number of things going for
it that should swell attendance:
</P>
<P>
   _Willis' presence as a veteran action star with proven
box-office appeal.
</P>
<P>
   _State-of-the art special effects, complete with Space Shuttle
launches, derring-do in outer space and demolition scenes in New
York City.
</P>
<P>
   _A romantic subplot between Ben Affleck of ``Good Will Hunting''
and MTV heartthrob Liv Tyler, who plays Willis' daughter.
</P>
<P>
   _The heightened interest in asteroids and their threat to Earth,
increased even more when the International Astronomical Union
warned in March that it discovered an asteroid with a trajectory
that could collide with Earth's in 30 years. The union has since
rescinded the prediction.
</P>
<P>
   _Dark humor, a key component in bringing in teen-agers. For
example, movie preview watchers have already seen Willis' crew
insist before the mission that they never have to pay taxes again.
One of the movie's taglines is ``Earth: It Was Fun While It
Lasted.''
</P>
<P>
   _A PG-13 rating, which makes the film more desirable to children
between 7 and 12 than a PG or G rating. ``Men In Black'' and ``My
Best Friend's Wedding'' became hits partly due to this phenomenon
while Disney's squeaky-clean animated films have been unable to
duplicate the success of 1994's ``The Lion King.''
</P>
<P>
   _Most importantly, timing. ``You want to open on Wednesday of
the Fourth of July weekend because people love to go see a movie or
several movies during that period and the newest is the one on
everyone's list,'' Devlin said.
</P>
<P>
   So what movie will be 1999's ``Armageddon''? No one knows, yet.
</P>
<P>
   Leading early candidates are Warner Bros. ``Wild Wild West,''
starring Will Smith and already into production, and a pair of
Universal projects: ``Everest,'' based on the eight deaths of Mt.
Everest climbers two years ago, and Ron Howard's ``edTV,'' a comedy
similar to ``The Truman Show'' about a video store clerk whose life
airs on cable 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   All three have strong credentials: ``Wild Wild West'' reteams
Smith with ``Men In Black'' producer Barry Sonnenfeld; interest has
been intense in stories about Mount Everest, with the giant-screen
``Everest'' film setting records; and Howard is one of Hollywood's
most bankable directors.
</P>
<P>
   ``You probably need to get the word out that you're going for
the Fourth about a year in advance and you need something that's
going to be so big that everyone else will clear out the date,''
Bucksbaum said. `` `Everest' could be a great Fourth of July movie
except that it may be hard to come up with a happy ending.''
</P>
<P>
   Other potential Fourth of July candidates: Fox's ``Martial Law''
with Willis; Sony's ``Jacob the Liar'' with Robin Williams;
Paramount's ``200 Cigarettes'' with Affleck; New Line's ``The Mask
2'' or ``Freddy and Jason''; two Disney animated projects,
``Tarzan'' and ``Toy Story 2,'' along with Julia Roberts' ``Martha
and Arthur''; and Warner's ``Fahrenheit 451'' with Mel Gibson.
</P>
<P>
   All of them, however, are expected to pale in comparison to the
movie that has already staked out Memorial Day 1999. That weekend
was set aside a long time ago for 20th Century Fox's release of
``Episode One,'' George Lucas' prequel to ``Star Wars.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
