<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CALLS FOR BROADENED HUMAN RIGHTS AROUND GLOBE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ President Clinton called Monday for the relationship
between the United States and China to ``blossom into a fuller
partnership for the new century,'' but warned the Chinese
government that to build economic stability it must allow its
citizens essential human rights.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to be delivered to students at Beijing University,
Clinton avoided even diplomatically cloaked threats and instead
struck the note that it was in the interest of the Chinese
leadership to broaden freedoms of speech, religion, and protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our experience demonstrates that freedom strengthens
stability,'' Clinton's speech said, according to excerpts released
by the White House before the address. ``In the global information
age, freedom is a powerful engine of progress. China's greatest
source of strength resides in the minds and hearts of its citizens.
It is profoundly in your interest, and the world's, that those
minds be free to reach the fullness of their potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's speech, billed by aides as the centerpiece address of
his nine-day diplomatic tour through China, was bald in its pursuit
of closer ties with Beijing and the belief that the United States
and China must engage in more open, more frequent exchanges for
improvements in human rights to be made.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton attempted to rebut critics at home who have contended
that through his policy of engagement in general and through his
visit Friday to Tiananmen Square, the United States is
relinquishing its concern about human rights. Those critics have
said that even after five years of dialogue with the United States,
Chinese officials have not done nearly enough to broaden basic
human rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are those in my country who question whether working
with China is in our interests,'' the speech said. ``There are
those in China who ask whether closer relations with the United
States makes sense for China. But everything we know about the way
the world is changing and the challenges your generation will face
tell us that our two nations will be better off working together
than apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Sensitive to Chinese reticence to outside influence, Clinton
purposely said the United States was not seeking ``to impose our
vision on others.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But we are convinced that certain rights are universal,''
Clinton said. ``I believe that everywhere, people aspire to be
treated with dignity, to give voice to their opinions, to choose
their own leaders, to associate with whom they wish, to worship
how, when, and where they want. These are not American rights or
European rights or developed-world rights. They are the birthrights
of people everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton lauded the Chinese for making strides in granting
citizens economic freedom through open-market competition. But he
added, ``True freedom must mean more than economic opportunity. In
America, we believe that freedom itself is indivisible.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the address, US officials were still basking Sunday in
the glow of Saturday's freewheeling news conference that Clinton
shared with Chinese President Jiang Zemin. Clinton's national
security adviser, Samuel R. Berger, described it as
``unprecedented'' and said the televised event reached 600 million
Chinese people, a figure that seemed doubtful given that many
Chinese do not own televisions.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides hinted Clinton intentionally toned down his
rhetoric on human rights in Monday's speech, also to be televised,
because he believed he made many of his points clear Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Even while glowing over the likelihood that Jiang himself had
approved the live broadcast, officials were quick to say that China
is by no means where it should be in terms of human rights and
basic freedoms of speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a long way to go,'' Secretary of State Madeleine K.
Albright told reporters. She later admitted that beyond Saturday's
exchange between Clinton and Jiang, there has been little progress
on human rights issues in this summit.
</P>
<P>
   Berger, speaking on CNN, said that life has changed dramatically
in China since President Richard M. Nixon visited in 1972. People
can choose their line of work and where they attend school, he
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   But, he quickly added: ``I still think China's human rights
record is terrible. I still think China's an authoritarian
society.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Clinton temporarily put aside matters of international
diplomacy to play the more basic role of American tourist, braving
sweltering heat to pay a visit to two of China's most famous
attractions.
</P>
<P>
   In the morning, after attending church services in Beijing,
Clinton, Hillary Rodham Clinton, Chelsea, and a delegation of White
House figures entered the Forbidden City, a complex of palaces and
ornate gates once occupied by the emperors from the Ming and Qing
dynasties.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an amazing place,'' Clinton said, shortly after his guide
explained to him how a small army of servants used to carry
emperors in their chariots up the steep palace steps.
</P>
<P>
   Looking upbeat, Clinton said of China, ``The last 25 years, it's
been changing quite a lot.'' Asked if the change was enough,
Clinton said, ``After Sunday, I feel much better. I thought it was
good.'' With that, he turned away and headed through the Gate of
Celestial Purity.
</P>
<P>
   As the Clintons wandered through some of the nearly 10,000
buildings in the city, which is protected by a high wall and
surrounded by a moat, Chelsea appeared to be the best versed on
Chinese history, stopping her parents to point out sites and
apparently explain their significance.
</P>
<P>
   The city housed 24 Chinese emperors, their servants, their
wives, and as many as 2,000 concubines per emperor from the early
1400s until the early 1900s. It was the setting for Bernardo
Bertolucci's ``The Last Emperor,'' and now serves as a main Beijing
tourist attraction.
</P>
<P>
   From the city, the White House party drove nearly 40 miles to
the Great Wall, where sweating tourists hiked up a steep hill, rode
a tram, and then climbed stairs to the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite unbelievable,'' Clinton proclaimed. ``It's amazing to
imagine that it was done so long ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Construction of the 3,000-mile wall began in rough terrain in
the seventh century BC to provide protection from rival kingdoms.
Emperor Qin Shihuang ordered the existing walls linked and new ones
constructed. The wall was extended and strengthened all the way
through the Ming Dynasty in 1644.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe this wall now is a symbol that China shows to the
rest of the world, not a wall to keep people out,'' Clinton said
Sunday. ``It sort of unifies the country for over 7,000
kilometers.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made his only policy statements of the day from the
pulpit of the Chongwenmen Christian Church, where he called for
more religious freedoms in a country in which practicing religion
can still be cause for arrest. The government has sanctioned some
religious worship but still requires a pledge of allegiance to
state ahead of religion, and limits church construction and
baptisms of children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that Chinese and Americans are brothers and sisters
as children of God,'' Clinton told the congregation where President
Bush worshipped when he was US ambassador to China. ``We come here
in that spirit Monday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
