6-28 -- In less than six years, Russian entreprenuer Felix Komarov
has become a patron of culture and charitable causes, founded a
weekly Russian-language newspaper in New York and started a
Rolls-Royce dealership in Moscow. And just this month, he opened a
lavish three-story Russian cabaret-restaurant on the East Side of
Manhattan. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) OAKLAND, Calif -- June 28, 1998 -- AT&AMP;T-TCI, 6-28 --
Charles Vandagriff talks to his daughter Rachel, as his wife, Kathy
Sinsheimer, watches their other daughter, Corinne, at a computer.
Their Oakland household is one of millions with multiple PC's and
phone lines. Someday, AT&AMP;T wants families like the Vandagriffs to
turn to the company for one-stop shopping for not only all of their
telephone and cable television services but new information
services as well. (Dan Krauss/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WASHINGTON -- June 28, 1998 -- REPUBS-CLASSOF94, 6-28 --
Representative Jon Christensen, right, who has six months left in
the House, meets with two Nebraska constituents and Representative
John Ensign. Christensen, one of the House Republican freshmen of
1994, lost his congressional seat by finishing last in the
three-way primary for governor. Ensign, a 1994 freshman as well, is
involved in a similar uphill challenge for higher office this year.
(Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) CONCORD, N.H. -- June 28, 1998 --
NEWHAMPSHIRE-TAX-POLITICS, 6-28 -- Three members of the New
Hampshire House of Representatives meet in the House chamber to
discuss the financing of the state's schools. From left are Douglas
Teschner, R-Haverhill; Clifton Below, D-Lebanon, and Jeb Bradley,
R-Wolfeboro. More than those in any other state, New Hampshire's
schools have been financed by local government - about 90 percent
of the $1-billion-plus education budget, compared with about 50
percent nationwide. (Evan Richman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- June 28, 1998 -- INTERNET-ACTIVISTS, 6-28 --
Jon Postel, left, considered the ``grandfather of the Internet,''
in his office at the Information Sciences Institute, Marina del
Rey, Calif. (Chris Pizzello/New York Times Photo) David Farber,
center, one of a few people known for their e-mail lists, which
circulate polemics, policy positions and appeals that help frame
Internet issues, at his home in Landenberg, Pa. (Tim Shaffer/New
York Times Photo) Tamar Frankel, right, of the Boston University
School of Law, in her office in Boston. (Evan Richman/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- June 28, 1998 -- TV-CBS-MEDIA, 6-28 -- Andrew
Heyward, CBS News head, has learned to be a hard-headed business
strategist and a slick diplomat. He knows his mandate: to earn
attention, ratings and profits without compromising the prestige of
CBS News. And since he took over the news division two and a half
years ago, its flagship programs have shown increases in the
Nielsen ratings. (Ozier Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BASKING RIDGE, N.J. -- June 28, 1998 -- AT&AMP;T-ARMSTRONG,
6-28 -- AT&AMP;T's chairman and chief executive, C. Michael Armstrong,
says the TCI deal was necessary because AT&AMP;T has a lot of catching
up to do. ``It has to be bold because I'm working against time and
the forces of industry, of change, of technology and of
competition,'' he says. Armstrong now must convince investors of
the wisdom of acquiring TCI's cable operation and combining it with
AT&AMP;T's consumer business as a new subsidiary. So far, such
convincing has not been easy. (Norman Y. Lono/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- June 28, 1998 -- SKIN-TEETH-THEATER-REVIEW,
6-28 -- Frances Conroy and John Goodman in a performance of
Thornton Wilder's ``Skin of Our Teeth'' at the Delacorte Theater in
Central Park. The New York Shakespeare Festival's revival of
``Skin,'' captured the spirit of the 1942 play, a wry paean to the
tenacity of the human spirit. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- June 28, 1998 -- EDITING-DECLINE, 6-28 --
Michael Carlisle, left, whose literary agency now includes Neal
Bascomb, right, an in-house editor who will work closely with
fiction writers. With publishing cycles compressed, leaving less
time for editing, and editors distracted by other corporate duties
are increasingly recruiting hired pens - independent editors who
sharpen text or copy editors who correct grammar, inconsistencies
and spelling errors for fees ranging from $1,000 to $25,000.
(Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- June 28, 1998 -- CRAMER-PROFILE-MEDIA, 6-28
-- James Cramer is the co-founder of TheStreet.com, an investment
news service published on the World Wide Web, as well as one of its
marquee columnists. Cramer's reach extends well beyond the computer
terminal and this has made him a kind of Zelig of the information
age, cutting across all media and raising the issue of his own
involvement in the market as the manager of a $350 million private
investment firm. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) SAN FRANCISCO -- June 28, 1998 -- COMPUSA-COMPUTERCITY,
6-28 -- CompUSA's chief executive, James Halpin, came in and saved
the company in 1994 when it was on the brink of collapse. But the
industry has become even more competitive in the last four years.
CompUSA, having just agreed to pay $275 million to buy its chief
rival, Computer City, from Tandy, is out to prove that the computer
retail store is here to stay. (Dan Krauss/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- June 28, 1998 -- AT&AMP;T-TCI-MARKETPLACE, 6-28
-- In a mere eight days of negotiations, John Malone, the wily
chairman of Tele-Communications Inc., struck a good deal for
shareholders - and an even richer deal for himself by agreeing to
sell his company to AT&AMP;T Corp. for $31.8 billion in stock. Malone
owns an estimated 30 million class B shares, or more than half of
the outstanding 50 million class B shares, compared with just 1.5
million class A shares, a fraction of the 472 million outstanding.
(Ozier Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
