<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-28 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1025 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LIFEGUARD-SHORTAGE     06-28 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LIFEGUARD-SHORTAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORKERS BARRED FROM WATER AT BEACHES WITHOUT LIFEGUARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As long as Michael Mancino didn't look out toward the
water, Sunday was a perfect beach day at the end of Brighton Second
Street in Brighton Beach, Brooklyn. Kids flew kites. A man with a
metal detector roamed up and down. But as Mancino lay sunning
himself on a towel, his view of the infinite ocean was obscured by
the slats of a fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come here every day and they tell me there's no lifeguard,''
said Mancino, 55, who lives a few blocks inland. ``What can you
do?''
</P>
<P>
   Yuri Nazarov was not so philosophical.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is absolutely crazy,'' Nazarov, 50, said after emerging
from the water a few hundred yards away, where the beach was open,
and trudging along the closed beach back toward his apartment on
the boardwalk. ``I don't understand why they're closing all this
down.''
</P>
<P>
   So it went on the most dazzling weekend of the young season as
New York City beachgoers struggled to cope with the ongoing
shortage of lifeguards. On Sunday, nearly a third of the city's 14
miles of public beach were closed because the city is about 100
lifeguards short of a full staff of 600.
</P>
<P>
   At least Mancino and Nazarov were able to walk along their
closed beach. In much of the Rockaways, in Queens, sand and sea
alike were off limits, and park rangers shooed people off one
section of beach while sunbathers were pressed towel-to-towel just
feet away.
</P>
<P>
   Parks Department officials are quick to point out that the
shortage, caused largely by the fact that more than 80 percent of
people who take the lifeguard test fail it, is not as bad as it was
last year. And they add, many of the closings are from acts of
nature, like erosion and the nesting of the endangered piping
plover.
</P>
<P>
   But that does not make the situation any easier for beachgoers
to accept. On Sunday morning, protesters from the Rockaway Beach
Civic Association, some carrying rubber hammers and signs that said
``Hammering home the point: Stop ignoring Rockaway,'' held a rally
on the boardwalk to demand action.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Skyler, a Parks Department spokesman, said that during
the week, the shortage gets worse because many of the lifeguards
have other jobs and work only on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   But Skyler said a few more stretches of beach are expected to
open next weekend because a new class is graduating this week from
the city's lifeguard school. Most of the graduates, however, will
be qualified to work only in the city's pools, where the test is
easier. Aspiring lifeguards must swim 440 yards in six minutes to
get a beach job; the cutoff for pool work is seven minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The pools, which open Thursday, are also short on lifeguards,
but Skyler said all 55 pools will be up and running.
</P>
<P>
   Skyler played down the inconvenience and said it was for
people's own good.
</P>
<P>
   ``No complete beach is shut down,'' he said. ``All we're doing
is asking people to walk a couple of blocks. We'd rather have
people do that than put their lives in jeopardy by having us hire
people who aren't qualified.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was something in the closing of a beach that seemed
to call for civil disobedience. Near Beach 75th Street in Rockaway,
Taras Mashtalir, 22, continued to sunbathe on the wrong side of the
line in the sand even though he had been warned several times to
move. Mashtalir needed to move only feet to be in compliance, but
he refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can I say?'' he said slyly. ``I'm a rebel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
