<HEADLINE>
ROLAND WOLSELEY, 94, SYRACUSE PROFESSOR
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN.: Ore., Idaho) 
(ja) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roland Wolseley, a journalism teacher who wrote one of the first
surveys of the black press, died at his home in Syracuse, N.Y., on
May 31. He was 94.
</P>
<P>
   Wolseley began his career as a reporter and editor of newspapers
in Reading, Pa. After receiving a master's degree at the Medill
School of Journalism at Northwestern University, he began to teach.
In 1946, after eight years of teaching, he lost his position at
Northwestern for being a pacifist. He was offered a teaching post
at Syracuse University, where he taught journalism for 26 years.
</P>
<P>
   Wolseley wrote more than 1,000 magazine articles and for 65
years was the book review editor for Quill and Scroll magazine, a
publication of the international honorary society of high school
journalists, based at the University of Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   He was best known for the book ``Black Press U.S.A.,'' which was
published in 1972 and was one first surveys of black journalism in
the country. He also wrote textbooks on journalism, including ``The
Magazine World'' (Prentice-Hall).
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Isabel Champ Wolseley of Syracuse
and two stepsons, John Champ Jr. of Canby, Ore., and Kelly Champ
Sr. of Boise, Idaho.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
