<SLUG> BC-OBIT-TREYZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLIVER TREYZ, 80, A POWER AT ABC TV IN '50S AND '60S
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN.: Calif.) 
(ja) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oliver Treyz, who helped make ABC's television network a
formidable competitor to CBS and NBC in the 1950s and '60s, died
June 14 at a retirement home in Englewood, N.J., from kidney
failure caused by prostate cancer, his son James Treyz said. He was
80.
</P>
<P>
   As head of the American Broadcasting Co.'s television operation,
from 1956 to 1962, Treyz relied on strong ties to West Coast film
companies and a rich diet of hourlong prime-time action programs to
help ABC shed its image as the perennial also-ran of the television
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oliver headed the first major threat to the two networks, NBC
and CBS,'' said Michael Dann, a broadcast consultant who was the
head of programming at CBS when Treyz was the president of ABC's
television unit. ``ABC got an ascendancy under Ollie Treyz that is
unheard of before, during or since.''
</P>
<P>
   The ABC success story was built on westerns and shows about
private detectives and law enforcement officials, including
``Adventures in Paradise,'' ``Cheyenne,'' ``Hawaiian Eye,'' ``77
Sunset Strip,'' ``Surfside 6,'' `Maverick,'' ``The Rifleman'' and
``The Untouchables.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the shows were produced by the broadcast unit at Warner
Brothers, with which ABC and Treyz enjoyed a close relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the founder of CBS, Dann said: ``I can remember
William S. Paley calling me and saying: `This Ollie Treyz has all
this product. Why don't we get some Warner Brothers product?'''
</P>
<P>
   But the very programming formula that drove Treyz's success also
contributed to his ouster from ABC. In December 1961, ABC broadcast
an episode of a program called ``Bus Stop'' that dealt with
adultery and suicide and starred Fabian, the popular singer, as a
psychopath who attacked an elderly man with an ax.
</P>
<P>
   Protest over the episode led to federal hearings about violence
on television. Before a Senate subcommittee in January 1962, Treyz
defended the decision to broadcast the episode in the name of
artistic freedom. But the following month he told the Federal
Communications Commission that broadcasting the show had been a
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   By that time ABC had reverted to the No. 3 position in the
ratings. In March 1962, Treyz was dismissed as the network's
president.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1960s Treyz attempted unsuccessfully to start a
fourth television network. He later worked as a television
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Hamilton College in 1939, Treyz began his
career in broadcasting at a small radio station in Binghamton, N.Y.
During World War II, Treyz served in the Army Air Corps.
</P>
<P>
   He joined ABC in 1948 as a presentation writer and was director
of the company's radio network in 1954 when he left to become the
founding president of the Television Bureau of Advertising, a trade
group for local television stations.
</P>
<P>
   Treyz rejoined ABC in 1956 and was named president in 1957.
</P>
<P>
   Treyz is survived by two sons, Donald, of San Diego and James,
of Chappaqua, N.Y., and two granddaughters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-98 2259EDT &QL; 
