<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLUG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALIOUNE BLONDIN BEYE, U.N. ENVOY, DIES AT 59
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By ERIC PACE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alioune Blondin Beye, a U.N. envoy on a diplomatic mission aimed
at averting renewed bloodshed in Angola, was apparently killed on
Friday night in the crash of a light plane near Abidjan, the
capital of the Ivory Coast. He was 59 and was based in Lusaka,
Zambia.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities at the crash scene Sunday did not make official
identification of the remains found by a search team near the
wreckage of the plane, a chartered twin-turboprop Beechcraft 200,
which went down in an area of forests and mangrove swamps.
</P>
<P>
   But searchers found passports belonging to Beye, a Malian, and
others who had been on the plane. Reuters reported that the plane
had been flying from Togo to Abidjan carrying Beye and five other
members of the U.N. observer mission in Angola. It also had three
crew members on board, officials in Togo said.
</P>
<P>
   A U.N. spokeswoman in New York, Judith Modeste, said Sunday:
``The rescue team reached the site of the crash, collected the
passports, but there was no evidence of survivors. They have called
off the rescue efforts for today and will continue on Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Secretary General Kofi Annan of the United Nations
said Beye had been ``traveling in the region in yet another attempt
to seek support of African leaders in overcoming the present
crisis'' over the agreement that ended Angola's long civil war.
</P>
<P>
   A former foreign minister of Mali, Beye was a highly regarded
lawyer, diplomat and political figure, known for his energy and
quick-wittedness. In 1993 he was designated by Boutros
Boutros-Ghali, Annan's predecessor as secretary general, as his
special representative for Angola.
</P>
<P>
   Beye began mediating efforts toward peace between Angolan rebels
and the Angolan government. He oversaw the negotiations that led to
a 1994 peace agreement under which the rebel group known as the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola, or Unita,
agreed to yield control of the large area it had taken over during
Angola's more than two decades of intermittent civil war.
</P>
<P>
   But the rebel group has lagged in carrying out its obligations
under the pact, and last month Beye threatened to quit his envoy's
post. He contended that neither Unita nor the Angolan government
possessed the ``political will'' necessary to see peace efforts
through to conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Before being named as a U.N. envoy, Beye held various posts. He
was Mali's minister of youth, sports, arts and culture in 1977
before serving as foreign minister from 1978 to 1986. He was legal
counsel to the president of Mali from 1986 to 1988, and in
subsequent years he was secretary general of the Afripment Bank in
Abidjan and the head of its legal department.
</P>
<P>
   He lectured on international public law at the University of
Dijon, France, and was a member of the Dijon bar. He was also a
professor at the National School of Administration in Bamako, Mali,
and appeared in Malian courts as chief of the government legal
department.
</P>
<P>
   He was married and had four children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-98 2307EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980628.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-28 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1130 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COL-RENT-A-COP-NYT     06-28 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-RENT-A-COP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: RENT-A-COP PROGRAM: THE BEST PROTECTION MONEY CAN BUY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ELIZABETH KOLBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``You pay for it, you've got it'' hasn't yet become
the city's motto, but we are making steady progress in that
direction.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last four years, New York has sold off its public radio
station, tried to sell its hospitals, ceded to business improvement
districts the upkeep of large swaths of Manhattan and handed over
Central Park to be run by a group of private citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it is introducing Rent-a-Cop. For $27 an hour, plus
handling charges, it is possible to put an order in with the city's
Police Department for a uniformed officer _ complete with
bulletproof vest and the power of arrest _ to keep the peace at
your private affair. To sweeten the deal, the city will even pick
up liability costs: If your rented officer happens to apply
excessive force or wrench his back, taxpayers will pick up the tab.
</P>
<P>
   The program, known officially as the Paid Detail Program, began
as a pilot project in early spring and has been growing steadily,
if quietly, ever since. According to Police Department figures,
10,000 officers have already signed on, and about 2,000 have served
on paid assignments, at places including Yankee Stadium,
Rockefeller Center and assorted movie theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, whether you were aware of it or not, there is a good
chance you've already been watched over by a rented cop.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the explanation for the program is much the same as
for other privatization schemes: improving city services at minimal
expense. As First Deputy Police Commissioner Patrick Kelleher put
it, ``The public will see more officers out on the street without
cost to the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Unofficially, there is a somewhat different justification:
putting money in officers' pockets without actually paying them
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the city's way of acknowledging they pay us so badly,''
said Bruce Robertson, financial secretary of the Patrolmen's
Benevolent Association.
</P>
<P>
   New York is by no means the first city to market its cops
actively. Miami and St. Petersburg, Fla., for example, have been
doing so for years.
</P>
<P>
   But the city had, until recently, resisted the idea. There were
concerns about fostering moonlighting, which police officials
feared made officers less fit for regular duty; worries over
officers' divided loyalties and a general discomfort with the
strong arm of the law being put up for hire.
</P>
<P>
   It is, after all, a standard feature of the modern dystopian
fantasy _ see ``Robocop'' _ that police protection is just another
commodity, the force controlled not by the community but by a
corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Police Department officials say they have built in enough
safeguards to address the old anxieties. All potential renters will
be vetted by the department; officers will be rotated so they do
not develop ties to a particular employer, and any officer with a
dubious record will not be allowed to participate.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, maintain that the Police Department has focused
on the narrow issues while the big ones remain unaddressed and are,
ultimately, unaddressable.
</P>
<P>
   David Bayley, a professor of criminal justice at the State
University of New York at Albany, described the Paid Detail Program
as, in essence, selling state power at bargain basement prices.
Officers, he pointed out, come not just indemnified by the city,
but with training, equipment and benefits all provided by the
taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means the affluent get more protection,'' he said, ``and
they get more protection without paying the overhead. It is a
particularly good deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Police officers randomly consulted about the program expressed
views mostly along these lines: if you need the money, it's a good
thing. Some did admit, though, that they might feel awkward working
in a public uniform for a private employer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is good for that employer,'' said one officer who was
patrolling midtown last week and spoke on the condition of
anonymity. ``It is not good for the cop.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, practically all forms of privatization introduce
inequities: Richer neighborhoods inevitably get cleaner streets and
brighter parks. But justice is, presumably, not just another city
service.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Rosenthal, a 33-year veteran of the city police force who
now teaches at John Jay College of Criminal Justice, argued this
point strongly, saying he did not think police power should ever be
put at the disposal of private enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Police are police, and their obligation is to be fair and
impartial,'' he said. When officers are rented out, he said, ``they
are no longer being paid to be impartial.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-98 2309EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
