<SLUG> BC-RAC-SKIP-AWAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKIP AWAY WINS SEVENTH CONSECUTIVE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By JAY PRIVMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Before the year started, trainer Sonny Hine
mapped out a schedule for his star horse, Skip Away, that looked
like the itinerary for a touring Broadway show. And on Sunday at
Hollywood Park, Skip Away brought down the house with a brilliant
performance that solidified his position as the best horse in the
country, if not the world.
</P>
<P>
   After being pressured by the race's defending champion,
Gentlemen, for the first nine furlongs of the mile and one-quarter
Hollywood Gold Cup, Skip Away disposed of his rival in the final
200 yards and went on to win his seventh consecutive race.
</P>
<P>
   At the wire, Skip Away finished 1} lengths in front of Puerto
Madero, who rallied late and outfinished Gentlemen, his stablemate,
by a length for second. As the 2-5 favorite, Skip Away paid $2.80
for a $2 bet to win, and he earned $600,000 of the race's $1
million purse, bringing his career earnings to $8,906,360. That is
second on the career list to Cigar's $9,999,815.
</P>
<P>
   Skip Away's performance elicited a series of rousing, emotional
cheers from a crowd that greeted him skeptically before the race.
On his way to the track for the post parade, there was a smattering
of boos. But as Skip Away was galloping back to the finish line
minutes after the race, applause rolled through the grandstand,
following him like an ocean's wave.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by the crowd's response and his horse's courageous
effort, jockey Jerry Bailey stopped Skip Away in front of the
finish line, then took off his helmet and waved it to the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got some boos leaving the paddock, just like I got some boos
here with Cigar,'' Bailey said, referring to the 1995 Gold Cup,
``but there weren't any afterwards. They appreciated the champion
they saw today. Since Cigar's last few races, I'd never heard any
cheers like I did today with Skip Away.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey, the regular rider for Cigar during his Horse of the Year
campaigns in 1995 and 1996, has ridden two of this decade's most
accomplished horses, who now stand as the two richest horses ever.
</P>
<P>
   The parallels between Cigar and Skip Away are becoming ever
greater. Cigar amassed a remarkable 16-race winning streak and
shipped around the country _ and halfway around the world to Dubai
_ while racking up the victories. Near the end of his career, the
baton seemed to be passed when Skip Away upset Cigar in the 1996
Jockey Club Gold Cup at Belmont Park.
</P>
<P>
   Skip Away, age 5, has won seven straight races while racing in
New York, California, Florida, Maryland and Massachusetts. But his
remarkable consistency has spanned more than two years. In his last
23 races, Skip Away has not finished worse than third. He has won
13 times, finished second seven times and been third three times.
Overall, he has captured 16 of 34 starts for his owner, Carolyn
Hine, Sonny's wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a special horse,'' Sonny Hine said. ``I don't know how
anybody can say he doesn't beat anybody. Who's left?''
</P>
<P>
   Gentlemen and Skip Away had met once before, in last year's
Pimlico Special, in which Gentlemen beat Skip Away by a
half-length. But Gentlemen had not raced since finishing last in
the Santa Anita Handicap on March 7.
</P>
<P>
   Gentlemen and Puerto Madero, both trained by Richard Mandella,
were coupled in the wagering and were the 17-10 second choice to
Skip Away. The odds on the other five runners ranged from 11-1 to
120-1. Each horse carried 124 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The match race everyone expected, especially with the withdrawal
of Silver Charm last week, materialized quickly. Skip Away broke
sharply from Post 2 and galloped to the front with his trademark
high, loping stride. Gentlemen, starting next to Skip Away in Post
3, also broke well, and by the time the field reached the first
turn, Skip Away and Gentlemen were 1-2.
</P>
<P>
   Skip Away led through fractions of 23 seconds and 46 2/5 for the
first half-mile while about one length in front of Gentlemen. Then,
as the field moved down the backside, the jockey Gary Stevens
decided to send Gentlemen after Skip Away.
</P>
<P>
   With Gentlemen at his throat, Skip Away had to rip through his
third quarter-mile in 23 one-fifth seconds, a demanding pace that
found him at the six-furlong mark in 1:09 three-fifths. Skip Away
and Gentlemen were nearly five lengths in front of the rest of the
field, but middle moves like that often take their toll in the
homestretch.
</P>
<P>
   Skip Away and Gentlemen continued dueling around the final turn,
then turned into the stretch nearly four lengths clear of the rest
of the field. Gentlemen was the first to crack. He began to wobble
with a furlong to go.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Madero rallied quickly along the rail. But Skip Away was
simply too tough, too courageous to be denied. He put his head down
and powered his way to the finish, and was greeted with a
congratulatory pat on the neck from Bailey as he crossed under the
wire. Skip Away completed the mile and one-quarter on the fast main
track in 2 minutes flat. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a special place in my heart for Cigar, but maybe Skip
Away's better,'' Bailey said. ``Surely there's a place in my heart
big enough for the two of them.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
