<SLUG> BC-RAC-GOLDCUP-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T PLAN ON DEL MAR REMATCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ A rematch at the beach? Don't bet on it.
</P>
<P>
   Gentlemen's trainer is willing, but Skip Away's trainer sounded
less than eager to ship his horse cross country again to run at Del
Mar in the Aug. 15 Pacific Classic, the next $1 million race for
older horses.
</P>
<P>
   Sonny Hine said Skip Away needs a week to 10 days off to let his
feet grow out again after the incident in which he got loose at
Belmont Park one morning last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can make it anyway, I will come,'' Hine said after Skip
Away won the Hollywood Gold Cup on Sunday, leaving Gentlemen a
tired third. ``But he ran so hard today, maybe we ought to wait a
little bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not out of the question. He'll tell me.''
</P>
<P>
   Hine's target is the $4 million Breeders' Cup Classic at
Churchill Downs on Nov. 7. Other major races between now and then:
the $400,000 Whitney Handicap at Saratoga on Aug. 8, the $500,000
Woodward at Belmont Park on Sept. 19, and the $1 million Jockey
Club Gold Cup at Belmont on Oct. 10.
</P>
<P>
   The question for Sonny and owner Carolyn Hine is whether to stay
home and run for less money or risk another trip west to run for $1
million again.
</P>
<P>
   Skip Away is scheduled to fly back to New York on Tuesday. If he
comes back, he'll be trying to match Gentlemen's 1997 feat, winning
the Gold Cup and Pacific Classic in the same summer.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Richard Mandella said he plans to run Gentlemen in the
Pacific Classic, hoping he'll be fitter after the Gold Cup, his
first race in 3{ months. Also pointing for the Del Mar race is
Silver Charm, whose withdrawal from the Gold Cup prevented a
much-anticipated race against Skip Away.
</P>
<P>
   On the undercard: A.P. Assay equaled the Hollywood Park record
for 7 furlongs at 1:20 2/5 in winning the A Gleam Handicap for
fillies and mares.
</P>
<P>
   Ridden by Eddie Delahoussaye, the 4-year-old daughter of 1992
Horse of the Year A.P. Indy outsprinted Advancing Star for the lead
and wasn't challenged as she upset a rusty Exotic Wood by 4{
lengths. A.P. Assay paid $23.40.
</P>
<P>
   She tied the record set by Memo in 1994 and matched by Hal's Pal
in November and Another Star in April. It's impressive because
those are male horses and the track Sunday wasn't playing
particularly fast.
</P>
<P>
   This was A.P. Assay's fourth victory in five starts and her try
at the stakes level.
</P>
<P>
   Son of a Pistol made it back-to-back stakes victories as he and
Alex Solis rallied from fourth in the $300,000 Triple Bend
Breeders' Cup Handicap, the meet's biggest sprint.
</P>
<P>
   Prosperous Bid tired to third in a turf race that marked the
3-year-old's first action since a flop in the Wood Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Golden Eagle Farms first-timer Admire the Flag won in :57 1/5,
the quickest 5 furlongs of the meet.
</P>
<P>
   Another first-timer, Dixieland Sham ($28.20), ended trainer
Jenine Sahadi's losing streak at 70 races.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere: 1997 Belmont Stakes winner Touch Gold, running for
the first time since he finished last in the Breeders' Cup Classic
and moved to trainer Patrick Byrne, won a mile race in 1:34, a tick
off the 29-year-old track record at Churchill Downs. He looks like
a big player in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: The crowd, 32,505, was the biggest at the track for a
Hollywood Gold Cup since 1991, before the advent of cross-town
wagering. Wagering exceeded $18 million, a Gold Cup-day record.
There was a cameras giveaway and a boxing exhibition.... Jerry
Bailey rode three winners Sunday, after winning the Vanity Handicap
aboard Escena on Saturday.... Today's 30th anniversary of jockey
Eddie Delahoussaye's first winner at Evangeline Downs in Louisiana
was marked with a winner's circle ceremony Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
