<HEADLINE>
HOUGH PRAISES VALDES _ AND PARK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Dodgers' clubhouse was still buzzing Sunday about Ismael
Valdes' near perfect game the night before, but new pitching coach
Charlie Hough said he also was impressed with the way Chan Ho Park
pitched Friday without his best stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can you say about Valdes _ that was an incredible
performance,'' Hough said. ``That kid is a pitcher. But the way
Park battled and won in his game tells me a lot, too.''
</P>
<P>
   With right-hander Ramon Martinez scheduled for season-ending
surgery on his shoulder Tuesday, the Dodgers are desperate to have
a leader emerge in the starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   In his past four starts, Valdes has allowed just four earned
runs in 301/3 innings (1.19 ERA). Before that, he was 4-7 with a
5.18 ERA. Park was the Dodgers' top pitcher last season, tying
Hideo Nomo with 14 victories, including an 8-1 stretch in July and
August. But this season he has struggled.
</P>
<P>
   In a stretch of seven starts between May 19 and June 21, Park
went 1-2 with a 6.15 ERA. Friday, he allowed 10 hits in 62/3
innings but defeated the Pirates 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   Park acknowledged his confidence was shattered after lasting
just 21/3 innings May 24 in an 8-4 loss at Arizona. Three days
later, Valdes gave up a career-high nine earned runs in 42/3
innings at Houston.
</P>
<P>
   There were some in the organization who thought pitching coach
Glenn Gregson was not the right guy to nurture the two young
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   But Hough's comments Sunday sounded a lot like Gregson, who was
fired Wednesday along with hitting instructor Reggie Smith and
bullpen coach Mark Cresse by general manager Tom Lasorda.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are still young (both 24), and they have to go
through some rough spots to see how they will respond,'' Hough
said. ``They have had success, but you can learn a lot about
yourself when you struggle. I learned a lot about him from that
outing.''
</P>
<P>
   Konerko contributes: Left fielder Paul Konerko, who left
Saturday's game in the sixth inning after fouling a ball off his
foot, returned Sunday and gave the Dodgers a 4-1 lead with a
sixth-inning single.
</P>
<P>
   Konerko, still bothered by the bruise to his left heel, left the
game for pinch runner Roger Cedeno. But he went 6 for 13 during the
five-game homestand, raising his average from .199 to .224. Konerko
said he received quite a confidence boost Saturday when Lasorda
told him he would not be involved in any trade for Cincinnati
closer Jeff Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know those things can change in a minute,'' Konerko said,
``but hearing that really meant a lot. I don't want to be traded. I
want to prove I can do it here.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
