<SLUG> BC-OBIT-DAVIDSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT DAVIDSON, 89; BUILT A CHURCHILL LIBRARY
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert L.D. Davidson, president emeritus of Westminster College
in Fulton, Mo., who built the Churchill Memorial and Library there
in a historic church transplanted from London, died on June 20 in a
car accident in Missouri. He was 89 and lived in Fulton.
</P>
<P>
   Winston Churchill delivered his famous ``Iron Curtain'' speech
at Westminster College in 1946.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson later proposed the memorial library to honor Churchill
and Fulton's place in history. To house the library, he planned and
executed the transfer of the Church of St. Mary the Virgin in
Aldermanbury, which was rebuilt on the Westminster campus beginning
in 1964. The memorial was dedicated in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   The church was designed by Christopher Wren in the 1670's after
the Great Fire, which consumed much of London, including the
original Church of St. Mary the Virgin in Aldermanbury. Wren's
church was heavily damaged by German bombing in World War II, but
the exterior was largely intact.
</P>
<P>
   It now is a chapel and houses the library in its undercroft. Its
structure remains true to the Wren design.
</P>
<P>
   While Davidson was president of the college, from 1955 to 1973,
enrollment and the endowment grew and the campus changed noticeably
with the addition of a science center, freshman quadrangle, dining
hall and three residence halls known as the triangle.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Laurenson Dashiell Davidson, who was known as Larry, was
born in Dover, Del. He graduated Phi Beta Kappa from Dickinson
College in Carlisle, Pa., in 1931 and earned a master's degree in
history in 1937 and an Ed.D. in 1946, both from Temple University.
He did postgraduate work at New York University from 1937 to 1941
while he was a high school principal in Clayton, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   He served as a lieutenant commander in the Navy in World War II,
commanding a torpedo boat in the South Pacific. After the war, he
joined the Temple faculty and was an associate dean and associate
professor of social science there when Westminster recruited him as
its president.
</P>
<P>
   As president emeritus, Davidson remained active at the library
and in college affairs.
</P>
<P>
   A stamp collector, he was a past president of the American
Philatelic Congress and director-at-large of the American
Philatelic Society. He also was an arbitrator for the Federal
Mediation and Conciliation Service for many years.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson's wife of nearly 60 years, Lois Buckingham Davidson,
died last December. He is survived by their daughter, Roberta D.
Cupp, and son, Francis G., both of Fulton, and three grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-98 2343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980628.0226 </DOCNO>
