<SLUG> BC-BBO-SMITH-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: VALENTINE CANNOT CONTROL EVERYTHING 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CLAIRE SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Baseball's version of March madness, with all of its
seasons within the constraints of nine-inning games, finally ended
on Sunday night, pleasantly for the Yankees, mercifully for the
Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Interleague play, New York City style, designed to raise the
temperature not only in the stands but in the boroughs as well,
also comes with an unwanted stick of dynamite, one that inevitably
lands in the lap of the losing manager. If that manager lets it.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre of the Yankees probably won't let it, if and when the
Yankees drop a series to a team he is supposed to beat. The litmus
test won't occur this season, though, not after taking three of
four from Atlanta and two of three from the Mets, assuring that all
the proper people, including the placated George Steinbrenner,
remain suitably star-struck.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Valentine? For a second straight season, the Mets manager
stuck in the understudy role in this city is left to clean up the
mess.
</P>
<P>
   Unfair? Yes, in the sense that the Mets should not have been
expected to overwhelm the Yankees when no other team, including the
mighty Braves, has.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine isn't responsible for all the hype that accompanies
the closest thing to a Subway Series this town has to play host to.
Valentine is not responsible for the Yankees' brassy payroll or
blue-collar toughness. Nor can Valentine ward off the demons when
they insist on playing the cruelest of jokes, such as ripping up Al
Leiter's knee in the series opener on Friday, extracting the
pitcher from his finest season and from the most satisfying of
starts for the former Yankee.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is more to the mess than just the Mets' inability to
emulate the Yankees. As often happens, two divergent issues have
bubbled to the surface, one dealing with victories and losses, the
other with a manager who can't help but hit discordant notes while
trying to be winsome.
</P>
<P>
   He is a manager who loves to control but is spinning too rapidly
to have his actions look anything short of contrived. Take
Saturday. Did he or didn't he look daggers at some writers during
the game because he won a point while losing the game? That point
was that the left-hander Bill Pulsipher wasn't the go-to guy to get
the the left-handed-hitting Paul O'Neill out.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Pulsipher wasn't, Valentine insisted, when he instead
called on the right-hander Mel Rojas in a crucial situation, and
O'Neill hit a three-run home run. On Saturday, when Valentine did
call on Pulsipher, O'Neill singled in a run in the Yankees' 7-2
victory. That caused some to question whether Valentine turned and
glared at the press box, something denied by Valentine, who said
that he had had to explain the controversy to his bosses.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday the debate raged, making the battle for the final game
of the series, a 2-1 Mets victory, less meaningful. Was Valentine
still having fun? Was there proof on tape? In a funny, curious
pre-game scene, Valentine was asked if he had ever had
psychoanalysis. ``Not where I pay for it,'' he said. Members of the
news media reviewed the tape, shades of Zapruder, or Fellini, or
both, and Valentine actually did word association. Reliever?
``Bohanon.'' Second-guessing? ``Often.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a spectacle fraught with Freudian follies, involving the
dissection of the psyches of the manager, the city and its news
media. It was a display that has yet to spring up around Torre, who
has removed the need for psychology from the Bronx team.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine, for one, insists that he is having fun and that he
has had fun from Day 1. ``I haven't been miserable,'' he said.
``Yesterday I was a little agitated, and that was a big, big
mistake. But humans are allowed; they make mistakes.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet, this does not explain Valentine's remarkable ability to
attract controversy or to at least be among the list of usual
suspects when it rears its head. (Did he or didn't he leak
information about Todd Hundley, coax Masato Yoshii to defeat the
archenemy Pete Harnisch, or leer at the evil empire in the press
box?) And the more he tries to defuse, the more the quintessential
Valentine becomes the telling conundrum.
</P>
<P>
   Even Valentine's boss, General Manager Steve Phillips,
acknowledges as much. ``There are things that are special about
Bobby,'' he said on Sunday. ``The passion and the emotion that make
him very good at what he does at times cause him problems in other
ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine doesn't expect things to necessarily smooth out for
himself or his struggling team once the invading news media from
the Bronx move on. There is no normal here, the manager believes,
only fractious New York. ``It's never just baseball, so why should
we fool ourselves into thinking that's going to happen when this
series ends?'' Valentine said. ``There will always be something
else happening. It's all a part of playing in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, it's also a part of Valentine. ``I don't want to change
that,'' Phillips said when addressing Valentine's personality. ``We
talk about it and hope we can manage the situation the next time so
we don't have a controversy.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, that sounds like managing the manager, something that
once seemed a necessary routine across town but has now found the
Mets, leaving Valentine in the unpleasant position of trying to
disassociate himself not from his passion but too often from what
it spawns. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-98 2352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980628.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-28 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
