<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WYDEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETER WYDEN, WHO WROTE OF SON'S SCHIZOPHRENIA, DIES AT 74 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Peter Wyden, a journalist and author whose most recent book
delved into his younger son's fight against schizophrenia, died
Saturday evening at Danbury Hospital in Danbury, Conn. He was 74.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a stroke and a subdural hematoma, or blood on the
brain, according to a statement issued by his older son, Senator
Ron Wyden of Oregon. Wyden's wife, Elaine, said that he had bumped
his head getting out of a car on Wednesday and that doctors thought
he had probably burst a blood vessel, which led to the stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Wyden, who lived in Ridgefield, Conn., with his wife, was born
in Berlin in 1923. He came to New York City when he was 13 and
attended the City College of New York. His journalism career took
him from The Wichita Eagle of Kansas to Newsweek to Ladies' Home
Journal.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote more than a dozen books, one of which, ``Bay of Pigs:
The Untold Story,'' won an Overseas Press Club Award. His other
books included the story of a Holocaust survivor and a peek inside
the Masters and Johnson sex clinic, the latter written with his
second wife, Barbara. That marriage, like the one to his first
wife, Edith, ended in divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Wyden's most recent book chronicled his son Jeff's battle
against mental illness. The book, ``Conquering Schizophrenia: A
Father, His Son and a Medical Breakthrough,'' was published by
Alfred A. Knopf this spring.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife and his sons, Wyden is survived by his
two former wives; two stepchildren, James Seaton, 48, of Silver
Spring, Md., and Andrea Miller, 45, of New Haven; two grandchildren
and two step-grandchildren.
</P>
